sty comrades perished, but I clasped in my arms the keel of my curved ship and was borne drifting for nine days, '),(10222,'and on the tenth black night the gods brought me to the isle, Ogygia, where  the fair-tressed Calypso dwells, a dread goddess. She took me to her home with kindly welcome, and gave me food, and said that she would make me immortal and ageless all my days;'),(10223,' but she could never persuade the heart in my breast.'),(10224,' There for seven years\' space I remained continually, and ever  with my tears would I wet the immortal raiment which Calypso gave me. '),(10225,'But when the eight year came in circling course, then she roused me and bade me go, either because of some message from Zeus, or because her own mind was turned. '),(10226,' And she sent me on my way on a raft, stoutly bound, and gave me abundant store  of bread and sweet wine, and clad me in immortal raiment, and sent forth a gentle wind and warm.'),(10227,' So for seventeen days I sailed over the sea, and on the eighteenth appeared the shadowy mountains of your land; and my heart was glad,  ill-starred that I was;'),(10228,'for verily I was yet to have fellowship with great woe, which Poseidon, the earth-shaker, sent upon me. For he stirred up the winds against me and stayed my course, and wondrously roused the sea, nor would the wave suffer me to be borne upon my raft, as I groaned ceaselessly.'),(10229,' My raft indeed the storm shattered,'),(10230,' but by swimming I clove my way through yon gulf of the sea, until the wind and the waves, as they bore me, brought me to your shores.'),(10231,' There, had I sought to land, the waves would have hurled me upon the shore, and dashed me against the great crags and a cheerless place, '),(10232,' but I gave way, and swam back until I came to a river, where seemed to me the best place, since it was smooth of rocks, and besides there was shelter from the wind.'),(10233,' Forth then I staggered, and sank down, gasping for breath, and immortal night came on. '),(10234,'Then I went forth from the heaven-fed river,  and lay down to sleep in the bushes, gathering leaves about me; '),(10235,' and a god shed over me infinite sleep. '),(10236,' So there among the leaves I slept, my heart sore stricken, the whole night through, until the morning and until midday; '),(10237,'and the sun turned to his setting ere sweet sleep released me.'),(10238,'  Then I saw the handmaids of thy daughter on the shore at play, and amid them was she, fair as the goddesses.'),(10239,'To her I made my prayer;'),(10240,' and she in no wise failed in good understanding, to do as thou wouldst not deem that one of younger years would do on meeting thee; '),(10241,'for younger folk are ever thoughtless.'),(10242,'  She gave bread in plenty and sparkling wine, and bathed me in the river, and gave me this raiment.'),(10243,' In this, for all my sorrows, have I told thee the truth.”'),(10244,'\nThen in turn Alcinous answered him, and said:'),(10245,'“Stranger, verily my daughter was not minded aright in this,  that she did not bring thee to our house with her maidens. Yet it was to her first that thou didst make thy prayer.”'),(10246,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(10247,' “Prince, rebuke not for this, I pray thee, thy blameless daughter. '),(10248,'She did indeed bid me follow with her maidens,  but I would not for fear and shame, lest haply thy heart should darken with wrath as thou sawest it; '),(10249,'for we are quick to anger, we tribes of men upon the earth.\"'),(10250,'And again Alcinous answered him, and said:'),(10251,'“Stranger, not such is the heart in my breast,  to be filled with wrath without a cause. '),(10252,' Better is due measure in all things.'),(10253,'I would, O father Zeus, and Athena and Apollo, that thou, so goodly a man, and like-minded with me, wouldst have my daughter to wife, and be called my son, and abide here; '),(10254,'a house and possessions would I give thee,  if thou shouldst choose to remain, '),(10255,'but against thy will shall no one of the Phaeacians keep thee; '),(10256,'let not that be the will of father Zeus. '),(10257,' But as for thy sending, that thou mayest know it surely, I appoint a time thereto, even the morrow. '),(10258,'Then shalt thou lie down, overcome by sleep, and they shall row thee over the calm sea until thou comest  to thy country and thy house, or to whatsoever place thou wilt, aye though it be even far beyond Euboea, which those of our people who saw it, when they carried fair-haired Rhadamanthus to visit Tityus, the son of Gaea, say is the furthest of lands.'),(10259,'  Thither they went, and without toil accomplished their journey, and on the selfsame day came back home.'),(10260,' So shalt thou, too, know for thyself how far my ships are the best, and my youths at tossing the brine with the oar-blade.\"'),(10261,'So said he, and the much-enduring goodly Odysseus was glad;  and he spoke in prayer, and said: '),(10262,'“Father Zeus, grant that Alcinous may bring to pass all that he has said.'),(10263,' So shall his fame be unquenchable over the earth, the giver of grain, and I shall reach my native land.\"'),(10264,'Thus they spoke to one another, '),(10265,' and white-armed Arete bade her maidens place a bedstead under cover of the portico, and to lay on it fair blankets of purple, and to spread there over coverlets, and on these to put fleecy cloaks for clothing.'),(10266,' So they went forth from the hall with torches in their hands.'),(10267,'  But when they had busily spread the stout-built bedstead, they came to Odysseus, and called to him, and said:'),(10268,'thy bed is made.”'),(10269,'thy bed is made.”'),(10270,'Thus they spoke, and welcome did it seem to him to lay him down to sleep.'),(10271,' So there he slept, the much-enduring goodly Odysseus,  on the corded bedstead under the echoing portico. '),(10272,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.346-7.347'),(10273,' As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, the strong and mighty Alcinous rose from his couch, and up rose also Zeus-born Odysseus, the sacker of cities.'),(10274,' And the strong and mighty Alcinous led the way  to the place of assembly of the Phaeacians, which was builded for them hard by their ships.'),(10275,'Thither they came and sat down on the polished stones close by one another;'),(10276,' and Pallas Athena went throughout the city, in the likeness of the herald of wise Alcinous, devising a return for great-hearted Odysseus.  To each man\'s side she came, and spoke and said:'),(10277,'“Hither now, leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians, come to the place of assembly, that you may learn of the stranger who has newly come to the palace of wise Alcinous after his wanderings over the sea, and in form is like unto the immortals.\"'),(10278,'  So saying she roused the spirit and heart of each man,'),(10279,' and speedily the place of assembly and the seats were filled with men that gathered.'),(10280,' And many marvelled at the sight of the wise son of Laertes, '),(10281,'for wondrous was the grace that Athena shed upon his head and shoulders;  and she made him taller and sturdier to behold, that he might be welcomed by all the Phaeacians, and win awe and reverence, and might accomplish the many feats wherein the Phaeacians made trial of Odysseus.'),(10282,' Now when they were assembled and met together,  Alcinous addressed their assembly and spoke among them:'),(10283,'“Hearken to me, leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians, that I may speak what the heart in my breast bids me.'),(10284,' This stranger—I know not who he is—has come to my house in his wanderings, whether from men of the east or of the west.'),(10285,'  He urges that he be sent on his way, and prays for assurance,'),(10286,' and let us on our part, as of old we were wont, speed on his sending; '),(10287,' for verily no man soever who comes to my house, abides here long in sorrow for lack of sending. '),(10288,'Nay come, let us draw a black ship down to the bright sea  for her first voyage, and let men choose two and fifty youths from out the people, even those that have heretofore been the best.'),(10289,' And when you have all duly lashed the oars to the thole-pins, go ashore,'),(10290,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 8.38-8.39'),(10291,' and then go your way to my house, and prepare a feast with speed; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 38 to line 39'),(10292,' To the youths this is my command,'),(10293,' but do you others, the sceptred kings, come to my fair palace, that we may entertain yon stranger in the halls; and let no man say me nay.'),(10294,' And summon hither the divine minstrel, Demodocus; '),(10295,'for to him above all others has the god granted skill in song,  to give delight in whatever way his spirit prompts him to sing.”'),(10296,' \nSo saying, he led the way, and the sceptred kings followed him, '),(10297,'while a herald went for the divine minstrel.'),(10298,' And chosen youths, two and fifty, went, as he bade, to the shore of the unresting sea.'),(10299,'  And when they had come down to the ship and to the sea, they drew the black ship down to the deep water, and placed the mast and sail in the black ship, and fitted the oars in the leathern thole-straps, all in due order, and spread the white sail.'),(10300,' Well out in the roadstead they moored the ship,'),(10301,'  and then went their way to the great palace of the wise Alcinous.'),(10302,' Filled were the porticoes and courts and rooms with the men that gathered, '),(10303,' for many there were, both young and old.'),(10304,'For them Alcinous slaughtered twelve sheep,  and eight white-tusked boars, and two oxen of shambling gait. '),(10305,'These they flayed and dressed, and made ready a goodly feast.'),(10306,'\nThen the herald drew near, leading the good minstrel, whom the Muse loved above all other men, and gave him both good and evil; '),(10307,'of his sight she deprived him, but gave him the gift of sweet song.'),(10308,'  For him Pontonous, the herald, set a silver-studded chair in the midst of the banqueters, leaning it against a tall pillar, '),(10309,' and he hung the clear-toned lyre from a peg close above his head, and showed him how to reach it with his hands. '),(10310,'And beside him he placed a basket and a beautiful table,  and a cup of wine, to drink when his heart should bid him.'),(10311,'So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. '),(10312,' But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, the Muse moved the minstrel to sing of the glorious deeds of warriors, from that lay the fame whereof had then reached broad heaven,  even the quarrel of Odysseus and Achilles, son of Peleus, how once they strove with furious words at a rich feast of the gods, and Agamemnon, king of men, was glad at heart that the best of the Achaeans were quarrelling;'),(10313,'for thus Phoebus Apollo, in giving his response, had told him that it should be,  in sacred Pytho, when he passed over the threshold of stone to enquire of the oracle.'),(10314,' For then the beginning of woe was rolling upon Trojans and Danaans through the will of great Zeus. '),(10315,' \nThis song the famous minstrel sang; '),(10316,'but Odysseus grasped his great purple cloak with his stout hands,  and drew it down over his head, and hid his comely face; '),(10317,'for he had shame of the Phaeacians as he let fall tears from beneath his eyebrows.'),(10318,' Yea, and as often as the divine minstrel ceased his singing, Odysseus would wipe away his tears and draw the cloak from off his head, and taking the two-handled cup would pour libations to the gods.'),(10319,'  But as often as he began again, and the nobles of the Phaeacians bade him sing, because they took pleasure in his lay, Odysseus would again cover his head and moan.'),(10320,' Now from all the rest he concealed the tears that he shed, but Alcinous alone marked him and took heed,  for he sat by him, and heard him groaning heavily.'),(10321,' And straightway he spoke among the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar:'),(10322,'“Hear me, ye leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians, '),(10323,'already have we satisfied our hearts with the equal banquet and with the lyre, which is the companion of the rich feast.'),(10324,'  But now let us go forth, and make trial of all manner of games, that yon stranger may tell his friends, when he returns home, how far we excel other men in boxing and wrestling and leaping and in speed of foot.\"'),(10325,'So saying, he led the way, and they followed him.'),(10326,'  From the peg the herald hung the clear-toned lyre, and took Demodocus by the hand, and led him forth from the hall, '),(10327,'guiding him by the self-same road by which the others, the nobles of the Phaeacians, had gone to gaze upon the games.'),(10328,'They went their way to the place of assembly, and with them went a great throng,  past counting; '),(10329,' and up rose many noble youths.'),(10330,'There rose Acroneus, and Ocyalus, and Elatreus, and Nauteus, and Prymneus, and Anchialus, and Eretmeus, and Ponteus, and Proreus, Thoon and Anabesineus,  and Amphialus, son of Polyneus, son of Tecton; '),(10331,'and up rose also Euryalus, the peer of man-destroying Ares, the son of Naubolus, who in comeliness and form was the best of all the Phaeacians after peerless Laodamas; '),(10332,'and up rose the three sons of noble Alcinous, Laodamas, and Halius, and godlike Clytoneus. '),(10333,' These then first made trial in the foot-race.'),(10334,' A course was marked out for them from the turning point,'),(10335,' and they all sped swiftly, raising the dust of the plain; '),(10336,'but among them noble Clytoneus was far the best at running,'),(10337,'and by as far as is the range of a team of mules in fallow land,  by so far he shot to the front and reached the host, and the others were left behind.'),(10338,' Then they made trial of toilsome wrestling,'),(10339,' and here in turn Euryalus excelled all the princes.'),(10340,'And in leaping Amphialus was best of all,'),(10341,'  and with the discus again far the best of all was Elatreus,  and in boxing Laodamas, the good son of Alcinous.'),(10342,'But when the hearts of all had taken pleasure in the contests, Laodamas, the son of Alcinous, spoke among them:'),(10343,'\n“Come, friends, let us ask yon stranger whether he knows and has learned any contests. '),(10344,'In build, surely, he is no mean man,  in thighs and calves, and in his two arms above, his stout neck, and his great might.'),(10345,' In no wise does he lack aught of the strength of youth, but he has been broken by many troubles.'),(10346,' For to my mind there is naught worse than the sea to confound a man, be he never so strong.\"'),(10347,'  And Euryalus in turn answered him, and said:'),(10348,'“Laodamas, this word of thine is right fitly spoken.'),(10349,' Go now thyself and challenge him, and make known thy word.\"'),(10350,'Now when the good son of Alcinous heard this he came and took his stand in the midst and spoke to Odysseus:'),(10351,'  “Come, Sir stranger, do thou, too, make trial of the contests, if thou knowest any;'),(10352,'and it must be that thou knowest contests, '),(10353,'for there is no greater glory for a man so long as he lives than that which he achieves by his own hands and his feet.'),(10354,' Nay, come, make trial, and cast away care from thy heart.'),(10355,'  Thy journey shall no more be long delayed, nay, even now thy ship is launched and the crew is ready.”'),(10356,' Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(10357,' “Laodamas, why do ye mock me with this challenge? '),(10358,'Sorrow is in my mind far more than contests,  seeing that in time past I have suffered much and toiled much, and now I sit in the midst of your assembly, longing for my return home, and making my prayer to the king and to all the people.”'),(10359,' Then again Euryalus made answer and taunted him to his face:'),(10360,'“Nay verily, stranger, for I do not liken thee to a man that is skilled  in contests, such as abound among men, but to one who, faring to and fro with his benched ship, is a captain of sailors who are merchantmen, one who is mindful of his freight, and has charge of a home-borne cargo, and the gains of his greed.'),(10361,' Thou dost not look like an athlete.” '),(10362,' \n  Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered him:'),(10363,' thou art as one blind with folly.'),(10364,' thou art as one blind with folly.'),(10365,' So true is it that the gods do not give gracious gifts to all alike, not form nor mind nor eloquence. '),(10366,'For one man is inferior in comeliness,  but the god sets a crown of beauty upon his words, and men look upon him with delight, '),(10367,' and he speaks on unfalteringly with sweet modesty, and is conspicuous among the gathered people, and as he goes through the city men gaze upon him as upon a god.'),(10368,'Another again is in comeliness like the immortals,  but no crown of grace is set about his words. So, in thy case, thy comeliness is preeminent, nor could a god himself mend it, but in mind thou art stunted. '),(10369,' Thou hast stirred the spirit in my breast by speaking thus unmannerly.'),(10370,'I am not unskilled in sports  as thou pratest, nay, methinks I was among the first so long as I trusted in my youth and in my hands.'),(10371,' But now I am bound by suffering and pains; '),(10372,' for much have I endured in passing through wars of men and the grievous waves.'),(10373,'But even so, though I have suffered much, I will make trial of the contests, '),(10374,' for thy word has stung me to the heart, and thou hast provoked me with thy speech.”'),(10375,'He spoke, and, leaping up with his cloak about him as it was, seized a discus larger than the rest and thick, no little heavier than those with which the Phaeacians were wont to contend one with another.'),(10376,' This with a whirl he sent from his stout hand,  and the stone hummed as it flew; '),(10377,'and down they crouched to the earth, the Phaeacians of the long oars, men famed for their ships, beneath the rush of the stone.'),(10378,' Past the marks of all it flew, speeding lightly from his hand, '),(10379,'and Athena, in the likeness of a man, set the mark, and she spoke and addressed him:'),(10380,'\n  “Even a blind man, stranger, could distinguish this mark, groping for it with his hands, for it is in nowise confused with the throng of the others, but is far the first.'),(10381,' Be thou of good cheer for this bout at least:'),(10382,' no one of the Phaeacians will reach this, or cast beyond it.” '),(10383,' \nSo she spoke, and the much-enduring goodly Odysseus was glad,  rejoicing that he saw a true friend in the lists. '),(10384,'  Then with a lighter heart he spoke among the Phaeacians:'),(10385,'\n“Reach this now, young men; '),(10386,'and presently, methinks, I will send another after it, as far or even further. '),(10387,' Of the rest, if any man\'s heart and spirit bid him,  let him come hither and make trial—for ye have greatly angered me—be it in boxing or in wrestling, aye, or in running, I care not; let any one come of all the Phaeacians, save Laodamas alone.'),(10388,' and who would quarrel with one that entertains him? '),(10389,' and who would quarrel with one that entertains him? '),(10390,'Foolish is that man and worthless,  who challenges to a contest the host who receives him in a strange land; '),(10391,'he does but mar his own fortunes.'),(10392,' But of all the rest I refuse none, and make light of none, but am fain to know them, and make trial of them man to man.'),(10393,' For in all things I am no weakling, even in all the contests that are practised among men.'),(10394,'  Well do I know how to handle the polished bow,'),(10395,' and ever would I be the first to shoot and smite my man in the throng of the foe, even though many comrades stood by me and were shooting at the men.'),(10396,' Only Philoctetes excelled me with the bow  in the land of the Trojans, when we Achaeans shot. '),(10397,' But of all others I declare that I am best by far, of all mortals that are now upon the earth and eat bread.'),(10398,' Yet with men of former days I will not seek to vie, with Heracles or with Eurytus of Oechalia,  who strove even with the immortals in archery. '),(10399,' Wherefore great Eurytus died soon, nor did old age come upon him in his halls, '),(10400,'for Apollo waxed wroth and slew him, because he had challenged him to a contest with the bow.'),(10401,' And with the spear I throw farther than any other man can shoot with an arrow.'),(10402,'  In the foot race alone I fear that someone of the Phaeacians may out strip me, '),(10403,'for cruelly have I been broken amid the many waves, since there was in my ship no lasting store of provisions; '),(10404,'therefore my limbs are loosened.\"'),(10405,'So he spoke and they were all hushed in silence; '),(10406,'  but Alcinous alone answered him and said:'),(10407,'“Stranger, since not ungraciously dost thou speak thus in our midst, but art minded to shew forth the prowess which waits upon thee, in anger that yonder man came up to thee in the lists and taunted thee in a way in which no mortal would make light of thy prowess,  who knew in his heart how to speak fitly; '),(10408,'come, now, hearken to my words, that thou mayest tell to another hero, when in thy halls thou art feasting with thy wife and children, and rememberest our skill, what feats  Zeus has vouchsafed to us from our fathers\' days even until now. '),(10409,'For we are not faultless boxers or wrestlers, but in the foot race we run swiftly, and we are the best seamen; and ever to us is the banquet dear, and the lyre, and the dance, and changes of raiment, and warm baths, and the couch. '),(10410,'   But come now, all ye that are the best dancers of the Phaeacians, make sport, that the stranger may tell his friends on reaching home how far we surpass others in seamanship and in fleetness of foot, and in the dance and in song.'),(10411,' And let one go straightway  and fetch for Demodocus the clear-toned lyre which lies somewhere in our halls.”'),(10412,'So spoke Alcinous the godlike, and the herald rose to fetch the hollow lyre from the palace of the king.'),(10413,' Then stood up masters of the lists, nine in all, men chosen from out the people, who in their gatherings were wont to order all things aright.  They levelled a place for the dance, and marked out a fair wide ring,'),(10414,' and the herald came near, bearing the clear-toned lyre for Demodocus.'),(10415,' He then moved into the midst, '),(10416,'and around him stood boys in the first bloom of youth, well skilled in the dance, and they smote the goodly dancing floor with their feet.'),(10417,' And Odysseus  gazed at the twinklings of their feet and marvelled in spirit.'),(10418,'But the minstrel struck the chords in prelude to his sweet lay and sang of the love of Ares and Aphrodite of the fair crown, how first they lay together in the house of Hephaestus secretly; and Ares gave her many gifts, and shamed the bed  of the lord Hephaestus.'),(10419,' But straightway one came to him with tidings, even Helius, who had marked them as they lay together in love.'),(10420,' And when Hephaestus heard the grievous tale, he went his way to his smithy, pondering evil in the deep of his heart, and set on the anvil block the great anvil and forged bonds  which might not be broken or loosed, that the lovers might bide fast where they were. '),(10421,' But when he had fashioned the snare in his wrath against Ares, he went to his chamber where lay his bed, and everywhere round about the bed-posts he spread the bonds, '),(10422,'and many too were hung from above, from the roof-beams,  fine as spiders\' webs, so that no one even of the blessed gods could see them, '),(10423,'so exceeding craftily were they fashioned.'),(10424,' But when he had spread all his snare about the couch, he made as though he would go to Lemnos, that well-built citadel, which is in his eyes far the dearest of all lands.'),(10425,'  And no blind watch did Ares of the golden rein keep, when he saw Hephaestus, famed for his handicraft, departing, '),(10426,'but he went his way to the house of famous Hephaestus, eager for the love of Cytherea of the fair crown.'),(10427,' Now she had but newly come from the presence of her father, the mighty son of Cronos,  and had sat her down.'),(10428,'And Ares came into the house and clasped her hand and spoke and addressed her:'),(10429,'\n“Come, love, let us to bed and take our joy, couched together.'),(10430,' For Hephaestus is no longer here in the land, but has now gone, I ween, to Lemnos, to visit the Sintians of savage speech.” '),(10431,'  So he spoke, and a welcome thing it seemed to her to lie with him.'),(10432,'So they two went to the couch, and lay them down to sleep,'),(10433,'and about them clung the cunning bonds of the wise Hephaestus, nor could they in any wise stir their limbs or raise them up.'),(10434,' Then at length they learned that there was no more escaping.'),(10435,'  And near to them came the famous god of the two strong arms, having turned back before he reached the land of Lemnos; '),(10436,'for Helius had kept watch for him and had brought him word.'),(10437,' So he went to his house with a heavy heart, '),(10438,'and stood at the gateway, and fierce anger seized him.'),(10439,' And terribly he cried out and called to all the gods:'),(10440,'\n“Father Zeus, and ye other blessed gods that are forever, come hither that ye may see a laughable matter and a monstrous, even how Aphrodite, daughter of Zeus, scorns me for that I am lame and loves destructive Ares  because he is comely and strong of limb, whereas I was born misshapen.'),(10441,' Yet for this is none other to blame but my two parents—would they had never begotten me!'),(10442,' But ye shall see where these two have gone up into my bed and sleep together in love; and I am troubled at the sight.'),(10443,'  Yet, methinks, they will not wish to lie longer thus, no, not for a moment, how loving soever they are.'),(10444,' Soon shall both lose their desire to sleep;'),(10445,'but the snare and the bonds shall hold them until her father pays back to me all the gifts of wooing that I gave him for the sake of his shameless girl;  for his daughter is fair but bridles not her passion.”'),(10446,'So he spoke and the gods gathered to the house of the brazen floor.'),(10447,' Poseidon came, the earth-enfolder, and the helper Hermes came, and the lord Apollo, the archer god.'),(10448,' Now the goddesses abode for shame each in her own house, '),(10449,' but the gods, the givers of good things, stood in the gateway; '),(10450,'and unquenchable laughter arose among the blessed gods as they saw the craft of wise Hephaestus.'),(10451,' And thus would one speak, with a glance at his neighbor:'),(10452,'\n“Ill deeds thrive not. '),(10453,' The slow catches the swift;  even as now Hephaestus, slow though he is, has out-stripped Ares for all that he is the swiftest of the gods who hold Olympus. Lame though he is, he has caught him by craft,'),(10454,'wherefore Ares owes the fine of the adulterer.\"'),(10455,'Thus they spoke to one another.'),(10456,' But to Hermes the lord Apollo, son of Zeus, said:'),(10457,'\n  “Hermes, son of Zeus, messenger, giver of good things, wouldst thou in sooth be willing, even though ensnared with strong bonds, to lie on a couch by the side of golden Aphrodite?\"'),(10458,'Then the messenger, Argeiphontes, answered him:'),(10459,'“Would that this might befall, lord Apollo, thou archer god— '),(10460,' that thrice as many bonds inextricable might clasp me about and ye gods, aye, and all the goddesses too might be looking on, but that I might sleep by the side of golden Aphrodite.” '),(10461,' \nSo he spoke and laughter arose among the immortal gods.'),(10462,' Yet Poseidon laughed not, but ever besought  Hephaestus, the famous craftsman, to set Ares free; '),(10463,'and he spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(10464,'“Loose him,'),(10465,'and I promise, as thou biddest me, that he shall himself pay thee all that is right in the presence of the immortal gods.\"'),(10466,'Then the famous god of the two strong arms answered him:'),(10467,' “Ask not this of me, Poseidon, thou earth-enfolder.'),(10468,' A sorry thing to be sure of is the surety for a sorry knave.'),(10469,' How could I put thee in bonds among the immortal gods, if Ares should avoid both the debt and the bonds and depart?\"'),(10470,'Then again Poseidon, the earth-shaker, answered him:'),(10471,'  “Hephaestus, even if Ares shall avoid the debt and flee away, I will myself pay thee this.\"'),(10472,'Then the famous god of the two strong arms answered him:'),(10473,' “It may not be that I should say thee nay, nor were it seemly.\"'),(10474,'So saying the mighty Hephaestus loosed the bonds '),(10475,' and the two, when they were freed from that bond so strong, sprang up straightway. And Ares departed to Thrace, but she, the laughter-loving Aphrodite, went to Cyprus, to Paphos,'),(10476,'  where is her demesne and fragrant altar.'),(10477,'There the Graces bathed her and anointed her with  immortal oil, such as gleams upon the gods that are forever.'),(10478,' And they clothed her in lovely raiment, a wonder to behold.'),(10479,'\nThis song the famous minstrel sang; and Odysseus was glad at heart as he listened, and so too were the Phaeacians of the long oars, men famed for their ships.'),(10480,'\n  Then Alcinous bade Halius and Laodamas dance alone, for no one could vie with them. '),(10481,'And when they had taken in their hands the beautiful ball of purple, which wise Polybus had made for them, the one  would lean backward and toss it toward the shadowy clouds, and the other would leap up from the earth and skilfully catch it before his feet touched the ground again.'),(10482,' But when they had tried their skill in throwing the ball straight up, the two fell to dancing on the bounteous earth, ever tossing the ball to and fro, '),(10483,' and the other youths  stood in the lists and beat time, and thereat a great din arose.'),(10484,'Then to Alcinous spoke goodly Odysseus:'),(10485,' “Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, thou didst boast that thy dancers were the best, and lo, thy words are made good; '),(10486,'amazement holds me as I look on them.” '),(10487,' \n  So he spoke, and the strong and mighty Alcinous was glad; and straightway he spoke among the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar:'),(10488,'\n“Hear me, leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians.'),(10489,' This stranger verily seems to me a man of understanding.'),(10490,' Come then, let us give him a gift of friendship, as is fitting; '),(10491,' for twelve glorious kings bear sway in our land as rulers, and I myself am the thirteenth.'),(10492,' Now do you, each of the twelve, bring a newly washed cloak and tunic, and a talent of precious gold, '),(10493,'and let us straightway bring all together,  that the stranger with our gifts in his hands may go to his supper glad at heart. '),(10494,'And let Euryalus make amends to the stranger himself with words and with a gift, for the word that he spoke was in no wise seemly.\"'),(10495,'So he spoke, and they all praised his words and bade that so it should be, and sent forth every man a herald to fetch the gifts.'),(10496,' And Euryalus in turn made answer, and said:'),(10497,'“Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, I will indeed make amends to the stranger, as thou biddest me.'),(10498,' I will give him this sword, all of bronze, whereon is a hilt of silver, and a scabbard of new-sawn ivory  is wrought about it; '),(10499,'and it shall be to him a thing of great worth.”'),(10500,'So saying, he put into his hands the silver-studded sword, and spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(10501,' “Hail, Sir stranger; '),(10502,'but if any word has been spoken that was harsh, may the storm-winds straightway snatch it and bear it away.'),(10503,'  And for thyself, may the gods grant thee to see thy wife, and to come to thy native land, for long time hast thou been suffering woes far from thy friends.\"'),(10504,'And Odysseus of many wiles answered him:'),(10505,' “All hail to thee, too, friend; and may the gods grant thee happiness, '),(10506,'and mayest thou never hereafter miss  this sword which thou hast given me, making amends with gentle speech.”'),(10507,'He spoke, and about his shoulders hung the silver-studded sword.'),(10508,' And the sun set, and the glorious gifts were brought him.'),(10509,' These the lordly heralds bore to the palace of Alcinous, '),(10510,'and the sons of peerless Alcinous  took the beautiful gifts and set them before their honored mother. '),(10511,'And the strong and mighty Alcinous led the way, and they came in and sat down on the high seats.'),(10512,' Then to Arete spoke the mighty Alcinous:'),(10513,'\n“Bring hither, wife, a goodly chest, the best thou hast, '),(10514,' and thyself place in it a newly-washed cloak and tunic; '),(10515,'and do ye heat for the stranger a cauldron on the fire, and warm water, that when he has bathed and has seen well bestowed all the gifts which the noble Phaeacians have brought hither, he may take pleasure in the feast, and in hearing the strains of the song.'),(10516,'  And I will give him this beautiful cup of mine, wrought of gold, that he may remember me all his days as he pours libations in his halls to Zeus and to the other gods.” '),(10517,' \nSo he spoke, and Arete bade her handmaids to set a great cauldron on the fire with all speed.'),(10518,'  And they set on the blazing fire the cauldron for filling the bath, and poured in water, and took billets of wood and kindled them beneath it.'),(10519,' Then the fire played about the belly of the cauldron, and the water grew warm;'),(10520,'but meanwhile Arete brought forth for the stranger a beautiful chest from the treasure chamber, and placed in it the goodly gifts,  the raiment and the gold, which the Phaeacians gave. '),(10521,'And therein she herself placed a cloak and a fair tunic; and she spoke and addressed Odysseus with winged words:'),(10522,'\n“Look now thyself to the lid, and quickly cast a cord upon it, lest some one despoil thee of thy goods on the way, when later on  thou art lying in sweet sleep, as thou farest in the black ship.”'),(10523,'Now when the much-enduring goodly Odysseus heard these words, he straightway fitted on the lid, and quickly cast a cord upon it—a cunning knot, which queenly Circe once had taught him.'),(10524,' Then forthwith the housewife bade him  go to the bath and bathe; '),(10525,'and his heart was glad when he saw the warm bath, for he had not been wont to have such tendance from the time that he left the house of faired-haired Calypso, '),(10526,'but until then he had tendance continually as a god.'),(10527,'Now when the handmaids had bathed him and anointed him with oil,  and had cast about him a fair cloak and a tunic, he came forth from the bath, and went to join the men at their wine.'),(10528,' And Nausicaa, gifted with beauty by the gods, stood by the door-post of the well-built hall, and she marvelled at Odysseus, as her eyes beheld him,  and she spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(10529,'“Farewell, stranger, and hereafter even in thy own native land mayest thou remember me, for to me first thou owest the price of thy life.\"'),(10530,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her:'),(10531,'“Nausicaa, daughter of great-hearted Alcinous,  so may Zeus grant, the loud-thundering lord of Here, that I may reach my home and see the day of my returning.'),(10532,' Then will I even there pray to thee as to a god all my days, '),(10533,'for thou, maiden, hast given me life.\"'),(10534,' \nHe spoke, and sat down on a chair beside king Alcinous.'),(10535,' And now they were serving out portions and mixing the wine.'),(10536,' Then the herald came near, leading the good minstrel, Demodocus, held in honor by the people, '),(10537,' and seated him in the midst of the banqueters, leaning his chair against a high pillar.'),(10538,'Then to the herald said Odysseus of many wiles,  cutting off a portion of the chine of a white-tusked boar, whereof yet more was left, and there was rich fat on either side:'),(10539,'\n“Herald, take and give this portion to Demodocus, that he may eat, '),(10540,' and I will greet him, despite my grief. '),(10541,'For among all men that are upon the earth minstrels  win honor and reverence, for that the Muse has taught them the paths of song, and loves the tribe of minstrels.\"'),(10542,'So he spoke, and the herald bore the portion and placed it in the hands of the lord Demodocus,'),(10543,' and he took it and was glad at heart.'),(10544,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(10545,'  But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, then to Demodocus said Odysseus of many wiles:'),(10546,'\n“Demodocus, verily above all mortal men do I praise thee, '),(10547,'whether it was the Muse, the daughter of Zeus, that taught thee, or Apollo; '),(10548,'for well and truly dost thou sing of the fate of the Achaeans,  all that they wrought and suffered, and all the toils they endured, as though haply thou hadst thyself been present, or hadst heard the tale from another.'),(10549,' But come now, change thy theme, and sing of the building of the horse of wood, which Epeius made with Athena\'s help, the horse which once Odysseus led up into the citadel as a thing of guile,  when he had filled it with the men who sacked Ilios. '),(10550,' If thou dost indeed tell me this tale aright, I will declare to all mankind that the god has of a ready heart granted thee the gift of divine song.”'),(10551,'So he spoke, and the minstrel, moved by the god, began, and let his song be heard,  taking up the tale where the Argives had embarked on their benched ships and were sailing away, after casting fire on their huts, while those others led by glorious Odysseus were now sitting in the place of assembly of the Trojans, hidden in the horse; '),(10552,'for the Trojans had themselves dragged it to the citadel.'),(10553,'  So there it stood, while the people talked long as they sat about it, and could form no resolve.'),(10554,' Nay, in three ways did counsel find favour in their minds: either to cleave the hollow timber with the pitiless bronze, or to drag it to the height and cast it down the rocks, or to let it stand as a great offering to propitiate the gods,  even as in the end it was to be brought to pass; '),(10555,'for it was their fate to perish when their city should enclose the great horse of wood, wherein were sitting all the best of the Argives, bearing to the Trojans death and fate.'),(10556,' And he sang how the sons of the Achaeans  poured forth from the horse and, leaving their hollow ambush, sacked the city. '),(10557,'Of the others he sang how in divers ways they wasted the lofty city, but of Odysseus, how he went like Ares to the house of Deiphobus together with godlike Menelaus.'),(10558,' There it was, he said, that Odysseus braved the most terrible fight  and in the end conquered by the aid of great-hearted Athena.'),(10559,' \nThis song the famous minstrel sang.'),(10560,' But the heart of Odysseus was melted and tears wet his cheeks beneath his eyelids.'),(10561,' And as a woman wails and flings herself about her dear husband, who has fallen in front of his city and his people,  seeking toward off from his city and his children the pitiless day; '),(10562,'and as she beholds him dying and gasping for breath, she clings to him and shrieks aloud, '),(10563,'while the foe behind her smite her back and shoulders with their spears, and lead her away to captivity to bear toil and woe,'),(10564,' while with most pitiful grief her cheeks are wasted: '),(10565,'even so did Odysseus let fall pitiful tears from beneath his brows.'),(10566,' Now from all the rest he concealed the tears that he shed, but Alcinous alone marked him and took heed,  for he sat by him and heard him groaning heavily. '),(10567,'And straightway he spoke among the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar:'),(10568,'“Hear me, leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians, and let Demodocus now check his clear-toned lyre, '),(10569,' for in no wise to all alike does he give pleasure with this song.'),(10570,'Ever since we began to sup and the divine minstrel was moved to sing,  from that time yon stranger has never ceased from sorrowful lamentation; '),(10571,'surely, methinks, grief has encompassed his heart.'),(10572,' Nay, let the minstrel cease, that we may all make merry, hosts and guest alike, since it is better thus.'),(10573,' Lo, for the sake of the honored stranger all these things have been made ready,  his sending and the gifts of friendship which we give him of our love. '),(10574,' Dear as a brother is the stranger and the suppliant to a man whose wits have never so short a range.'),(10575,' Therefore do not thou longer hide with crafty thought whatever I shall ask thee;'),(10576,'to speak out plainly is the better course. '),(10577,'  \n  Tell me the name by which they were wont to call thee in thy home, even thy mother and thy father and other folk besides, thy townsmen and the dwellers round about.'),(10578,' For there is no one of all mankind who is nameless, be he base man or noble, when once he has been born, but parents bestow names on all when they give them birth.'),(10579,'  And tell me thy country,'),(10580,'thy people, and thy city, that our ships may convey thee thither, discerning the course by their wits.'),(10581,' For the Phaeacians have no pilots, nor steering-oars such as other ships have, '),(10582,'but their ships of themselves understand the thoughts and minds of men,  and they know the cities and rich fields of all peoples, and most swiftly do they cross over the gulf of the sea, hidden in mist and cloud, '),(10583,' nor ever have they fear of harm or ruin.'),(10584,'Yet this story I once heard thus told by my father  Nausithous, who was wont to say that Poseidon was wroth with us because we give safe convoy to all men.'),(10585,' He said that someday, as a well-built ship of the Phaeacians was returning from a convoy over the misty deep, Poseidon would smite her and would fling a great mountain about our city.'),(10586,'  So that old man spoke,'),(10587,' and these things the god will haply bring to pass, or will leave unfulfilled, as may be his good pleasure. '),(10588,'But come, now, tell me this and declare it truly: whither thou hast wandered and to what countries of men thou hast come; tell me of the people and of their well-built cities,  both of those who are cruel and wild and unjust, and of those who love strangers and fear the gods in their thoughts.'),(10589,' And tell me why thou dost weep and wail in spirit as thou hearest the doom of the Argive Danaans and of Ilios.'),(10590,' This the gods wrought, and spun the skein of ruin  for men, that there might be a song for those yet to be born. '),(10591,'Did some kinsman of thine fall before Ilios, some good, true man, thy daughter\'s husband or thy wife\'s father, such as are nearest to one after one\'s own kin and blood?'),(10592,' Or was it haply some comrade dear to thy heart,  some good, true man? '),(10593,'For no whit worse than a brother is a comrade who has an understanding heart.”'),(10594,' Then Odysseus, of many wiles, answered him, and said:'),(10595,' “Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, verily this is a good thing, to listen to a minstrel such as this man is, like unto the gods in voice.'),(10596,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 9.11'),(10597,' But thy heart is turned to ask of my grievous woes, that I may weep and groan the more.'),(10598,' What, then, shall I tell thee first, what last?'),(10599,' for woes full many have the heavenly gods given me.'),(10600,'First now will I tell my name, that ye, too, may know it, and that I hereafter, when I have escaped from the pitiless day of doom, may be your host, though I dwell in a home that is afar.'),(10601,' I am Odysseus, son of Laertes, who  am known among men for all manner of wiles, and my fame reaches unto heaven.'),(10602,'But I dwell in clear-seen Ithaca,'),(10603,' wherein is a mountain, Neriton, covered with waving forests, conspicuous from afar; '),(10604,'and round it lie many isles hard by one another, Dulichium, and Same, and wooded Zacynthus.'),(10605,'  Ithaca itself lies close in to the mainland the furthest toward the gloom, but the others lie apart toward the Dawn and the sun—a rugged isle, but a good nurse of young men; '),(10606,' and for myself no other thing can I see sweeter than one\'s own land.'),(10607,' Of a truth Calypso, the beautiful goddess, sought to keep me by her  in her hollow caves, yearning that I should be her husband; '),(10608,'and in like manner Circe would fain have held me back in her halls, the guileful lady of Aeaea, yearning that I should be her husband; '),(10609,' but they could never persuade the heart within my breast.'),(10610,'So true is it that naught is sweeter than a man\'s own land and his parents,  even though it be in a rich house that he dwells afar in a foreign land away from his parents.'),(10611,' But come, let me tell thee also of my woeful home-coming, which Zeus laid upon me as I came from Troy.'),(10612,'\n“From Ilios the wind bore me and brought me to the Cicones,  to Ismarus. '),(10613,'There I sacked the city and slew the men; '),(10614,'and from the city we took their wives and great store of treasure, and divided them among us, that so far as lay in me no man might go defrauded of an equal share.'),(10615,' Then verily I gave command that we should flee with swift foot, but the others in their great folly did not hearken.'),(10616,'  But there much wine was drunk, and many sheep they slew by the shore, and sleek kine of shambling gait. '),(10617,' Meanwhile the Cicones went and called to other Cicones who were their neighbors, at once more numerous and braver than they—men that dwelt inland and were skilled  at fighting with their foes from chariots, and, if need were, on foot.'),(10618,'So they came in the morning, as thick as leaves or flowers spring up in their season; '),(10619,'and then it was that an evil fate from Zeus beset us luckless men, that we might suffer woes full many.'),(10620,' They set their battle in array and fought by the swift ships,   and each side hurled at the other with bronze-tipped spears.'),(10621,'Now as long as it was morn and the sacred day was waxing, so long we held our ground and beat them off, though they were more than we.'),(10622,' But when the sun turned to the time for the unyoking of oxen, then the Cicones prevailed and routed the Achaeans,'),(10623,'  and six of my well-greaved comrades perished from each ship; '),(10624,'but the rest of us escaped death and fate.'),(10625,'“Thence we sailed on, grieved at heart, glad to have escaped from death, though we had lost our dear comrades; '),(10626,'nor did I let my curved ships pass on  till we had called thrice on each of those hapless comrades of ours who died on the plain, cut down by the Cicones.'),(10627,' But against our ships Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, roused the North Wind with a wondrous tempest, and hid with clouds the land and the sea alike, '),(10628,'and night rushed down from heaven.'),(10629,'  Then the ships were driven headlong, and their sails were torn to shreds by the violence of the wind.'),(10630,' So we lowered the sails and stowed them aboard, in fear of death, and rowed the ships hurriedly toward the land.'),(10631,' There for two nights and two days continuously  we lay, eating our hearts for weariness and sorrow.'),(10632,'But when now fair-tressed Dawn brought to its birth the third day, we set up the masts and hoisted the white sails, and took our seats, and the wind and the helmsmen steered the ships.'),(10633,' And now all unscathed should I have reached my native land, '),(10634,' but the wave and the current and the North Wind beat me back as I was rounding Malea, and drove me from my course past Cythera. '),(10635,' “Thence for nine days\' space I was borne by direful winds over the teeming deep; '),(10636,'but on the tenth we set foot on the land of the Lotus-eaters, who eat a flowery food.'),(10637,'  There we went on shore and drew water, and straightway my comrades took their meal by the swift ships.'),(10638,' But when we had tasted food and drink, I sent forth some of my comrades to go and learn who the men were, who here ate bread upon the earth;  two men I chose, sending with them a third as a herald. '),(10639,'So they went straightway and mingled with the Lotus-eaters,'),(10640,' and the Lotus-eaters did not plan death for my comrades, but gave them of the lotus to taste. '),(10641,'And whosoever of them ate of the honey-sweet fruit of the lotus,  had no longer any wish to bring back word or to return, but there they were fain to abide among the Lotus-eaters, feeding on the lotus, and forgetful of their homeward way.'),(10642,' These men, therefore, I brought back perforce to the ships, weeping, and dragged them beneath the benches and bound them fast in the hollow ships; '),(10643,' and I bade the rest of my trusty comrades to embark with speed on the swift ships, lest perchance anyone should eat of the lotus and forget his homeward way.'),(10644,' So they went on board straightway and sat down upon the benches, and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars.'),(10645,' “Thence we sailed on, grieved at heart, '),(10646,'and we came to the land of the Cyclopes, an overweening and lawless folk, who, trusting in the immortal gods, plant nothing with their hands nor plough; but all these things spring up for them without sowing or ploughing,  wheat, and barley, and vines, which bear the rich clusters of wine, and the rain of Zeus gives them increase.'),(10647,' Neither assemblies for council have they, nor appointed laws, but they dwell on the peaks of lofty mountains in hollow caves, and each one is lawgiver  to his children and his wives, and they reck nothing one of another.'),(10648,' \n“Now there is a level isle that stretches aslant outside the harbor, neither close to the shore of the land of the Cyclopes, nor yet far off, a wooded isle.'),(10649,' Therein live wild goats innumerable, '),(10650,'for the tread of men scares them not away,  nor are hunters wont to come thither, men who endure toils in the woodland as they course over the peaks of the mountains.'),(10651,' Neither with flocks is it held, nor with ploughed lands, but unsown and untilled all the days it knows naught of men, but feeds the bleating goats.'),(10652,'  For the Cyclopes have at hand no ships with vermilion cheeks, nor are there ship-wrights in their land who might build them well-benched ships, which should perform all their wants, passing to the cities of other folk, as men often cross the sea in ships to visit one another— '),(10653,' craftsmen, who would have made of this isle also a fair settlement.'),(10654,' For the isle is nowise poor, but would bear all things in season.'),(10655,'In it are meadows by the shores of the grey sea, well-watered meadows and soft,'),(10656,'where vines would never fail,'),(10657,'and in it level ploughland, '),(10658,'whence  they might reap from season to season harvests exceeding deep, so rich is the soil beneath;'),(10659,'and in it, too, is a harbor giving safe anchorage, where there is no need of moorings, either to throw out anchor-stones or to make fast stern cables, but one may beach one\'s ship and wait until the sailors\' minds bid them put out, and the breezes blow fair.'),(10660,'  Now at the head of the harbor a spring of bright water flows forth from beneath a cave, '),(10661,'and round about it poplars grow.'),(10662,'Thither we sailed in, and some god guided us through the murky night; for there was no light to see, '),(10663,' but a mist lay deep about the ships and the moon  showed no light from heaven, but was shut in by clouds.'),(10664,' Then no man\'s eyes beheld that island, nor did we see the long waves rolling on the beach, until we ran our well-benched ships on shore.'),(10665,' And when we had beached the ships we lowered all the sails  and ourselves went forth on the shore of the sea, '),(10666,'and there we fell asleep and waited for the bright Dawn.'),(10667,'“As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, we roamed throughout the isle marvelling at it;'),(10668,' and the nymphs, the daughters of Zeus who bears the aegis, roused  the mountain goats, that my comrades might have whereof to make their meal.'),(10669,'Straightway we took from the ships our curved bows and long javelins, and arrayed in three bands we fell to smiting;'),(10670,'  and the god soon gave us game to satisfy our hearts.'),(10671,' The ships that followed me were twelve, and to each  nine goats fell by lot, '),(10672,'but for me alone they chose out ten.'),(10673,' \n“So then all day long till set of sun we sat feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine.'),(10674,' For not yet was the red wine spent from out our ships, but some was still left; '),(10675,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 9.164-9.165'),(10676,'for abundant store  had we drawn in jars for each crew ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 164 to line 165'),(10677,'And we looked across to the land of the Cyclopes, who dwelt close at hand, and marked the smoke, and the voice of men, and of the sheep, and of the goats.'),(10678,' But when the sun set and darkness came on, then we lay down to rest on the shore of the sea.'),(10679,'  And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, I called my men together and spoke among them all:'),(10680,'\n“‘Remain here now, all the rest of you, my trusty comrades, '),(10681,'but I with my own ship and my own company will go and make trial of yonder men, to learn who they are,  whether they are cruel, and wild, and unjust, or whether they love strangers and fear the gods in their thoughts.\'\"'),(10682,'So saying, I went on board the ship and bade my comrades themselves to embark, and to loose the stern cables.'),(10683,' So they went on board straightway and sat down upon the benches,  and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars.  '),(10684,' But when we had reached the place, which lay close at hand, there on the land\'s edge hard by the sea we saw a high cave, roofed over with laurels, '),(10685,'and there many flocks, sheep and goats alike, were wont to sleep.'),(10686,' Round about it  a high court was built with stones set deep in the earth, and with tall pines and high-crested oaks.'),(10687,' There a monstrous man was wont to sleep, who shepherded his flocks alone and afar, '),(10688,'and mingled not with others, but lived apart, with his heart set on lawlessness.'),(10689,'  For he was fashioned a wondrous monster, and was not like a man that lives by bread, but like a wooded peak of lofty mountains, which stands out to view alone, apart from the rest. '),(10690,' \n“Then I bade the rest of my trusty comrades to remain there by the ship and to guard the ship,  but I chose twelve of the best of my comrades and went my way.'),(10691,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 9.196-9.200'),(10692,' With me I had a goat-skin of the dark, sweet wine, which Maro, son of Euanthes, had given me, the priest of Apollo, the god who used to watch over Ismarus. And he had given it me because we had protected him with his child and wife  out of reverence; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 196 to line 200'),(10693,'And he gave me splendid gifts: '),(10694,'of well-wrought gold he gave me seven talents, and he gave me a mixing-bowl all of silver; and besides these, wine, wherewith he filled twelve jars in all,  wine sweet and unmixed, a drink divine. '),(10695,'Not one of his slaves nor of the maids in his halls knew thereof, but himself and his dear wife, and one house-dame only. '),(10696,' And as often as they drank that honey-sweet red wine he would fill one cup and pour it into twenty measures of water,  and a smell would rise from the mixing-bowl marvellously sweet; '),(10697,'then verily would one not choose to hold back.'),(10698,' With this wine I filled and took with me a great skin, and also provision in a scrip;'),(10699,'for my proud spirit had a foreboding that presently a man would come to me clothed in great might,  a savage man that knew naught of justice or of law.'),(10700,'“Speedily we came to the cave, nor did we find him within, but he was pasturing his fat flocks in the fields.'),(10701,' So we entered the cave and gazed in wonder at all things there.'),(10702,' The crates were laden with cheeses, and the pens were crowded  with lambs and kids. '),(10703,' Each kind was penned separately: by themselves the firstlings, by themselves the later lambs, and by themselves again the newly weaned.'),(10704,' And with whey were swimming all the well-wrought vessels, the milk-pails and the bowls into which he milked. '),(10705,'Then my comrades spoke and besought me first of all  to take of the cheeses and depart, and thereafter speedily to drive to the swift ship the kids and lambs from out the pens, and to sail over the salt water.'),(10706,' But I did not listen to them—verily it would have been better far—to the end that I might see the man himself, and whether he would give me gifts of entertainment. '),(10707,' Yet, as it fell, his appearing was not to prove a joy to my comrades.'),(10708,' \n“Then we kindled a fire and offered sacrifice, and ourselves, too, took of the cheeses and ate, and thus we sat in the cave and waited for him until he came back, herding his flocks.'),(10709,' He bore a mighty weight of dry wood to serve him at supper time,  and flung it down with a crash inside the cave, '),(10710,'but we, seized with terror, shrank back into a recess of the cave.'),(10711,' But he drove his fat flocks into the wide cavern—all those that he milked; but the males—the rams and the goats—he left without in the deep court.'),(10712,'  Then he lifted on high and set in place the great door-stone, a mighty rock; '),(10713,' two and twenty stout four-wheeled wagons could not lift it from the ground, '),(10714,' such a towering mass of rock he set in the doorway.'),(10715,' Thereafter he sat down and milked the ewes and bleating goats  all in turn, and beneath each dam he placed her young. '),(10716,' Then presently he curdled half the white milk, and gathered it in wicker baskets and laid it away, and the other half he set in vessels that he might have it to take and drink, and that it might serve him for supper.'),(10717,'  But when he had busily performed his tasks, then he rekindled the fire, and caught sight of us, and asked:'),(10718,'Whence do ye sail over the watery ways? '),(10719,'Whence do ye sail over the watery ways? '),(10720,' Is it on some business, or do ye wander at random over the sea, even as pirates, who wander,  hazarding their lives and bringing evil to men of other lands?\"'),(10721,'So he spoke, and in our breasts our spirit was broken for terror of his deep voice and monstrous self;'),(10722,' yet even so I made answer and spoke to him, saying:'),(10723,'“‘We, thou must know, are from Troy, Achaeans, driven wandering  by all manner of winds over the great gulf of the sea. Seeking our home, we have come by another way, by other paths;'),(10724,'  so, I ween, Zeus was pleased to devise.'),(10725,' And we declare that we are the men of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, whose fame is now mightiest under heaven, '),(10726,'  so great a city did he sack, and slew many people; '),(10727,'but we on our part, thus visiting thee, have come as suppliants to thy knees, in the hope that thou wilt give us entertainment, or in other wise make some present, as is the due of strangers.'),(10728,' Nay, mightiest one, reverence the gods; '),(10729,'we are thy suppliants;  and Zeus is the avenger of suppliants and strangers—Zeus, the strangers\' god—who ever attends upon reverend strangers.\'\"'),(10730,'So I spoke, and he straightway made answer with pitiless heart:'),(10731,' ‘A fool art thou, stranger, or art come from afar, seeing that thou biddest me either to fear or to shun the gods.'),(10732,'  For the Cyclopes reck not of Zeus, who bears the aegis, nor of the blessed gods, since verily we are better far than they.'),(10733,' Nor would I, to shun the wrath of Zeus, spare either thee or thy comrades, unless my own heart should bid me.'),(10734,' But tell me where thou didst moor thy well-wrought ship on thy coming.  Was it haply at a remote part of the land, or close by? I fain would know.’'),(10735,' \n“So he spoke, tempting me, but he trapped me not because of my great cunning; and I made answer again in crafty words:'),(10736,'\n“‘My ship Poseidon, the earth-shaker, dashed to pieces, casting her upon the rocks at the border of your land;  for he brought her close to the headland,'),(10737,'and the wind drove her in from the sea. '),(10738,'But I, with these men here, escaped utter destruction.\"'),(10739,'So I spoke, but from his pitiless heart he made no answer, but sprang up and put forth his hands upon my comrades. Two of them at once he seized and dashed to the earth like puppies,'),(10740,'   and the brain flowed forth upon the ground and wetted the earth.'),(10741,' Then he cut them limb from limb and made ready his supper,'),(10742,' and ate them as a mountain-nurtured lion, leaving naught—ate the entrails, and the flesh, and the marrowy bones.'),(10743,' And we with wailing held up our hands to Zeus,  beholding his cruel deeds; and helplessness possessed our souls. '),(10744,'But when the Cyclops had filled his huge maw by eating human flesh and thereafter drinking pure milk, he lay down within the cave, stretched out among the sheep.'),(10745,'And I formed a plan in my great heart  to steal near him, and draw my sharp sword from beside my thigh and smite him in the breast, where the midriff holds the liver, feeling for the place with my hand.'),(10746,' But a second thought checked me, '),(10747,'for right there should we, too, have perished in utter ruin.'),(10748,'for right there should we, too, have perished in utter ruin. For we should not have been able  to thrust back with our hands from the high door the mighty stone which he had set there. '),(10749,' So then, with wailing, we waited for the bright Dawn.'),(10750,'\n“As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, he rekindled the fire and milked his goodly flocks all in turn, and beneath each dam placed her young.'),(10751,'  Then, when he had busily performed his tasks, again he seized two men at once and made ready his meal.'),(10752,' And when he had made his meal he drove his fat flocks forth from the cave, easily moving away the great door-stone;'),(10753,'and then he put it in place again, as one might set the lid upon a quiver.'),(10754,'  Then with loud whistling the Cyclops turned his fat flocks toward the mountain, '),(10755,'and I was left there, devising evil in the deep of my heart, if in any way I might take vengeance on him, and Athena grant me glory. '),(10756,' \n“Now this seemed to my mind the best plan.'),(10757,' There lay beside a sheep-pen a great club of the Cyclops,  a staff of green olive-wood, '),(10758,'which he had cut to carry with him when dry; '),(10759,'and as we looked at it we thought it as large as is the mast of a black ship of twenty oars, a merchantman, broad of beam, which crosses over the great gulf; '),(10760,'so huge it was in length and in breadth to look upon.'),(10761,'  To this I came, and cut off therefrom about a fathom\'s length and handed it to my comrades, bidding them dress it down; '),(10762,'and they made it smooth,'),(10763,'and I, standing by, sharpened it at the point, and then straightway took it and hardened it in the blazing fire.'),(10764,' Then I laid it carefully away, hiding it beneath the dung,  which lay in great heaps throughout the cave. '),(10765,'And I bade my comrades cast lots among them, which of them should have the hardihood with me to lift the stake and grind it into his eye when sweet sleep should come upon him.'),(10766,' And the lot fell upon those whom I myself would fain have chosen;  four they were, and I was numbered with them as the fifth.'),(10767,' At even then he came, herding his flocks of goodly fleece,'),(10768,' and straightway drove into the wide cave his fat flocks one and all, and left not one without in the deep court, either from some foreboding or because a god so bade him.'),(10769,'  Then he lifted on high and set in place the great door-stone, and sitting down he milked the ewes and bleating goats all in turn, and beneath each dam he placed her young.'),(10770,' But when he had busily performed his tasks, again he seized two men at once and made ready his supper.'),(10771,'  Then I drew near and spoke to the Cyclops, holding in my hands an ivy bowl of the dark wine:'),(10772,' “‘Cyclops, take and drink wine after thy meal of human flesh, that thou mayest know what manner of drink this is which our ship contained.'),(10773,'It was to thee that I was bringing it as a drink offering, in the hope that, touched with pity,  thou mightest send me on my way home; '),(10774,'but thou ragest in a way that is past all bearing.'),(10775,'Cruel man, how shall any one of all the multitudes of men ever come to thee again hereafter, seeing that thou hast wrought lawlessness?\"'),(10776,'So I spoke, and he took the cup and drained it, '),(10777,'and was wondrously pleased as he drank the sweet draught, and asked me for it again a second time:'),(10778,'\n  “‘Give it me again with a ready heart, and tell me thy name straightway, that I may give thee a stranger\'s gift whereat thou mayest be glad.'),(10779,' For among the Cyclopes the earth, the giver of grain, bears the rich clusters of wine, and the rain of Zeus gives them increase; '),(10780,'but this is a streamlet of ambrosia and nectar.'),(10781,' \n  “So he spoke, and again I handed him the flaming wine.'),(10782,'Thrice I brought and gave it him, and thrice he drained it in his folly.'),(10783,' But when the wine had stolen about the wits of the Cyclops, then I spoke to him with gentle words:'),(10784,'\n“‘Cyclops, thou askest me of my glorious name, and I  will tell it thee;'),(10785,' and do thou give me a stranger\'s gift, even as thou didst promise.'),(10786,'Noman is my name,'),(10787,'  Noman do they call me—my mother and my father, and all my comrades as well.\"'),(10788,'So I spoke, and he straightway answered me with pitiless heart:'),(10789,' ‘Noman will I eat last among his comrades,  and the others before him; '),(10790,'this shall be thy gift.’'),(10791,'“He spoke, and reeling fell upon his back, and lay there with his thick neck bent aslant, and sleep, that conquers all, laid hold on him.'),(10792,' And from his gullet came forth wine and bits of human flesh, '),(10793,'and he vomited in his drunken sleep.'),(10794,'  Then verily I thrust in the stake under the deep ashes until it should grow hot, '),(10795,' and heartened all my comrades with cheering words, that I might see no man flinch through fear.'),(10796,'But when presently that stake of olive-wood was about to catch fire, green though it was, and began to glow terribly,  then verily I drew nigh, bringing the stake from the fire, and my comrades stood round me '),(10797,'and a god breathed into us great courage.'),(10798,' They took the stake of olive-wood, sharp at the point, and thrust it into his eye, '),(10799,'while I, throwing my weight upon it from above, whirled it round, as when a man bores a ship\'s timber  with a drill, while those below keep it spinning with the thong, which they lay hold of by either end, and the drill runs around unceasingly.'),(10800,' Even so we took the fiery-pointed stake and whirled it around in his eye, and the blood flowed around the heated thing.'),(10801,' And his eyelids wholly and his brows round about did the flame singe  as the eyeball burned, and its roots crackled in the fire.'),(10802,' And as when a smith dips a great axe or an adze in cold water amid loud hissing to temper it—'),(10803,'for therefrom comes the strength of iron—even so did his eye hiss round the stake of olive-wood.'),(10804,'  Terribly then did he cry aloud, and the rock rang around; and we, seized with terror, shrank back, '),(10805,'while he wrenched from his eye the stake, all befouled with blood, '),(10806,' and flung it from him, wildly waving his arms. Then he called aloud to the Cyclopes, who  dwelt round about him in caves among the windy heights, '),(10807,'and they heard his cry and came thronging from every side, and standing around the cave asked him what ailed him:'),(10808,'\n“‘What so sore distress is thine, Polyphemus, that thou criest out thus through the immortal night, and makest us sleepless?'),(10809,'  Can it be that some mortal man is driving off thy flocks against thy will,'),(10810,' or slaying thee thyself by guile or by might?\"'),(10811,'Then from out the cave the mighty Polyphemus answered them:'),(10812,' ‘My friends, it is Noman that is slaying me by guile and not by force.\"'),(10813,' ‘My friends, it is Noman that is slaying me by guile and not by force.\"'),(10814,' \n“And they made answer and addressed him with winged words:'),(10815,'  ‘If, then, no man does violence to thee in thy loneliness, sickness which comes from great Zeus thou mayest in no wise escape. Nay, do thou pray to our father, the lord Poseidon.\"'),(10816,'So they spoke and went their way; and my heart laughed within me that my name and cunning device had so beguiled.'),(10817,'  But the Cyclops, groaning and travailing in anguish, groped with his hands and took away the stone from the door, and himself sat in the doorway with arms outstretched in the hope of catching anyone who sought to go forth with the sheep—'),(10818,'so witless, forsooth, he thought in his heart to find me.'),(10819,'  But I took counsel how all might be the very best, if I might haply find some way of escape from death for my comrades and for myself.'),(10820,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 9.422-9.423'),(10821,' And I wove all manner of wiles and counsel, as a man will in a matter of life and death; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 422 to line 423'),(10822,' And this seemed to my mind the best plan.'),(10823,'  Rams there were, well-fed and thick of fleece, fine beasts and large, with wool dark as the violet.'),(10824,' These I silently bound together with twisted withes on which the Cyclops, that monster with his heart set on lawlessness, was wont to sleep. Three at a time I took.'),(10825,' The one in the middle in each case bore a man,  and the other two went, one on either side, saving my comrades. '),(10826,' Thus every three sheep bore a man.'),(10827,' But as for me—there was a ram, far the best of all the flock; him I grasped by the back, and curled beneath his shaggy belly, '),(10828,'lay there face upwards  with steadfast heart, clinging fast with my hands to his wondrous fleece. '),(10829,'So then, with wailing, we waited for the bright dawn.'),(10830,'\n“As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, then the males of the flock hastened forth to pasture and the females bleated unmilked about the pens, '),(10831,' for their udders were bursting.'),(10832,'And their master, distressed with grievous pains, felt along the backs of all the sheep as they stood up before him,'),(10833,'  but in his folly he marked not this, that my men were bound beneath the breasts of his fleecy sheep.'),(10834,' Last of all the flock the ram went forth,  burdened with the weight of his fleece and my cunning self. '),(10835,'And mighty Polyphemus, as he felt along his back, spoke to him, saying:'),(10836,'\n“‘Good ram, why pray is it that thou goest forth thus through the cave the last of the flock?'),(10837,'Thou hast not heretofore been wont to lag behind the sheep, but wast ever far the first to feed on the tender bloom of the grass,  moving with long strides, and ever the first didst reach the streams of the river, and the first didst long to return to the fold at evening.'),(10838,' But now thou art last of all.'),(10839,'Surely thou art sorrowing for the eye of thy master, which an evil man blinded along with his miserable fellows, when he had overpowered my wits with wine,  even Noman, who, I tell thee, has not yet escaped destruction.'),(10840,' If only thou couldst feel as I do, and couldst get thee power of speech to tell me where he skulks away from my wrath, '),(10841,'then should his brains be dashed on the ground here and there throughout the cave, when I had smitten him, and my heart  should be lightened of the woes which good-for-naught Noman has brought me.’'),(10842,' \n“So saying, he sent the ram forth from him.'),(10843,' And when we had gone a little way from the cave and the court, I first loosed myself from under the ram and set my comrades free. '),(10844,' Speedily then we drove off those long-shanked sheep, rich with fat,  turning full often to look about until we came to the ship.'),(10845,' And welcome to our dear comrades was the sight of us who had escaped death, but for the others they wept and wailed; '),(10846,' yet I would not suffer them to weep, but with a frown forbade each man. Rather I bade them  to fling on board with speed the many sheep of goodly fleece, and sail over the salt water. '),(10847,'So they went on board straightway and sat down upon the benches, and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars.'),(10848,' But when I was as far away as a man\'s voice carries when he shouts, then I spoke to the Cyclops with mocking words:'),(10849,'\n  “‘Cyclops, that man, it seems, was no weakling, whose comrades thou wast minded to devour by brutal strength in thy hollow cave.'),(10850,' Full surely were thy evil deeds to fall on thine own head, thou cruel wretch, who didst not shrink from eating thy guests in thine own house.'),(10851,' Therefore has Zeus taken vengeance on thee, and the other gods.’'),(10852,'  “So I spoke, and he waxed the more wroth at heart, and broke off the peak of a high mountain and hurled it at us, and cast it in front of the dark-prowed ship. And the sea surged beneath the stone as it fell, '),(10853,' and the backward flow, like a flood from the deep, bore the ship swiftly landwards and drove it upon the shore.'),(10854,' But I seized a long pole in my hands and shoved the ship off and along the shore,  and with a nod of my head I roused my comrades, and bade them fall to their oars that we might escape out of our evil plight.'),(10855,' And they bent to their oars and rowed. '),(10856,' But when, as we fared over the sea, we were twice as far distant, then was I fain to call to the Cyclops, '),(10857,'though round about me my comrades, one after another, sought to check me with gentle words:'),(10858,'\n“‘Reckless one, why wilt thou provoke to wrath a savage man, '),(10859,' who but now hurled his missile into the deep and drove our ship back to the land, and verily we thought that we had perished there?'),(10860,' And had he heard one of us uttering a sound or speaking, he would have hurled a jagged rock and crushed our heads and the timbers of our ship, '),(10861,'so mightily does he throw.\"'),(10862,' \n  “So they spoke, but they could not persuade my great-hearted spirit; and I answered him again with angry heart:'),(10863,'\n“‘Cyclops, if any one of mortal men shall ask thee about the shameful blinding of thine eye, say that Odysseus, the sacker of cities, blinded it,  even the son of Laertes, whose home is in Ithaca.’'),(10864,'\n“So I spoke, and he groaned and said in answer:'),(10865,'‘Lo now, verily a prophecy uttered long ago is come upon me.'),(10866,' There lived here a soothsayer, a good man and tall, Telemus, son of Eurymus, who excelled all men in soothsaying,  and grew old as a seer among the Cyclopes.'),(10867,' He told me that all these things should be brought to pass in days to come, that by the hands of Odysseus I should lose my sight.'),(10868,' But I ever looked for some tall and comely man to come hither, clothed in great might, '),(10869,' but now one that is puny, a man of naught and a weakling, has blinded me of my eye when he had overpowered me with wine.'),(10870,' Yet come hither, Odysseus, that I may set before thee gifts of entertainment, and may speed thy sending hence, that the glorious Earth-shaker may grant it thee.'),(10871,' For I am his son, and he declares himself my father; '),(10872,'  and he himself will heal me, if it be his good pleasure, but none other either of the blessed gods or of mortal men.’'),(10873,' \n“So he spoke in prayer, and the dark-haired god heard him.'),(10874,' But the Cyclops lifted on high again a far greater stone, and swung and hurled it, putting into the throw measureless strength. He cast it  a little behind the dark-prowed ship, and barely missed the end of the steering-oar. '),(10875,'And the sea surged beneath the stone as it fell, '),(10876,' and the wave bore the ship onward and drove it to the shore.'),(10877,'\n“Now when we had come to the island, where our other well-benched ships lay all together, and round about them our comrades,  ever expecting us, sat weeping, then, on coming thither, we beached our ship on the sands, and ourselves went forth upon the shore of the sea.'),(10878,' Then we took from out the hollow ship the flocks of the Cyclops, and divided them, that so far as in me lay no man might go defrauded of an equal share.'),(10879,'  But the ram my well-greaved comrades gave to me alone, when the flocks were divided, as a gift apart; '),(10880,'and on the shore I sacrificed him to Zeus, son of Cronos, god of the dark clouds, who is lord of all, and burned the thigh-pieces.'),(10881,' Howbeit he heeded not my sacrifice, but was planning how all  my well-benched ships might perish and my trusty comrades.'),(10882,'“So, then, all day long till set of sun we sat feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine; '),(10883,'but when the sun set and darkness came on, then we lay down to rest on the shore of the sea.'),(10884,'  And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, I roused my comrades, and bade them themselves to embark and to loose the stern cables.'),(10885,' So they went on board straightway and sat down upon the benches, and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars.'),(10886,'\n  “Thence we sailed on, grieved at heart, glad to have escaped death, though we had lost our dear comrades.'),(10887,' “Then to the Aeolian isle we came, '),(10888,' where dwelt Aeolus, son of Hippotas, dear to the immortal gods, in a floating island, '),(10889,'and all around it is a wall of unbreakable bronze, and the cliff runs up sheer.'),(10890,'  Twelve children of his, too, there are in the halls, six daughters and six sturdy sons, '),(10891,' and he gave his daughters to his sons to wife. '),(10892,' These, then, feast continually by their dear father and good mother, and before them lies boundless good cheer.  And the house, filled with the savour of feasting, resounds all about even in the outer court by day,'),(10893,' and by night again they sleep beside their chaste wives on blankets and on corded bedsteads.'),(10894,' To their city, then, and fair palace did we come, '),(10895,'and for a full month he made me welcome and questioned me about each thing,  about Ilios, and the ships of the Argives, and the return of the Achaeans. '),(10896,'And I told him all the tale in due order.'),(10897,' But when I, on my part, asked him that I might depart and bade him send me on my way, he, too, denied me nothing, but furthered my sending.'),(10898,' He gave me a wallet, made of the hide of an ox nine years old, which he flayed,  and therein he bound the paths of the blustering winds; '),(10899,'for the son of Cronos had made him keeper of the winds, both to still and to rouse whatever one he will.'),(10900,' And in my hollow ship he bound it fast with a bright cord of silver, that not a breath might escape, were it never so slight.'),(10901,'  But for my furtherance he sent forth the breath of the West Wind to blow, that it might bear on their way both ships and men.'),(10902,' Yet this he was not to bring to pass,'),(10903,' for we were lost through our own folly.'),(10904,'\n“For nine days we sailed, night and day alike, and now on the tenth our native land came in sight,  and lo, we were so near that we saw men tending the beacon fires. '),(10905,' Then upon me came sweet sleep in my weariness, for I had ever kept in hand the sheet of the ship, and had yielded it to none other of my comrades, that we might the sooner come to our native land. '),(10906,' But my comrades meanwhile began to speak one to another,  and said that I was bringing home for myself gold and silver as gifts from Aeolus, the great-hearted son of Hippotas.'),(10907,'And thus would one speak, with a glance at his neighbor:'),(10908,' \n“‘Out on it, how beloved and honored this man is by all men, to whose city and land soever he comes!'),(10909,'  Much goodly treasure is he carrying with him from the land of Troy from out the spoil, while we, who have accomplished the same journey as he, are returning, bearing with us empty hands.'),(10910,' And now Aeolus has given him these gifts, granting them freely of his love.'),(10911,' Nay, come, let us quickly see what is here,   what store of gold and silver is in the wallet.\"'),(10912,' \nSo they spoke, and the evil counsel of my comrades prevailed.'),(10913,' They loosed the wallet, and all the winds leapt forth, '),(10914,'and swiftly the storm-wind seized them and bore them weeping out to sea away from their native land; '),(10915,'but as for me,  I awoke, and pondered in my goodly heart whether I should fling myself from the ship and perish in the sea, or endure in silence and still remain among the living.'),(10916,' However, I endured and abode, and covering my head lay down in the ship.'),(10917,' But the ships were borne by an evil blast of wind  back to the Aeolian isle; and my comrades groaned.'),(10918,'\n“There we went ashore and drew water, and straightway my comrades took their meal by the swift ships.'),(10919,' But when we had tasted of food and drink, I took with me a herald and one companion  and went to the glorious palace of Aeolus, '),(10920,' and I found him feasting beside his wife and his children.'),(10921,' So we entered the house and sat down by the doorposts on the threshold, '),(10922,'and they were amazed at heart, and questioned us:'),(10923,'What cruel god assailed thee?'),(10924,'What cruel god assailed thee?'),(10925,'  Surely we sent thee forth with kindly care, that thou mightest reach thy native land and thy home, and whatever place thou wouldest.\"'),(10926,'So said they, but I with a sorrowing heart spoke among them and said:'),(10927,' ‘Bane did my evil comrades work me, and therewith sleep accursed; '),(10928,'for with you is the power.’'),(10929,'for with you is the power.’'),(10930,'  “So I spoke and addressed them with gentle words, but they were silent.'),(10931,' Then their father answered and said:'),(10932,'\n“‘Begone from our island with speed, thou vilest of all that live.'),(10933,' In no wise may I help or send upon his way that man who is hated of the blessed gods.  '),(10934,' Begone, for thou comest hither as one hated of the immortals.’'),(10935,'“So saying, he sent me forth from the house, groaning heavily. '),(10936,' Thence we sailed on, grieved at heart.'),(10937,'And worn was the spirit of the men by the grievous rowing, because of our own folly, for no longer appeared any breeze to bear us on our way.'),(10938,'  So for six days we sailed, night and day alike, and on the seventh we came to the lofty citadel of Lamus, even to Telepylus of the Laestrygonians, where herdsman calls to herdsman as he drives in his flock, and the other answers as he drives his forth.'),(10939,' There a man who never slept could have earned a double wage,  one by herding cattle, and one by pasturing white sheep; '),(10940,'for the out goings of the night and of the day are close together.  '),(10941,' \nWhen we had come thither into the goodly harbor, about which on both sides a sheer cliff runs continuously, and projecting headlands opposite to one another  stretch out at the mouth, and the entrance is narrow, then all the rest steered their curved ships in, '),(10942,'and the ships were moored within the hollow harbor close together; '),(10943,'for therein no wave ever swelled, great or small, but all about was a bright calm.'),(10944,'  But I alone moored my black ship outside, there on the border of the land, making the cables fast to the rock.'),(10945,' Then I climbed to a rugged height, a point of outlook, and there took my stand; '),(10946,'from thence no works of oxen or of men appeared; smoke alone we saw springing up from the land.'),(10947,'  So then I sent forth some of my comrades to go and learn who the men were, who here ate bread upon the earth—two men I chose, and sent with them a third as a herald. '),(10948,' Now when they had gone ashore, they went along a smooth road by which wagons were wont to bring wood down to the city from the high mountains. And before the city they met a maiden drawing water, the goodly daughter of Laestrygonian Antiphates, '),(10949,' who had come down to the fair-flowing spring Artacia, '),(10950,'from whence they were wont to bear water to the town.'),(10951,'So they came up to her and spoke to her,  and asked her who was king of this folk, and who they were of whom he was lord. '),(10952,'And she showed them forth with the high-roofed house of her father. '),(10953,' Now when they had entered the glorious house, they found there his wife, huge as the peak of a mountain, and they were aghast at her.'),(10954,'At once she called from the place of assembly the glorious Antiphates,  her husband, and he devised for them woeful destruction. '),(10955,'Straightway he seized one of my comrades and made ready his meal, '),(10956,' but the other two sprang up and came in flight to the ships.'),(10957,'Then he raised a cry throughout the city, '),(10958,'and as they heard it the mighty Laestrygonians came thronging from all sides,  a host past counting, not like men but like the Giants.'),(10959,' They hurled at us from the cliffs with rocks huge as a man could lift,'),(10960,' and at once there rose throughout the ships a dreadful din, alike from men that were dying and from ships that were being crushed.'),(10961,' And spearing them like fishes they bore them home, a loathly meal.'),(10962,'  Now while they were slaying those within the deep harbor, I meanwhile drew my sharp sword from beside my thigh, and cut therewith the cables of my dark-prowed ship; '),(10963,'and quickly calling to my comrades bade them fall to their oars, that we might escape from out our evil plight.'),(10964,'  And they all tossed the sea with their oar-blades in fear of death,'),(10965,' and joyfully seaward, away from the beetling cliffs, my ship sped on;'),(10966,'but all those other ships were lost together there. '),(10967,' \n“Thence we sailed on, grieved at heart, glad to have escaped death, though we had lost our dear comrades; '),(10968,' and we came to the isle of Aeaea, '),(10969,' where dwelt fair-tressed Circe, a dread goddess of human speech, own sister to Aeetes of baneful mind; '),(10970,'and both are sprung from Helius, who gives light to mortals, and from Perse, their mother, whom Oceanus begot.'),(10971,'  Here we put in to shore with our ship in silence, into a harbor where ships may lie, and some god guided us.'),(10972,' Then we disembarked, and lay there for two days and two nights, eating our hearts for weariness and sorrow. '),(10973,' But when fair-tressed Dawn brought to its birth the third day,  then I took my spear and my sharp sword, and quickly went up from the ship to a place of wide prospect, in the hope that I might see the works of men, and hear their voice.'),(10974,' So I climbed to a rugged height, a place of outlook, and there took my stand, and I saw smoke rising from the broad-wayed earth  in the halls of Circe, through the thick brush and the wood. '),(10975,' And I debated in mind and heart, whether I should go and make search, when I had seen the flaming smoke.'),(10976,' And as I pondered, this seemed to me to be the better way, to go first to the swift ship and the shore of the sea,  and give my comrades their meal, and send them forth to make search. '),(10977,' But when, as I went, I was near to the curved ship, then some god took pity on me in my loneliness, and sent a great, high-horned stag into my very path.'),(10978,' He was coming down to the river from his pasture in the wood  to drink, '),(10979,'for the might of the sun oppressed him; '),(10980,'and as he came out I struck him on the spine in the middle of the back, '),(10981,'and the bronze spear passed right through him, and down he fell in the dust with a moan, and his spirit flew from him.'),(10982,' Then I planted my foot upon him,  and drew the bronze spear forth from the wound,'),(10983,'and left it there to lie on the ground. '),(10984,' But for myself, I plucked twigs and osiers, and weaving a rope as it were a fathom in length, well twisted from end to end, I bound together the feet of the monstrous beast, and went my way to the black ship, bearing him across my back and  leaning on my spear, since in no wise could I hold him on my shoulder with one hand, '),(10985,' for he was a very mighty beast.'),(10986,' Down I flung him before the ship, and heartened my comrades with gentle words, coming up to each man in turn:'),(10987,'\n“‘Friends, not yet shall we go down  to the house of Hades, despite our sorrows, before the day of fate comes upon us. '),(10988,'Nay, come, while there is yet food and drink in our swift ship, let us bethink us of food, that we pine not with hunger.\''),(10989,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 10.177'),(10990,' \n“So I spoke, and they quickly hearkened to my words. From their faces they drew their cloaks,  and marvelled at the stag on the shore of the unresting sea, '),(10991,'for he was a very mighty beast.'),(10992,'But when they had satisfied their eyes with gazing, they washed their hands, and made ready a glorious feast.'),(10993,' So then all day long till set of sun we sat feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine.'),(10994,'  But when the sun set and darkness came on, then we lay down to rest on the shore of the sea.'),(10995,' And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, I called my men together, and spoke among them all:'),(10996,'\n“‘Hearken to my words, comrades, for all your evil plight.'),(10997,'  My friends, we know not where the darkness is or where the dawn, neither where the sun, who give light to mortals, goes beneath the earth, nor where he rises;'),(10998,' but let us straightway take thought if any device be still left us.'),(10999,' As for me I think not that there is.'),(11000,' For I climbed to a rugged point of outlook, and beheld  the island, about which is set as a crown the boundless deep.'),(11001,' The isle itself lies low, '),(11002,'and in the midst of it my eyes saw smoke through the thick brush and the wood.\"'),(11003,'So I spoke, and their spirit was broken within them, as they remembered the deeds of the Laestrygonian, Antiphates,  and the violence of the great-hearted Cyclops, the man-eater.'),(11004,'And they wailed aloud, and shed big tears.'),(11005,'  But no good came of their mourning.'),(11006,'\n“Then I told off in two bands all my well-greaved comrades, and appointed a leader for each band.'),(11007,' Of the one I took command, and of the other godlike Eurylochus.'),(11008,' Quickly then we shook lots in a brazen helmet,'),(11009,'  and out leapt the lot of great-hearted Eurylochus. '),(11010,' So he set out, and with him went two-and-twenty comrades, all weeping; '),(11011,'and they left us behind, lamenting.'),(11012,'  Within the forest glades they found the house of Circe, built of polished stone in a place of wide outlook, '),(11013,' and round about it were mountain wolves and lions, whom Circe herself had bewitched; for she gave them evil drugs.'),(11014,' Yet these beasts did not rush upon my men,  but pranced about them fawningly, wagging their long tails.'),(11015,' And as when hounds fawn around their master as he comes from a feast, for he ever brings them bits to soothe their temper, so about them fawned the stout-clawed wolves and lions;'),(11016,' but they were seized with fear, as they saw the dread monsters.'),(11017,'  So they stood in the gateway of the fair-tressed goddess, and within they heard Circe singing with sweet voice, as she went to and fro before a great imperishable web, such as is the handiwork of goddesses, finely-woven and beautiful, and glorious.'),(11018,' Then among them spoke Polites, a leader of men,  dearest to me of my comrades, and trustiest:'),(11019,'“‘Friends, within someone goes to and fro before a great web, singing sweetly, so that all the floor echoes; some goddess it is, or some woman. '),(11020,'Come, let us quickly call to her.'),(11021,'“So he spoke, and they cried aloud, and called to her. '),(11022,' And she straightway came forth and opened the bright doors, and bade them in; '),(11023,' and all went with her in their folly.'),(11024,'Only Eurylochus remained behind, for he suspected that there was a snare.'),(11025,' She brought them in and made them sit on chairs and seats, and made for them a potion of cheese and barley meal and yellow honey  with Pramnian wine; '),(11026,'but in the food she mixed baneful drugs, that they might utterly forget their native land.'),(11027,' Now when she had given them the potion, and they had drunk it off, then she presently smote them with her wand, and penned them in the sties.'),(11028,' And they had the heads, and voice, and bristles,  and shape of swine, but their minds remained unchanged even as before. '),(11029,'So they were penned there weeping, and before them Circe flung mast and acorns, and the fruit of the cornel tree, to eat, such things as wallowing swine are wont to feed upon.'),(11030,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 10.244-10.245'),(11031,'\n“But Eurylochus came back straightway to the swift, black ship,  to bring tiding of his comrades and their shameful doom. ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 244 to line 245'),(11032,'and his eyes were filled with tears, and his spirit was set on lamentation.'),(11033,' But when we questioned him in amazement,  then he told the fate of the others, his comrades.'),(11034,'“‘We went through the thickets, as thou badest, noble Odysseus.'),(11035,' We found in the forest glades a fair palace, built of polished stones, in a place of wide outlook.'),(11036,' There someone was going to and fro before a great web, and singing with clear voice,  some goddess or some woman, '),(11037,' and they cried aloud, and called to her.'),(11038,'And she came forth straightway, and opened the bright doors, and bade them in;'),(11039,' and they all went with her in their folly.'),(11040,'  But I remained behind, for I suspected that there was a snare.'),(11041,'Then they all vanished together, nor did one of them  appear again, '),(11042,' though I sat long and watched.’'),(11043,' \n“So he spoke, and I cast my silver-studded sword about my shoulders, a great sword of bronze, and slung my bow about me, '),(11044,'and bade him lead me back by the self-same road.'),(11045,' But he clasped me with both hands, and be sought me by my knees,  and with wailing he spoke to me winged words:'),(11046,'“‘Lead me not thither against my will, O thou fostered of Zeus, but leave me here.'),(11047,' For I know that thou wilt neither come back thyself, nor bring anyone of thy comrades.'),(11048,' Nay, with these that are here let us flee with all speed, '),(11049,'for still we may haply escape the evil day.'),(11050,'  “So he spoke, but I answered him, and said:'),(11051,'‘Eurylochus, do thou stay here in this place, eating and drinking by the hollow, black ship; '),(11052,' but I will go, for strong necessity is laid upon me.\''),(11053,'\n“So saying, I went up from the ship and the sea.'),(11054,'  But when, as I went through the sacred glades, I was about to come to the great house of the sorceress, Circe, then Hermes, of the golden wand, met me as I went toward the house, in the likeness of a young man with the first down upon his lip, in whom the charm of youth is fairest.'),(11055,'  He clasped my hand, and spoke, and addressed me:'),(11056,'\n“‘Whither now again, hapless man, dost thou go alone through the hills, knowing naught of the country?'),(11057,' Lo, thy comrades yonder in the house of Circe are penned like swine in close-barred sties. '),(11058,' And art thou come to release them?'),(11059,'Nay, I tell thee, thou shalt not  thyself return, but shalt remain there with the others. '),(11060,'But come, I will free thee from harm, and save thee.'),(11061,' Here, take this potent herb, and go to the house of Circe, and it shall ward off from thy head the evil day.'),(11062,' And I will tell thee all the baneful wiles of Circe.'),(11063,'  She will mix thee a potion, and cast drugs into the food;'),(11064,' but even so she shall not be able to bewitch thee, '),(11065,' for the potent herb that I shall give thee will not suffer it. And I will tell thee all.'),(11066,' When Circe shall smite thee with her long wand, then do thou draw thy sharp sword from beside thy thigh,  and rush upon Circe, as though thou wouldst slay her. '),(11067,' And she will be seized with fear, and will bid thee lie with her.'),(11068,' Then do not thou thereafter refuse the couch of the goddess, that she may set free thy comrades, and give entertainment to thee. '),(11069,'But bid her swear a great oath by the blessed gods,  that she will not plot against thee any fresh mischief to thy hurt, lest when she has thee stripped she may render thee a weakling and unmanned.’ '),(11070,' \n“So saying, Argeiphontes gave me the herb, drawing it from the ground, and showed me its nature.'),(11071,' At the root it was black, but its flower was like milk.'),(11072,'  Moly the gods call it,'),(11073,' and it is hard for mortal men to dig; but with the gods all things are possible.'),(11074,' Hermes then departed to high Olympus through the wooded isle, and I went my way to the house of Circe, and many things did my heart darkly ponder as I went.'),(11075,'  So I stood at the gates of the fair-tressed goddess.'),(11076,' There I stood and called, and the goddess heard my voice.'),(11077,' Straightway then she came forth, and opened the bright doors, and bade me in; '),(11078,' and I went with her, my heart sore troubled.'),(11079,'She brought me in and made me sit on a silver-studded chair,  a beautiful chair, richly wrought, '),(11080,'and beneath was a foot-stool for the feet. '),(11081,'And she prepared me a potion in a golden cup, that I might drink, and put therein a drug, with evil purpose in her heart.'),(11082,' But when she had given it me, and I had drunk it off, yet was not bewitched, she smote me with her wand, and spoke, and addressed me:'),(11083,'  ‘Begone now to the sty, and lie with the rest of thy comrades.’');
INSERT INTO `Sentence_Translation` VALUES (11084,'“So she spoke, but I, drawing my sharp sword from beside my thigh, rushed upon Circe, as though I would slay her.'),(11085,' But she, with a loud cry, ran beneath, and clasped my knees, and with wailing she spoke to me winged words:'),(11086,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(11087,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(11088,'Amazement holds me that thou hast drunk this charm and wast in no wise bewitched.'),(11089,'  For no man else soever hath withstood this charm, when once he has drunk it, and it has passed the barrier of his teeth.'),(11090,' Nay, but the mind in thy breast is one not to be beguiled.'),(11091,'  Surely thou art Odysseus, the man of ready device, who Argeiphontes of the golden wand ever said to me would come hither on his way home from Troy with his swift, black ship.'),(11092,' Nay, come, put up thy sword in its sheath, and let us two then go up into my bed, that couched together  in love we may put trust in each other.’'),(11093,'“So she spoke, but I answered her, and said:'),(11094,'‘Circe, how canst thou bid me be gentle to thee, who hast turned my comrades into swine in thy halls, and now keepest me here, and with guileful purpose biddest me  go to thy chamber, and go up into thy bed, that when thou hast me stripped thou mayest render me a weakling and unmanned?'),(11095,' Nay, verily, it is not I that shall be fain to go up into thy bed, unless thou, goddess, wilt consent to swear a mighty oath that thou wilt not plot against me any fresh mischief to my hurt.’ '),(11096,' \n  “So I spoke, and she straightway swore the oath to do me no harm, as I bade her. '),(11097,'But when she had sworn, and made an end of the oath, then I went up to the beautiful bed of Circe.'),(11098,'\n“But her handmaids meanwhile were busied in the halls, four maidens who are her serving-women in the house.'),(11099,'  Children are they of the springs and groves, and of the sacred rivers that flow forth to the sea, '),(11100,'and of them one threw upon chairs fair rugs of purple above, and spread beneath them a linen cloth;'),(11101,'another drew up before the chairs tables  of silver, and set upon them golden baskets; '),(11102,' and the third mixed sweet, honey-hearted wine in a bowl of silver, and served out golden cups; '),(11103,' and the fourth brought water, and kindled a great fire beneath a large cauldron, '),(11104,'and the water grew warm.'),(11105,'  But when the water boiled in the bright bronze, she set me in a bath, and bathed me with water from out the great cauldron, mixing it to my liking, and pouring it over my head and shoulders, till she took from my limbs soul-consuming weariness. '),(11106,'But when she had bathed me, and anointed me richly with oil,  and had cast about me a fair cloak and a tunic, she brought me into the hall, and made me sit upon a silver-studded chair—a beautiful chair, richly wrought, and beneath was a foot-stool for the feet.'),(11107,' Then a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin  for me to wash, '),(11108,' and beside me drew up a polished table.'),(11109,'And the grave housewife brought and set before me bread, and therewith meats in abundance, granting freely of her store.'),(11110,' Then she bade me eat,'),(11111,'  but my heart inclined not thereto. Rather, I sat with other thoughts, and my spirit boded ill.'),(11112,'\n  “Now when Circe noted that I sat thus, and did not put forth my hands to the food, but was burdened with sore grief, she came close to me, and spoke winged words:'),(11113,'\n“‘Why, Odysseus, dost thou sit thus like one that is dumb, eating thy heart, and dost not touch food or drink?'),(11114,'  Dost thou haply forbode some other guile?'),(11115,'Nay, thou needest in no wise fear,'),(11116,'  for already have I sworn a mighty oath to do thee no harm.\''),(11117,'“So she spoke, but I answered her, and said:'),(11118,'‘Circe, what 