ed about me weeping, '),(11137,' and it seemed to their hearts as though they had got to their native land, and the very city of rugged Ithaca, where they were bred and born.'),(11138,' And with wailing they spoke to me winged words:'),(11139,'\n“‘At thy return, O thou fostered of Zeus, we are as glad  as though we had returned to Ithaca, our native land.'),(11140,' But come, tell the fate of the others, our comrades.'),(11141,'“So they spoke, and I answered them with gentle words: '),(11142,'‘First of all let us draw the ship up on the land, and store our goods and all the tackling in caves.'),(11143,'  Then haste you, one and all, to go with me that you may see your comrades in the sacred halls of Circe, drinking and eating, '),(11144,'for they have unfailing store.’ '),(11145,' \n“So I spoke, and they quickly hearkened to my words.'),(11146,' Eurylochus alone sought to hold back all my comrades, '),(11147,'   and he spoke, and addressed them with winged words:'),(11148,' Why are you so enamoured of these woes,'),(11149,' Why are you so enamoured of these woes,'),(11150,'as to go down to the house of Circe, who will change us all to swine, or wolves, or lions, that so we may guard her great house perforce?  Even so did the Cyclops, when our comrades went to his fold, and with them went this reckless Odysseus.'),(11151,' For it was through this man\'s folly that they too perished.\''),(11152,'“So he spoke, and I pondered in heart, whether to draw my long sword from beside my stout thigh,  and therewith strike off his head, and bring it to the ground, near kinsman of mine by marriage though he was; '),(11153,'but my comrades one after another sought to check me with gentle words:'),(11154,'“‘O thou sprung from Zeus, as for this man, we will leave him, if thou so biddest, to abide here by the ship, and to guard the ship,'),(11155,' but as for us, do thou lead us to the sacred house of Circe.’'),(11156,'“So saying, they went up from the ship and the sea.'),(11157,' Nor was Eurylochus left beside the hollow ship, but he went with us, '),(11158,'for he feared my dread reproof.'),(11159,'“Meanwhile in her halls Circe  bathed the rest of my comrades with kindly care, and anointed them richly with oil, and cast about them fleecy cloaks and tunics; '),(11160,' and we found them all feasting bountifully in the halls.'),(11161,'But when they saw and recognized one another, face to face, they wept and wailed, and the house rang around.'),(11162,' Then the beautiful goddess drew near me, and said:'),(11163,'“‘No longer now do ye rouse this plenteous lamenting.'),(11164,' Of myself I know both all the woes you have suffered on the teeming deep, and all the wrong that cruel men have done you on the land.'),(11165,'  Nay, come, eat food and drink wine, until you once more get spirit in your breasts such as when at the first you left your native land of rugged Ithaca; '),(11166,' but now ye are withered and spiritless, ever thinking of your weary wanderings, nor are your  hearts ever joyful, for verily ye have suffered much.’'),(11167,'“So she spoke, and our proud hearts consented. '),(11168,' So there day after day for a full year we abode, feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine.'),(11169,'But when a year was gone and the seasons turned,  as the months waned and the long days were brought in their course, then my trusty comrades called me forth, and said:'),(11170,'“‘Strange man, bethink thee now at last of thy native land, if it is fated for thee to be saved, and to reach thy high-roofed house and thy native land.'),(11171,' \n  “So they spoke, and my proud heart consented. '),(11172,'So then all day long till set of sun we sat feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine.'),(11173,' But when the sun set and darkness came on, they lay down to sleep throughout the shadowy halls, '),(11174,'but I went up to the beautiful bed of Circe, and besought her by her knees; and the goddess heard my voice, '),(11175,'and I spoke, and addressed her with winged words:'),(11176,'\n“‘Circe, fulfil for me the promise which thou gavest to send me home; '),(11177,'for my spirit is now eager to be gone,  and the spirit of my comrades, who make my heart to pine, as they sit about me mourning, whensoever thou haply art not at hand.\''),(11178,'“So I spoke, and the beautiful goddess straightway made answer:'),(11179,' ‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, abide ye now no longer in my house against your will; '),(11180,' but you must first complete another journey, and come to the house of Hades and dread Persephone, to seek soothsaying of the spirit of Theban Teiresias, the blind seer, whose mind abides steadfast.'),(11181,' To him even in death Persephone has granted reason,  that he alone should have understanding; but the others flit about as shadows.'),(11182,'“So she spoke, and my spirit was broken within me,'),(11183,' and I wept as I sat on the bed, nor had my heart any longer desire to live and behold the light of the sun. '),(11184,'But when I had my fill of weeping and writhing,  then I made answer, and addressed her, saying:'),(11185,'“‘O Circe, who will guide us on this journey?'),(11186,' To Hades no man ever yet went in a black ship.’ '),(11187,' \n“So I spoke, and the beautiful goddess straightway made answer: '),(11188,'‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices,  let there be in thy mind no concern for a pilot to guide thy ship, but set up thy mast, and spread the white sail, and sit thee down; '),(11189,' and the breath of the North Wind will bear her onward.'),(11190,'But when in thy ship thou hast now crossed the stream of Oceanus, where is a level shore and the groves of Persephone—  tall poplars, and willows that shed their fruit—there do thou beach thy ship by the deep eddying Oceanus, but go thyself to the dank house of Hades.'),(11191,' There into Acheron flow Periphlegethon and Cocytus, which is a branch of the water of the Styx;  and there is a rock, and the meeting place of the two roaring rivers.'),(11192,'Thither, prince, do thou draw nigh, as I bid thee, and dig a pit of a cubit\'s length this way and that, and around it pour a libation to all the dead, first with milk and honey, thereafter with sweet wine,  and in the third place with water,'),(11193,'  and sprinkle thereon white barley meal. '),(11194,' And do thou earnestly entreat the powerless heads of the dead, vowing that when thou comest to Ithaca thou wilt sacrifice in thy halls a barren heifer, the best thou hast, and wilt fill the altar with rich gifts; and that to Teiresias alone thou wilt sacrifice separately a ram,  wholly black, the goodliest of thy flock. '),(11195,'But when with prayers thou hast made supplication to the glorious tribes of the dead, then sacrifice a ram and a black ewe, turning their heads toward Erebus but thyself turning backward, and setting thy face towards the streams of the river.'),(11196,' Then many  ghosts of men that are dead will come forth. '),(11197,' But do thou thereafter call to thy comrades, and bid them flay and burn the sheep that lie there, slain by the pitiless bronze, and make prayer to the gods, to mighty Hades and to dread Persephone.'),(11198,'  And do thou thyself draw thy sharp sword from beside thy thigh, and sit there, not suffering the powerless heads of the dead to draw near to the blood, till thou hast enquired of Teiresias.'),(11199,' Then the seer will presently come to thee, leader of men, and he will tell thee thy way and the measures of thy path,  and of thy return, how thou mayest go over the teeming deep.\''),(11200,' “So she spoke, and straightway came golden-throned Dawn.'),(11201,'Round about me then she cast a cloak and tunic as raiment,'),(11202,'  and the nymph clothed herself in a long white robe, finely-woven and beautiful, and about her waist she cast  a fair girdle of gold, and upon her head she put a veil.'),(11203,' But I went through the halls, and roused my men with gentle words, coming up to each man in turn.'),(11204,' “‘No longer now sleep ye, and drowse in sweet slumber, but let us go; lo!'),(11205,'queenly Circe has told me all.’'),(11206,' \n  “So I spoke, and their proud hearts consented.'),(11207,' But not even from thence could I lead my men unscathed.'),(11208,' There was one, Elpenor, the youngest of all, not over valiant in war nor sound of understanding, '),(11209,'who had laid him down apart from his comrades in the sacred house of Circe,  seeking the cool air, for he was heavy with wine.'),(11210,' He heard the noise and the bustle of his comrades as they moved about, and suddenly sprang up, and forgot to go to the long ladder that he might come down again, but fell headlong from the roof,'),(11211,' and his neck  was broken away from the spine, and his spirit went down to the house of Hades.'),(11212,'“But as my men were going on their way I spoke among them, saying:'),(11213,'‘Ye think, forsooth, that ye are going to your dear native land;'),(11214,'  but Circe has pointed out for us another journey, even to the house of Hades and dread Persephone,  to consult the spirit of Theban Teiresias.\''),(11215,'“So I spoke, and their spirit was broken within them, and sitting down right where they were, they wept and tore their hair. '),(11216,'But no good came of their lamenting.'),(11217,'\n“But when we were on our way to the swift ship and the shore of the sea,  sorrowing and shedding big tears, meanwhile Circe had gone forth and made fast beside the black ship a ram and a black ewe, for easily had she passed us by.'),(11218,' Who with his eyes could behold a god against his will, whether going to or fro?'),(11219,' “But when we had come down to the ship and to the sea, first of all we drew the ship down to the bright sea, and set the mast and sail in the black ship, and took the sheep and put them aboard,  and ourselves embarked, sorrowing, and shedding big tears.'),(11220,' And for our aid in the wake of our dark-prowed ship a fair wind that filled the sail, a goodly comrade, was sent by fair-tressed Circe, dread goddess of human speech.'),(11221,' So when we had made fast all the tackling throughout the ship,  we sat down, '),(11222,' and the wind and the helms man made straight her course.'),(11223,' All the day long her sail was stretched as she sped over the sea; '),(11224,'and the sun set and all the ways grew dark.'),(11225,'“She came to deep-flowing Oceanus, that bounds the Earth,'),(11226,'where is the land and city of the Cimmerians,  wrapped in mist and cloud.'),(11227,' Never does the bright sun look down on them with his rays either when he mounts the starry heaven or when he turns again to earth from heaven, but baneful night is spread over wretched mortals.'),(11228,'  Thither we came and beached our ship, and took out the sheep,'),(11229,' and ourselves went beside the stream of Oceanus until we came to the place of which Circe had told us.'),(11230,'\n“Here Perimedes and Eurylochus held the victims, '),(11231,'while I drew my sharp sword from beside my thigh,  and dug a pit of a cubit\'s length this way and that, and around it poured a libation to all the dead, first with milk and honey, thereafter with sweet wine, and in the third place with water, '),(11232,' and I sprinkled thereon white barley meal.'),(11233,'And I earnestly entreated the powerless heads of the dead,  vowing that when I came to Ithaca I would sacrifice in my halls a barren heifer, the best I had, and pile the altar with goodly gifts, and to Teiresias alone would sacrifice separately a ram, wholly black, the goodliest of my flocks. '),(11234,'But when with vows and prayers  I had made supplication to the tribes of the dead, I took the sheep and cut their throats over the pit, and the dark blood ran forth.'),(11235,' Then there gathered from out of Erebus the spirits of those that are dead,'),(11236,'brides, and unwedded youths, and toil-worn old men, and tender maidens with hearts yet new to sorrow,  and many, too, that had been wounded with bronze-tipped spears, men slain in fight, wearing their blood-stained armour.'),(11237,' These came thronging in crowds about the pit from every side, with a wondrous cry;'),(11238,' and pale fear seized me. '),(11239,' Then I called to my comrades and bade them flay and burn  the sheep that lay there slain with the pitiless bronze, and to make prayer to the gods, to mighty Hades and dread Persephone.'),(11240,' And I myself drew my sharp sword from beside my thigh and sat there, and would not suffer the powerless heads of the dead  to draw near to the blood until I had enquired of Teiresias.'),(11241,' \n“The first to come was the spirit of my comrade Elpenor.'),(11242,' Not yet had he been buried beneath the broad-wayed earth,'),(11243,' we had left his corpse behind us in the hall of Circe, unwept and unburied, since another task was then urging us on.'),(11244,'  When I saw him I wept, and my heart had compassion on him; and I spoke and addressed him with winged words:'),(11245,'\n“‘Elpenor, how didst thou come beneath the murky darkness?'),(11246,' Thou coming on foot hast out-stripped me in my black ship.\''),(11247,'\n“So I spoke, and with a groan he answered me and said:'),(11248,'  ‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, an evil doom of some god was my undoing, and measureless wine.'),(11249,' When I had lain down to sleep in the house of Circe I did not think to go to the long ladder that I might come down again, but fell headlong from the roof, '),(11250,' and my neck  was broken away from the spine and my spirit went down to the house of Hades. '),(11251,'Now I beseech thee by those whom we left behind, who are not present with us, by thy wife and thy father who reared thee when a babe, and by Telemachus whom thou didst leave an only son in thy halls; '),(11252,'for I know that as thou goest hence from the house of Hades  thou wilt touch at the Aeaean isle with thy well-built ship. '),(11253,' There, then, O prince, I bid thee remember me. '),(11254,' Leave me not behind thee unwept and unburied as thou goest thence, and turn not away from me, lest haply I bring the wrath of the gods upon thee. Nay, burn me with my armour, all that is mine,  and heap up a mound for me on the shore of the grey sea, in memory of an unhappy man, that men yet to be may learn of me.'),(11255,' Fulfil this my prayer, and fix upon the mound my oar wherewith I rowed in life when I was among my comrades.\''),(11256,'“So he spoke, and I made answer and said:'),(11257,'  ‘All this, unhappy man, will I perform and do.’'),(11258,'\n“Thus we two sat and held sad converse one with the other, I on one side holding my sword over the blood, while on the other side the phantom of my comrade spoke at large.'),(11259,'\n“Then there came up the spirit of my dead mother,  Anticleia, the daughter of great-hearted Autolycus, whom I had left alive when I departed for sacred Ilios.'),(11260,' At sight of her I wept, and my heart had compassion on her, '),(11261,'but even so I would not suffer her to come near the blood, for all my great sorrow, until I had enquired of Teiresias.'),(11262,'\n  “Then there came up the spirit of the Theban Teiresias, bearing his golden staff in his hand, and he knew me and spoke to me:'),(11263,' ‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, what now, hapless man? Why hast thou left the light of the sun and come hither to behold the dead and a region where is no joy?'),(11264,'  Nay, give place from the pit and draw back thy sharp sword, that I may drink of the blood and tell thee sooth.’ '),(11265,' \n“So he spoke, and I gave place and thrust my silver-studded sword into its sheath,'),(11266,'  and when he had drunk the dark blood, then the blameless seer spoke to me and said:'),(11267,' “‘Thou askest of thy honey-sweet return, glorious Odysseus,'),(11268,'\n  but this shall a god make grievous unto thee; '),(11269,'for I think not that thou shalt elude the Earth-shaker, seeing that he has laid up wrath in his heart against thee, angered that thou didst blind his dear son. '),(11270,'Yet even so ye may reach home, though in evil plight,  if thou wilt curb thine own spirit and that of thy comrades, as soon as thou shalt bring thy well-built ship to the island Thrinacia, escaping from the violet sea, and ye find grazing there the kine and goodly flocks of Helios, who over sees and overhears all things.'),(11271,'  If thou leavest these unharmed and heedest thy homeward way, verily ye may yet reach Ithaca, though in evil plight.'),(11272,' But if thou harmest them, then I foresee ruin for thy ship and thy comrades, '),(11273,'and even if thou shalt thyself escape, late shalt thou come home and in evil case, after losing all thy comrades,  in a ship that is another\'s, '),(11274,' and thou shalt find woes in thy house—proud men that devour thy livelihood, wooing thy godlike wife, and offering wooers\' gifts.'),(11275,' Yet verily on their violent deeds shalt thou take vengeance when thou comest. '),(11276,'But when thou hast slain the wooers in thy halls,  whether by guile or openly with the sharp sword, then do thou go forth, taking a shapely oar, until thou comest to men that know naught of the sea and eat not of food mingled with salt,'),(11277,' aye, and they know naught of ships with purple cheeks,  or of shapely oars that are as wings unto ships. '),(11278,' And I will tell thee a sign right manifest, which will not escape thee. '),(11279,'When another wayfarer, on meeting thee, shall say that thou hast a winnowing-fan on thy stout shoulder, then do thou fix in the earth thy shapely oar  and make goodly offerings to lord Poseidon—a ram, and a bull, and a boar that mates with sows—and depart for thy home and offer sacred hecatombs to the immortal gods who hold broad heaven, to each one in due order. '),(11280,'And death shall come to thee thyself far from the sea,  a death so gentle, that shall lay thee low when thou art overcome with sleek old age, '),(11281,'and thy people shall dwell in prosperity around thee.'),(11282,' In this have I told thee sooth.’ '),(11283,' \n“So he spoke, and I made answer and said:'),(11284,' ‘Teiresias, of all this, I ween, the gods themselves have spun the thread.'),(11285,'  But come, tell me this, and declare it truly.'),(11286,' I see here the spirit of my dead mother;'),(11287,' she sits in silence near the blood, and deigns not to look upon the face of her own son or to speak to him. '),(11288,'Tell me, prince, how she may recognize that I am he?\''),(11289,'  “So I spoke, and he straightway made answer, and said: '),(11290,'‘Easy is the word that I shall say and put in thy mind.'),(11291,' Whomsoever of those that are dead and gone thou shalt suffer to draw near the blood, he will tell thee sooth; '),(11292,'but whomsoever thou refusest, he surely will go back again.’'),(11293,'  “So saying the spirit of the prince, Teiresias, went back into the house of Hades, when he had declared his prophecies; '),(11294,' but I remained there steadfastly until my mother came up and drank the dark blood.'),(11295,'At once then she knew me, and with wailing she spoke to me winged words:'),(11296,'\n  “‘My child, how didst thou come beneath the murky darkness, being still alive?'),(11297,' Hard is it for those that live to behold these realms, '),(11298,' for between are great rivers and dread streams; Oceanus first, which one may in no wise cross on foot, but only if one have a well-built ship.'),(11299,'  Art thou but now come hither from Troy after long wanderings with thy ship and thy companions? '),(11300,'and hast thou not yet reached Ithaca, nor seen thy wife in thy halls?’'),(11301,' “So she spoke, and I made answer and said:'),(11302,' “So she spoke, and I made answer and said:‘My mother, necessity brought me down to the house of Hades,  to seek soothsaying of the spirit of Theban Teiresias. '),(11303,'For not yet have I come near to the shore of Achaea, nor have I as yet set foot on my own land, but have ever been wandering, laden with woe, from the day when first I went with goodly Agamemnon to Ilios, famed for its horses, to fight with the Trojans.'),(11304,'  But come, tell me this, and declare it truly.'),(11305,' What fate of grievous death overcame thee?'),(11306,' Was it long disease, or did the archer, Artemis, assail thee with her gentle shafts, and slay thee? '),(11307,'And tell me of my father and my son, whom I left behind me.  Does the honor that was mine still abide with them, or does some other man now possess it, and do they say that I shall no more return?'),(11308,' And tell me of my wedded wife, of her purpose and of her mind. Does she abide with her son, and keep all things safe? or has one already wedded her, whosoever is best of the Achaeans?’ '),(11309,' \n  “So I spoke, and my honored mother straightway answered: '),(11310,'‘Aye verily she abides with steadfast heart in thy halls, '),(11311,' and ever sorrowfully for her do the nights and the days wane, as she weeps.'),(11312,'But the fair honor that was thine no man yet possesses,  but Telemachus holds thy demesne unharassed, and feasts a equal banquets, such as it is fitting that one who deals judgment should share, '),(11313,'for all men invite him.'),(11314,' But thy father abides there in the tilled land, and comes not to the city, '),(11315,' nor has he, for bedding, bed and cloaks and bright coverlets,  but through the winter he sleeps in the house, where the slaves sleep, in the ashes by the fire, and wears upon his body mean raiment.'),(11316,' But when summer comes and rich autumn, then all about the slope of his vineyard plot are strewn his lowly beds of fallen leaves.'),(11317,'  There he lies sorrowing, and nurses his great grief in his heart, in longing for thy return, and heavy old age has come upon him.'),(11318,' Even so did I too perish and meet my fate.'),(11319,' Neither did the keen-sighted archer goddess assail me in my halls with her gentle shafts, and slay me,  nor did any disease come upon me, such as oftenest through grievous wasting takes the spirit from the limbs; '),(11320,'nay, it was longing for thee, and for thy counsels, glorious Odysseus, and for thy tender-heartedness, that robbed me of honey-sweet life.\''),(11321,'“So she spoke, and I pondered in heart, and was fain  to clasp the spirit of my dead mother. '),(11322,'Thrice I sprang towards her, and my heart bade me clasp her, and thrice she flitted from my arms like a shadow or a dream, '),(11323,' and pain grew ever sharper at my heart. And I spoke and addressed her with winged words:'),(11324,'\n  “‘My mother, why dost thou not stay for me, who am eager to clasp thee, that even in the house of Hades we two may cast our arms each about the other, and take our fill of chill lamenting.'),(11325,' Is this but a phantom that august Persephone has sent me, that I may lament and groan the more?\''),(11326,'  “So I spoke, and my honored mother straightway answered: '),(11327,'‘Ah me, my child, ill-fated above all men, in no wise does Persephone, the daughter of Zeus, deceive thee, but this is the appointed way with mortals when one dies. '),(11328,' For the sinews no longer hold the flesh and the bones together,  but the strong might of blazing fire destroys these, as soon as the life leaves the white bones, and the spirit, like a dream, flits away, and hovers to and fro.'),(11329,' But haste thee to the light with what speed thou mayest, '),(11330,'and bear all these things in mind, that thou mayest hereafter tell them to thy wife.’ '),(11331,' \n  “Thus we two talked with one another; and the women came, for august Persephone sent them forth, even all those that had been the wives and the daughters of chieftains.'),(11332,' These flocked in throngs about the dark blood, and I considered how I might question each; '),(11333,' and this seemed to my mind the best counsel. '),(11334,'I drew my long sword from beside my stout thigh, and would not suffer them to drink of the dark blood all at one time.'),(11335,' So they drew near, one after the other, and each declared her birth, '),(11336,'and I questioned them all.'),(11337,'\n  “Then verily the first that I saw was high-born Tyro, who said that she was the daughter of noble Salmoneus, and declared herself to be the wife of Cretheus, son of Aeolus.'),(11338,' She became enamoured of the river, divine Enipeus, who is far the fairest of rivers that send forth their streams upon the earth,  and she was wont to resort to the fair waters of Enipeus. '),(11339,'But the Enfolder and Shaker of the earth took his form, and lay with her at the mouths of the eddying river.'),(11340,' And the dark wave stood about them like a mountain, vaulted-over, and hid the god and the mortal woman.'),(11341,' And he loosed her maiden girdle, and shed sleep upon her.'),(11342,'  But when the god had ended his work of love, he clasped her hand, and spoke, and addressed her:'),(11343,'“‘Be glad, woman, in our love,'),(11344,' and as the year goes on its course thou shalt bear glorious children, for not weak are the embraces  of a god.'),(11345,' These do thou tend and rear.'),(11346,'  But now go to thy house, and hold thy peace, and tell no man;'),(11347,' but know that I am Poseidon, the shaker of the earth.\''),(11348,'“So saying, he plunged beneath the surging sea.'),(11349,' But she conceived and bore Pelias and Neleus,  who both became strong servants of great Zeus;'),(11350,'and Pelias dwelt in spacious Iolcus, and was rich in flocks, and the other dwelt in sandy Pylos.'),(11351,' But her other children she, the queenly among women, bore to Cretheus, even Aeson, and Pheres, and Amythaon, who fought from chariots.'),(11352,'\n  “And after her I saw Antiope, daughter of Asopus, who boasted that she had slept even in the arms of Zeus, and she bore two sons, Amphion and Zethus, who first established the seat of seven-gated Thebe, and fenced it in with walls, for they could not  dwell in spacious Thebe unfenced, how mighty soever they were.'),(11353,'\n“And after her I saw Alcmene, wife of Amphitryon, who lay in the arms of great Zeus, and bore Heracles, staunch in fight, the lion-hearted.'),(11354,' And Megara I saw, daughter of Creon, high-of-heart, whom the son of Amphitryon, ever stubborn in might, had to wife.'),(11355,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.271-11.273'),(11356,' \n“And I saw the mother of Oedipodes, fair Epicaste, who wrought a monstrous deed in ignorance of mind, in that she wedded her own son, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 271 to line 273'),(11357,'and straightway the gods made these things known among men.'),(11358,'  Howbeit he abode as lord of the Cadmeans in lovely Thebe, suffering woes through the baneful counsels of the gods, '),(11359,' but she went down to the house of Hades, the strong warder. She made fast a noose on high from a lofty beam, overpowered by her sorrow,'),(11360,'  but for him she left behind woes  full many, even all that the Avengers of a mother bring to pass.'),(11361,'“And I saw beauteous Chloris, whom once Neleus wedded because of her beauty, when he had brought countless gifts of wooing. Youngest daughter was she of Amphion, son of Iasus, who once ruled mightily in Orchomenus of the Minyae.'),(11362,'  And she was queen of Pylos, and bore to her husband glorious children, Nestor, and Chromius, and lordly Periclymenus, '),(11363,' and besides these she bore noble Pero, a wonder to men. Her all that dwelt about sought in marriage, '),(11364,' but Neleus would give her to no man, save to him who  should drive from Phylace the kine of mighty Iphicles, sleek and broad of brow; and hard they were to drive.'),(11365,' These the blameless seer alone undertook to drive off;'),(11366,' but a grievous fate of the gods ensnared him, even hard bonds and the herdsmen of the field.'),(11367,'  Howbeit when at length the months and the days were being brought to fulfillment, as the year rolled round, and the seasons came on, then verily mighty Iphicles released him, when he had told all the oracles; '),(11368,'and the will of Zeus was fulfilled.'),(11369,'“And I saw Lede, the wife of Tyndareus, who bore to Tyndareus two sons, stout of heart,  Castor the tamer of horses, and the boxer Polydeuces. These two the earth, the giver of life, covers, albeit alive,'),(11370,'and even in the world below they have honor from Zeus. One day they live in turn, and one day they are dead;'),(11371,'   and they have won honor like unto that of the gods.'),(11372,'  “And after her I saw Iphimedeia, wife of Aloeus, who declared that she had lain with Poseidon. She bore two sons, but short of life were they, godlike Otus, and far-famed Ephialtes—men whom the earth, the giver of grain, reared as the tallest,  and far the comeliest, after the famous Orion.'),(11373,' For at nine years they were nine cubits in breadth and in height nine fathoms.'),(11374,' Yea, and they threatened to raise the din of furious war against the immortals in Olympus.'),(11375,'  They were fain to pile Ossa on Olympus, and Pelion, with its waving forests, on Ossa, that so heaven might be scaled.'),(11376,' And this they would have accomplished, if they had reached the measure of manhood;'),(11377,' but the son of Zeus, whom fair-haired Leto bore, slew them both before  the down blossomed beneath their temples and covered their chins with a full growth of beard.'),(11378,' \n“And Phaedra and Procris I saw, and fair Ariadne, the daughter of Minos of baneful mind, whom once Theseus was fain to bear from Crete to the hill of sacred Athens; but he had no joy of her, '),(11379,'for ere that Artemis slew her  in sea-girt Dia because of the witness of Dionysus.'),(11380,'\n“And Maera and Clymene I saw, and hateful Eriphyle, who took precious gold as the price of the life of her own lord.'),(11381,' But I cannot tell or name all the wives and daughters of heroes that I saw; '),(11382,' ere that immortal night would wane. '),(11383,'Nay, it is now time to sleep, either when I have gone to the swift ship and the crew, or here.'),(11384,' My sending shall rest with the gods, and with you.\"'),(11385,'\nSo he spoke, and they were all hushed in silence, and were held spell-bound throughout the shadowy halls.'),(11386,'  Then among them white-armed Arete was the first to speak:'),(11387,'\n“Phaeacians, how seems this man to you for comeliness and stature, and for the balanced spirit within him?'),(11388,' And moreover he is my guest, though each of you has a share in this honor.'),(11389,' Wherefore be not in haste to send him away, nor  stint your gifts to one in such need; '),(11390,'for many are the treasures which lie stored in your halls by the favour of the gods.\"'),(11391,'Then among them spoke also the old lord Echeneus, who was an elder among the Phaeacians:'),(11392,'“Friends, verily not wide of the mark or of our own thought  are the words of our wise queen.'),(11393,' Nay, do you give heed to them. '),(11394,'Yet it is on Alcinous here that deed and word depend.\"'),(11395,'Then again Alcinous answered him and said:'),(11396,'“This word of hers shall verily hold, as surely as I live and am lord over the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar.'),(11397,'  But let our guest, for all his great longing to return, nevertheless endure to remain until tomorrow, till I shall make all our gift complete.'),(11398,' His sending shall rest with the men, with all, but most of all with me; '),(11399,'for mine is the control in the land.\"'),(11400,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said:'),(11401,'  “Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, if you should bid me abide here even for a year, and should further my sending, and give glorious gifts, even that would I choose; and it would be better far to come with a fuller hand to my dear native land. '),(11402,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.360-11.361'),(11403,' \nThen again Alcinous made answer and said:'),(11404,'“Odysseus, in no wise as we look on thee do we deem this of thee, that thou art a cheat and a dissembler, such as are many  whom the dark earth breeds scattered far and wide, men that fashion lies out of what no man can even see.'),(11405,' But upon thee is grace of words, and within thee is a heart of wisdom, '),(11406,' and thy tale thou hast told with skill, as doth a minstrel, even the grievous woes of all the Argives and of thine own self.'),(11407,'  But come, tell me this, and declare it truly, whether thou sawest any of thy godlike comrades, who went to Ilios together with thee, and there met their fate.'),(11408,' The night is before us, long, aye, wondrous long, '),(11409,' and it is not yet the time for sleep in the hall. Tell on, I pray thee, the tale of these wondrous deeds.'),(11410,'  Verily I could abide until bright dawn, so thou wouldest be willing to tell in the hall of these woes of thine.\"'),(11411,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said:'),(11412,' “Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, there is a time for many words and there is a time also for sleep.'),(11413,'  But if thou art fain still to listen, I would not begrudge to tell thee of other things more pitiful still than these, even the woes of my comrades, who perished afterward, who escaped from the dread battle-cry of the Trojans, but perished on their return through the will of an evil woman.'),(11414,'\n  “When then holy Persephone had scattered this way and that the spirits of the women, there came up the spirit of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, sorrowing; '),(11415,' and round about him others were gathered, spirits of all those who were slain with him in the house of Aegisthus, and met their fate.'),(11416,'  He knew me straightway, when he had drunk the dark blood,'),(11417,' and he wept aloud, and shed big tears, and stretched forth his hands toward me eager to reach me.'),(11418,' But no longer had he aught of strength or might remaining such as of old was in his supple limbs.'),(11419,'\n  “When I saw him I wept, and my heart had compassion on him, and I spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(11420,' ‘Most glorious son of Atreus, king of men, Agamemnon, what fate of grievous death overcame thee?'),(11421,' Did Poseidon smite thee on board thy ships,  when he had roused a furious blast of cruel winds? '),(11422,' Or did foemen work thee harm on the land, while thou wast cutting off their cattle and fair flocks of sheep, or wast fighting to win their city and their women?’ '),(11423,' \n“So I spoke, and he straightway made answer and said:'),(11424,'  ‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, neither did Poseidon smite me on board my ships, when he had roused a furious blast of cruel winds, nor did foemen work me harm on the land, but Aegisthus wrought for me death and fate,  and slew me with the aid of my accursed wife, when he had bidden me to his house and made me a feast, even as one slays an ox at the stall.'),(11425,' So I died by a most pitiful death, '),(11426,' and round about me the rest of my comrades were slain unceasingly like white-tusked swine, which are slaughtered in the house of a rich man of great might  at a marriage feast, or a joint meal, or a rich drinking-bout.'),(11427,'Ere now thou hast been present at the slaying of many men, killed in single combat or in the press of the fight,'),(11428,'  but in heart thou wouldst have felt most pity hadst thou seen that sight, how about the mixing bowl and the laden tables  we lay in the hall, and the floor all swam with blood. '),(11429,' But the most piteous cry that I heard was that of the daughter of Priam, Cassandra, whom guileful Clytemnestra slew by my side. And I sought to raise my hands and smite down the murderess, dying though I was, pierced through with the sword. '),(11430,' But she, the shameless one,  turned her back upon me, and even though I was going to the house of Hades deigned neither to draw down my eyelids with her fingers nor to close my mouth.'),(11431,' So true is it that there is nothing more dread or more shameless than a woman who puts into her heart such deeds, '),(11432,' even as she too devised a monstrous thing,  contriving death for her wedded husband.'),(11433,' Verily I thought that I should come home welcome to my children and to my slaves;'),(11434,' but she, with her heart set on utter wickedness, has shed shame on herself and on women yet to be, even upon her that doeth uprightly.\''),(11435,' “So he spoke, and I made answer and said: '),(11436,' ‘Ah, verily has Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, visited wondrous hatred on the race of Atreus from the first because of the counsels of women.'),(11437,' For Helen\'s sake many of us perished, and against thee Clytemnestra spread a snare whilst thou wast afar.’ '),(11438,' \n  “So I spoke, and he straightway made answer and said: '),(11439,' ‘Wherefore in thine own case be thou never gentle even to thy wife.'),(11440,' Declare not to her all the thoughts of thy heart, but tell her somewhat, and let somewhat also be hidden.'),(11441,' Yet not upon thee, Odysseus, shall death come from thy wife, '),(11442,' for very prudent and of an understanding heart is the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope.'),(11443,' Verily we left her a bride newly wed, when we went to the war,'),(11444,'and a boy was at her breast, a babe, who now, I ween, sits in the ranks of men, '),(11445,'  happy in that his dear father will behold him when he comes, and he will greet his father as is meet. '),(11446,' But my wife did not let me sate my eyes even with sight of my own son. '),(11447,' Nay, ere that she slew even me, her husband. '),(11448,'And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart:'),(11449,'  in secret and not openly do thou bring thy ship to the shore of thy dear native land; '),(11450,' for no longer is there faith in women.'),(11451,'But, come, tell me this, and declare it truly, whether haply ye hear of my son as yet alive in Orchomenus it may be, or in sandy Pylos,  or yet with Menelaus in wide Sparta; '),(11452,'for not yet has goodly Orestes perished on the earth.’'),(11453,'“So he spoke, and I made answer and said: '),(11454,'Son of Atreus, wherefore dost thou question me of this? '),(11455,'I know not at all whether he be alive or dead, '),(11456,' and it is an ill thing to speak words vain as wind.’'),(11457,'\n  “Thus we two stood and held sad converse with one another, sorrowing and shedding big tears; '),(11458,'and there came up the spirit of Achilles, son of Peleus, and those of Patroclus and of peerless Antilochus and of Aias, who in comeliness and form was the goodliest  of all the Danaans after the peerless son of Peleus. '),(11459,' And the spirit of the swift-footed son of Aeacus recognized me, and weeping, spoke to me winged words:'),(11460,'\n“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, rash man, what deed yet greater than this wilt thou devise in thy heart?'),(11461,'  How didst thou dare to come down to Hades, where dwell the unheeding dead, the phantoms of men outworn.’'),(11462,'“‘So he spoke, and I made answer and said:'),(11463,'‘Achilles, son of Peleus, far the mightiest of the Achaeans, I came through need of Teiresias, if haply  he would tell me some plan whereby I might reach rugged Ithaca. '),(11464,'For not yet have I come near to the land of Achaea, nor have I as yet set foot on my own country, but am ever suffering woes;'),(11465,' whereas than thou, Achilles, no man aforetime was more blessed nor shall ever be hereafter. '),(11466,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.484-11.486'),(11467,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.486'),(11468,' \n“So I spoke, and he straightway made answer and said:'),(11469,' ‘Nay, seek not to speak soothingly to me of death, glorious Odysseus.'),(11470,' I should choose, so I might live on earth, to serve as the hireling of another,  of some portionless man whose livelihood was but small, rather than to be lord over all the dead that have perished.'),(11471,' But come, tell me tidings of my son, that lordly youth, whether or not he followed to the war to be a leader. '),(11472,'And tell me of noble Peleus, if thou hast heard aught,  whether he still has honor among the host of the Myrmidons, or whether men do him dishonor throughout Hellas and Phthia, because old age binds him hand and foot.'),(11473,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.498-11.500'),(11474,' If but in such strength I could come, were it but for an hour, to my father\'s house, '),(11475,'I would give many a one of those who do him violence and keep him from his honor, cause to rue my strength and my invincible hands.\''),(11476,'“So he spoke, and I made answer and said:'),(11477,'  ‘Verily of noble Peleus have I heard naught, but as touching thy dear son, Neoptolemus, I will tell thee all the truth, as thou biddest me.'),(11478,' I it was, myself, who brought him from Scyros in my shapely, hollow ship to join the host of the well-greaved Archaeans.'),(11479,'  And verily, as often as we took counsel around the city of Troy, he was ever the first to speak, and made no miss of words; '),(11480,' godlike Nestor and I alone surpassed him.'),(11481,'But as often as we fought with the bronze on the Trojan plain, he would never remain behind in the throng or press of men,  but would ever run forth far to the front, yielding to none in his might; and many men he slew in dread combat. '),(11482,'All of them I could not tell or name, all the host that he slew in defence of the Argives; but what a warrior was that son of Telephus whom he slew with the sword,  the prince Eurypylus! Aye, and many of his comrades, the Ceteians, were slain about him, because of gifts a woman craved.'),(11483,' He verily was the comeliest man I saw, next to goodly Memnon.'),(11484,'And again, when we, the best of the Argives, were about to go down into the horse which Epeus made, and the command of all was laid upon me,  both to open and to close the door of our stout-built ambush, then the other leaders and counsellors of the Danaans would wipe away tears from their eyes, and each man\'s limbs shook beneath him, '),(11485,' but never did my eyes see his fair face grow pale at all, nor see him  wiping tears from his cheeks;'),(11486,' but he earnestly besought me to let him go forth from the horse, and kept handling his sword-hilt and his spear heavy with bronze, and was eager to work harm to the Trojans.'),(11487,' But after we had sacked the lofty city of Priam, he went on board his ship with his share of the spoil and a goodly prize—  all unscathed he was, neither smitten with the sharp spear nor wounded in close fight, as often befalls in war; '),(11488,'for Ares rages confusedly.’ '),(11489,' \n“So I spoke, and the spirit of the son of Aeacus departed with long strides over the field of asphodel,  joyful in that I said that his son was preeminent.'),(11490,'\n“And other spirits of those dead and gone stood sorrowing, and each asked of those dear to him.'),(11491,'Alone of them all the spirit of Aias, son of Telamon, stood apart, still full of wrath for the victory  that I had won over him in the contest by the ships for the arms of Achilles, '),(11492,' whose honored mother had set them for a prize; '),(11493,' and the judges were the sons of the Trojans and Pallas Athena.'),(11494,' I would that I had never won in the contest for such a prize, '),(11495,'over so noble a head did the earth close because of those arms,  even over Aias, who in comeliness and in deeds of war was above all the other Achaeans, next to the peerless son of Peleus.'),(11496,' To him I spoke with soothing words:'),(11497,'\n“‘Aias, son of peerless Telamon, wast thou then not even in death to forget thy wrath against me because of  those accursed arms?'),(11498,'Surely the gods set them to be a bane to the Argives: such a tower of strength was lost to them in thee;'),(11499,'  and for thee in death we Achaeans sorrow unceasingly, even as for the life of Achilles, son of Peleus.'),(11500,' Yet no other is to blame but Zeus,  who bore terrible hatred against the host of Danaan spearmen, and brought on thee thy doom.'),(11501,' Nay, come hither, prince, that thou mayest hear my word and my speech; '),(11502,'and subdue thy wrath and thy proud spirit.\''),(11503,'“So I spoke, but he answered me not a word, but went his way to Erebus to join the other spirits of those dead and gone. '),(11504,'  Then would he nevertheless have spoken to me for all his wrath, or I to him, '),(11505,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.566-11.567'),(11506,' \n“There then I saw Minos, the glorious son of Zeus, golden sceptre in hand, giving judgment to the dead  from his seat, while they sat and stood about the king through the wide-gated house of Hades, and asked of him judgment.'),(11507,'\n“And after him I marked huge Orion driving together over the field of asphodel wild beasts which he himself had slain on the lonely hills,  and in his hands he held a club all of bronze, ever unbroken.'),(11508,'\n“And I saw Tityos, son of glorious Gaea, lying on the ground.'),(11509,' Over nine roods he stretched, and two vultures sat, one on either side, and tore his liver, plunging their beaks into his bowels, nor could he beat them off with his hands.'),(11510,'  For he had offered violence to Leto, the glorious wife of Zeus, as she went toward Pytho through Panopeus with its lovely lawns.'),(11511,'\n“Aye, and I saw Tantalus in violent torment, standing in a pool, '),(11512,'\nand the water came nigh unto his chin.'),(11513,' He seemed as one athirst, but could not take and drink; '),(11514,' for as often as that old man stooped down, eager to drink, so often would the water be swallowed up and vanish away, and at his feet the black earth would appear, for some god made all dry.'),(11515,' And trees, high and leafy, let stream their fruits above his head, pears, and pomegranates, and apple trees with their bright fruit,  and sweet figs, and luxuriant olives. '),(11516,'But as often as that old man would reach out toward these, to clutch them with his hands, the wind would toss them to the shadowy clouds.'),(11517,'\n“Aye, and I saw Sisyphus in violent torment, seeking to raise a monstrous stone with both his hands.'),(11518,'  Verily he would brace himself with hands and feet, and thrust the stone toward the crest of a hill, '),(11519,' but as often as he was about to heave it over the top, the weight would turn it back, '),(11520,'and then down again to the plain would come rolling the ruthless stone.'),(11521,' But he would strain again and thrust it back, and the sweat  flowed down from his limbs, and dust rose up from his head.'),(11522,' \n“And after him I marked the mighty Heracles—his phantom; '),(11523,'for he himself among the immortal gods takes his joy in the feast, and has to wife Hebe, of the fair ankles, daughter of great Zeus and of Here, of the golden sandals.'),(11524,'  About him rose a clamor from the dead, as of birds flying everywhere in terror; '),(11525,' and he like dark night, with his bow bare and with arrow on the string, glared about him terribly, like one in act to shoot.'),(11526,'Awful was the belt about his breast,  a baldric of gold, whereon wondrous things were fashioned, bears and wild boars, and lions with flashing eyes, and conflicts, and battles, and murders, and slayings of men.'),(11527,' May he never have designed, or hereafter design such another, even he who stored up in his craft the device of that belt.'),(11528,'  He in turn knew me when his eyes beheld me, and weeping spoke to me winged words:'),(11529,'\n“‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, ah, wretched man, dost thou, too, drag out an evil lot such as I once bore beneath the rays of the sun?'),(11530,'  I was the son of Zeus, son of Cronos, but I had woe beyond measure; '),(11531,' for to a man far worse than I was I made subject, and he laid on me hard labours.'),(11532,' Yea, he once sent me hither to fetch the hound of Hades, '),(11533,' for he could devise for me no other task mightier than this.'),(11534,'  The hound I carried off and led forth from the house of Hades;'),(11535,' and Hermes was my guide, and flashing-eyed Athena.\''),(11536,'“So saying, he went his way again into the house of Hades, but I abode there steadfastly, in the hope that some other haply might still come forth of the warrior heroes who died in the days of old.'),(11537,'  And I should have seen yet others of the men of former time, whom I was fain to behold, even Theseus and Peirithous, glorious children of the gods, '),(11538,' but ere that the myriad tribes of the dead came thronging up with a wondrous cry, '),(11539,' and pale fear seized me, lest  august Persephone might send forth upon me from out the house of Hades the head of the Gorgon, that awful monster.'),(11540,'“Straightway then I went to the ship and bade my comrades themselves to embark, and to loose the stern cables.'),(11541,' So they went on board quickly and sat down upon the benches.'),(11542,' And the ship was borne down the stream Oceanus by the swelling flood,  first with our rowing, and afterwards the wind was fair.'),(11543,' “Now after our ship had left the stream of the river Oceanus and had come to the wave of the broad sea, and the Aeaean isle, where is the dwelling of early Dawn and her dancing-lawns, and the risings of the sun,  there on our coming we beached our ship on the sands, and ourselves went forth upon the shore of the sea, '),(11544,' and there we fell asleep, and waited for the bright Dawn.'),(11545,'\n“As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, then I sent forth my comrades to the house of Circe  to fetch the body of the dead Elpenor. '),(11546,'Straightway then we cut billets of wood and gave him burial where the headland runs furthest out to sea, sorrowing and shedding big tears.'),(11547,' But when the dead man was burned, and the armour of the dead, we heaped up a mound and dragged on to it a pillar,  and on the top of the mound we planted his shapely oar.'),(11548,'“We then were busied with these several tasks,'),(11549,'\n howbeit Circe was not unaware of our coming forth from the house of Hades, but speedily she arrayed herself and came, '),(11550,'and her handmaids brought with her bread and meat in abundance and flaming red wine.'),(11551,'  And the beautiful goddess stood in our midst, and spoke among us, saying:'),(11552,'\n“‘Rash men, who have gone down alive to the house of Hades to meet death twice, while other men die but once.'),(11553,' Nay, come, eat food and drink wine here this whole day through;'),(11554,' but at the coming of Dawn  ye shall set sail, '),(11555,'and I will point out the way and declare to you each thing, in order that ye may not suffer pain and woes through wretched ill-contriving either by sea or on land.\''),(11556,'“So she spoke, and our proud hearts consented.'),(11557,' So then all day long till set of sun  we sat feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine. '),(11558,'But when the sun set and darkness came on, they lay down to rest beside the stern cables of the ship; but Circe took me by the hand, and leading me apart from my dear comrades, made me to sit, and herself lay down close at hand and asked me all the tale. '),(11559,' And I told her all in due order.'),(11560,' Then queenly Circe spoke to me and said:'),(11561,'\n“All these things have thus found an end; but do thou hearken as I shall tell thee, and a god shall himself bring it to thy mind.'),(11562,' To the Sirens first shalt thou come, who  beguile all men whosoever comes to them. '),(11563,' Whoso in ignorance draws near to them and hears the Sirens\' voice, he nevermore returns, that his wife and little children may stand at his side rejoicing, but the Sirens beguile him with their clear-toned song,  as they sit in a meadow, and about them is a great heap of bones of mouldering men, and round the bones the skin is shrivelling.'),(11564,' But do thou row past them, and anoint the ears of thy comrades with sweet wax, which thou hast kneaded, lest any of the rest may hear. '),(11565,' But if thou thyself hast a will to listen,  let them bind thee in the swift ship hand and foot upright in the step of the mast, and let the ropes be made fast at the ends to the mast itself, that with delight thou mayest listen to the voice of the two Sirens.'),(11566,' And if thou shalt implore and bid thy comrades to loose thee, then let them bind thee with yet more bonds.'),(11567,'  But when thy comrades shall have rowed past these, thereafter I shall not fully say on which side thy course is to lie, but do thou thyself ponder it in mind, '),(11568,'and I will tell thee of both ways.'),(11569,' For on the one hand are beetling crags, and against them  roars the great wave of dark-eyed Amphitrite;'),(11570,'the Planctae do the blessed gods call these.'),(11571,' Thereby not even winged things may pass, no, not the timorous doves that bear ambrosia to father Zeus, but the smooth rock ever snatches away one even of these, '),(11572,' and the father sends in another to make up the tale. '),(11573,'And thereby has no ship of men ever yet escaped that has come thither, but the planks of ships and bodies of men are whirled confusedly by the waves of the sea and the blasts of baneful fire.'),(11574,' One seafaring ship alone has passed thereby,  that Argo famed of all, on her voyage from Aeetes, '),(11575,'and even her the wave would speedily have dashed there against the great crags, had not Here sent her through, for that Jason was dear to her. '),(11576,' \n“‘Now on the other path are two cliffs, one of which reaches with its sharp peak to the broad heaven, and a dark cloud surrounds it.'),(11577,'  This never melts away, nor does clear sky ever surround that peak in summer or in harvest time.'),(11578,' No mortal man could scale it or set foot upon the top, not though he had twenty hands and feet; '),(11579,'for the rock is smooth, as if it were polished.'),(11580,'  And in the midst of the cliff is a dim cave, turned to the West, toward Erebus, even where you shall steer your hollow ship, glorious Odysseus.'),(11581,' Not even a man of might could shoot an arrow from the hollow ship so as to reach into that vaulted cave.'),(11582,'  Therein dwells Scylla, yelping terribly.'),(11583,'Her voice is indeed but as the voice of a new-born whelp, but she herself is an evil monster,'),(11584,'  nor would anyone be glad at sight of her, no, not though it were a god that met her. '),(11585,' Verily she has twelve feet, all misshapen,  and six necks, exceeding long, and on each one an awful head, and therein three rows of teeth, thick and close, and full of black death.'),(11586,' Up to her middle she is hidden in the hollow cave, but she holds her head out beyond the dread chasm,  and fishes there, eagerly searching around the rock for dolphins and sea-dogs and whatever greater beast she may haply catch, such creatures as deep-moaning Amphitrite rears in multitudes past counting.'),(11587,' By her no sailors yet may boast that they have fled unscathed in their ship,'),(11588,' for with each head she carries off  a man, snatching him from the dark-prowed ship.'),(11589,'“‘But the other cliff, thou wilt note, Odysseus, is lower—'),(11590,' thou couldst even shoot an arrow across—'),(11591,' thou couldst even shoot an arrow across—'),(11592,'and on it is a great fig tree with rich foliage, '),(11593,' but beneath this divine Charybdis sucks down the black water.'),(11594,'  Thrice a day she belches it forth, and thrice she sucks it down terribly.'),(11595,'Mayest thou not be there when she sucks it down,'),(11596,'  for no one could save thee from ruin, no, not the Earth-shaker.'),(11597,' Nay, draw very close to Scylla\'s cliff, and drive thy ship past quickly; for it is better far   to mourn six comrades in thy ship than all together.’ '),(11598,' \n“So she spoke, but I made answer and said:'),(11599,' ‘Come, I pray thee, goddess, tell me this thing truly, if in any wise I might escape from fell Charybids, and ward off that other, when she works harm to my comrades.’'),(11600,'\n  “So I spoke, and the beautiful goddess answered and said: '),(11601,' ‘Rash man, lo, now again thy heart is set on the deeds of war and on toil.'),(11602,'  Wilt thou not yield even to the immortal gods?'),(11603,'  She is not mortal, but an immortal bane, dread, and dire, and fierce, and not to be fought with; '),(11604,'  there is no defence; '),(11605,' to flee from her is bravest. '),(11606,' For if thou tarriest to arm thyself by the cliff, I fear lest she may again dart forth and attack thee with as many heads and seize as many men as before.'),(11607,' Nay, row past with all thy might, and call upon Crataiis,  the mother of Scylla, who bore her for a bane to mortals. '),(11608,' Then will she keep her from darting forth again.'),(11609,' “‘And thou wilt come to the isle Thrinacia. '),(11610,'There in great numbers feed the kine of Helios and his goodly flocks, seven herds of kine and as many fair flocks of sheep,  and fifty in each. '),(11611,' These bear no young, nor do they ever die, '),(11612,' and goddesses are their shepherds, fair-tressed nymphs, Phaethusa and Lampetie, whom beautiful Neaera bore to Helios Hyperion. '),(11613,'These their honored mother, when she had borne and reared them,  sent to the isle Thrinacia to dwell afar, and keep the flocks of their father and his sleek kine. '),(11614,' If thou leavest these unharmed and heedest thy homeward way, verily ye may yet reach Ithaca, though in evil plight.'),(11615,' But if thou harmest them, then I foretell ruin  for thy ship and for thy comrades,'),(11616,'and even if thou shalt thyself escape, late shalt thou come home and in evil case, after losing all thy comrades.’'),(11617,' “So she spoke, and presently came golden-throned Dawn. '),(11618,'Then the beautiful goddess departed up the island,'),(11619,' but I went to the ship and roused my comrades  themselves to embark and to loose the stern cables. '),(11620,' So they went on board straightway and sat down upon the benches, '),(11621,'and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars. '),(11622,' And for our aid in the wake of our dark-prowed ship a fair wind that filled the sail, a goodly comrade, was sent  by fair-tressed Circe, dread goddess of human speech.'),(11623,' So when we had straightway made fast all the tackling throughout the ship we sat down,'),(11624,' but the wind and the helmsman guided the ship. '),(11625,' \n“Then verily I spoke among my comrades, grieved at heart:'),(11626,' ‘Friends, since it is not right that one or two alone should know  the oracles that Circe, the beautiful goddess, told me, '),(11627,'therefore will I tell them, in order that knowing them we may either die or, shunning death and fate, escape.'),(11628,' First she bade us avoid the voice of the wondrous Sirens, and their flowery meadow.'),(11629,'  Me alone she bade to listen to their voice;'),(11630,' but do ye bind me with grievous bonds, that I may abide fast where I am, upright in the step of the mast, and let the ropes be made fast at the ends to the mast itself; '),(11631,'and if I implore and bid you to loose me, then do ye tie me fast with yet more bonds.\''),(11632,' “Thus I rehearsed all these things and told them to my comrades. '),(11633,'Meanwhile the well-built ship speedily came to the isle of the two Sirens, '),(11634,'for a fair and gentle wind bore her on.'),(11635,' Then presently the wind ceased and there was a windless calm, and a god lulled the waves to sleep.'),(11636,'  But my comrades rose up and furled the sail and stowed it in the hollow ship, and thereafter sat at the oars and made the water white with their polished oars of fir.'),(11637,' But I with my sharp sword cut into small bits a great round cake of wax, and kneaded it with my strong hands, '),(11638,' and soon the wax grew warm, forced by the strong pressure and the rays of the lord Helios Hyperion.'),(11639,' Then I anointed with this the ears of all my comrades in turn; '),(11640,'and they bound me in the ship hand and foot, upright in the step of the mast, and made the ropes fast at the ends to the mast itself; '),(11641,' and themselves sitting down smote the grey sea with their oars. '),(11642,'But when we were as far distant as a man can make himself heard when he shouts, driving swiftly on our way, the Sirens failed not to note the swift ship as it drew near, and they raised their clear-toned song:'),(11643,'\n“‘Come hither, as thou farest, renowned Odysseus, great glory of the Achaeans;  stay thy ship that thou mayest listen to the voice of us two. '),(11644,' For never yet has any man rowed past this isle in his black ship until he has heard the sweet voice from our lips. Nay, he has joy of it, and goes his way a wiser man. '),(11645,'For we know all the toils that in wide Troy  the Argives and Trojans endured through the will of the gods, and we know all things that come to pass upon the fruitful earth.’ '),(11646,' \n“So they spoke, sending forth their beautiful voice, '),(11647,' and my heart was fain to listen, and I bade my comrades loose me, nodding to them with my brows; '),(11648,'but they fell to their oars and rowed on.'),(11649,'  And presently Perimedes and Eurylochus arose and bound me with yet more bonds and drew them tighter.'),(11650,' But when they had rowed past the Sirens, and we could no more hear their voice or their song, then straightway my trusty comrades took away the  wax with which I had anointed their ears and loosed me from my bonds.'),(11651,'“But when we had left the island, I presently saw smoke and a great billow, and heard a booming.'),(11652,' Then from the hands of my men in their terror the oars flew, and splashed one and all in the swirl, '),(11653,'and  the ship stood still where it was, when they no longer plied with their hands the tapering oars.'),(11654,' But I went through the ship and cheered my men with gentle words, coming up to each man in turn:'),(11655,'\n“‘Friends, hitherto we have been in no wise ignorant of sorrow; '),(11656,'surely this evil that besets us now is no greater than when the Cyclops  penned us in his hollow cave by brutal strength; '),(11657,' yet even thence we made our escape through my valor and counsel and wit; these dangers, too, methinks we shall some day remember.'),(11658,' But now come, as I bid, let us all obey.'),(11659,' Do you keep your seats on the benches  and smite with your oars the deep surf of the sea, in the hope that Zeus may grant us to escape and avoid this death.'),(11660,'  And to thee, steersman, I give this command,'),(11661,' and do thou lay it to heart, since thou wieldest the steering oar of the hollow ship.'),(11662,' From this smoke and surf keep  the ship well away and hug the cliff, lest, ere thou know it, the ship swerve off to the other side and thou cast us into destruction.\''),(11663,'“So I spoke, and they quickly hearkened to my words.'),(11664,'But of Scylla I went not on to speak, a cureless bane, lest haply my comrades, seized with fear, should cease  from rowing and huddle together in the hold.'),(11665,' Then verily I forgot the hard command of Circe, whereas she bade me in no wise to arm myself;'),(11666,' but when I had put on my glorious armour and grasped in my hand two long spears, I went to the fore-deck of the ship, '),(11667,'  whence I deemed that Scylla of the rock would first be seen, who was to bring ruin upon my comrades.'),(11668,' But nowhere could I descry her, and my eyes grew weary as I gazed everywhere toward the misty rock. '),(11669,' \n“We then sailed on up the narrow strait with wailing.'),(11670,'  For on one side lay Scylla and on the other divine Charybdis terribly sucked down the salt water of the sea.'),(11671,' Verily whenever she belched it forth, like a cauldron on a great fire she would seethe and bubble in utter turmoil, and high over head the spray would fall on the tops of both the cliffs.'),(11672,'  But as often as she sucked down the salt water of the sea, within she could all be seen in utter turmoil, and round about the rock roared terribly, while beneath the earth appeared black with sand;'),(11673,' and pale fear seized my men.'),(11674,' So we looked toward her and feared destruction; '),(11675,' but meanwhile Scylla seized from out the hollow ship six of my comrades who were the best in strength and in might.'),(11676,' Turning my eyes to the swift ship and to the company of my men, even then I noted above me their feet and hands as they were raised aloft.'),(11677,' To me they cried aloud, calling upon me  by name for that last time in anguish of heart. '),(11678,' And as a fisher on a jutting rock, when he casts in his baits as a snare to the little fishes, with his long pole lets down into the sea the horn of an ox of the steading, and then as he catches a fish flings it writhing ashore,  even so were they drawn writhing up towards the cliffs. '),(11679,'Then at her doors she devoured them shrieking and stretching out their hands toward me in their awful death-struggle.'),(11680,' Most piteous did mine eyes behold that thing of all that I bore while I explored the paths of the sea.'),(11681,'\n  “Now when we had escaped the rocks, and dread Charybdis and Scylla, presently then we came to the goodly island of the god,'),(11682,' where were the fair kine, broad of brow, and the many goodly flocks of Helios Hyperion. '),(11683,'Then while I was still out at sea in my black ship,  I heard the lowing of the cattle that were being stalled and the bleating of the sheep, '),(11684,'and upon my mind fell the words of the blind seer, Theban Teiresias, and of Aeaean Circe, who very straitly charged me to shun the island of Helios, who gives joy to mortals.'),(11685,' Then verily I spoke among my comrades, grieved at heart:'),(11686,' \n“‘Hear my words, comrades, for all your evil plight, that I may tell you the oracles of Teiresias and of Aeaean Circe, who very straitly charged me to shun the island of Helios, who gives joy to mortals; '),(11687,' for there, she said, was our most terrible bane. '),(11688,' Nay, row the black ship out past the island.’ '),(11689,' \n“So I spoke, but their spirit was broken within them, '),(11690,' \nand straightway Eurylochus answered me with hateful words:'),(11691,'\n“‘Hardy art thou, Odysseus; '),(11692,'\nthou hast strength beyond that of other men and thy limbs never  grow weary. '),(11693,' Verily thou art wholly wrought of iron, seeing that thou sufferest not thy comrades, worn out with toil and drowsiness, to set foot on shore, where on this sea-girt isle we might once more make ready a savoury supper; but thou biddest us even as we are to wander on through the swift night,  driven away from the island over the misty deep.'),(11694,'It is from the night that fierce winds are born, wreckers of ships.'),(11695,'  How could one escape utter destruction, if haply there should suddenly come a blast of the South Wind or the blustering West Wind, which oftenest  wreck ships in despite of the sovereign gods? '),(11696,'Nay, verily for this time let us yield to black night and make ready our supper, remaining by the swift ship, and in the morning we will go aboard, and put out into the broad sea.\''),(11697,'“So spoke Eurylochus, and the rest of my comrades gave assent.'),(11698,'  Then verily I knew that some god was assuredly devising ill, and I spoke and addressed him with winged words:'),(11699,'“‘Eurylochus, verily ye constrain me, who stand alone.'),(11700,'\n But come now, do ye all swear to me a mighty oath, '),(11701,'to the end that, if we haply find a herd of kine or a great flock of sheep,  no man may slay either cow or sheep in the blind folly of his mind; '),(11702,' but be content to eat the food which immortal Circe gave.\''),(11703,'\n“So I spoke; and they straightway swore that they would not, even as I bade them. '),(11704,'But when they had sworn and made an end of the oath,  we moored our well-built ship in the hollow harbor near a spring of sweet water, and my comrades went forth from the ship and skilfully made ready their supper.'),(11705,' But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, then they fell to weeping, as they remembered their dear comrades  whom Scylla had snatched from out the hollow ship and devoured;'),(11706,' and sweet sleep came upon them as they wept.'),(11707,' But when it was the third watch of the night, and the stars had turned their course, Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, roused against us a fierce wind with a wondrous tempest, and hid with clouds  the land and sea alike,'),(11708,'and night rushed down from heaven. '),(11709,' And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, we dragged our ship, and made her fast in a hollow cave, '),(11710,' where were the fair dancing-floors and seats of the nymphs.'),(11711,' Then I called my men together and spoke among them:'),(11712,'\n  “‘Friends, in our swift ship is meat and drink; let us therefore keep our hands from those kine lest we come to harm, '),(11713,'for these are the cows and goodly sheep of a dread god, even of Helios, who oversees all things and overhears all things.\''),(11714,'“So I spoke, and their proud hearts consented.'),(11715,'  Then for a full month the South Wind blew unceasingly, nor did any other wind arise except the East and the South. '),(11716,' \n“Now so long as my men had grain and red wine they kept their hands from the kine, for they were eager to save their lives.'),(11717,'But when all the stores had been consumed from out the ship,  and now they must needs roam about in search of game, fishes, and fowl, and whatever might come to their hands—fishing with bent hooks, for hunger pinched their bellies—'),(11718,'then I went apart up the island that I might pray to the gods in the hope that one of them might show me a way to go.'),(11719,'  And when, as I went through the island, I had got away from my comrades, I washed my hands in a place where there was shelter from the wind, and prayed to all the gods that hold Olympus; '),(11720,'but they shed sweet sleep upon my eyelids.'),(11721,' And meanwhile Eurylochus began to give evil counsel to my comrades:'),(11722,'  “‘Hear my words, comrades, for all your evil plight.'),(11723,'All forms of death are hateful to wretched mortals, but to die of hunger, and so meet one\'s doom, is the most pitiful.'),(11724,' Nay, come, let us drive off the best of the kine of Helios and offer sacrifice to the immortals who hold broad heaven.'),(11725,'   And if we ever reach Ithaca, our native land, we will straightway build a rich temple to Helios Hyperion and put therein many goodly offerings. '),(11726,' And if haply he be wroth at all because of his straight-horned kine, and be minded to destroy our ship, and the other gods consent,  rather would I lose my life once for all with a gulp at the wave, than pine slowly away in a desert isle.\''),(11727,'“So spoke Eurylochus, and the rest of my comrades gave assent.'),(11728,' Straightway they drove off the best of the kine of Helios from near at hand, for not far from the dark-prowed ship  were grazing the fair, sleek kine, broad of brow. '),(11729,'Around these, then, they stood and made prayer to the gods, plucking the tender leaves from off a high-crested oak; '),(11730,' for they had no white barley on board the well-benched ship.'),(11731,'Now when they had prayed and had cut the throats of the kine and flayed them,  they cut out the thigh-pieces and covered them with a double layer of fat and laid raw flesh upon them.'),(11732,' They had no wine to pour over the blazing sacrifice, but they made libations with water, and roasted all the entrails over the fire.  '),(11733,' Now when the thighs were wholly burned and they had tasted the inner parts,  they cut up the rest and spitted it. '),(11734,'Then it was that sweet sleep fled from my eyelids, and I went my way to the swift ship and the shore of the sea.'),(11735,' But when, as I went, I drew near to the curved ship, then verily the hot savour of the fat was wafted about me,'),(11736,' and I groaned and cried aloud to the immortal gods:'),(11737,'\n“‘Father Zeus and ye other blessed gods that are for ever, verily it was for my ruin that ye lulled me in pitiless sleep, '),(11738,' while my comrades remaining behind have contrived a monstrous deed.\''),(11739,'\n“Swiftly then to Helios Hyperion came  Lampetie of the long robes, bearing tidings that we had slain his kine; '),(11740,'and straightway he spoke among the immortals, wroth at heart:'),(11741,'\n“‘Father Zeus and ye other blessed gods that are for ever, take vengeance now on the comrades of Odysseus, son of Laertes, who have insolently slain my kine, in which I  ever took delight, when I went toward the starry heaven and when I turned back again to earth from heaven.'),(11742,' If they do not pay me fit atonement for the kine I will go down to Hades and shine among the dead.\''),(11743,'\n“Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered him and said:'),(11744,'  ‘Helios, do thou verily shine on among the immortals and among mortal men upon the earth, the giver of grain.'),(11745,' As for these men I will soon smite their swift ship with my bright thunder-bolt, and shatter it to pieces in the midst of the wine-dark sea.\''),(11746,'“This I heard from fair-haired Calypso, '),(11747,' and she said that she herself had heard it from the messenger Hermes.'),(11748,'“But when I had come down to the ship and to the sea I upbraided my men, coming up to each in turn, but we could find no remedy—the kine were already dead.'),(11749,' For my men, then, the gods straightway shewed forth portents.'),(11750,'  The hides crawled, the flesh, both roast and raw, bellowed upon the spits, and there was a lowing as of kine. '),(11751,' \n“For six days, then, my trusty comrades feasted on the best of the kine of Helios which they had driven off. '),(11752,' \nBut when Zeus, the son of Cronos, brought upon us the seventh day,  then the wind ceased to blow tempestuously, and we straightway went on board, and put out into the broad sea when we had set up the mast and hoisted the white sail.'),(11753,' \n“But when we had left that island and no other land appeared, but only sky and sea,  then verily the son of Cronos set a black cloud above the hollow ship, and the sea grew dark beneath it.'),(11754,' She ran on for no long time, '),(11755,' for straightway came the shrieking West Wind, blowing with a furious tempest, and the blast of the wind snapped both the fore-stays of the mast, '),(11756,' so that the mast fell backward and all its tackling was strewn in the bilge.'),(11757,' On the stern of the ship the mast struck the head of the pilot and crushed all the bones of his skull together, '),(11758,'and like a diver he fell from the deck and his proud spirit left his bones.  '),(11759,' Therewith Zeus thundered and hurled his bolt upon the ship,'),(11760,'and she quivered from stem to stern, smitten by the bolt of Zeus, and was filled with sulphurous smoke, and my comrades fell from out the ship.'),(11761,' Like sea-crows they were borne on the waves about the black ship, and the god took from them their returning.'),(11762,'  But I kept pacing up and down the ship till the surge tore the sides from the keel, and the wave bore her on dismantled and snapped the mast off at the keel; '),(11763,' but over the mast had been flung the back-stay fashioned of ox-hide; '),(11764,'with this I lashed the two together, both keel and mast,  and sitting on these was borne by the direful winds.'),(11765,' \n“Then verily the West Wind ceased to blow tempestuously, and swiftly the South Wind came, bringing sorrow to my heart, that I might traverse again the way to baneful Charybdis.'),(11766,' All night long was I borne, and at the rising of the sun  I came to the cliff of Scylla and to dread Charybdis.'),(11767,'She verily sucked down the salt water of the sea,'),(11768,' but I, springing up to the tall fig-tree, laid hold of it, and clung to it like a bat.'),(11769,' Yet I could in no wise plant my feet firmly or climb upon the tree, '),(11770,'  for its roots spread far below and its branches hung out of reach above, long and great, and overshadowed Charybdis.'),(11771,' There I clung steadfastly until she should vomit forth mast and keel again, '),(11772,' and to my joy they came at length. '),(11773,' At the hour when a man rises from the assembly for his supper,  one that decides the many quarrels of young men that seek judgment, even at that hour those spars appeared from out Charybdis.'),(11774,' And I let go hands and feet from above and plunged down into the waters out beyond the long spars, and sitting on these I rowed onward with my hands.'),(11775,'  But as for Scylla, the father of gods and men did not suffer her again to catch sight of me, '),(11776,' else should I never have escaped utter destruction.'),(11777,'\n“Thence for nine days was I borne, and on the tenth night the gods brought me to Ogygia, where the fair-tressed Calypso dwells, dread goddess of human speech,  who gave me welcome and tendance. '),(11778,'But why should I tell thee this tale?'),(11779,'For it was but yesterday that I told it in thy hall to thyself and to thy noble wife.'),(11780,' It is an irksome thing, meseems, to tell again a plain-told tale.”'),(11781,' So he spoke, and they were all hushed in silence, and were spellbound throughout the shadowy halls.'),(11782,' And Alcinous again answered him, and said:'),(11783,'“Odysseus, since thou hast come to my  high-roofed house with floor of brass, thou shalt not, methinks, be driven back, and return with baffled purpose, even though thou hast suffered much.'),(11784,' And to each man of you that in my halls are ever wont to drink the flaming wine of the elders, and to listen to the minstrel, I speak, and give this charge.'),(11785,'  Raiment for the stranger lies already stored in the polished chest, with gold curiously wrought and all the other gifts which the counsellors of the Phaeacians brought hither.'),(11786,' But, come now, let us give him a great tripod and a cauldron, each man of us,'),(11787,'and we in turn will gather the cost from among the people,  and repay ourselves. '),(11788,' It were hard for one man to give freely, without requital.”'),(11789,'So spake Alcinous, and his word was pleasing to them.'),(11790,' They then went, each man to his house, to take their rest; but as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, they hastened to the ship and brought the bronze, that gives strength to men.'),(11791,'  And the strong and mighty Alcinous went himself throughout the ship, and carefully stowed the gifts beneath the benches, that they might not hinder any of the crew at their rowing, when they busily plied the oars. '),(11792,'Then they went to the house of Alcinous, and prepared a feast.'),(11793,'And for them the strong and mighty Alcinous sacrificed a bull  to Zeus, son of Cronos, god of the dark clouds, who is lord of all.'),(11794,' Then, when they had burned the thigh-pieces, they feasted a glorious feast, and made merry,'),(11795,' and among them the divine minstrel Demodocus, held in honor by the people, sang to the lyre.'),(11796,' But Odysseus would ever turn his head toward the blazing sun,  eager to see it set, '),(11797,'for verily he was eager to return home.'),(11798,'And as a man longs for supper, for whom all day long a yoke of wine-dark oxen has drawn the jointed plough through fallow land,'),(11799,'  and gladly for him does the light of the sun sink, that he may busy him with his supper, and his knees grow weary as he goes; '),(11800,' even so gladly for Odysseus did the light of the sun sink. '),(11801,'Straightway then he spoke among the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar, and to Alcinous above all he declared his word, and said:'),(11802,'\n“Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, pour libations now, and send ye me on my way in peace; and yourselves too—Farewell!'),(11803,'  For now all that my heart desired has been brought to pass: a convoy, and gifts of friendship.  May the gods of heaven bless them to me,'),(11804,' and on my return may I find in my home my peerless wife with those I love unscathed; '),(11805,' and may you again, remaining here, make glad  your wedded wives and children;'),(11806,'and may the gods grant you prosperity of every sort, and may no evil come upon your people.” '),(11807,' \nSo he spoke, and they all praised his words, and bade send the stranger on his way, since he had spoken fittingly.'),(11808,' Then the mighty Alcinous spoke to the herald, saying:'),(11809,'  “Pontonous, mix the bowl, and serve out wine to all in the hall, in order that, when we have made prayer to father Zeus, we may send forth the stranger to his own native land.\"'),(11810,'So he spoke, and Pontonous mixed the honey hearted wine and served out to all, coming up to each in turn; '),(11811,' and they poured libations to the blessed gods, who hold broad heaven, from where they sat.'),(11812,' But goodly Odysseus arose, and placed in the hand of Arete the two-handled cup, and spoke, and addressed her with winged words:'),(11813,'\n“Fare thee well, O queen, throughout all the years, till old age  and death come, which are the lot of mortals.'),(11814,' As for me, I go my way,'),(11815,' but do thou in this house have joy of thy children and thy people and Alcinous the king.\"'),(11816,'So the goodly Odysseus spake and passed over the threshold. And with him the mighty Alcinous sent forth a herald  to lead him to the swift ship and the shore of the sea. '),(11817,' And Arete sent with him slave women, one bearing a newly washed cloak and a tunic, and another again she bade follow to bear the strong chest, '),(11818,'and yet another bore bread and red wine.'),(11819,'\n  But when they had come down to the ship and to the sea, straightway the lordly youths that were his escort took these things, and stowed them in the hollow ship, even all the food and drink.'),(11820,' Then for Odysseus they spread a rug and a linen sheet on the deck of the hollow ship  at the stern, that he might sleep soundly; '),(11821,' and he too went aboard, and laid him down in silence.'),(11822,' Then they sat down on the benches, each in order, and loosed the hawser from the pierced stone.'),(11823,' And as soon as they leaned back, and tossed the brine with their oarblades, sweet sleep fell upon his eyelids,  an unawakening sleep, most sweet, and most like to death.'),(11824,'And as on a plain four yoked stallions spring forward all together beneath the strokes of the lash, and leaping on high swiftly accomplish their way, even so the stern of that ship leapt on high, and in her wake  the dark wave of the loud-sounding sea foamed mightily, '),(11825,' and she sped safely and surely on her way; '),(11826,' not even the circling hawk, the swiftest of winged things, could have kept pace with her.'),(11827,' Thus she sped on swiftly and clove the waves of the sea, bearing a man the peer of the gods in counsel,'),(11828,'  one who in time past had suffered many griefs at heart in passing through wars of men and the grievous waves; but now he slept in peace, forgetful of all that he had suffered. '),(11829,' \nNow when that brightest of stars rose which ever comes to herald the light of early Dawn,  even then the seafaring ship drew near to the island.'),(11830,'\nThere is in the land of Ithaca a certain harbor of Phorcys, the old man of the sea, '),(11831,' and at its mouth two projecting headlands sheer to seaward, but sloping down on the side toward the harbor.These keep back the great waves raised by heavy winds  without, '),(11832,'but within the benched ships lie unmoored when they have reached the point of anchorage.'),(11833,' At the head of the harbor is a long-leafed olive tree, and near it a pleasant, shadowy cave sacred to the nymphs that are called Naiads.'),(11834,'  Therein are mixing bowls and jars of stone, '),(11835,' and there too the bees store honey.'),(11836,'And in the cave are long looms of stone, at which the nymphs weave webs of purple dye, a wonder to behold; '),(11837,' and therein are also ever-flowing springs.'),(11838,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 13.109-13.111'),(11839,'Two doors there are to the cave,  one toward the North Wind, by which men go down, but that toward the South Wind is sacred, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 109 to line 111'),(11840,'\nHere they rowed in, knowing the place of old; '),(11841,' and the ship ran full half her length on the shore  in her swift course,'),(11842,' at such pace was she driven by the arms of the rowers.'),(11843,'Then they stepped forth from the benched ship upon the land, and first they lifted Odysseus out of the hollow ship, with the linen sheet and bright rug as they were, and laid him down on the sand, still overpowered by sleep.  And they lifted out the goods which the lordly Phaeacians had given him, as he set out for home, through the favour of great-hearted Athena.'),(11844,' These they set all together by the trunk of the olive tree, out of the path, lest haply some wayfarer, before Odysseus awoke, might come upon them and spoil them.'),(11845,'  Then they themselves returned home again.'),(11846,' But the Shaker of the Earth did not forget the threats wherewith at the first he had threatened godlike Odysseus, and he thus enquired of the purpose of Zeus:'),(11847,'\n“Father Zeus, no longer shall I, even I, be held in honor among the immortal gods, seeing that mortals honor me not a whit—  even the Phaeacians, who, thou knowest, are of my own lineage.'),(11848,' For I but now declared that Odysseus should suffer many woes ere he reached his home,'),(11849,' though I did not wholly rob him of his return when once thou hadst promised it and confirmed it with thy nod; '),(11850,' yet in his sleep these men have borne him in a swift ship over the sea  and set him down in Ithaca, and have given him gifts past telling, stores of bronze and gold and woven raiment, more than Odysseus would ever have won for himself from Troy, if he had returned unscathed with his due share of the spoil.” '),(11851,' \nThen Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered him, and said: '),(11852,' \n “Ah me, thou shaker of the earth, wide of sway, what a thing hast thou said!'),(11853,' The gods do thee no dishonor;'),(11854,' hard indeed would it be to assail with dishonor our eldest and best.'),(11855,' But as for men, if any one, yielding to his might and strength, fails to do thee honor in aught, '),(11856,'thou mayest ever take vengeance, even thereafter.'),(11857,' Do as thou wilt, and as is thy good pleasure.”'),(11858,'Then Poseidon, the earth-shaker, answered him:'),(11859,' “Straightway should I have done as thou sayest, thou god of the dark clouds,'),(11860,' but I ever dread and avoid thy wrath.'),(11861,'But now I am minded to smite the fair ship of the Phaeacians,  as she comes back from his convoy on the misty deep, that hereafter they may desist and cease from giving convoy to men, and to fling a great mountain about their city.\"'),(11862,'Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered him and said: '),(11863,' “Lazy one, hear what seems best in my sight. When all the people are looking forth from the city upon her as she speeds on her way, then do thou turn her to stone hard by the land—a stone in the shape of a swift ship, that all men may marvel; and do thou fling a great mountain about their city.\"'),(11864,'Now when Poseidon, the earth-shaker, heard this  he went his way to Scheria, where the Phaeacians dwell, '),(11865,'and there he waited.'),(11866,' And she drew close to shore, the seafaring ship, speeding swiftly on her way.'),(11867,' Then near her came the Earth-shaker and turned her to stone, and rooted her fast beneath by a blow of the flat of his hand, and then he was gone.'),(11868,'and then he was gone.'),(11869,'\n  But they spoke winged words to one another, the Phaeacians of the long oars, men famed for their ships.'),(11870,' And thus would one speak, with a glance at his neighbor:'),(11871,'\n“Ah me, who has now bound our swift ship on the sea as she sped homeward?'),(11872,' Lo, she was in plain sight.\"'),(11873,'but they knew not how these things were to be. '),(11874,'but they knew not how these things were to be. '),(11875,'Then Alcinous addressed their company and said:'),(11876,'\n“Lo now, verily the oracles of my father, uttered long ago, have come upon me. He was wont to say that Poseidon was wroth with us because we give safe convoy to all men.'),(11877,'  He said that some day, as a beautiful ship of the Phaeacians was returning from a convoy over the misty deep, Poseidon would smite her, and would fling a great mountain about our town.'),(11878,' and lo, now all this is being brought to pass.'),(11879,' and lo, now all this is being brought to pass.'),(11880,' But now come, as I bid let us all obey.'),(11881,'  Cease ye to give convoy to mortals, when anyone comes to our city, '),(11882,'and let us sacrifice to Poseidon twelve choice bulls, if haply he may take pity, and not fling a lofty mountain about our town.” '),(11883,' \nSo he spoke, and they were seized with fear and made ready the bulls.'),(11884,'  Thus they were praying to the lord Poseidon, the leaders and counsellors of the land of the Phaeacians, as they stood about the altar, '),(11885,' but Odysseus awoke out of his sleep in his native land. Yet he knew it not after his long absence,'),(11886,'for about him the goddess had shed a mist,  even Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus, that she might render him unknown, and tell him all things, so that his wife might not know him, nor his townsfolk, nor his friends, until the wooers had paid the full price of all their transgressions.'),(11887,' Therefore all things seemed strange to their lord,  the long paths, the bays offering safe anchorage, the sheer cliffs, and the luxuriant trees.'),(11888,' So he sprang up and stood and looked upon his native land, '),(11889,' and then he groaned and smote both of his thighs with the flat of his hands, and mournfully spoke, and said:'),(11890,'  “Woe is me, to the land of what mortals am I now come?'),(11891,' Are they cruel, and wild, and unjust, or do they love strangers and fear the gods in their thoughts?'),(11892,' Whither shall I bear all this wealth, '),(11893,' or whither shall I myself go wandering on? '),(11894,'Would that I had remained there among the Phaeacians, '),(11895,' and had then come to some other of the mighty kings, who would have entertained me and sent me on my homeward way.'),(11896,' But now I know not where to bestow this wealth; yet here will I not leave it, lest haply it become the spoil of others to my cost.'),(11897,' Out upon them; not wholly wise, it seems, nor just  were the leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians who have brought me to a strange land. Verily they said that they would bring me to clear-seen Ithaca, but they have not made good their word.'),(11898,' May Zeus, the suppliant\'s god, requite them, who watches over all men, and punishes him that sins.'),(11899,'  But come, I will number the goods, and go over them, lest to my cost these men have carried off aught with them in the hollow ship.” '),(11900,' \nSo he spake, and set him to count the beautiful tripods, and the cauldrons, and the gold, and the fair woven raiment, '),(11901,' and of these he missed nothing. '),(11902,'Then, mournfully longing for his native land,  he paced by the shore of the loud-sounding sea, uttering many a moan.'),(11903,' And Athena drew near him in the form of a young man, a herdsman of sheep, one most delicate, as are the sons of princes. In a double fold about her shoulders she wore a well-wrought cloak,'),(11904,'  and beneath her shining feet she had sandals, and in her hands a spear. '),(11905,' Then Odysseus was glad at sight of her, and came to meet her, and he spoke, and addressed her with winged words:'),(11906,'\n“Friend, since thou art the first to whom I have come in this land, hail to thee, and mayst thou meet me with no evil mind.  Nay, save this treasure, and save me;'),(11907,'  for to thee do I pray, as to a god, and am come to thy dear knees.'),(11908,' And tell me this also truly, that I may know full well.'),(11909,' What land, what people is this? What men dwell here?'),(11910,' Is it some clear-seen island, or a shore  of the deep-soiled mainland that lies resting on the sea?”'),(11911,'\nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(11912,' “A fool art thou, stranger, or art come from far, if indeed thou askest of this land.'),(11913,' Surely it is no wise so nameless, '),(11914,'but full many know it,  both all those who dwell toward the dawn and the sun, and all those that are behind toward the murky darkness.'),(11915,' It is a rugged isle, not fit for driving horses, yet it is not utterly poor, though it be but narrow.'),(11916,' Therein grows corn beyond measure, and the wine-grape as well,'),(11917,' and the rain never fails it, nor the rich dew.'),(11918,' It is a good land for pasturing goats and kine;'),(11919,' there are trees of every sort, and in it also pools for watering that fail not the year through.'),(11920,' Therefore, stranger, the name of Ithaca has reached even to the land of Troy which, they say, is far from this land of Achaea.” '),(11921,' \n  So she spake, and the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus was glad, and rejoiced in his land, the land of his fathers, as he heard the word of Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus, who bears the aegis; '),(11922,'  and he spoke, and addressed her with winged words; '),(11923,' yet he spoke not the truth, but checked the word ere it was uttered,  ever revolving in his breast thoughts of great cunning:'),(11924,'“I heard of Ithaca, even in broad Crete, far over the sea;'),(11925,'\n and now have I myself come hither with these my goods. '),(11926,'And I left as much more with my children, when I fled the land, after I had slain the dear son of Idomeneus,  Orsilochus, swift of foot, who in broad Crete surpassed in fleetness all men that live by toil. Now he would have robbed me of all that booty of Troy, for which I had borne grief of heart, passing through wars of men and the grievous waves,  for that I would not shew favour to his father, and serve as his squire in the land of the Trojans, but commanded other men of my own.'),(11927,' So I smote him with my bronze-tipped spear as he came home from the field, lying in wait for him with one of my men by the roadside.'),(11928,' A dark night covered the heavens, and no  man was ware of us, but unseen I took away his life.'),(11929,' Now when I had slain him with the sharp bronze, I went straightway to a ship, and made prayer to the lordly Phoenicians, giving them booty to satisfy their hearts.'),(11930,' I bade them take me aboard and land me at Pylos,  or at goodly Elis, where the Epeans hold sway. '),(11931,'Yet verily the force of the wind thrust them away from thence, sore against their will, nor did they purpose to play me false; '),(11932,' but driven wandering from thence we came hither by night.'),(11933,'With eager haste we rowed on into the harbor, nor had we any  thought of supper, sore as was our need of it, but even as we were we went forth from the ship and lay down, one and all.'),(11934,' Then upon me came sweet sleep in my weariness, but they took my goods out of the hollow ship and set them where I myself lay on the sands.'),(11935,'  And they went on board, and departed for the well-peopled land of Sidon; '),(11936,'but I was left here, my heart sore troubled.” '),(11937,' \nSo he spoke, and the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, smiled, and stroked him with her hand, '),(11938,'and changed herself to the form of a woman, comely and tall, and skilled in glorious handiwork.'),(11939,'  And she spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(11940,'\n“Cunning must he be and knavish, who would go beyond thee in all manner of guile, aye, though it were a god that met thee.'),(11941,' Bold man, crafty in counsel, insatiate in deceit, not even in thine own land, it seems, wast thou to cease from guile  and deceitful tales, which thou lovest from the bottom of thine heart. '),(11942,' But come, let us no longer talk of this, being both well versed in craft, since thou art far the best of all men in counsel and in speech, and I among all the gods am famed for wisdom and craft.'),(11943,' Yet thou didst not know  Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus, even me, who ever stand by thy side, and guard thee in all toils. Aye, and I made thee beloved by all the Phaeacians. And now am I come hither to weave a plan with thee, and to hide all the treasure, which the lordly Phaeacians  gave thee by my counsel and will, when thou didst set out for home; and to tell thee all the measure of woe it is thy fate to fulfil in thy well-built house.'),(11944,' But do thou be strong, for bear it thou must, and tell no man of them all nor any woman that thou hast come back from thy wanderings, but in silence  endure thy many griefs, and submit to the violence of men.”'),(11945,'\nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(11946,' “Hard is it, goddess, for a mortal man to know thee when he meets thee, how wise soever he be, '),(11947,'for thou takest what shape thou wilt.'),(11948,' But this I know well, that of old thou wast kindly toward me,  so long as we sons of the Achaeans were warring in the land of Troy.'),(11949,'But after we had sacked the lofty city of Priam, and had gone away in our ships, and a god had scattered the Achaeans, never since then have I seen thee, daughter of Zeus, nor marked thee coming on board my ship, that thou mightest ward off sorrow from me.'),(11950,'  Nay, I ever wandered on, bearing in my breast a stricken heart, till the gods delivered me from evil,'),(11951,'  even until in the rich land of the Phaeacians thou didst cheer me with thy words, and thyself lead me to their city.'),(11952,' But now I beseech thee by thy father—for I think not  that I am come to clear-seen Ithaca; nay, it is some other land over which I roam, '),(11953,'and thou, methinks, dost speak thus in mockery to beguile my mind—tell me whether in very truth I am come to my dear native land.” '),(11954,' \nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(11955,'  “Ever such is the thought in thy breast,'),(11956,' and therefore it is that I cannot leave thee in thy sorrow, for thou art soft of speech, keen of wit, and prudent.'),(11957,' Eagerly would another man on his return from wanderings have hastened to behold in his halls his children and his wife;'),(11958,' but thou art not yet minded to know or learn of aught, till thou hast furthermore proved thy wife, who abides as of old in her halls, and ever sorrowfully for her the nights and days wane, as she weeps.'),(11959,' But as for me, I never doubted of this, but in my heart  knew it well, that thou wouldest come home after losing all thy comrades. '),(11960,'Yet, thou must know, I was not minded to strive against Poseidon, my father\'s brother, who laid up wrath in his heart against thee, angered that thou didst blind his dear son.'),(11961,' But come, I will shew thee the land of Ithaca, that thou mayest be sure.'),(11962,'  This is the harbor of Phorcys, the old man of the sea, and here at the head of the harbor is the long-leafed olive tree, '),(11963,'and near it is the pleasant, shadowy cave, sacred to the nymphs that are called Naiads.'),(11964,' This, thou must know, is the vaulted cave in which thou  wast wont to offer to the nymphs many hecatombs that bring fulfillment; '),(11965,'and yonder is Mount Neriton, clothed with its forests.\"'),(11966,'So spake the goddess, and scattered the mist, and the land appeared.'),(11967,' Glad then was the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus, rejoicing in his own land, and he kissed the earth, the giver of grain.'),(11968,'  And straightway he prayed to the nymphs with upstretched hands:'),(11969,'“Ye Naiad Nymphs, daughters of Zeus, never did I think to behold you again,'),(11970,' but now I hail you with loving prayers. '),(11971,'Aye, and gifts too will I give, as aforetime, if the daughter of Zeus, she that drives the spoil, shall graciously grant me  to live, and shall bring to manhood my dear son.\"'),(11972,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him again:'),(11973,' “Be of good cheer, and let not these things distress thy heart.'),(11974,' But let us now forthwith set thy goods in the innermost recess of the wondrous cave, where they may abide for thee in safety, '),(11975,'  and let us ourselves take thought how all may be far the best.”'),(11976,' \nSo saying, the goddess entered the shadowy cave and searched out its hiding-places.'),(11977,' And Odysseus brought all the treasure thither, the gold and the stubborn bronze and the finely-wrought raiment, which the Phaeacians gave him.'),(11978,'  These things he carefully laid away, and Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus, who bears the aegis, set a stone at the door.'),(11979,' Then the two sat them down by the trunk of the sacred olive tree, and devised death for the insolent wooers.'),(11980,' And the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, was the first to speak, saying:'),(11981,'\n  “Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, take thought how thou mayest put forth thy hands on the shameless wooers, who now for three years have been lording it in thy halls, wooing thy godlike wife, and offering wooers\' gifts. '),(11982,' And she, as she mournfully looks for thy coming,  offers hopes to all, and has promises for each man, sending them messages, but her mind is set on other things.\"'),(11983,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(11984,' “Lo now, of a surety I was like to have perished in my halls by the evil fate of Agamemnon, son of Atreus,  hadst not thou, goddess, duly told me all.'),(11985,'  But come, weave some plan by which I may requite them;'),(11986,' and stand thyself by my side, and endue me with dauntless courage, even as when we loosed the bright diadem of Troy. '),(11987,' Wouldest thou but stand by my side, thou flashing-eyed one, as eager as thou wast then,  I would fight even against three hundred men, with thee, mighty goddess, if with a ready heart thou wouldest give me aid.\"'),(11988,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(11989,' “Yea verily, I will be with thee, and will not forget thee, when we are busied with this work; '),(11990,'and methinks many a one  of the wooers that devour thy substance shall bespatter the vast earth with his blood and brains.'),(11991,' But come, I will make thee unknown to all mortals. '),(11992,' I will shrivel the fair skin on thy supple limbs, and destroy the flaxen hair from off thy head, and clothe thee in a ragged garment,  such that one would shudder to see a man clad therein. And I will dim thy two eyes that were before so beautiful, that thou mayest appear mean in the sight of all the wooers, and of thy wife, and of thy son, whom thou didst leave in thy halls. '),(11993,'And for thyself, do thou go first of all  to the swineherd who keeps thy swine, and withal has a kindly heart towards thee, and loves thy son and constant Penelope.'),(11994,'Thou wilt find him abiding by the swine,'),(11995,'  and they are feeding by the rock of Corax and the spring Arethusa, eating acorns to their heart\'s content and  drinking the black water, things which cause the rich flesh of swine to wax fat. '),(11996,'There do thou stay, and sitting by his side question him of all things, while I go to Sparta, the land of fair women, to summon thence Telemachus, thy dear son, Odysseus, '),(11997,' who went to spacious Lacedaemon to the house of Menelaus,  to seek tidings of thee, if thou wast still anywhere alive.”'),(11998,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered her:'),(11999,' “Why then, I pray thee, didst thou not tell him, thou whose mind knows all things?'),(12000,' Nay, was it haply that he too might suffer woes, wandering over the unresting sea, '),(12001,' and that others might devour his substance?\"'),(12002,'  Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him: '),(12003,' “Nay verily, not for him be thy heart overmuch troubled.'),(12004,' It was I that guided him, that he might win good report by going thither, '),(12005,' and he has no toil, but sits in peace in the palace of the son of Atreus, and good cheer past telling is before him.'),(12006,'  Truly young men in a black ship lie in wait for him, eager to slay him before he comes to his native land, '),(12007,' but methinks this shall not be. Ere that shall the earth cover many a one of the wooers that devour thy substance.\"'),(12008,'So saying, Athena touched him with her wand.'),(12009,'  She withered the fair flesh on his supple limbs, and destroyed the flaxen hair from off his head, and about all his limbs she put the skin of an aged old man. And she dimmed his two eyes that were before so beautiful,'),(12010,'  and clothed him in other raiment,  a vile ragged cloak and a tunic, tattered garments and foul, begrimed with filthy smoke.'),(12011,'And about him she cast the great skin of a swift hind, stripped of the hair,'),(12012,'  and she gave him a staff, and a miserable wallet, full of holes, '),(12013,'slung by a twisted cord.'),(12014,'\nSo when the two had thus taken counsel together, they parted; '),(12015,'and thereupon the goddess went to goodly Lacedaemon to fetch the son of Odysseus.'),(12016,' But Odysseus went forth from the harbor by the rough path up over the woodland and through the heights to the place where Athena had shewed him that he should find the goodly swineherd, who cared for his substance above all the slaves that goodly Odysseus had gotten.'),(12017,'\n  He found him sitting in the fore-hall of his house, where his court was built high in a place of wide outlook, a great and goodly court with an open space around it.'),(12018,' This the swineherd had himself built for the swine of his master, that was gone, without the knowledge of his mistress and the old man Laertes. With huge stones had he built it, and set on it a coping of thorn.'),(12019,'  Without he had driven stakes the whole length, this way and that, huge stakes, set close together, which he had made by splitting an oak to the black core;'),(12020,' and within the court he had made twelve sties close by one another, as beds for the swine, '),(12021,' and in each one  were penned fifty wallowing swine, females for breeding; '),(12022,'but the boars slept without. These were far fewer in numbers,'),(12023,'for on them the godlike wooers feasted, and lessened them, for the swineherd ever sent in the best of all the fatted hogs,'),(12024,'for on them the godlike wooers feasted, and lessened them, for the swineherd ever sent in the best of all the fatted hogs,'),(12025,' By these ever slept four dogs, savage as wild beasts, which the swineherd had reared, a leader of men.'),(12026,' But he himself was fitting boots about his feet, cutting an ox-hide of good color, '),(12027,'while the others  had gone, three of them, one here one there, with the droves of swine;'),(12028,'and the fourth he had sent to the city to drive perforce a boar to the insolent wooers, that they might slay it and satisfy their souls with meat.'),(12029,'\nSuddenly then the baying hounds caught sight of Odysseus, '),(12030,' and rushed upon him with loud barking, '),(12031,' but Odysseus sat down in his cunning, and the staff fell from his hand.'),(12032,' Then even in his own farmstead would he have suffered cruel hurt,'),(12033,'but the swineherd with swift steps followed after them, and hastened through the gateway, and the hide fell from his hand.'),(12034,'  He called aloud to the dogs, and drove them this way and that with a shower of stones, '),(12035,' and spoke to his master, and said:'),(12036,'\n“Old man, verily the dogs were like to have torn thee to pieces all of a sudden, and on me thou wouldest have shed reproach.'),(12037,' Aye, and the gods have given me other griefs and sorrow.'),(12038,'  It is for a godlike master that I mourn and grieve, as I abide here, and rear fat swine for other men to eat,'),(12039,'while he haply in want of food wanders over the land and city of men of strange speech, if indeed he still lives and sees the light of the sun.'),(12040,'  But come with me, let us go to the hut, old man, that when thou hast satisfied thy heart with food and wine, thou too mayest tell whence thou art, and all the woes thou hast endured.” '),(12041,' \nSo saying, the goodly swineherd led him to the hut, and brought him in, and made him sit, strowing beneath thick brushwood,  and thereon spreading the skin of a shaggy wild goat, large and hairy, on which he was himself wont to sleep.'),(12042,' And Odysseus was glad that he gave him such welcome, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(12043,'\n“Stranger, may Zeus and the other immortal gods grant thee what most thou desirest, since thou with a ready heart hast given me welcome.\"'),(12044,'  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say:'),(12045,'“Nay, stranger, it were not right for me, even though one meaner than thou were to come, to slight a stranger:'),(12046,' for from Zeus are all strangers and beggars,'),(12047,'  and a gift, though small, is welcome from such as we; '),(12048,'since this is the lot of slaves,  ever in fear when over them as lords their masters hold sway—young masters such as ours.'),(12049,'For verily the gods have stayed the return of him who would have loved me with all kindness, and would have given me possessions of my own, a house and a bit of land, and a wife, sought of many wooers, even such things as a kindly master gives to his thrall  who has toiled much for him, and whose labour the god makes to prosper, even as this work of mine prospers, to which I give heed.'),(12050,' Therefore would my master have richly rewarded me, if he had grown old here at home:'),(12051,' Therefore would my master have richly rewarded me, if he had grown old here at home:'),(12052,'  For he too went forth to win recompense for Agamemnon to Ilios, famed for its horses, that he might fight with the Trojans.” '),(12053,' \nSo saying, he quickly bound up his tunic with his belt, and went to the sties, where the tribes of swine were penned.'),(12054,' Choosing two from thence, he brought them in and slew them both,  and singed, and cut them up, and spitted them. '),(12055,'Then, when he had roasted all, he brought and set it before Odysseus, hot upon the spits, '),(12056,' and sprinkled over it white barley meal.'),(12057,' Then in a bowl of ivy wood he mixed honey-sweet wine, and himself sat down over against Odysseus, and bade him to his food, and said:'),(12058,'\n  “Eat now, stranger, such food as slaves have to offer, meat of young pigs;'),(12059,'the fatted hogs the wooers eat, who reck not in their hearts of the wrath of the gods, nor have any pity.'),(12060,' Verily the blessed gods love not reckless deeds, but they honor justice and the righteous deeds of men.'),(12061,'  Even cruel foemen that set foot on the land of others, and Zeus gives them booty, and they fill their ships and depart for home—even on the hearts of these falls great fear of the wrath of the gods.'),(12062,' But these men here, look you, know somewhat, and have heard some voice of a god  regarding my master\'s pitiful death, seeing that they will not woo righteously, nor go back to their own, but at their ease they waste our substance in insolent wise, and there is no sparing.'),(12063,' For every day and night that comes from Zeus they sacrifice not one victim nor two alone, '),(12064,' and they draw forth wine, and waste it in insolent wise.'),(12065,' Verily his substance was great past telling,'),(12066,' so much has no lord either on the dark mainland or in Ithaca itself; '),(12067,' nay, not twenty men together have wealth so great.'),(12068,'Lo, I will tell thee the tale thereof; '),(12069,' twelve herds of kine has he on the mainland; '),(12070,' as many flocks of sheep; as many droves of swine; as many packed herds of goats do herdsmen, both foreigners and of his own people, pasture.'),(12071,' And here too graze roving herds of goats on the borders of the island, eleven in all, and over them trusty men keep watch.'),(12072,'  And each man of these ever drives up day by day one of his flock for the wooers, even that one of the fatted goats which seems to him the best.'),(12073,' But as for me, I guard and keep these swine, and choose out with care and send them the best of the boars.” '),(12074,' \nSo he spoke, but Odysseus eagerly ate flesh and drank wine,  greedily, in silence, and was sowing the seeds of evil for the wooers. '),(12075,' But when he had dined, and satisfied his soul with food, then the swineherd filled the bowl from which he was himself wont to drink, and gave it him brim full of wine, '),(12076,' and he took it, and was glad at heart; and he spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(12077,'\n  “Friend, who was it who bought thee with his wealth, a man so very rich and mighty, as thou tellest?'),(12078,' Thou saidest that he died to win recompense for Agamemnon;'),(12079,' tell me, if haply I may know him, being such an one.'),(12080,' For Zeus, I ween, and the other immortal gods know  whether I have seen him, and could bring tidings;'),(12081,' for I have wandered far.\"'),(12082,'Then the swineherd, a leader of men, answered him:'),(12083,' “Old man, no wanderer that came and brought tidings of him could persuade his wife and his dear son; nay, at random, when they have need of entertainment, do vagabonds  lie, and are not minded to speak the truth. '),(12084,' Whosoever in his wanderings comes to the land of Ithaca, goes to my mistress and tells a deceitful tale.'),(12085,' And she, receiving him kindly, gives him entertainment, and questions him of all things, and the tears fall from her eyelids, while she weeps,  as is the way of a woman, when her husband dies afar. '),(12086,' And readily wouldest thou too, old man, fashion a story, '),(12087,' if one would give thee a cloak and a tunic for raiment.'),(12088,'But as for him, ere now dogs and swift birds are like to have torn the flesh from his bones, and his spirit has left him; '),(12089,' or in the sea fishes have eaten him, and his bones lie there on the shore, wrapped in deep sand.'),(12090,' Thus has he perished yonder, and to his friends grief is appointed for days to come, to all, but most of all to me. '),(12091,' For never again shall I find a master so kind, how far soever I go,  not though I come again to the house of my father and mother, where at the first I was born, and they reared me themselves.'),(12092,' Yet it is not for them that I henceforth mourn so much, eager though I am to behold them with my eyes and to be in my native land; '),(12093,' nay, it is longing for Odysseus, who is gone, that seizes me.'),(12094,'  His name, stranger, absent though he is, I speak with awe, '),(12095,'for greatly did he love me and care for me at heart; '),(12096,' but I call him my lord beloved, for all he is not here.” '),(12097,' \nThen the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him:'),(12098,' “Friend, since thou dost utterly make denial, and declarest  that he will never come again, and thy heart is ever unbelieving, '),(12099,'therefore will I tell thee, not at random but with an oath, that Odysseus shall return.'),(12100,' And let me have a reward for bearing good tidings, as soon as he shall come, and reach his home; '),(12101,'clothe me in a cloak and tunic, goodly raiment.'),(12102,'  But ere that, how sore soever my need, I will accept naught;'),(12103,' for hateful in my eyes as the gates of Hades is that man, who, yielding to stress of poverty, tells a deceitful tale.'),(12104,' Now be my witness Zeus, above all gods, and this hospitable board, and the hearth of noble Odysseus to which I am come,'),(12105,' that verily all these things shall be brought to pass even as I tell thee.'),(12106,' In the course of this self-same day Odysseus shall come hither,'),(12107,' as the old moon wanes, and the new appears. He shall return, and take vengeance on all those who here dishonor his wife and his glorious son.\"'),(12108,'  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say: '),(12109,'“Old man, neither shall I, meseems, pay thee this reward for bearing good tidings, nor shall Odysseus ever come to his home.'),(12110,' Nay, drink in peace, and let us turn our thoughts to other things, and do not thou recall this to my mind; '),(12111,'for verily the heart in my breast  is grieved whenever any one makes mention of my good master. '),(12112,'But as for thy oath, we will let it be; yet I would that Odysseus might come, even as I desire, I, and Penelope, and the old man Laertes, and godlike Telemachus.'),(12113,' But now it is for his son that I grieve unceasingly,  even for Telemachus, whom Odysseus begot.'),(12114,' When the gods had made him grow like a sapling, and I thought that he would be among men no whit worse than his dear father, glorious in form and comeliness, then some one of the immortals marred the wise spirit within him, or haply some man,'),(12115,' and he went  to sacred Pylos after tidings of his father. '),(12116,' For him now the lordly wooers lie in wait on his homeward way, that the race of godlike Arceisius may perish out of Ithaca, and leave no name.'),(12117,' But verily we will let him be; he may be taken, or he may escape, and the son of Cronos stretch forth his hand to guard him.'),(12118,'  But come, do thou, old man, tell me of thine own sorrows, and declare me this truly, that I may know full well.'),(12119,'  Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(12120,'  Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(12121,' On what manner of ship didst thou come,'),(12122,' and how did sailors bring thee to Ithaca?'),(12123,'Who did they declare themselves to be?'),(12124,'  For nowise, methinks, didst thou come hither on foot.”'),(12125,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: “Then verily I will frankly tell thee all.'),(12126,' Would that now we two might have food and sweet wine for the while,  to feast on in quiet here in thy hut, and that others might go about their work; '),(12127,'easily then might I tell on for a full year, and yet in no wise finish the tale of the woes of my spirit—even all the toils that I have endured by the will of the gods.'),(12128,'\n“From broad Crete I declare that I am come by lineage,  the son of a wealthy man.'),(12129,' And many other sons too were born and bred in his halls, true sons of a lawful wife; '),(12130,' but the mother that bore me was bought, a concubine. Yet Castor, son of Hylax, of whom I declare that I am sprung, honored me even as his true-born sons.  He was at that time honored as a god among the Cretans in the land for his good estate, and his wealth, and his glorious sons.'),(12131,' But the fates of death bore him away to the house of Hades, '),(12132,'and his proud sons divided among them his substance, and cast lots therefor. To me they gave a very small portion, and allotted a dwelling.'),(12133,'  But I took unto me a wife from a house that had wide possessions, winning her by my valor; for I was no weakling, nor a coward in fight.'),(12134,' Now all that strength is gone; yet even so, in seeing the stubble, methinks  thou mayest judge what the grain was; '),(12135,'for verily troubles in full measure encompass me. '),(12136,'But then Ares and Athena gave me courage, and strength that breaks the ranks of men; '),(12137,' and whenever I picked the best warriors for an ambush, sowing the seeds of evil for the foe, never did my proud spirit forbode death,  but ever far the first did I leap forth, and slay with my spear whosoever of the foe gave way in flight before me.'),(12138,' Such a man was I in war, '),(12139,'but labour in the field was never to my liking, nor the care of a household, which rears goodly children, but oared ships were ever dear to me,  and wars, and polished spears, and arrows,—grievous things, whereat others are wont to shudder.'),(12140,'  But those things, I ween, were dear to me, which a god put in my heart; '),(12141,' for different men take joy in different works.'),(12142,'For before the sons of the Achaeans set foot on the land of Troy,  I had nine times led warriors and swift-faring ships against foreign folk, and great spoil had ever fallen to my hands. '),(12143,' Of this I would choose what pleased my mind, and much I afterwards obtained by lot. '),(12144,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 14.233-14.234'),(12145,' \n  “But when Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, devised that hateful journey which loosened the knees of many a warrior, then they bade me and glorious Idomeneus to lead the ships to Ilios,'),(12146,' nor was there any way to refuse, for the voice of the people pressed hard upon us.'),(12147,'  There for nine years we sons of the Achaeans warred, and in the tenth we sacked the city of Priam, and set out for home in our ships, and a god scattered the Achaeans.'),(12148,' But for me, wretched man that I was, Zeus, the counsellor, devised evil.'),(12149,' For a month only I remained, taking joy in my children,  my wedded wife, and my wealth; '),(12150,'and then to Egypt did my spirit bid me voyage with my godlike comrades, when I had fitted out my ships with care. '),(12151,' Nine ships I fitted out, and the host gathered speedily.'),(12152,'Then for six days my trusty comrades  feasted, '),(12153,' and I gave them many victims, that they might sacrifice to the gods, and prepare a feast for themselves; '),(12154,'and on the seventh we embarked and set sail from broad Crete, with the North Wind blowing fresh and fair, and ran on easily as if down stream. '),(12155,'No  harm came to any of my ships, but free from scathe and from disease we sat, and the wind and the helmsman guided the ships.'),(12156,' “On the fifth day we came to fair-flowing Aegyptus, and in the river Aegyptus I moored my curved ships.'),(12157,' Then verily I bade my trusty comrades  to remain there by the ships, and to guard the ships, and I sent out scouts to go to places of outlook. '),(12158,' But my comrades, yielding to wantonness, and led on by their own might, straightway set about wasting the fair fields of the men of Egypt; and they carried off the women and little children,  and slew the men; '),(12159,'and the cry came quickly to the city. '),(12160,'Then, hearing the shouting, the people came forth at break of day, '),(12161,'and the whole plain was filled with footmen, and chariots and the flashing of bronze.'),(12162,' But Zeus who hurls the thunderbolt cast an evil panic upon my comrades, and none had the courage  to hold his ground and face the foe;'),(12163,' for evil surrounded us on every side.'),(12164,' So then they slew many of us with the sharp bronze, and others they led up to their city alive, to work for them perforce.'),(12165,' But in my heart Zeus himself put this thought—I would that I had rather died and met my fate  there in Egypt, '),(12166,'for still was sorrow to give me welcome. Straightway I put off from my head my well-wrought helmet, and the shield from off my shoulders, and let the spear fall from my hand, '),(12167,' and went toward the chariot horses of the king. I clasped, and kissed his knees, '),(12168,'and he delivered me, and took pity on me,  and, setting me in his chariot, took me weeping to his home. '),(12169,' Verily full many rushed upon me with their ashen spears, eager to slay me, for they were exceeding angry. But he warded them off, and had regard for the wrath of Zeus, the stranger\'s god, who above all others hath indignation at evil deeds. '),(12170,' \n  “There then I stayed seven years, and much wealth did I gather among the Egyptians, '),(12171,' for all men gave me gifts.'),(12172,' But when the eighth circling year was come, then there came a man of Phoenicia, well versed in guile, a greedy knave, who had already wrought much evil among men.'),(12173,'  He prevailed upon me by his cunning, and took me with him, until we reached Phoenicia, where lay his house and his possessions.'),(12174,' There I remained with him for a full year. '),(12175,'But when at length the months and the days were being brought to fulfillment, as the year rolled round and the seasons came on,  he set me on a seafaring ship bound for Libya, having given lying counsel to the end that I should convey a cargo with him, but in truth that, when there, he might sell me and get a vast price.'),(12176,' So I went with him on board the ship, suspecting his guile, yet perforce.'),(12177,' And she ran before the North Wind, blowing fresh and fair,  on a mid-sea course to the windward of Crete, '),(12178,' and Zeus devised destruction for the men.'),(12179,'  But when we had left Crete, and no other land appeared, but only sky and sea,  then verily the son of Cronos set a black cloud above the hollow ship, and the sea grew dark beneath it.'),(12180,'Therewith Zeus thundered, and hurled his bolt upon the ship, '),(12181,'and she quivered from stem to stern, smitten by the bolt of Zeus, and was filled with sulphurous smoke, '),(12182,' and all the crew fell from out the ship.'),(12183,'Like sea-crows they were borne on the waves about the black ship,'),(12184,'  and the god took from them their returning.'),(12185,'  But as for me, Zeus himself when my heart was compassed with woe, put into my hands the tossing mast of the dark-prowed ship, that I might again escape destruction.'),(12186,' Around this I clung, and was borne by the direful winds. '),(12187,'For nine days I was borne, but on the tenth black night  the great rolling wave brought me to the land of the Thesprotians.'),(12188,'There the king of the Thesprotians, lord Pheidon, took me in, and asked no ransom,'),(12189,'  for his dear son came upon me, overcome as I was with cold and weariness, and raised me by the hand, and led me until he came to his father\'s palace; '),(12190,' and he clothed me in a cloak and tunic, as raiment.'),(12191,' \n“There I learned of Odysseus,'),(12192,' for the king said that he had entertained him, and given him welcome on his way to his native land. And he showed me all the treasure that Odysseus had gathered, bronze, and gold, and iron, wrought with toil; '),(12193,' verily unto the tenth generation would it feed his children after him, '),(12194,'so great was the wealth that lay stored for him in the halls of the king.'),(12195,' But Odysseus, he said, had gone to Dodona, to hear the will of Zeus from the high-crested oak of the god, even how he might return to the rich land of Ithaca  after so long an absence, whether openly or in secret.'),(12196,' And moreover he swore in my own presence, as he poured libations in his house, that the ship was launched, and the men ready, who were to convey him to his dear native land.'),(12197,' But me he sent forth first,'),(12198,' for a ship  of the Thesprotians chanced to be setting out for Dulichium, rich in wheat. '),(12199,'Thither he bade them to convey me with kindly care, to king Acastus.'),(12200,' But an evil counsel regarding me found favour in their hearts, that I might even yet be brought into utter misery.'),(12201,' When the sea-faring ship had sailed far from the land,  they presently sought to bring about for me the day of slavery.'),(12202,' They stripped me of my garments, my cloak and tunic, and clothed me in other raiment, a vile ragged cloak and tunic, even the tattered garments which thou seest before thine eyes;'),(12203,' and at evening they reached the tilled fields of clear-seen Ithaca.'),(12204,'  Then with a twisted rope they bound me fast in the benched ship, and themselves went ashore, and made haste to take their supper by the shore of the sea.'),(12205,' But as for me, the gods themselves undid my bonds full easily, '),(12206,'and, wrapping the tattered cloak about my head,  I slid down the smooth lading-plank, and brought my breast to the sea, and then struck out with both hands, and swam, and very soon was out of the water, and away from them.'),(12207,' Then I went up to a place where there was a thicket of leafy wood, and lay there crouching.'),(12208,'  And they went hither and thither with loud cries;'),(12209,' but as there seemed to be no profit in going further in their search, they went back again on board their hollow ship.'),(12210,' And the gods themselves hid me easily, and led me, and brought me to the farmstead of a wise man; '),(12211,'for still haply it is my lot to live.” '),(12212,' \n  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say: '),(12213,' “Ah, wretched stranger, verily thou hast stirred my heart deeply in telling all the tale of thy sufferings and thy wanderings.'),(12214,' But in this, methinks, thou hast not spoken aright, nor shalt thou persuade me with thy tale about Odysseus.'),(12215,' Why shouldst thou, who art in such plight  lie to no purpose? '),(12216,'Nay, of myself I know well regarding the return of my master, that he was utterly hated of all the gods, in that they did not slay him among the Trojans, or in the arms of his friends, when he had wound up the skein of war. '),(12217,'  Then would the whole host of the Achaeans have made him a tomb,  and for his son too he would have won great glory in days to come. But as it is the spirits of the storm have swept him away, and left no tidings.'),(12218,'  I, for my part, dwell aloof with the swine,'),(12219,'  nor do I go to the city, unless haply wise Penelope bids me thither, when tidings come to her from anywhere.'),(12220,'  Then men sit around him that comes, and question him closely, both those that grieve for their lord, that has long been gone, and those who rejoice, as they devour his substance without atonement. '),(12221,' But I care not to ask or enquire, since the time when an Aetolian beguiled me with his story,  one that had killed a man, and after wandering over the wide earth came to my house,'),(12222,' and I gave him kindly welcome.'),(12223,' He said that he had seen Odysseus among the Cretans at the house of Idomeneus, mending his ships which storms had shattered.'),(12224,' And he said that he would come either by summer or by harvest-time,  bringing much treasure along with his godlike comrades. '),(12225,'Thou too, old man of many sorrows, since a god has brought thee to me, seek not to win my favour by lies, nor in any wise to cajole me.'),(12226,' It is not for this that I shall shew thee respect or kindness, but from fear of Zeus, the stranger\'s god, and from pity for thyself.”'),(12227,'\n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: “Verily thou hast in thy bosom a heart that is slow to believe, seeing that in such wise, even with an oath, I won thee not, neither persuade thee.'),(12228,' But come now, let us make a covenant, '),(12229,'and the gods who hold Olympus shall be witnesses for us both in time to come.'),(12230,'  If thy master returns to this house, clothe me in a cloak and tunic, as raiment, and send me on my way to Dulichium, where I desire to be.'),(12231,' But if thy master does not come as I say, set the slaves upon me, and fling me down from a great cliff,  that another beggar may beware of deceiving.”'),(12232,' \nAnd the goodly swineherd answered him, and said:'),(12233,' “Aye, stranger, so should I indeed win fair fame and prosperity among men both now and hereafter, if I, who brought thee to my hut and gave thee entertainment,  should then slay thee, and take away thy dear life. '),(12234,' With a ready heart thereafter should I pray to Zeus, son of Cronos.'),(12235,' But it is now time for supper, '),(12236,'and may my comrades soon be here, that we may make ready a savoury supper in the hut.\"'),(12237,'Thus they spoke to one another,  and the swine and the swineherds drew near. '),(12238,' The sows they shut up to sleep in their wonted sties, and a wondrous noise arose from them, as they were penned. Then the goodly swineherd called to his comrades saying: '),(12239,'\n“Bring forth the best of the boars, that I may slaughter him for the stranger  who comes from afar,'),(12240,' and we too shall have some profit therefrom, who have long borne toil and suffering for the sake of the white-tusked swine,'),(12241,' while others devour our labour without atonement.”'),(12242,'So saying, he split wood with the pitiless bronze, and the others brought in a fatted boar of five years old, '),(12243,' and set him by the hearth.'),(12244,'Nor did the swineherd forget the immortals,'),(12245,'  for he had an understanding heart, '),(12246,' but as a first offering he cast into the fire bristles from the head of the white-tusked boar, and made prayer to all the gods that wise Odysseus might return to his own house.'),(12247,'  Then he raised himself up, and smote the boar with a billet of oak, which he had left when splitting the wood,'),(12248,' And the others cut the boar\'s throat, '),(12249,' And the others cut the boar\'s throat, '),(12250,'and signed him, '),(12251,'and quickly cut him up, and the swineherd took as first offerings bits of raw flesh from all the limbs, and laid them in the rich fat. These he cast into the fire, when he had sprinkled them with barley meal,  but the rest they cut up and spitted, and roasted it carefully, and drew it all off the spits, and cast it in a heap on platters.'),(12252,' Then the swineherd stood up to carve,'),(12253,' for well did his heart know what was fair,'),(12254,'and he cut up the mess and divided it into seven portions.'),(12255,'  One with a prayer he set aside for the nymphs and for Hermes, son of Maia, and the rest he distributed to each.'),(12256,' And Odysseus he honored with the long chine of the white-tusked boar, and made glad the heart of his master; '),(12257,'and Odysseus of many wiles spoke to him, and said:'),(12258,'\n  “Eumaeus, mayest thou be as dear to father Zeus as thou art to me, since thou honourest me with a good portion, albeit I am in such plight.\"'),(12259,'To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say:'),(12260,' “Eat, unhappy stranger, and have joy of such fare as is here.'),(12261,' It is the god that will give one thing and withhold another,  even as seems good to his heart; '),(12262,'for he can do all things.”'),(12263,' \nHe spoke, and sacrificed the firstling pieces to the gods that are for ever, and, when he had made libations of the flaming wine, he placed the cup in the hands of Odysseus, the sacker of cities, '),(12264,' and took his seat by his own portion.'),(12265,'And bread was served to them by Mesaulius, whom the swineherd  had gotten by himself alone, while his master was gone, without the knowledge of his mistress or the old Laertes, '),(12266,'buying him of the Taphians with his own goods.'),(12267,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. '),(12268,'But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink,  Mesaulius took away the food, and they were fain to go to their rest, sated with bread and meat.'),(12269,'\nNow the night came on, foul and without a moon, and Zeus rained the whole night through, and the West Wind, ever the rainy wind, blew strong. '),(12270,'Then Odysseus spoke among them, making trial of the swineherd,  to see whether he would strip off his own cloak and give it him, or bid some other of his comrades to do so, since he cared for him so greatly:'),(12271,'\n“Hear me now, Eumaeus and all the rest of you, his men, with a wish in my heart will I tell a tale; '),(12272,'for the wine bids me, befooling wine, which sets one, even though he be right wise, to singing  and laughing softly, and makes him stand up and dance, aye, and brings forth a word which were better unspoken.'),(12273,' Still, since I have once spoken out, I will hide nothing.'),(12274,' Would that I were young and my strength firm as when we made ready our ambush, and led it beneath the walls of Troy.'),(12275,'  The leaders were Odysseus and Menelaus, son of Atreus, and with them I was third in command; '),(12276,'for so had they ordered it themselves.'),(12277,' Now when we had come to the city and the steep wall, round about the town in the thick brushwood among the needs and swamp-land  we lay, crouching beneath our arms, '),(12278,'and night came on, foul, when the North Wind had fallen, and frosty, '),(12279,'and snow came down on us from above, covering us like rime, bitter cold, and ice formed upon our shields.'),(12280,' Now all the rest had cloaks and tunics, and slept in peace, with their shields covering their shoulders, '),(12281,' but I, when I set out, had left my cloak behind with my comrades in my folly, for I did not think that even so I should be cold, and had come with my shield alone and my bright kilt.'),(12282,' But when it was the third watch of the night, and the stars had turned their course, then I spoke to Odysseus, who was near me,  nudging him with my elbow; '),(12283,'and he straightway gave ear:'),(12284,'\n“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, lo now, no longer shall I be among the living. Nay, the cold is killing me, '),(12285,'for I have no cloak.'),(12286,'Some god beguiled me to wear my tunic only,'),(12287,'  and now there is no more escape.’'),(12288,'  “So I spoke, and he then devised this plan in his heart, such a man was he both to plan and to fight; '),(12289,'and speaking in a low voice he said to me:'),(12290,' ‘Be silent now, lest another of the Achaeans hear thee.’ '),(12291,' \n“With this he raised his head upon his elbow, and spoke, saying: '),(12292,' a dream from the gods came to me in my sleep.'),(12293,' a dream from the gods came to me in my sleep.'),(12294,' \nLo, we have come very far from the ships,'),(12295,'  and I would that there were one to bear word to Agamemnon, son of Atreus, shepherd of the host, in the hope that he might bid more men to come from the ships.’'),(12296,'\n“So he spoke, and Thoas, son of Andraemon, sprang up  quickly, and from him flung his purple cloak, and set out to run to the ships.'),(12297,' Then in his garment I gladly lay, and golden-throned Dawn appeared.'),(12298,' Would that I were young as then, and my strength as firm;'),(12299,'then would one of the swineherds in the farmstead give me a cloak  both from kindness and from respect for a brave warrior. '),(12300,' But as it is they scorn me, since I have foul raiment about me.\"'),(12301,'To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say:'),(12302,' “Old man, the tale thou hast told is a good one, nor hast thou thus far spoken aught amiss or unprofitably.'),(12303,'  Wherefore thou shalt lack neither clothing nor aught else that a sore-tried suppliant should receive, when he meets one—for this night at least; '),(12304,'but in the morning thou shalt shake about thee those rags of thine.'),(12305,' For not many cloaks are here or changes of tunics to put on, but each man has one alone.'),(12306,'  But when the dear son of Odysseus comes, he will himself give thee a cloak and a tunic as raiment, and will send thee whithersoever thy heart and spirit bid thee go.\"'),(12307,'So saying, he sprang up and placed a bed for Odysseus near the fire, and cast upon it skins of sheep and goats.'),(12308,'  There Odysseus lay down,'),(12309,' and the swineherd threw over him a great thick cloak, which he kept at hand for a change of clothing whenever a terrible storm should arise.'),(12310,'\nSo there Odysseus slept, and beside him slept the young men. '),(12311,' But the swineherd  liked not a bed in that place, that he should lay him down away from the boars; so he made ready to go outside.'),(12312,' And Odysseus was glad that he took such care of his master\'s substance while he was afar. '),(12313,'First Eumaeus flung his sharp sword over his strong shoulders, and then put about him a cloak, very thick, to keep off the wind;  and he picked up the fleece of a large, well-fatted goat, took a sharp javelin to ward off dogs and men, '),(12314,'and went forth to lie down to sleep where the white-tusked boars slept beneath a hollow rock, in a place sheltered from the North Wind.'),(12315,' But Pallas Athena went to spacious Lacedaemon to remind the glorious son of great-hearted Odysseus of his return, and to hasten his coming. '),(12316,'She found Telemachus and the noble son of Nestor  lying in the fore-hall of the palace of glorious Menelaus. Now Nestor\'s son was overcome with soft sleep,'),(12317,' but sweet sleep did not hold Telemachus, but all through the immortal night anxious thoughts for his father kept him wakeful.'),(12318,' And flashing-eyed Athena stood near him, and said:'),(12319,'\n  “Telemachus, thou dost not well to wander longer far from thy home, leaving behind thee thy wealth and men in thy house so insolent,'),(12320,' lest they divide and devour all thy possessions, and thou shalt have gone on a fruitless journey.'),(12321,' Nay, rouse with all speed Menelaus, good at the war-cry,  to send thee on thy way, that thou mayest find thy noble mother still in her home. '),(12322,'For now her father and her brothers bid her wed Eurymachus, '),(12323,' for he surpasses all the wooers in his presents, and has increased his gifts of wooing.'),(12324,' Beware lest she carry forth from thy halls some treasure against thy will.'),(12325,' For thou knowest what sort of a spirit there is in a woman\'s breast; '),(12326,' she is fain to increase the house of the man who weds her, but of her former children and of the lord of her youth she takes no thought, when once he is dead, and asks no longer concerning them. '),(12327,'Nay, go, and thyself put all thy possessions in the charge of whatsoever one  of the handmaids seems to thee the best, until the gods shall show thee a noble bride.'),(12328,' And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(12329,' The best men of the wooers lie in wait for thee of set purpose in the strait between Ithaca and rugged Samos, '),(12330,'  eager to slay thee before thou comest to thy native land.'),(12331,' But methinks this shall not be; '),(12332,' ere that shall the earth cover many a one of the wooers that devour thy substance.'),(12333,' But do thou keep thy well-built ship far from the islands, and sail by night as well as by day, '),(12334,'and that  one of the immortals, who keeps and guards thee, will send a fair breeze in thy wake.'),(12335,'But when thou hast reached the nearest shore of Ithaca, send thy ship and all thy comrades on to the city, but thyself go first of all to the swineherd who keeps thy swine, and withal has a kindly heart toward thee.'),(12336,' There do thou spend the night,'),(12337,'  and bid him to go to the city to bear word to wise Penelope that she has thee safe, and thou art come from Pylos.\"'),(12338,'So saying, she departed to high Olympus. But Telemachus woke the son of Nestor out of sweet sleep,  rousing him with a touch of his heel, and spoke to him, saying:'),(12339,'“Awake, Peisistratus, son of Nestor; bring up thy fiery-hoofed horses, and yoke them beneath the car, that we may speed on our way.” '),(12340,' \nThen Peisistratus, son of Nestor, answered, and said:'),(12341,' “Telemachus, in no wise may we  drive through the dark night, how eager soever for our journey; '),(12342,'and soon it will be dawn.'),(12343,' Wait then, until the warrior son of Atreus, Menelaus, famed for his spear, shall bring gifts and set them on the car, and shall send us on our way with kindly words of farewell.'),(12344,' For a guest remembers all his days  the host who shews him kindness.”'),(12345,'So he spoke, and presently came golden-throned Dawn.'),(12346,' Up to them then came Menelaus, good at the war-cry, rising from his couch from beside fair-tressed Helen. '),(12347,'  And when the prince, the dear son of Odysseus, saw him,  he made haste to put about him his bright tunic, and to fling over his mighty shoulders a great cloak, and went forth. Then Telemachus, the dear son of divine Odysseus, came up to Menelaus, and addressed him, saying:'),(12348,'\n“Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts,  send me back now at length to my dear native land, '),(12349,'for now my heart is eager to return home.”'),(12350,' Then Menelaus, good at the war-cry, answered him: '),(12351,' “Telemachus, I verily shall not hold thee here a long time, when thou art eager to return.'),(12352,'Nay, I should blame another,   who, as host, loves overmuch or hates overmuch; '),(12353,' better is due measure in all things. '),(12354,' \'Tis equal wrong if a man speed on a guest who is loath to go, and if he keep back one that is eager to be gone.'),(12355,'One should make welcome the present guest, and send forth him that would go.'),(12356,'  But stay, till I bring fair gifts and put them on thy car, and thine own eyes behold them, and till I bid the women make ready a meal in the halls of the abundant store that is within.'),(12357,' It is a double boon—honor and glory it brings, and profit withal—that the traveller should dine before he goes forth over the wide and boundless earth.'),(12358,'  And if thou art fain to journey through Hellas and mid-Argos, be it so, to the end that I may myself go with thee, and I will yoke for thee horses, and lead thee to the cities of men.'),(12359,' Nor will any one send us away empty-handed, but will give us some one thing at least to bear with us, a fair brazen tripod or cauldron,  or a pair of mules, or a golden cup.”'),(12360,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12361,' “Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts, rather would I go at once to my home, '),(12362,'for when I departed I left behind me no one to watch over my possessions.'),(12363,'  I would not that in seeking for my god-like father I myself should perish, or some goodly treasure be lost from my halls.” '),(12364,' \nNow when Menelaus, good in battle, heard this, he straightway bade his wife and her handmaids make ready a meal in the halls of the abundant store that was within.'),(12365,'  Up to him then came Eteoneus, son of Boethous, just risen from his bed, for he dwelt not far from him.'),(12366,' Him Menelaus, good at the war-cry, bade kindle a fire and roast of the flesh;'),(12367,' and he heard, and obeyed.'),(12368,' And Menelaus himself went down to his vaulted treasure-chamber,  not alone, for with him went Helen and Megapenthes. '),(12369,'But when they came to the place where his treasures were stored, the son of Atreus took a two-handled cup, and bade his son Megapenthes bear a mixing bowl of silver.'),(12370,' And Helen came up to the chests  in which were her richly-broidered robes, that she herself had wrought.'),(12371,'One of these Helen, the beautiful lady, lifted out and bore away, the one that was fairest in its broideries, and the amplest. It shone like a star, '),(12372,' and lay beneath all the rest.'),(12373,'Then they went forth through the house until they came to  Telemachus; '),(12374,' and fair-haired Menelaus spoke to him, and said:'),(12375,'\n“Telemachus, may Zeus, the loud-thundering lord of Here, verily bring to pass for thee thy return, even as thy heart desires.'),(12376,' And of all the gifts that lie stored as treasures in my house, I will give thee that one which is fairest and costliest.'),(12377,'  I will give thee a well-wrought mixing-bowl.'),(12378,' It is all of silver, and with gold are the rims thereof gilded, the work of Hephaestus;'),(12379,' and the warrior Phaedimus, king of the Sidonians, gave it me, when his house sheltered me as I came thither; '),(12380,'and now I am minded to give it to thee.”'),(12381,'  So saying, the warrior, son of Atreus, placed the two-handled cup in his hands.'),(12382,' And the strong Megapenthes brought the bright mixing-bowl of silver and set it before him, '),(12383,'and fair-cheeked Helen came up with the robe in her hands, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(12384,'\n  “Lo, I too give thee this gift, dear child, a remembrance of the hands of Helen, against the day of thy longed-for marriage, for thy bride to wear it.'),(12385,' But until then let it lie in thy halls in the keeping of thy dear mother.'),(12386,' And for thyself I wish that with joy thou mayest reach thy well-built house and thy native land.” '),(12387,' \n  So saying, she placed it in his hands, and he took it gladly. '),(12388,'And the prince Peisistratus took the gifts, and laid them in the box of the chariot, and gazed at them all wondering in his heart.'),(12389,' Then fair-haired Menelaus led them to the house,'),(12390,'and the two sat down on chairs and high seats.'),(12391,'  And a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin for them to wash, '),(12392,'and beside them drew up a polished table.'),(12393,' And the grave housewife brought and set before them bread, '),(12394,'and therewith meats in abundance, granting freely of her store. '),(12395,'  And hard by the son of Boethous carved the meat, and divided the portions, '),(12396,'and the son of glorious Menelaus poured the wine.'),(12397,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. '),(12398,'But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, then Telemachus and the glorious son of Nestor  yoked the horses and mounted the inlaid car, and drove forth from the gateway and the echoing portico.'),(12399,' After them went the son of Atreus, fair-haired Menelaus, bearing in his right hand honey-hearted wine in a cup of gold, that they might pour libations ere they set out.'),(12400,'  And he took his stand before the horses, and pledged the youths, and said:'),(12401,'\n“Fare ye well, young men, and bear greeting to Nestor, shepherd of the host, '),(12402,'for verily he was kind as a father to me, while we sons of the Achaeans warred in the land of Troy.\"'),(12403,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12404,'  “Aye, verily, king, fostered of Zeus, to him will we tell all this on our coming, as thou dost bid.'),(12405,' And I would that, when I return to Ithaca, I might as surely find Odysseus in his house, to tell him how I met with every kindness at thy hands, ere I departed and bring with me treasures many and goodly.”'),(12406,'  Even as he spoke a bird flew by on the right, an eagle, bearing in his talons a great, white goose, a tame fowl from the yard, '),(12407,' and men and women followed shouting.'),(12408,' But the eagle drew near to them, and darted off to the right in front of the horses; '),(12409,' and  they were glad as they saw it, and the hearts in the breasts of all were cheered.'),(12410,'And among them Peisistratus, son of Nestor, was first to speak:'),(12411,'\n“Consider, Menelaus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts, whether it was for us two that the god showed this sign, or for thyself.\"'),(12412,'so he spoke, and Menelaus, dear to Ares, pondered  how he might with understanding interpret the sign aright.'),(12413,' But long-robed Helen took the word from him, and said:'),(12414,'\n“Hear me, '),(12415,' and I will prophesy as the immortals put it into my heart, and as I think it will be brought to pass.'),(12416,'Even as this eagle came  from the mountain, where are his kin, and where he was born, and snatched up the goose that was bred in the house, even so shall Odysseus return to his home after many toils and many wanderings, and shall take vengeance; '),(12417,'or even now he is at home, and is sowing the seeds of evil for all the wooers.” '),(12418,' \nThen again wise Telemachus answered her: '),(12419,' “So may Zeus grant, the loud-thundering lord of Here; '),(12420,'then will I even there ever pray to thee, as to a god.\"'),(12421,'He spoke, and touched the two horses with the lash, '),(12422,' and they sped swiftly toward the plain, coursing eagerly through the city.'),(12423,' So all day long they shook the yoke they bore about their necks.'),(12424,'  And the sun set, and all the ways grew dark.'),(12425,' And they came to Pherae, to the house of Diocles, son of Ortilochus, whom Alpheus begot.'),(12426,' There they spent the night, and before them he set the entertainment due to strangers. '),(12427,'As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered,  they yoked the horses, and mounted the inlaid car, and drove forth from the gateway and the echoing portico.'),(12428,' Then Peisistratus touched the horses with the whip to start them, and nothing loath the pair sped onward,'),(12429,' and soon thereafter they reached the steep citadel of Pylos.'),(12430,' Then Telemachus spoke to the son of Nestor, saying:'),(12431,'\n  “Son of Nestor, wilt thou now make me a promise, and fulfil it, as I bid?'),(12432,' Friends from of old we call ourselves by reason of our fathers\' friendship, and we are moreover of the same age, '),(12433,' and this journey shall yet more stablish us in oneness of heart.'),(12434,'Lead me not past my ship, O thou fostered of Zeus, but leave me there,  lest that old man keep me in his house against my will, fain to show me kindness, '),(12435,'whereas I must needs hasten home.\"'),(12436,'So he spoke, and the son of Nestor took counsel with his heart, how he might duly give the promise and fulfil it.'),(12437,' And, as he pondered, this seemed to him the better course.'),(12438,'  He turned his horses to the swift ship and the shore of the sea, and took out, and set in the stern of the ship the beautiful gifts, the raiment and gold, which Menelaus gave him.'),(12439,' And he urged on Telemachus, and addressed him with winged words:'),(12440,'\n“Make haste now to go on board, and bid all thy comrades to do likewise,  before I reach home and bring the old man word. '),(12441,'For well I know this in mind and heart,'),(12442,'so masterful is his spirit he will not let thee go, but will himself come hither to bid thee to his house; and, I tell thee, he will not go back without thee; '),(12443,'for very wroth will he be, despite of all.” '),(12444,'  So saying, he drove his horses with beautiful mane back to the city of the Pylians, and speedily reached the palace.'),(12445,' And Telemachus called to his men, and gave command to them, saying:'),(12446,'\n“Set all the gear in order, men, in the black ship, and let us go on board ourselves, that we may speed on our way.”'),(12447,'  So he spoke, and they readily hearkened and obeyed; and at once they went on board, and sat down upon the benches. '),(12448,' \nHe verily was busied thus, and was praying and offering sacrifice to Athena by the stern of the ship,'),(12449,'when there drew nigh to him a man from a far land, one that was fleeing out of Argos because he had slain a man;  and he was a seer.'),(12450,' By lineage he was sprung from Melampus, who of old dwelt in Pylos, mother of flocks, a rich man and one that had a very wealthy house among the Pylians, '),(12451,' but had afterward come to a land of strangers, fleeing from his country and from great-hearted Neleus, the lordliest of living men,  who for a full year had kept much wealth from him by force.'),(12452,' Now Melampus meanwhile lay bound with bitter bonds in the halls of Phylacus, suffering grievous pains because of the daughter of Neleus, and the terrible blindness of heart which the goddess, the Erinys, who brings houses to ruin, had laid upon him.'),(12453,'  Howbeit he escaped his fate, and drove off the deep-lowing kine from Phylace to Pylos, and avenged the cruel deed upon godlike Neleus, and brought the maiden home to be his own brother\'s wife.'),(12454,' For himself, he went to the land of other men, to horse-pasturing Argos,'),(12455,'for there it was appointed him  to dwell, bearing sway over many Argives. There he wedded a wife and built him a high-roofed house, and begot Antiphates and Mantius, two stalwart sons.'),(12456,'Now Antiphates begot great-hearted Oicles, and Oicles Amphiaraus, the rouser of the host,  whom Zeus, who bears the aegis, and Apollo heartily loved with all manner of love.'),(12457,' Yet he did not reach the threshold of old age, but died in Thebe, because of a woman\'s gifts.'),(12458,' To him were born sons, Alcmaeon and Amphilochus.'),(12459,' And Mantius on his part begot Polypheides and Cleitus.'),(12460,'  Now Cleitus golden-throned Dawn snatched away by reason of his beauty, that he might dwell with the immortals;'),(12461,' but of Polypheides, high of heart, Apollo made a seer, far the best of mortals, after that Amphiaraus was dead.'),(12462,' He removed to Hyperesia, having waxed wroth with his father,  and there he dwelt and prophesied to all men.'),(12463,'His son it was, Theoclymenus by name, who now came and stood by Telemachus;'),(12464,' and he found him pouring libations and praying by his swift, black ship, and he spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(12465,'\n  “Friend, since I find thee making burnt-offering in this place, I beseech thee by thine offerings and by the god, aye, and by thine own life and the lives of thy comrades who follow thee, tell me truly what I ask, and hide it not.'),(12466,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?” '),(12467,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?” '),(12468,' \n  And wise Telemachus answered him: '),(12469,'“Then verily, stranger, will I frankly tell thee all.'),(12470,' Of Ithaca I am by birth, and my father is Odysseus, as sure as ever such a one there was;'),(12471,' but now he has perished by a pitiful fate.'),(12472,' Therefore have I now taken my comrades and a black ship,  and am come to seek tidings of my father, that has long been gone.”'),(12473,'Then godlike Theoclymenus answered him:'),(12474,' “Even so have I, too, fled from my country, for that I slew a man, one of mine own kin.'),(12475,' And many brethren and kinsmen of his there are in horse-pasturing Argos, and mightily do they bear sway over the Achaeans.'),(12476,'  It is to shun death and black fate at their hands that I flee, for, I ween, it is my lot to be a wanderer among men.'),(12477,' But do thou set me on thy ship, since in my flight I have made prayer to thee, lest they utterly slay me; '),(12478,' for methinks they are in pursuit.\"'),(12479,'And wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12480,'  “Then will I in no wise thrust thee from my shapely ship, since thou art eager to come.\n Nay, follow with us,'),(12481,' and in our home shalt thou find entertainment such as we have.\"'),(12482,'So saying, he took from him his spear of bronze, and laid it at length on the deck of the curved ship,'),(12483,' and himself went aboard the seafaring ship. '),(12484,' Then he sat down in the stern and made Theoclymenus sit down beside him; '),(12485,' and his men loosed the stern cables.'),(12486,'And Telemachus called to his men and bade them lay hold of the tackling, '),(12487,' and they quickly obeyed. '),(12488,'The mast of fir  they raised and set in the hollow socket, and made it fast with fore-stays, and hauled up the white sail with twisted thongs of oxhide. '),(12489,' And flashing-eyed Athena sent them a favorable wind, blowing strongly through the sky, that, speeding swiftly, the ship might accomplish her way over the salt water of the sea.'),(12490,'  So they fared past Crouni and Chalcis, with its beautiful streams.'),(12491,'Now the sun set and all the ways grew dark. '),(12492,'And the ship drew near to Pheae, sped by the wind of Zeus, and on past goodly Elis, where the Epeans hold sway.'),(12493,' From thence again he steered for the sharp isles  pondering whether he should escape death or be taken.'),(12494,' \nBut the two, Odysseus and the goodly swineherd, were supping in the hut, '),(12495,' and with them supped the other men.'),(12496,'But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, Odysseus spoke among them, making trial of the swineherd to see  whether he would still entertain him with kindly care and bid him remain there at the farmstead, or send him forth to the city:'),(12497,'\n“Hearken now, Eumaeus, and all ye other men.'),(12498,' In the morning I am minded to go forth to the city to beg, that I may not be the ruin of thee and of thy men. '),(12499,' Now then, give me good counsel, and send with me a trusty guide to lead me thither; '),(12500,'  but through the city will I wander by myself perforce, in the hope that one haply will give me a cup of water and a loaf.'),(12501,'Aye, and I would go to the house of godlike Odysseus and bear tidings to the wise Penelope,  and join the company of the insolent wooers, if perchance they may give me a meal, since they have good cheer in abundance.'),(12502,' Straightway might I do good service among them in all that they would.'),(12503,' For I will tell thee, and do thou give heed and hearken.'),(12504,' By the favour of Hermes, the messenger, who  lends grace and glory to all men\'s work, in the business of serving no man beside can vie with me, in piling well a fire, in splitting dry faggots, in carving and roasting meat, and in pouring wine —in all things in which meaner men serve the noble.\"'),(12505,'  Then deeply moved didst thou speak to him, swineherd Eumaeus:'),(12506,' “Ah me, stranger, why has such a thought come into thy mind?'),(12507,' Verily thou art fain utterly to perish there, '),(12508,'if thou wouldest indeed enter the throng of the wooers, whose wantonness and violence reach the iron heaven.'),(12509,'  Not such as thou are their serving men; nay, they that serve them are young men, well clad in cloaks and tunics, and ever are their heads and bright faces sleek; '),(12510,'and polished tables are laden with bread, and meat, and wine.'),(12511,'  Nay, abide here;'),(12512,' there is none that is vexed by thy presence, not I, nor any other of the men that are with me.'),(12513,' But when the dear son of Odysseus comes, he will himself clothe thee in a cloak and a tunic as raiment, and will send thee whithersoever thy heart and spirit bid thee go.” '),(12514,' \n  Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him: '),(12515,'“Would, Eumaeus, that thou mightest be as dear to father Zeus as thou art to me, for that thou hast made me cease from wandering and from grievous hardships.'),(12516,'Than roaming naught else is more evil for mortals;'),(12517,'  yet for their cursed belly\'s sake  men endure evil woes, when wandering and sorrow and pain come upon them.'),(12518,'But now, since thou keepest me here and biddest me await thy master, come, tell me of the mother of godlike Odysseus, and of the father, whom, when he went forth, he left behind him on the threshold of old age. Are they haply still living beneath the rays of the sun?   or are they now dead and in the house of Hades?\"'),(12519,'Then the swineherd, a leader of men, answered him:'),(12520,' “Then verily, stranger, will I frankly tell thee.'),(12521,' Laertes still lives, but ever prays to Zeus that his life may waste away from his limbs within his halls.'),(12522,'  For wondrously does he grieve for his son that is gone, and for the wise lady, his wedded wife, whose death troubled him most of all, and brought him to untimely old age.'),(12523,' But she died of grief for her glorious son by a miserable death, as I would that no man may die  who dwells here as my friend and does me kindness.'),(12524,' So long as she lived, though it was in sorrow, it was ever a pleasure to me to ask and enquire after her, for she herself had brought me up with long-robed Ctimene, her noble daughter, whom she bore as her youngest child.'),(12525,'  With her was I brought up, and the mother honored me little less than her own children.'),(12526,' But when we both reached the longed-for prime of youth they sent her to Same to wed, and got themselves countless bridal gifts, but as for me, my lady clad me in a cloak and tunic, right goodly raiment, and gave me sandals for my feet  and sent me forth to the field; '),(12527,' but in her heart she loved me the more.'),(12528,' But now I lack all this, '),(12529,'though for my own part the blessed gods make to prosper the work to which I give heed.'),(12530,' Therefrom have I eaten and drunk, and given to reverend strangers.'),(12531,'But from my mistress I may hear naught pleasant,  whether word or deed, for a plague has fallen upon the house, even overweening men.'),(12532,' Yet greatly do servants long to speak before their mistress, and learn of all, and to eat and drink, and thereafter to carry off somewhat also to the fields, such things as ever make the heart of a servant to grow warm.” '),(12533,' \n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(12534,'“Lo now, surely when thou wast but a child, swineherd Eumaeus, thou didst wander far from thy country and thy parents. '),(12535,'But come now, tell me this, and declare it truly. Was a broad-wayed city of men sacked,  wherein thy father and honored mother dwelt? Or, when thou wast alone with thy sheep or cattle, did foemen take thee in their ships and bear thee for sale to the house of this thy master, who paid for thee a goodly price?\"'),(12536,'Then the swineherd, a leader of men, answered him:'),(12537,'  “Stranger, since thou dost ask and question me of this, hearken now in silence, and take thy joy, and drink thy wine, as thou sittest here. '),(12538,' These nights are wondrous long.'),(12539,'There is time for sleep, and there is time to take joy in hearing tales; '),(12540,'thou needest not lay thee down till it be time; '),(12541,'there is weariness even in too much sleep.'),(12542,'  As for the rest, if any man\'s heart and spirit bid him, let him go forth and sleep,'),(12543,' and at daybreak let him eat, and follow our master\'s swine.'),(12544,' But we two will drink and feast in the hut, and will take delight each in the other\'s grievous woes,  as we recall them to mind.'),(12545,'For in after time a man finds joy even in woes, whosoever has suffered much, and wandered much.'),(12546,' But this will I tell thee, of which thou dost ask and enquire. '),(12547,'“There is an isle called Syria, if haply thou hast heard thereof, above Ortygia, where are the turning-places of the sun.  It is not so very thickly settled, but it is a good land, rich in herds, rich in flocks, full of wine, abounding in wheat.'),(12548,' Famine never comes into the land, nor does any hateful sickness besides fall on wretched mortals; '),(12549,' but when the tribes of men grow old throughout the city,  Apollo, of the silver bow, comes with Artemis, and assails them with his gentle shafts, and slays them.'),(12550,' In that isle are two cities, and all the land is divided between them,'),(12551,' and over both ruled as king my father, Ctesius, son of Ormenus, a man like to the immortals. '),(12552,' \n  “Thither came Phoenicians, men famed for their ships, greedy knaves, bringing countless trinkets in their black ship.'),(12553,' Now there was in my father\'s house a Phoenician woman, comely and tall, and skilled in glorious handiwork.'),(12554,' Her the wily Phoenicians beguiled.'),(12555,'  First, as she was washing clothes, one of them lay with her in love by the hollow ship; for this beguiles the minds of women, even though one be upright.'),(12556,' Then he asked her who she was, and whence she came, '),(12557,' and she straightway shewed him the high-roofed home of my father, and said:'),(12558,'\n  “‘Out of Sidon, rich in bronze, I declare that I come, and I am the daughter of Arybas, to whom wealth flowed in streams.'),(12559,' But Taphian pirates seized me, as I was coming from the fields, and brought me hither, and sold me to the house of yonder man, '),(12560,'and he paid for me a goodly price.'),(12561,'  “Then the man who had lain with her in secret answered her: '),(12562,'‘Wouldest thou then return again with us to thy home, that thou mayest see the high-roofed house of thy father and mother, and see them too?'),(12563,' For of a truth they yet live, and are accounted rich.\''),(12564,'“Then the woman answered him, and said:'),(12565,'  ‘This may well be, if you sailors will pledge yourselves by an oath, that you will bring me safely home.\''),(12566,'“So she spoke, and they all gave an oath thereto, as she bade them.'),(12567,' But when they had sworn and made an end of the oath, the woman again spoke among them, and made answer:'),(12568,'\n  “‘Be silent now, and let no one of your company speak to me, if he meets me in the street or haply at the well, '),(12569,'lest some one go to the palace and tell the old king, and he wax suspicious and bind me with grievous bonds, and devise death for you.'),(12570,' Nay, keep my words in mind, and speed the barter of your wares.'),(12571,'  But, when your ship is laden with goods, let a message come quickly to me at the palace; '),(12572,' for I will also bring whatever gold comes under my hand.'),(12573,'Aye, and I would gladly give another thing for my passage.'),(12574,'  There is a child of my noble master, whose nurse I am in the palace, such a cunning child, who ever runs abroad with me.'),(12575,' Him would I bring on board, and he would fetch you a vast price, wherever you might take him for sale among men of strange speech.’ '),(12576,' \n“So saying, she departed to the fair palace.  And they remained there in our land a full year, and got by trade much substance in their hollow ship.'),(12577,' But when their hollow ship was laden for their return, then they sent a messenger to bear tidings to the woman.'),(12578,' There came a man, well versed in guile, to my father\'s house  with a necklace of gold, and with amber beads was it strung between.'),(12579,' This the maidens in the hall and my honored mother were handling, and were gazing on it, and were offering him their price;'),(12580,'  but he nodded to the woman in silence.'),(12581,' Then verily when he had nodded to her, he went his way to the hollow ship,  but she took me by the hand, and led me forth from the house.'),(12582,' Now in the fore-hall of the palace she found the cups and tables of the banqueters, who waited upon my father.'),(12583,' They had gone forth to the council and the people\'s place of debate, but she quickly hid three goblets in her bosom,  and bore them away;'),(12584,'and I followed in my heedlessness.'),(12585,' Then the sun set, and all the ways grew dark. '),(12586,'And we made haste and came to the goodly harbor, where was the swift ship of the Phoenicians.'),(12587,' Then they embarked,  putting both of us on board as well, and sailed over the watery ways,'),(12588,'and Zeus sent them a favorable wind.'),(12589,' For six days we sailed, night and day alike;'),(12590,' but when Zeus, son of Cronos, brought upon us the seventh day, then Artemis, the archer, smote the woman, and she fell with a thud into the hold, as a sea bird plunges.'),(12591,'  Her they cast forth to be a prey to seals and fishes, '),(12592,' but I was left, my heart sore stricken.'),(12593,' Now the wind, as it bore them, and the wave, brought them to Ithaca, where Laertes bought me with his wealth. '),(12594,'Thus it was that my eyes beheld this land.”'),(12595,'  To him then Zeus-born Odysseus made answer, and said: '),(12596,' “Eumaeus, of a truth thou hast deeply stirred the heart in my breast in telling all this tale of the sorrow thou hast borne at heart.'),(12597,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 15.488-15.491'),(12598,' Yet verily in thy case Zeus has given good side by side with the evil, since after all thy toil thou hast come to the house of  a kindly man, who gives thee food and drink, and that with kindness, and thou livest well; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 488 to line 491'),(12599,' \nThus they spoke to one another, and then lay down to sleep, for no long time, but for a little;'),(12600,'  for soon came fair-throned Dawn.'),(12601,'But the comrades of Telemachus, drawing near the shore, furled the sail, and took down the mast quickly, and rowed the ship to her anchorage with their oars.'),(12602,' Then they cast out the mooring-stones and made fast the stern cables,'),(12603,' and themselves went forth upon the shore of the sea,  and made ready their meal and mixed the flaming wine. '),(12604,'But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, among them wise Telemachus was the first to speak, saying:'),(12605,'\n“Do you now row the black ship to the city, but I will visit the fields and the herdsmen, '),(12606,' and at evening will come to the city when I have looked over my lands. '),(12607,' And in the morning I will set before you, as wages for your journey, a good feast of flesh and sweet wine.\"'),(12608,'Then godlike Theoclymenus answered him: '),(12609,' “Whither shall I go, dear child?'),(12610,' To whose house shall I come  of those who rule in rocky Ithaca? '),(12611,'Or shall I go straight to thy mother\'s house and thine?”'),(12612,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12613,'“Were things otherwise, I should bid thee go even to our house, '),(12614,'for there is in no wise lack of entertainment for strangers, '),(12615,' but  it would be worse for thyself, since I shall be away, and my mother will not see thee.'),(12616,' For she does not often appear before the wooers in the house, but apart from them weaves at her loom in an upper chamber.'),(12617,' But I will tell thee of another man to whom thou mayest go, Eurymachus, glorious son of wise Polybus,  whom now the men of Ithaca look upon as on a god. '),(12618,' For he is by far the best man, and is most eager to marry my mother and to have the honor of Odysseus.'),(12619,' Nevertheless Olympian Zeus, who dwells in the sky, knows this, whether or not before marriage he will fulfil for them the evil day.” '),(12620,' \n  Even as he spoke a bird flew forth upon the right, a hawk, the swift messenger of Apollo.'),(12621,' In his talons he held a dove, and was plucking her and shedding the feathers down on the ground midway between the ship and Telemachus himself.'),(12622,' Then Theoclymenus called him apart from his companions,  and clasped his hand, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(12623,'“Telemachus, surely not without a god\'s warrant has this bird flown forth upon our right, for I knew, as I looked upon him, that he was a bird of omen.'),(12624,' Than yours is no other house in the land of Ithaca more kingly; nay, ye are ever supreme.\"'),(12625,'  Then wise Telemachus answered him again: '),(12626,' “Ah, stranger, I would that this word of thine might be fulfilled.'),(12627,' Then shouldest thou straightway know of kindness and many a gift from me, so that one that met thee would call thee blessed.\"'),(12628,'Therewith he spoke to Peiraeus, his trusty comrade:'),(12629,'   “Peiraeus, son of Clytius, it is thou that in other matters art wont to hearken to me above all my comrades, who went with me to Pylos; '),(12630,' so now do thou, I pray thee, take this stranger and give him kindly welcome in thy house, and show him honor until I come.\"'),(12631,'  Then Peiraeus, the famous spearman, answered him:'),(12632,'“Telemachus, though thou shouldest stay here long, I will entertain him, and he shall have no lack of what is due to strangers.\"'),(12633,'So saying, he went on board the ship, and bade his comrades themselves to embark and to loose the stern cables.'),(12634,' So they went on board straightway, and sat down upon the benches.'),(12635,'  But Telemachus bound beneath his feet his fair sandals, and took his mighty spear, tipped with sharp bronze, from the deck of the ship.'),(12636,' Then the men loosed the stern cables, '),(12637,'and thrusting off, sailed to the city, as Telemachus bade, the dear son of divine Odysseus.'),(12638,'  But his feet bore him swiftly on, as he strode forward, until he reached the farmstead where were his countless swine, among whom slept the worthy swineherd with a heart loyal to his masters.'),(12639,' Meanwhile the two in the hut, Odysseus and the goodly swineherd, had kindled a fire, and were making ready their breakfast at dawn, and had sent forth the herdsmen with the droves of swine; '),(12640,' but around Telemachus the baying hounds fawned,  and barked not as he drew near.'),(12641,'And goodly Odysseus noted the fawning of the hounds, and the sound of footsteps fell upon his ears;'),(12642,'  and straightway he spoke to Eumaeus winged words:'),(12643,'\n“Eumaeus, surely some comrade of thine will be coming, or at least some one thou knowest, for the hounds do not bark,  but fawn about him, '),(12644,'and I hear the sound of footsteps.”'),(12645,'Not yet was the word fully uttered, when his own dear son stood in the doorway.'),(12646,' In amazement up sprang the swineherd, and from his hands the vessels fell with which he was busied as he mixed the flaming wine. '),(12647,'And he went to meet his lord,  and kissed his head and both his beautiful eyes and his two hands,'),(12648,'  and a big tear fell from him.'),(12649,'And as a loving father greets his own dear son, who comes in the tenth year from a distant land—his only son and well-beloved, for whose sake he has borne much sorrow—  even so did the goodly swineherd then clasp in his arms godlike Telemachus, and kiss him all over as one escaped from death;'),(12650,'and with wailing he addressed him with winged words:'),(12651,'“Thou art come, Telemachus, sweet light of my eyes.'),(12652,' I thought I should never see thee more after thou hadst gone in thy ship to Pylos.'),(12653,'  But come, enter in, dear child, that I may delight my heart with looking at thee here in my house, who art newly come from other lands.'),(12654,' For thou dost not often visit the farm and the herdsmen, but abidest in the town;'),(12655,' so, I ween, has it seemed good to thy heart, to look upon the destructive throng of the wooers.\"'),(12656,'  Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12657,' “So shall it be, father. '),(12658,'It is for thy sake that I am come hither, to see thee with my eyes, and to hear thee tell whether my mother still abides in the halls, or whether by now some other man has wedded her, and the couch of Odysseus  lies haply in want of bedding, covered with foul spider-webs.\"'),(12659,'Then the swineherd, a leader of men, answered him:'),(12660,' “Aye, verily, she abides with steadfast heart in thy halls,'),(12661,' and ever sorrowfully for her the nights and the days wane as she weeps.”'),(12662,'  So saying, he took from him the spear of bronze, '),(12663,' and Telemachus went in and passed over the stone threshold.'),(12664,' As he drew near, his father, Odysseus, rose from his seat and gave him place,'),(12665,' but Telemachus on his part checked him, and said:'),(12666,'“Be seated, stranger, '),(12667,'and we shall find a seat elsewhere  in our farmstead.'),(12668,'There is a man here who will set us one.”'),(12669,'and for Telemachus the swineherd '),(12670,'and for Telemachus the swineherd '),(12671,'strewed green brushwood beneath and a fleece above it, '),(12672,' and there the dear son of Odysseus sat down. '),(12673,'Then the swineherd set before them platters  of roast meats, which they had left at their meal the day before, and quickly heaped up bread in baskets, and mixed in a bowl of ivy wood honey-sweet wine, '),(12674,'and himself sat down over against divine Odysseus.'),(12675,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(12676,'  But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, Telemachus spoke to the goodly swineherd, and said:'),(12677,'\n“Father, from whence did this stranger come to thee?'),(12678,' How did sailors bring him to Ithaca?'),(12679,' Who did they declare themselves to be?'),(12680,' For nowise, methinks, did he come hither on foot.\"'),(12681,'  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say: '),(12682,'“Then verily, my child, I will tell thee all the truth.'),(12683,' From broad Crete he declares that he has birth, and he says that he has wandered roaming through many cities of mortals; '),(12684,'so has a god spun for him this lot.'),(12685,'  But now he has run away from a ship of the Thesprotians and come to my farmstead, and I shall put him in thy hands. '),(12686,' He declares himself thy suppliant.”'),(12687,' He declares himself thy suppliant.”'),(12688,' Then again wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12689,'“Eumaeus, verily this word which thou hast uttered stings me to the heart.'),(12690,'  For how am I to welcome this stranger in my house?'),(12691,' I am myself but young, nor have I yet trust in my might to defend me against a man, when one waxes wroth without a cause. '),(12692,'And as for my mother, the heart in her breast wavers this way and that, whether to abide here with me and keep the house,  respecting the bed of her husband and the voice of the people, or to go now with him whosoever is best of the Achaeans that woo her in the halls, and offers the most gifts of wooing. '),(12693,'But verily, as regards this stranger, now that he has come to thy house, I will clothe him in a cloak and tunic, fair raiment,  and will give him a two-edged sword, and sandals for his feet, and send him whithersoever his heart and spirit bid him go.'),(12694,' Or, if thou wilt, do thou keep him here at the farmstead, and care for him, '),(12695,'and raiment will I send hither and all his food to eat, that he be not the ruin of thee and of thy men.'),(12696,'  But thither will I not suffer him to go, to join the company of the wooers, '),(12697,'for they are over-full of wanton insolence, '),(12698,' lest they mock him, and dread grief come upon me.'),(12699,' And to achieve aught is hard for one man among many, how mighty soever he be, for verily they are far stronger.” '),(12700,' \n  Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him: '),(12701,' “Friend, since surely it is right for me to make answer—verily ye rend my heart, as I hear your words, such wantonness you say the wooers devise in the halls in despite of thee, so goodly a man.'),(12702,'  Tell me, art thou willingly thus oppressed? Or do the people throughout the land hate thee, following the voice of a god? Or hast thou cause to blame thy brothers, in whose fighting a man trusts even if a great strife arise.'),(12703,' Would that with my present temper I were as young as thou,  either the son of blameless Odysseus, or Odysseus himself, '),(12704,' straightway then might some stranger cut my head from off my neck, if I did not prove myself the bane of them all when I had come to the halls of Odysseus, son of Laertes.'),(12705,'  But if they should overwhelm me by their numbers, alone as I was, far rather would I die, slain in my own halls, than behold continually these shameful deeds, strangers mishandled, and men dragging the handmaidens in shameful fashion through the fair halls,  and wine drawn to waste, and men devouring my bread all heedlessly, without limit, with no end to the business.”'),(12706,' And wise Telemachus answered him: '),(12707,'“Then verily, stranger, I will frankly tell thee all.'),(12708,'Neither do the people at large bear me any grudge or hatred,  nor have I cause to blame brothers, in whose fighting a man trusts, even if a great strife arise.'),(12709,' For in this wise has the son of Cronos made our house to run in but a single line.'),(12710,' As his only son did Arceisius beget Laertes, as his only son again did his father beget Odysseus, '),(12711,' and Odysseus  begot me as his only son, and left me in his halls, and had no joy of me.'),(12712,'Therefore it is that foes past counting are now in the house;'),(12713,'  for all the princes who hold sway over the islands—Dulichium, and Same, and wooded Zacynthus—and those who lord it over rocky Ithaca,  all these woo my mother and lay waste my house.'),(12714,' And she neither refuses the hateful marriage, nor is she able to make an end;'),(12715,' but they with feasting consume my substance, '),(12716,'and will ere long bring me, too, to ruin. '),(12717,'Yet these things verily lie on the knees of the gods.'),(12718,'  But, father, do thou go with speed, and tell constant Penelope that she has me safe, and I am come from Pylos.'),(12719,' But I will abide here, and do thou come back hither, when thou hast told thy tale to her alone;  '),(12720,' but of the rest of the Achaeans let no one learn it, '),(12721,'for many there are who contrive evil against me.” '),(12722,' \n  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say:'),(12723,' this thou biddest one with understanding. '),(12724,' this thou biddest one with understanding. '),(12725,' But come now, tell me this, and declare it truly; whether I shall go on the self-same way with tidings to Laertes also, wretched man, who for a time, though grieving sorely for Odysseus,  was still wont to oversee the fields, and would eat and drink with the slaves in the house, as the heart in his breast bade him.'),(12726,' But now, from the day when thou wentest in thy ship to Pylos, they say he has no more eaten and drunk as before, nor overseen the fields, but with groaning and wailing  he sits and weeps, and the flesh wastes from off his bones.\"'),(12727,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12728,' “\'Tis the sadder; but none the less we will let him be, despite our sorrow;'),(12729,' for if in any wise all things might be had by mortals for the wishing, we should choose first of all the day of my father\'s return.'),(12730,' No, do thou come back, when thou hast given thy message, and wander not over the fields in search of Laertes;'),(12731,' but did my mother with all speed send forth her handmaid, the housewife, secretly, '),(12732,'for she might bear word to the old man.\"'),(12733,'With this he roused the swineherd,'),(12734,' and he took his sandals in his hands  and bound them beneath his feet and went forth to the city.'),(12735,' Nor was Athena unaware that the swineherd Eumaeus was gone from the farmstead, but she drew near'),(12736,' in the likeness of a woman, comely and tall, and skilled in glorious handiwork. '),(12737,' And she stood over against the door of the hut, shewing herself to Odysseus, '),(12738,' but Telemachus did not see her before him, or notice her; for in no wise do the gods appear in manifest presence to all. But Odysseus saw her, and the hounds, and they barked not, but with whining slunk in fear to the further side of the farmstead.'),(12739,'The she made a sign with her brows,'),(12740,'and goodly Odysseus perceived it,  and went forth from the hall, past the great wall of the court, and stood before her, '),(12741,'and Athena spoke to him, saying:'),(12742,'“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices,'),(12743,' even now do thou reveal thy word to thy son, and hide it not, that when you two have planned death and fate for the wooers,  you may go to the famous city.'),(12744,' Nor will I myself be long away from you, for I am eager for the battle.”'),(12745,'With this, Athena touched him with her golden wand.'),(12746,'\n A well-washed cloak and a tunic she first of all cast about his breast, and she increased his stature and his youthful bloom. '),(12747,'  Once more he grew dark of color, and his cheeks filled out, and dark grew the beard about his chin.'),(12748,' Then, when she had wrought thus, she departed, '),(12749,'but Odysseus went into the hut.'),(12750,' And his dear son marvelled, and, seized with fear, turned his eyes aside, lest it should be a god.   And he spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(12751,'“Of other sort thou seemest to me now, stranger, than awhile ago, and other are the garments thou hast on, and thy color is no more the same.'),(12752,' Verily thou art a god, one of those who hold broad heaven.'),(12753,'\n Nay then, be gracious, that we may offer to thee acceptable sacrifices  and golden gifts, finely wrought; '),(12754,'but do thou spare us.”'),(12755,' \nThen the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him:'),(12756,' why dost thou liken me to the immortals?'),(12757,' why dost thou liken me to the immortals?'),(12758,' Nay, I am thy father, for whose sake thou dost with groaning endure many griefs, and submittest to the violence of men.” '),(12759,'  So saying, he kissed his son, and from his cheeks let fall a tear to earth, '),(12760,'but before he ever steadfastly held them back.'),(12761,' Howbeit Telemachus—for he did not yet believe that it was his father—again answered, and spoke to him, saying:'),(12762,'\n“Thou verily art not my father Odysseus, but some god  beguiles me, that I may weep and groan yet more. '),(12763,' For nowise could a mortal man contrive this by his own wit, unless a god were himself to come to him, and easily by his will make him young or old.'),(12764,' For verily but now thou wast an old man and meanly clad, '),(12765,'  whereas now thou art like the gods, who hold broad heaven.”'),(12766,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(12767,' “Telemachus, it beseems thee not to wonder overmuch that thy father is in the house, or to be amazed. '),(12768,'For thou mayest be sure no other Odysseus will ever come hither;  but I here, I, even such as thou seest me, after sufferings and many wanderings, am come in the twentieth year to my native land.'),(12769,' But this, thou must know, is the work of Athena, driver of the spoil, who makes me such as she will—for she has the power—now like a beggar, and now again  like a young man, and one wearing fair raiment about his body.'),(12770,' Easy it is for the gods, who hold broad heaven, both to glorify a mortal man and to abase him.\"'),(12771,'So saying, he sat down, and Telemachus, flinging his arms about his noble father, wept and shed tears,  and in the hearts of both arose a longing for lamentation. '),(12772,' And they wailed aloud more vehemently than birds, sea-eagles, or vultures with crooked talons, whose young the country-folk have taken from their nest before they were fledged; '),(12773,'even so piteously did they let tears fall from beneath their brows.'),(12774,'  And now would the light of the sun have gone down upon their weeping, had not Telemachus spoken to his father suddenly:'),(12775,'\n“In what manner of ship, dear father, have sailors now brought thee hither to Ithaca?'),(12776,' Who did they declare themselves to be?'),(12777,' For nowise, methinks, didst thou come hither on foot.” '),(12778,' \n  And the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him: '),(12779,'“Then verily, my child, I will tell thee all the truth.'),(12780,' The Phaeacians brought me, men famed for their ships, who send other men too on their way, whosoever comes to them. '),(12781,'And they brought me as I slept in a swift ship over the sea,  and set me down in Ithaca, and gave me glorious gifts, stores of bronze and gold and woven raiment.'),(12782,' These treasures, by the favour of the gods, are lying in caves.'),(12783,' And now I am come hither at the bidding of Athena, that we may take counsel about the slaying of our foes.'),(12784,'  Come now, count me the wooers, and tell their tale, that I may know how many they are and what manner of men,'),(12785,'and that I may ponder in my noble heart and decide whether we two shall be able to maintain our cause against them alone without others, or whether we shall also seek out others.\"'),(12786,'  Then wise Telemachus answered him: '),(12787,'“Father, of a truth I have ever heard of thy great fame, that thou wast a warrior in strength of hand and in wise counsel, '),(12788,' amazement holds me.'),(12789,' amazement holds me.'),(12790,'It could not be that two men should fight against many men and mighty.'),(12791,'  For of the wooers there are not ten alone, or twice ten, but full many more.'),(12792,' Here as we are shalt thou straightway learn their number.'),(12793,' From Dulichium there are two and fifty chosen youths, and six serving men attend them; '),(12794,'from Same came four and twenty men;  from Zacynthus there are twenty youths of the Achaeans; and from Ithaca itself twelve men, all of them the noblest, and with them is Medon, the herald, and the divine minstrel, and two squires skilled in carving meats.'),(12795,' If we shall meet all these within the halls,  bitter, I fear, and with bane will be thy coming to avenge violence. '),(12796,' Nay, do thou consider, if thou canst bethink thee of any helper—one that would aid us two with a ready heart.”'),(12797,'Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him:'),(12798,'“Well, then, I will tell thee, and do thou give heed and hearken to my words, '),(12799,'  and consider whether for us two Athena, with father Zeus, will be enough, or whether I shall bethink me of some other helper.”'),(12800,'Then wise Telemachus answered him: '),(12801,' “Good, thou mayest be sure, are these two helpers whom thou dost mention, though high in the clouds do they abide,'),(12802,'and they  rule over all men alike and the immortal gods.”'),(12803,' \nThen the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered:'),(12804,' “Not long of a surety will those two hold aloof from the mighty fray, when between the wooers and us in my halls the might of Ares is put to the test.'),(12805,'  But for the present, do thou go at daybreak to thy house and join the company of the haughty wooers.'),(12806,' As for me, the swineherd will lead me later on to the city in the likeness of a woeful and aged beggar. '),(12807,'And if they shall put despite on me in the house,  let the heart in thy breast endure while I am evil entreated, even if they drag me by the feet through the house to the door, or hurl at me and smite me; '),(12808,' still do thou endure to behold it. '),(12809,'Thou shalt indeed bid them cease their folly, seeking to dissuade them with gentle words; '),(12810,'yet in no wise  will they hearken to thee, '),(12811,' for verily their day of doom is at hand. '),(12812,'And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart. '),(12813,' When Athena, rich in counsel, shall put it in my mind, I will nod to thee with my head; and do thou thereupon, when thou notest it, take all the weapons of war that lie in thy halls,  and lay them away one and all in the secret place of the lofty store-room.'),(12814,' And as for the wooers, when they miss the arms and question thee, do thou beguile them with gentle words, saying:'),(12815,'“‘Out of the smoke have I laid them, since they are no longer like those which of old Odysseus left behind him when he went forth to Troy,  but are all befouled so far as the breath of the fire has reached them. '),(12816,' And furthermore this greater fear has the son of Cronos put in my heart, lest haply, when heated with wine, you may set a quarrel afoot among you and wound one another, and so bring shame on your feast and on your wooing.'),(12817,' For of itself does the iron draw a man to it.’'),(12818,'  “But for us two alone do thou leave behind two swords and two spears, and two ox-hide shields for us to grasp, that we may rush upon them and seize them; '),(12819,'while as for the wooers, Pallas Athena and Zeus, the counsellor, will beguile them.'),(12820,' And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(12821,'  If in truth thou art my son and of our blood, then let no one hear that Odysseus is at home; neither let Laertes know it, nor the swineherd, nor any of the household, nor Penelope herself; but by ourselves thou and I will learn the temper of the women.'),(12822,'  Aye, and we will likewise make trial of many a one of the serving men, and see where any of them honours us two and fears us at heart, and who recks not of us and scorns thee, a man so goodly.”  '),(12823,' \nThen his glorious son answered him, and said: “Father, my spirit, methinks,  thou shalt verily come to know hereafter, '),(12824,' for no slackness of will possesses me. '),(12825,' But I think not that this plan will be a gain to us both, and so I bid thee take thought.'),(12826,' Long time shalt thou vainly go about, '),(12827,'making trial of each man as thou visitest the farms, '),(12828,'while in thy halls those others at their ease  are wasting thy substance in insolent wise, and there is no sparing. '),(12829,' Yet verily, as for the women, I do bid thee learn who among them dishonor thee, and who are guiltless.'),(12830,' But of the men in the farmsteads I would not that we should make trial, but that we should deal therewith hereafter,  if in very truth thou knowest some sign from Zeus who bears the aegis.”'),(12831,'Thus they spoke to one another, but meanwhile into Ithaca put the well-built ship that brought Telemachus and all his comrades from Pylos;'),(12832,'and they, when they had come into the deep harbor,  drew the black ship up on the shore, while proud squires bore forth their armour and straightway carried the beauteous gifts to the house of Clytius.'),(12833,'But they sent a herald forth to the house of Odysseus to bear word to wise Penelope  that Telemachus was at the farm, and had bidden the ship to sail on to the city, lest the noble queen might grow anxious and let round tears fall. So the two met, the herald and the goodly swineherd, on the self-same errand, to bear tidings to the lady.'),(12834,'  And when they reached the palace of the godlike king, the herald spoke out in the midst of the handmaids, and said: '),(12835,'\"Even now, queen, thy son has come back from Pylos.”'),(12836,'But the swineherd came close to Penelope and told her all that her dear son had bidden him say.'),(12837,'  And when he had fully told all that had been commanded him, he went his way to the swine and left the courtyard and the hall.'),(12838,'\nBut the wooers were dismayed and downcast in spirit, and forth they went from the hall past the great wall of the court, and there before the gates they sat down. '),(12839,' Then among them Eurymachus, son of Polybus, was the first to speak:'),(12840,'\n“My friends, verily a great deed has been insolently brought to pass by Telemachus, even this journey,'),(12841,' and we deemed that he would never see it accomplished.'),(12842,' But come, let us launch a black ship, the best we have, and let us get together seamen as rowers that they may straightway  bear tidings to those others speedily to return home.”'),(12843,' \nNot yet was the word fully uttered when Amphinomus, turning in his place, saw a ship in the deep harbor and men furling the sail, and with oars in their hands.'),(12844,' Then, breaking into a merry laugh, he spoke among his comrades:'),(12845,' for here they are at home.'),(12846,' for here they are at home.'),(12847,'\n Either some god told them of this, or they themselves caught sight of the ship of Telemachus as she sailed by, but could not catch her.\"'),(12848,'So he spoke, and they rose up and went to the shore of the sea. Swiftly the men drew up the black ship on the shore,  and proud squires bore forth their armour.'),(12849,'Themselves meanwhile went all together to the place of assembly, and none other would they suffer to sit with them, either of the young men or the old.'),(12850,'Then among them spoke Antinous, son of Eupeithes:'),(12851,'“Lo, now, see how the gods have delivered this man from destruction.'),(12852,'  Day by day watchmen sat upon the windy heights, watch ever following watch, '),(12853,' and at set of sun we never spent a night upon the shore, but sailing over the deep in our swift ship we waited for the bright Dawn, lying in wait for Telemachus, that we might take him and slay  the man himself; '),(12854,' howbeit meanwhile some god has brought him home. But, on our part, let us here devise for him a woeful death, even for Telemachus, and let him not escape from out our hands, '),(12855,' for I deem that while he lives this work of ours will not prosper.'),(12856,'For he is himself shrewd in counsel and in wisdom,  and the people nowise show us favour any more.'),(12857,'Nay, come, before he gathers the Achaeans to the place of assembly—for methinks he will in no wise be slow to act, but will be full of wrath, and rising up will declare among them all how that we contrived against him utter destruction, but did not catch him; '),(12858,' and they will not praise us when they hear of our evil deeds. '),(12859,' Beware, then, lest they work us some harm and drive us out from our country, and we come to the land of strangers.'),(12860,' Nay, let us act first, and seize him in the field far from the city, or on the road; '),(12861,'and his substance let us ourselves keep, and his wealth,  dividing them fairly among us; though the house we would give to his mother to possess, and to him who weds her. '),(12862,'Howbeit if this plan does not please you, but you choose rather that he should live and keep all the wealth of his fathers, let us not continue to devour his store of pleasant things  as we gather together here, but let each man from his own hall woo her with his gifts and seek to win her; '),(12863,'and she then would wed him who offers most, and who comes as her fated lord.” '),(12864,' \nSo he spoke, and they were all hushed in silence. '),(12865,' Then Amphinomus addressed their assembly, and spoke among them. He was the glorious son of the prince Nisus, son of Aretias, and he led the wooers who came from Dulichium, rich in wheat and in grass, and above all the others he pleased Penelope with his words, '),(12866,'for he had an understanding heart.'),(12867,' He it was who with good intent addressed their assembly, and spoke among them:'),(12868,'\n  “Friends, I surely would not choose to kill Telemachus;'),(12869,'a dread thing is it to slay one of royal stock.'),(12870,' Nay, let us first seek to learn the will of the gods.'),(12871,' If the oracles of great Zeus approve, I will myself slay him, and bid all the others do so; '),(12872,'  but if the gods turn us from the act, I bid you desist.”'),(12873,'Thus spoke Amphinomus, and his word was pleasing to them.'),(12874,' So they arose straightway and went to the house of Odysseus, and entering in, sat down on the polished seats.'),(12875,'\nThen the wise Penelope took other counsel,  to show herself to the wooers, overweening in their insolence.'),(12876,'For she had learned of the threatened death of her son in her halls, '),(12877,' for the herald Medon told her, who had heard their counsel.'),(12878,' So she went her way toward the hall with her handmaids. '),(12879,' But when the fair lady reached the wooers,  she stood by the doorpost of the well-built hall, holding before her face her shining veil; and she rebuked Antinous, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(12880,' “Antinous, full of insolence, deviser of evil! and yet it is thou, men say, that dost excel among all of thy years in the land of Ithaca  in counsel and in speech. '),(12881,'But thou, it seems, art not such a man. '),(12882,' Madman! why dost thou devise death and fate for Telemachus, and carest not for suppliants, for whom Zeus is witness. '),(12883,'\'Tis an impious thing to plot evil one against another.'),(12884,'Dost thou not know of the time when thy father came to this house a fugitive  in terror of the people? '),(12885,' For of a truth they were greatly wroth with him because he had joined Taphian pirates and harried the Thesprotians, '),(12886,' who were in league with us.'),(12887,'Him, then, they were minded to slay, and take from him his life by violence, and utterly to devour his great and pleasant livelihood; '),(12888,' but Odysseus held them back, and stayed them despite their eagerness. '),(12889,'His house it is that thou consumest now without atonement, and wooest his wife, and seekest to slay his son, and on me thou bringest great distress.'),(12890,' Nay, forbear, I charge thee, and bid the rest forbear.” '),(12891,' \nThen Eurymachus, son of Polybus, answered her:'),(12892,'  “Daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, be of good cheer, '),(12893,'and let not things distress thy heart.'),(12894,' That man lives not, nor shall live, nor shall ever be born, who shall lay hands upon thy son Telemachus while I live and behold the light upon the earth.'),(12895,'  For thus will I speak out to thee, and verily it shall be brought to pass.'),(12896,' Quickly shall that man\'s black blood flow forth about my spear; for of a truth me, too, did Odysseus the sacker of cities often set upon his knees, and put roast meat in my hands, and hold to my lips red wine.'),(12897,'  Therefore Telemachus is far the dearest of all men to me, and I bid him have no fear of death, at least from the wooers; '),(12898,'but from the gods can no man avoid it.”'),(12899,'Thus he spoke to cheer her, but against that son he was himself plotting death. '),(12900,' So she went up to her bright upper chamber  and then bewailed Odysseus, her dear husband, until flashing-eyed Athena cast sweet sleep upon her eyelids.'),(12901,'\nBut at evening the goodly swineherd came back to Odysseus and his son, '),(12902,' and they were busily making ready their supper, and had slain a boar of a year old.'),(12903,'Then Athena  came close to Odysseus, son of Laertes, and smote him with her wand, and again made him an old man; and mean raiment she put about his body, lest the swineherd might look upon him and know him, and might go to bear tidings to constant Penelope, and not hold the secret fast in his heart.'),(12904,'\n  Now Telemachus spoke first to the swineherd, and said:'),(12905,'What news is there in the city? '),(12906,'What news is there in the city? '),(12907,' Have the proud wooers by this time come home from their ambush, or are they still watching for me where they were, to take me on my homeward way?\"'),(12908,'To him, then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer and say:'),(12909,'  “I was not minded to go about the city, asking and enquiring of this; '),(12910,'my heart bade me with all speed to come back hither when I had given my message.'),(12911,' But there joined me a swift messenger from thy companions, a herald, who was the first to tell the news to thy mother.'),(12912,'for I saw it with my eyes.'),(12913,'for I saw it with my eyes.'),(12914,'  I was now above the city, as I went on my way, where the hill of Hermes is, when I saw a swift ship putting into our harbor, '),(12915,' and there were many men in her, and she was laden with shields and double-pointed spears.'),(12916,'   And I thought it was they, but I have no knowledge.”'),(12917,'\nSo he spoke, and the strong and mighty Telemachus smiled and with his eyes he glanced at his father, but shunned the swineherd\'s eye.'),(12918,'\nAnd when they had ceased from their labour and had made ready the meal, they fell to feasting, nor did their hearts lack aught of the equal feast.'),(12919,'  But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, they bethought them of rest, and took the gift of sleep.'),(12920,' As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, Telemachus, the dear son of divine Odysseus, bound beneath his feet his fair sandals and took his mighty spear, that fitted his grasp,  hasting to the city; and he spoke to his swineherd, saying:'),(12921,' “Father, I verily am going to the city, that my mother may see me,'),(12922,'\n for, methinks, she will not cease from woeful wailing and tearful lamentation until she sees my very self.'),(12923,' But to thee I give this charge.'),(12924,'  Lead this wretched stranger to the city, that there he may beg his food, '),(12925,' and whoso will shall give him a loaf and a cup of water.'),(12926,'For my part, I can in no wise burden myself with all men, seeing that I have grief at heart.'),(12927,' But if the stranger is sore angered at this,  it will be the worse for him. '),(12928,'I verily love to speak the truth.”'),(12929,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: '),(12930,' “Friend, be sure I am not myself fain to be left here.'),(12931,'For a beggar it is better to beg his food in the town than in the fields,'),(12932,' and whoso will shall give it me.'),(12933,'  For I am no more of an age to remain at the farmstead, so as to obey in all things the command of an overseer.'),(12934,' Nay, go thy way; '),(12935,'this man that thou biddest will lead me as soon as I have warmed myself at the fire, and the sun has grown hot. '),(12936,' For miserably poor are these garments which I wear, '),(12937,' and I fear lest  the morning frost may overcome me; '),(12938,' and ye say it is far to the city.” '),(12939,'\nSo he spoke, and Telemachus passed out through the farmstead with rapid strides, and was sowing the seeds of evil for the wooers.'),(12940,' But when he came to the stately house he set his spear in place, leaning it against a tall pillar,  and himself went in and crossed the threshold of stone.'),(12941,'Him the nurse Eurycleia was far the first to see, as she was spreading fleeces on the richly-wrought chairs. With a burst of tears she came straight toward him, '),(12942,' and round about them gathered the other maids of Odysseus of the steadfast heart,  and they kissed his head and shoulders in loving welcome.'),(12943,'\nThen forth from her chamber came wise Penelope, like unto Artemis or golden Aphrodite, and bursting into tears she flung her arms about her dear son, and kissed his head and both his beautiful eyes;  and with wailing she spoke to him winged words:'),(12944,'“Thou art come, Telemachus, sweet light of my eyes;'),(12945,'\n I thought I should never see thee more after thou hadst gone in thy ship to Pylos—secretly, and in my despite, to seek tidings of thy dear father.'),(12946,' Come, then, tell me what sight thou hadst of him.” '),(12947,' \n  Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(12948,'“My mother, stir not lamentation, I pray thee, nor rouse the heart in my breast, seeing that I am escaped from utter destruction. '),(12949,'Nay, bathe thyself, and take clean raiment for thy body, and then, going to thy upper chamber with thy handmaids,  vow to all the gods that thou wilt offer hecatombs that bring fulfillment, in the hope that Zeus may some day bring deeds of requital to pass.'),(12950,' But I will go to the place of assembly that I may bid to our house a stranger who followed me from Pylos on my way hither. '),(12951,' Him I sent forward with my godlike comrades,  and I bade Peiraeus take him home and give him kindly welcome, and show him honor until I should come.\"'),(12952,'So he spoke, but her word remained unwinged.'),(12953,' Then she bathed and took clean raiment for her body, and vowed to all the gods that she would offer hecatombs  that bring fulfillment, in the hope that Zeus would some day bring deeds of requital to pass.'),(12954,'But Telemachus thereafter went forth through the hall with his spear in his hand,'),(12955,'\n and with him went two swift hounds.'),(12956,'And wondrous was the grace that Athena shed upon him,'),(12957,'  and all the people marvelled at him as he came.'),(12958,'  Round about him the proud wooers thronged, speaking him fair, but pondering evil in the deep of their hearts.'),(12959,' Howbeit he avoided the great throng of these men, but where Mentor sat, and Antiphus, and Halitherses, who were friends of his father\'s house of old,  there he went and sat down, '),(12960,' and they questioned him of each thing. '),(12961,'Then Peiraeus, the famous spearman, drew near, leading the stranger through the city to the place of assembly; '),(12962,' and Telemachus did not long turn away from his guest, but went up to him.'),(12963,' Then Peiraeus was the first to speak, saying:'),(12964,'\n  “Telemachus, quickly send women to my house, that I may send to thee the gifts which Menelaus gave thee.\"'),(12965,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12966,' “Peiraeus, we know not how these things will be. '),(12967,'If the proud wooers  shall secretly slay me in my hall, and divide among them all the goods of my fathers, I would that thou shouldest keep and enjoy these things thyself rather than one of these.'),(12968,' But if I shall sow for them the seeds of death and fate, then do thou bring all to my house gladly, as I shall be glad.” '),(12969,' \nSo saying, he led the sore-tired stranger to the house.'),(12970,'  Now when they had come to the stately house they laid their cloaks on the chairs and high seats, and went into the polished baths and bathed.'),(12971,' And when the maids had bathed them and anointed them with oil, and had cast about them fleecy cloaks and tunics,  they came forth from the baths and sat down upon the chairs.'),(12972,' Then a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin for them to wash,'),(12973,' and beside them drew up a polished table.'),(12974,' And the grave housewife brought and set before them bread,  and therewith meats in abundance, granting freely of her store.'),(12975,' And his mother sat over against Telemachus by the door-post of the hall, leaning against a chair and spinning fine threads of yarn.'),(12976,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink,  the wise Penelope spoke first among them:'),(12977,'“Telemachus, I truly will go to my upper chamber and lay me on my bed, which has become for me a bed of wailing, ever wet with my tears, since the day when Odysseus set forth with the sons of Atreus for Ilios.'),(12978,'But thou tookest no care,  before the proud wooers come into this house, to tell me plainly of the return of thy father, if haply thou heardest aught.\"'),(12979,'And wise Telemachus answered her:'),(12980,'\n “Then verily, mother, I will tell thee all the truth.'),(12981,' We went to Pylos and to Nestor, the shepherd of the people,'),(12982,' and he received me in his lofty house and gave me kindly welcome, as a father might his own son who after a long time had newly come from a far:'),(12983,' even so kindly he tended me with his glorious sons.'),(12984,' Yet of Odysseus of the steadfast heart,  whether living or dead, he said he had heard naught from any man on earth. '),(12985,' But he sent me on my way with horses and jointed car to Menelaus, son of Atreus, the famous spearman.'),(12986,' There I saw Argive Helen, for whose sake Argives and Trojans toiled much by the will of the gods. '),(12987,' \n  And straightway Menelaus, good at the war-cry, asked me in quest of what I had come to goodly Lacedaemon;'),(12988,'and I told him all the truth.'),(12989,' Then he made answer to me, and said:'),(12990,'\n“‘Out upon them! for verily in the bed of a man of valiant heart  were they fain to lie, who are themselves cravens. '),(12991,'Even as when in the thicket-lair of a mighty lion a hind has laid to sleep her new-born suckling fawns, and roams over the mountain slopes and grassy vales seeking pasture, and then the lion comes to his lair  and upon the two lets loose a cruel doom, so will Odysseus let loose a cruel doom upon these men. '),(12992,' I would, O father Zeus, and Athena, and Apollo, that in such strength, as when once in fair-stablished Lesbos he rose up and wrestled a match with Philomeleides  and threw him mightily, and all the Achaeans rejoiced, even in such strength Odysseus might come among the wooers; '),(12993,'then should they all find swift destruction and bitterness in their wooing. '),(12994,'But in this matter of which thou dost ask and entreat me, verily I will not swerve aside to speak of other things, nor will I deceive thee;  but of all that the unerring old man of the sea told me, not one thing will I hide from thee or conceal.'),(12995,' He said that he had seen Odysseus in an island in grievous distress, in the halls of the nymph Calypso, who keeps him there perforce.'),(12996,' And he cannot come to his own native land, '),(12997,'for he has at hand no ships with oars, and no comrades,  to send him on his way over the broad back of the sea.’\n“So spoke Menelaus, son of Atreus, the famous spearman.'),(12998,' Now when I had made an end of all this I set out for home, '),(12999,'and the immortals gave me a fair wind and brought me quickly to my dear native land.\"'),(13000,'  So he spoke, and stirred the heart in her breast.'),(13001,'Then among them spoke also the godlike Theoclymenus, saying:'),(13002,'\n“Honored wife of Odysseus, son of Laertes, he truly has no clear understanding; but do thou hearken to my words, '),(13003,'for with certain knowledge will I prophesy to thee, and will hide naught.'),(13004,'  Be my witness Zeus above all gods, and this hospitable board and the hearth of noble Odysseus to which I am come, that verily Odysseus is even now in his native land, resting or moving, learning of these evil deeds, and he is sowing the seeds of evil for all the wooers.'),(13005,'  So plain a bird of omen did I mark as I sat on the benched ship, and I declared it to Telemachus.\"'),(13006,'Then wise Penelope answered him:'),(13007,' “Ah, stranger, I would that this word of thine might be fulfilled.'),(13008,' Then shouldest thou straightway know of kindness and many a gift  from me, so that one who met thee would call the blessed.”'),(13009,' \nThus they spoke to one another. And the wooers meanwhile in front of the palace of Odysseus were making merry, throwing the discus and the javelin in a levelled place, as their wont was, in insolence of heart.'),(13010,'  But when it was the hour for dinner, and the flocks came in from all sides from the fields, and the men led them who were wont to lead, then Medon, '),(13011,'who of all the heralds was most to their liking and was ever present at their feasts, spoke to them, saying:'),(13012,'\n“Youths, now that you have all made glad your hearts with sport,  come to the house that we may make ready a feast; '),(13013,'for it is no bad thing to take one\'s dinner in season.\"'),(13014,'So he spoke, and they rose up and went, and hearkened to his word. '),(13015,'And when they had come to the stately house they laid their cloaks on the chairs and high seats,  and men fell to slaying great sheep and fat goats, aye, and fatted and swine, and a heifer of the herd, and so made ready the meal.'),(13016,' But Odysseus and the goodly swineherd were making haste to go from the field to the city; '),(13017,' and the swineherd, a leader of men, spoke first, and said:'),(13018,'\n  “Stranger, since thou art eager to go the city today, as my master bade—though for myself I would rather have thee left here to keep the farmstead; '),(13019,'but I reverence and fear him, lest hereafter he chide me, '),(13020,'and hard are the rebukes of masters—  come now, let us go. '),(13021,' The day is far spent, and soon thou wilt find it colder toward evening.”'),(13022,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: '),(13023,'this thou biddest one with understanding. '),(13024,'this thou biddest one with understanding. '),(13025,' Come, let us go, and be thou my guide all the way.'),(13026,'  But give me a staff to lean upon, if thou hast one cut anywhere, for verily ye said that the way was treacherous.\"'),(13027,'He spoke, and flung about his shoulders his miserable wallet, full of holes, '),(13028,'slung by a twisted cord,'),(13029,'and Eumaeus gave him a staff to his liking.'),(13030,'  So they two set forth, and the dogs and the herdsmen stayed behind to guard the farmstead;'),(13031,' but the swineherd led his master to the city in the likeness of a woeful and aged beggar, leaning on a staff; '),(13032,'and miserable was the raiment that he wore about his body. '),(13033,' \nBut when, as they went along the rugged path,  they were near the city, and had come to a well-wrought, fair-flowing fountain, wherefrom the townsfolk drew water—this Ithacus had made, and Neritus, and Polyctor,'),(13034,'and around was a grove of poplars, that grow by the waters, circling it on all sides, and down the cold water flowed  from the rock above,'),(13035,'and on the top was built an altar to the nymphs where all passers-by made offerings—'),(13036,'there Melantheus, son of Dolius, met them as he was driving his she-goats, the best that were in all the herds, to make a feast for the wooers; '),(13037,' and two herdsmen followed with him.'),(13038,'  As he saw them, he spoke and addressed them, and reviled them in terrible and unseemly words,'),(13039,'and stirred the heart of Odysseus:'),(13040,'\n“Lo, now, in very truth the vile leads the vile. As ever, the god is bringing like and like together.'),(13041,' Whither, pray, art thou leading this filthy wretch, thou miserable swineherd,  this nuisance of a beggar to mar our feasts? '),(13042,' He is a man to stand and rub his shoulders on many doorposts, begging for scraps, not for swords or cauldrons.'),(13043,' If thou wouldest give me this fellow to keep my farmstead, to sweep out the pens and to carry young shoots to the kids,  then by drinking whey he might get himself a sturdy thigh.'),(13044,'But since he has learned only deeds of evil, he will not care to busy himself with work, but is minded rather to go skulking through the land, that by begging he may feed his insatiate belly.'),(13045,' But I will speak out to thee, and this word shall verily be brought to pass.'),(13046,'  If he comes to the palace of divine Odysseus, many a footstool, hurled about his head by the hands of those that are men, shall be broken on his ribs as he is pelted through the house.\"'),(13047,'So he spoke, and as he passed he kicked Odysseus on the hip in his folly,'),(13048,' yet he did not drive him from the path,  but he stood steadfast.'),(13049,' And Odysseus pondered whether he should leap upon him and take his life with his staff, or seize him round about, and lift him up, and dash his head upon the ground.'),(13050,' Yet he endured, and stayed him from his purpose.'),(13051,'And the swineherd looked the man in the face, and rebuked him, and lifted up his hands, and prayed aloud:'),(13052,'\n  “Nymphs of the fountain, daughters of Zeus, if ever Odysseus burned upon your altars pieces of the thighs of lambs or kids, wrapped in rich fat, fulfil for me this prayer; grant that he, my master, may come back, and that some god may guide him. '),(13053,'Then would he scatter all the proud airs  which now thou puttest on in thy insolence,ever roaming about the city, '),(13054,'while evil herdsmen destroy the flock.” '),(13055,' \nThen Melanthius, the goatherd, answered him:'),(13056,' “Lo now, how the cur talks, his mind full of mischief. Him will I some day  take on a black, benched ship far from Ithaca, that he may bring me in much wealth. '),(13057,' Would that Apollo, of the silver bow, might smite Telemachus to-day in the halls, or that he might be slain by the wooers, as surely as for Odysseus in a far land the day of return has been lost.\"'),(13058,'So saying, he left them there, as they walked slowly on,  but himself strode forward and right swiftly came to the palace of the king.'),(13059,'Straightway he entered in and sat down among the wooers over against Eurymachus, '),(13060,'for he loved him best of all.'),(13061,' Then by him those that served set a portion of meat, and the grave housewife brought and set before him bread,  for him to eat. '),(13062,'And Odysseus and the goodly swineherd halted as they drew nigh, and about them rang the sound of the hollow lyre, '),(13063,' for Phemius was striking the chords to sing before the wooers.'),(13064,' Then Odysseus clasped the swineherd by the hand, and said:'),(13065,'\n“Eumaeus, surely this is the beautiful house of Odysseus.  Easily might it be known, though seen among many.'),(13066,' There is building upon building, and the court is built with wall and coping, and the double gates are well-fenced; '),(13067,'no man may scorn it. '),(13068,'And I mark that in the house itself many  men are feasting: for the savour of meat arises from it, and therewith resounds the voice of the lyre, which the gods have made the companion of the feast.\"'),(13069,'To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say:'),(13070,' “Easily hast thou marked it, for in all things thou art ready of wit.'),(13071,' But come, let us take thought how these things shall be.'),(13072,'  Either do thou go first into the stately palace, and enter the company of the wooers, and I will remain behind here, '),(13073,' or, if thou wilt, remain thou here and I will go before thee.'),(13074,' But do not thou linger long, lest some man see thee without and pelt thee or smite thee.'),(13075,' Of this I bid thee take thought.”'),(13076,'\n  Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him:'),(13077,' this thou biddest one with understanding.'),(13078,' this thou biddest one with understanding.'),(13079,' But go thou before, and I will remain behind here;'),(13080,' for no whit unused am I to blows and peltings.'),(13081,' Staunch is my heart, for much evil have I suffered  amid the waves and in war;'),(13082,' let this too be added to what has gone before.'),(13083,'But a ravening belly may no man hide, an accursed plague that brings many evils upon men. Because of it are the benched ships also made ready, that bear evil to foemen over the unresting sea.” '),(13084,' \n  Thus they spoke to one another. '),(13085,'And a hound that lay there raised his head and pricked up his ears, Argos, the hound of Odysseus, of the steadfast heart, whom of old he had himself bred, but had no joy of him, for ere that he went to sacred Ilios.'),(13086,' In days past the young men were wont to take the hound to hunt  the wild goats, and deer, and hares; '),(13087,'but now he lay neglected, his master gone, in the deep dung of mules and cattle, which lay in heaps before the doors, till the slaves of Odysseus should take it away to dung his wide lands.'),(13088,'  There lay the hound Argos, full of vermin;'),(13089,' yet even now, when he marked Odysseus standing near, he wagged his tail and dropped both his ears, but nearer to his master he had no longer strength to move.'),(13090,' Then Odysseus looked aside and wiped away a tear,  easily hiding from Eumaeus what he did; and straightway he questioned him, and said:'),(13091,'“Eumaeus, verily it is strange that this hound lies here in the dung.'),(13092,'\n He is fine of form, but I do not clearly know whether he has speed of foot to match this beauty or whether he is merely as table-dogs  are, '),(13093,'which their masters keep for show.”'),(13094,'\nTo him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer and say:'),(13095,' “Aye, verily this is the hound of a man that has died in a far land.'),(13096,' If he were but in form and in action such as he was when Odysseus left him and went to Troy,  thou wouldest soon be amazed at seeing his speed and his strength.'),(13097,' No creature that he started in the depths of the thick wood could escape him,'),(13098,' and in tracking too he was keen of scent.'),(13099,' But now he is in evil plight, and his master has perished far from his native land, and the heedless women give him no care.'),(13100,'  Slaves, when their masters lose their power, are no longer minded thereafter to do honest service:'),(13101,' for Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, takes away half his worth from a man, when the day of slavery comes upon him.\"'),(13102,'So saying, he entered the stately house  and went straight to the hall to join the company of the lordly wooers. '),(13103,'But as for Argos, the fate of black death seized him straightway when he had seen Odysseus in the twentieth year.'),(13104,'\nNow as the swineherd came through the hall godlike Telemachus was far the first to see him, and quickly  with a nod he called him and to his side. '),(13105,'And Eumaeus looked about him and took a stool that lay near, on which the carver was wont to sit when carving for the wooers the many joints of meat, as they feasted in the hall.'),(13106,' This he took and placed at the table of Telemachus, over against him, and there sat down himself.'),(13107,' And a herald  took a portion of meat and set it before him, and bread from out the basket.'),(13108,' \nNight after him Odysseus entered the palace in the likeness of a woeful and aged beggar, leaning on a staff, '),(13109,'and miserable was the raiment that he wore about his body. '),(13110,' He sat down upon the ashen threshold within the doorway,  leaning against a post of cypress wood, which of old a carpenter had skilfully planed, and made straight to the line.'),(13111,' Then Telemachus called the swineherd to him, and, taking a whole loaf from out the beautiful basket, and all the meat his hands could hold in their grasp, spoke to him saying:'),(13112,'\n  “Take, and give this mess to yon stranger, and bid him go about himself and beg of the wooers one and all.'),(13113,' Shame is no good comrade for a man that is in need.\"'),(13114,'So he spoke, and the swineherd went, when he had heard this saying, and coming up to Odysseus spoke to him winged words:'),(13115,'\n  “Stranger, Telemachus gives thee these, and bids thee go about and beg of the wooers one and all.'),(13116,' Shame, he says, is no good thing in a beggar man.”'),(13117,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said, '),(13118,'“King Zeus, grant, I pray thee, that Telemachus may be blest among men,  and may have all that his heart desires.”'),(13119,'He spoke, and took the mess in both his hands and set it down there before his feet on his miserable wallet. Then he ate so long as the minstrel sang in the halls.'),(13120,' But when he had dined and the divine minstrel was ceasing to sing, '),(13121,' the wooers broke into uproar throughout the halls;'),(13122,' but Athena drew close to the side of Odysseus, son of Laertes, and roused him to go among the wooers and gather bits of bread, and learn which of them were righteous and which lawless.'),(13123,' Yet even so she was not minded to save one of them from ruin.'),(13124,'  So he set out to beg of every man, beginning on the right, stretching out his hand on every side, as though he had been long a beggar.'),(13125,' And they pitied him and gave, and marvelled at him, asking one another who he was and whence he came.'),(13126,'\nThen among them spoke Melanthius, the goatherd:'),(13127,'  “Hear me, wooers of the glorious queen, regarding this stranger, '),(13128,' for verily I have seen him before.'),(13129,'Truly it was the swineherd that led him hither, but of the man himself I know not surely from whence he declares his birth to be.\"'),(13130,'So he spoke, and Antinous rebuked the swineherd, saying:'),(13131,'  “Notorious swineherd, why, pray, didst thou bring this man to the city?'),(13132,' Have we not vagabonds enough without him, nuisances of beggars to mar our feast?'),(13133,' Dost thou not think it enough that they gather here and devour the substance of thy master, that thou dost bid this fellow too?” '),(13134,' \n  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say: '),(13135,'“Antinous, no fair words are these thou speakest, noble though thou art.'),(13136,' Who pray, of himself ever seeks out and bids a stranger from abroad, unless it be one of those that are masters of some public craft, a prophet, or a healer of ills, or a builder,  aye, or a divine minstrel, who gives delight with his song?'),(13137,'For these men are bidden all over the boundless earth.'),(13138,' Yet a beggar would no man bid to be burden to himself.'),(13139,' But thou art ever harsh above all the wooers to the slaves of Odysseus, and most of all to me; '),(13140,'yet I  care not, so long as my lady, the constant Penelope, lives in the hall, and godlike Telemachus.\"'),(13141,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(13142,'  “Be silent: do not, I bid thee, answer yonder man with many words, '),(13143,'for Antinous is wont ever in evil wise to provoke to anger  with harsh words, aye, and urges on the others too.”'),(13144,'With this he spoke winged words to Antinous:'),(13145,' “Antinous, truly thou carest well for me, as a father for his son, seeing that thou biddest me drive yonder stranger from the hall with a word of compulsion.'),(13146,' May the god never bring such a thing to pass.'),(13147,'but rather myself bid thee give.'),(13148,'but rather myself bid thee give.'),(13149,'but rather myself bid thee give.'),(13150,'  In this matter regard not my mother, no, nor any of the slaves that are in the house of divine Odysseus.'),(13151,' But verily far other is the thought in thy breast; '),(13152,'for thou art far more fain thyself to eat than to give to another.”'),(13153,'  Then Antinous answered him, and said: '),(13154,'“Telemachus, thou braggart, unrestrained in daring, what a thing hast thou said! '),(13155,'If all the wooers would but hand him as much as I, for full three months\' space this house would keep him at a distance.”'),(13156,'\nSo he spoke, and seized the footstool  on which he was wont to rest his shining feet as he feasted, and shewed it from beneath the table, where it lay. '),(13157,'But all the rest gave gifts, and filled the wallet with bread and bits of meat.'),(13158,' And now Odysseus was like to have gone back again to the threshold, and to have made trial of the Achaeans without cost,'),(13159,'but he paused by Antinous, and spoke to him, saying:'),(13160,'  “Friend, give me some gift; '),(13161,'thou seemest not in my eyes to be the basest of the Achaeans, but rather the noblest, for thou art like a king.'),(13162,' Therefore it is meet that thou shouldest give even a better portion of bread than the rest; '),(13163,' so would I make thy fame known all over the boundless earth.'),(13164,'For I too once dwelt in a house of my own among men,  a rich man in a wealthy house, and full often I gave gifts to a wanderer, whosoever he was and with whatsoever need he came.'),(13165,' Slaves too I had past counting, and all other things in abundance whereby men live well and are reputed wealthy. '),(13166,' \nBut Zeus, son of Cronos, brought all to naught—so, I ween, was his good pleasure—  who sent me forth with roaming pirates to go to Egypt, a far voyage, that I might meet my ruin;'),(13167,'and in the river Aegyptus I moored my curved ships.'),(13168,' Then verily I bade my trusty comrades to remain there by the ships and to guard the ships,  and I sent out scouts to go to places of outlook. '),(13169,'But my comrades, yielding to wantonness and led on by their own might, straightway set about wasting the fair fields of the men of Egypt; and they carried off the women and little children, and slew the men; '),(13170,'and the cry came quickly to the city.'),(13171,'  Then, hearing the shouting, the people came forth at break of day,'),(13172,' and the whole plain was filled with footmen and chariots and the flashing of bronze.'),(13173,' And Zeus, who hurls the thunderbolt, cast an evil panic upon my comrades, and none had courage to take his stand and face the foe; '),(13174,'for evil surrounded us on every side.'),(13175,'  So then they slew many of us with the sharp bronze, and others they led up to their city alive, to work for them perforce.'),(13176,' But they gave me to a friend who met them to take to Cyprus, even to Dmetor, son of Iasus, who ruled mightily over Cyprus; '),(13177,'and from thence am I now come hither, sore distressed.\"'),(13178,'  Then Antinous answered him, and said: '),(13179,'“What god has brought this bane hither to trouble our feast?'),(13180,' Stand off yonder in the midst, away from my table, lest thou come presently to a bitter Egypt and a bitter Cyprus, '),(13181,' seeing that thou art a bold and shameless beggar.'),(13182,' Thou comest up to every man in turn,'),(13183,'  and they give recklessly; for there is no restraint or scruple in giving freely of another\'s goods, since each man has plenty beside him.”'),(13184,' Then Odysseus of many wiles drew back, and said to him:'),(13185,'“Lo, now, it seems that thou at least hast not wits to match thy beauty.'),(13186,'  Thou wouldest not out of thine own substance give even a grain of salt to thy suppliant, thou who now, when sitting at another\'s table, hadst not the heart to take of the bread and give me aught. '),(13187,'Yet here lies plenty at thy hand.”'),(13188,'So he spoke, and Antinous waxed the more wroth at heart, and with an angry glance from beneath his brows spoke to him winged words:'),(13189,'\n  “Now verily, methinks, thou shalt no more go forth from the hall in seemly fashion, since thou dost even utter words of reviling.” '),(13190,' \nSo saying, he seized the footstool and flung it, and struck Odysseus on the base of the right shoulder, where it joins the back.'),(13191,' But he stood firm as a rock, nor did the missile of Antinous make him reel;  but he shook his head in silence, pondering evil in the deep of his heart. '),(13192,'Then back to the threshold he went and sat down, and down he laid his well-filled wallet; and he spoke among the wooers:'),(13193,' \n“Hear me, wooers of the glorious queen, that I may say what the heart in my breast bids me.'),(13194,'  Verily there is no pain of heart nor any grief when a man is smitten while fighting for his own possessions, whether for his cattle or for his white sheep;'),(13195,' but Antinous has smitten me for my wretched belly\'s sake, an accursed plague that brings many evils upon men.'),(13196,'  Ah, if for beggars there are gods and avengers, may the doom of death come upon Antinous before his marriage.\"'),(13197,'Then Antinous, son of Eupeithes, answered him:'),(13198,' “Sit still, and eat, stranger, or go elsewhere; lest the young men drag thee  by hand or foot through the house for words like these, and strip off all thy skin.”'),(13199,'So he spoke, but they all were filled with exceeding indignation, '),(13200,'and thus would one of the proud youths speak:'),(13201,'\n“Antinous, thou didst not well to strike the wretched wanderer. Doomed man that thou art, what if haply he be some god come down from heaven!'),(13202,'  Aye, and the gods in the guise of strangers from afar put on all manner of shapes, and visit the cities, beholding the violence and the righteousness of men.\"'),(13203,'So spoke the wooers, but Antinous paid no heed to their words. '),(13204,' And Telemachus nursed in his heart great grief  for the smiting, though he let no tear fall from his eyelids to the ground; but he shook his head in silence, pondering evil in the deep of his heart.'),(13205,'\nHowbeit when wise Penelope heard of the man\'s being smitten in the hall, she spoke among her handmaids, and said:'),(13206,' “Even so may thine own self be smitten by the famed archer Apollo.\"'),(13207,'  And again the housewife Eurynome said to her: '),(13208,'“Would that fulfillment might be granted to our prayers.'),(13209,' So should not one of these men come to the fair-throned Dawn.\"'),(13210,'And wise Penelope answered her:'),(13211,' “Nurse, enemies are they all, for they devise evil.'),(13212,' But Antinous more than all is like black fate. '),(13213,'Some wretched stranger roams through the house, begging alms of the men, '),(13214,'for want compels him, '),(13215,'and all the others filled his wallet and gave him gifts, but Antinous flung a footstool and smote him at the base of the right shoulder.” '),(13216,' \n  So she spoke among her handmaids, sitting in her chamber, '),(13217,' \n while goodly Odysseus was at meat.'),(13218,' Then she called to her the goodly swineherd, and said:'),(13219,'\n“Go, goodly Eumaeus, and bid the stranger come hither, that I may give him greeting, and ask him  if haply he has heard of Odysseus of the steadfast heart, or has seen him with his eyes.'),(13220,' He seems like one that has wandered far.\"'),(13221,'To her, then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say: “I would, O queen, that the Achaeans would keep silence, '),(13222,'for he speaks such words as would charm thy very soul.'),(13223,'  Three nights I had him by me, and three days I kept him in my hut, '),(13224,' for to me first he came when he fled by stealth from a ship,'),(13225,'but he had not yet ended the tale of his sufferings.'),(13226,' Even as when a man gazes upon a minstrel who sings to mortals songs of longing that the gods have taught him,  and their desire to hear him has no end, whensoever he sings, '),(13227,' even so he charmed me as he sat in my hall.'),(13228,' He says that he is an ancestral friend of Odysseus, and that he dwells in Crete, where is the race of Minos.'),(13229,' From thence has he now come on this journey hither, ever suffering woes  as he wanders on and on. '),(13230,'And he insists that he has heard tidings of Odysseus, near at hand in the rich land of the Thesprotians and yet alive; '),(13231,'and he is bringing many treasures to his home.\"'),(13232,'Then wise Penelope answered him:'),(13233,' “Go, call him hither, that he may himself tell me to my face. '),(13234,' But as for these men, let them make sport as they sit in the doorway '),(13235,'or here in the house, since their hearts are merry.'),(13236,' For their own possessions lie untouched in their homes, bread and sweet wine, '),(13237,'and on these do their servants feed. But themselves throng our house day after day,  slaying our oxen, and sheep, and fat goats, and keep revel and drink the flaming wine recklessly, '),(13238,' and havoc is made of all this wealth, '),(13239,' for there is no man here such as Odysseus was to keep ruin from the house.'),(13240,' But if Odysseus should come and return to his native land,  straightway would he with his son take vengeance on these men for their violent deeds.\"'),(13241,'So she spoke, and Telemachus sneezed loudly, and all the room round about echoed wondrously.'),(13242,' And Penelope laughed, and straightway spoke to Eumaeus winged words:'),(13243,'“Go, pray, call the stranger here before me.'),(13244,'  Dost thou not note that my son has sneezed at all my words.'),(13245,' Therefore shall utter death fall upon the wooers one and all, nor shall one of them escape death and the fates.'),(13246,' And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(13247,' If I find that he speaks all things truly,  I will clothe him in a cloak and tunic, fair raiment.”'),(13248,'So she spoke, and the swineherd went when he had heard this saying; '),(13249,'and coming up to Odysseus he spoke to him winged words:'),(13250,' \n“Sir stranger, wise Penelope calls for thee, the mother of Telemachus,'),(13251,' and her heart  bids her make enquiry about her husband, though she has suffered many woes. '),(13252,' And if she finds that thou speakest all things truly, she will clothe thee in a cloak and tunic, which thou needest most of all.'),(13253,' As for thy food, thou shalt beg it through the land, and feed thy belly, '),(13254,'and whoso will shall give it thee.” '),(13255,' \n  Then the much-enduring goodly Odysseus answered him: '),(13256,' “Eumaeus, soon will I tell all the truth to the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope.'),(13257,' For well do I know of Odysseus, and in common have we borne affliction.'),(13258,' But I have fear of this throng of harsh wooers,  whose wantonness and violence reach the iron heaven.'),(13259,' For even now, when, as I was going through the hall doing no evil, this man struck me and hurt me, neither Telemachus nor any other did aught to ward off the blow.'),(13260,' Wherefore now bid Penelope  to wait in the halls, eager though she be, till set of sun; '),(13261,'and then let her ask me of her husband regarding the day of his return, giving me a seat nearer the fire, '),(13262,'for lo, the raiment that I wear is mean, '),(13263,' and this thou knowest of thyself, for to thee first did I make my prayer.\"'),(13264,'So he spoke, and the swineherd went when he had heard this saying.'),(13265,'  And as he passed over the threshold Penelope said to him:'),(13266,' What does the wanderer mean by this?'),(13267,' What does the wanderer mean by this?'),(13268,' Does he fear some one beyond measure, or does he idly feel ashamed in the house?'),(13269,' \'Tis ill for a beggar to feel shame.\"'),(13270,'To her, then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer and say:'),(13271,'  “He speaks rightly, even as any other man would deem, in seeking to shun the insolence of overweening men.'),(13272,' But he bids thee to wait till set of sun.'),(13273,' And for thyself, too, it is far more seemly, O queen, to speak to the stranger alone, and to hear his words.\"'),(13274,'  Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(13275,' he divines how it may be.'),(13276,' he divines how it may be.'),(13277,'There are no mortal men, methinks, who in wantonness devise such wicked folly as these.\"'),(13278,'So she spoke, and the goodly swineherd departed  into the throng of the wooers when he had told her all. '),(13279,'And straightway he spoke winged words to Telemachus, holding his head close to him that the others might not hear:'),(13280,'\n“Friend, I am going forth to guard the swine and all things there, thy livelihood and mine; '),(13281,' but have thou charge of all things here.'),(13282,'  Thine own self do thou keep safe first of all, and let thy mind beware lest some ill befall thee, '),(13283,'for many of the Achaeans are devising evil, whom may Zeus utterly destroy before harm fall on us.\"'),(13284,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(13285,'go thy way when thou hast supped.'),(13286,'go thy way when thou hast supped.'),(13287,'  And in the morning do thou come and bring goodly victims.'),(13288,' But all matters here shall be a care to me and to the immortals.\"'),(13289,'So he spoke, and the swineherd sat down again on the polished chair. But when he had satisfied his heart with meat and drink, he went his way to the swine, and left the courts and the hall  full of banqueters.'),(13290,' And they were making merry with dance and song,'),(13291,' for evening had now come on.'),(13292,' Now there came up a public beggar who was wont to beg through the town of Ithaca, and was known for his greedy belly, eating and drinking without end.'),(13293,' No strength had he nor might, but in bulk was big indeed to look upon.'),(13294,'  Arnaeus was his name, '),(13295,'for this name his honored mother had given him at his birth; '),(13296,'but Irus all the young men called him, because he used to run on errands when anyone bade him.'),(13297,' He came now, and was for driving Odysseus from his own house; and he began to revile him, and spoke winged words:'),(13298,' “Give way, old man, from the doorway, lest soon thou be even dragged out by the foot.'),(13299,'Dost thou not see that all men are winking at me, and bidding me drag thee?'),(13300,'Yet for myself, I am ashamed to do it. '),(13301,' Nay, up with thee, lest our quarrel even come to blows.\"'),(13302,'Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered him:'),(13303,'  “Good fellow, I harm thee not in deed or word, nor do I begrudge that any man should give thee, though the portion he took up were a large one.'),(13304,' This threshold will hold us both, and thou hast no need to be jealous for the goods of other folk.'),(13305,' Thou seemest to me to be a vagrant, even as I am; and as for happy fortune, it is the gods that are like to give us that.'),(13306,'  But with thy fists do not provoke me overmuch, lest thou anger me, and, old man though I am, I befoul thy breast and lips with blood.'),(13307,' So should I have the greater peace tomorrow,'),(13308,' for I deem not that thou shalt return a second time to the hall of Odysseus, son of Laertes.\"'),(13309,'  Then, waxing wroth, the vagrant Irus said to him: '),(13310,'“Now see how glibly the filthy wretch talks, like an old kitchen-wife.'),(13311,' But I will devise evil for him, smiting him left and right, and will scatter on the ground all the teeth from his jaws, as though he were a swine wasting the corn.'),(13312,'  Gird thyself now, that these men, too, may all know our fighting.'),(13313,'But how couldst thou fight with a younger man?\"'),(13314,' Thus on the polished threshold before the lofty doors they stirred one another\'s rage right heartily.'),(13315,' And the strong and mighty Antinous heard the two,  and, breaking into a merry laugh, he spoke among the wooers:'),(13316,'\n“Friends, never before has such a thing come to pass, that a god has brought sport like this to this house.'),(13317,' Yon stranger and Irus are provoking one another to blows.'),(13318,' Come, let us quickly set them on.”'),(13319,'  So he spoke, and they all sprang up laughing and gathered about the tattered beggars.'),(13320,' And Antinous, son of Eupeithes, spoke among them, and said:'),(13321,'\n“Hear me, ye proud wooers, that I may say somewhat.'),(13322,' Here at the fire are goats\' paunches lying, which  we set there for supper, when we had filled them with fat and blood.'),(13323,'Now whichever of the two wins and proves himself the better man, let him rise and choose for himself which one of these he will.'),(13324,' And furthermore he shall always feast with us, nor will we suffer any other beggar to join our company and beg of us.” '),(13325,' \n  So spoke Antinous, and his word was pleasing to them. '),(13326,' Then with crafty mind Odysseus of many wiles spoke among them:'),(13327,'\n“Friends, in no wise may an old man that is overcome with woe fight with a younger.'),(13328,' Howbeit my belly, that worker of evil, urges me on, that I may be overcome by his blows.'),(13329,'  But come now, do you all swear to me a mighty oath, to the end that no man, doing a favour to Irus, may deal me a foul blow with heavy hand, and so by violence subdue me to this fellow.\"'),(13330,'So he spoke, and they all gave the oath not to smite him, even as he bade.'),(13331,' But when they had sworn and made an end of the oath,  among them spoke again the strong and mighty Telemachus:'),(13332,'“Stranger, if thy heart and thy proud spirit bid thee beat off this fellow, then fear not thou any man of all the Achaeans, for whoso strikes thee shall have to fight with more than thou.'),(13333,' Thy host am I, and the princes assent hereto,  Antinous and Eurymachus, men of prudence both.”'),(13334,'So he spoke, and they all praised his words.'),(13335,' But Odysseus girded his rags about his loins and showed his thighs, comely and great, and his broad shoulders came to view, and his chest and mighty arms.'),(13336,' And Athena  drew nigh and made greater the limbs of the shepherd of the people. '),(13337,' Then all the wooers marvelled exceedingly, '),(13338,' and thus would one speak with a glance at his neighbor:'),(13339,'“Right soon shall Irus, un-Irused, have a bane of his own bringing, such a thigh does yon old man show from beneath his rags.”'),(13340,'  So they spoke, and the mind of Irus was miserably shaken; '),(13341,' yet even so the serving men girded him, and led him out perforce all filled with dread, '),(13342,'and his flesh trembled on his limbs. '),(13343,'Then Antinous rated him and spoke, and addressed him:'),(13344,'“Better were it now, thou braggart, that thou wert not living, nor hadst ever been born,  if thou quailest and art so terribly afraid of this fellow—a man that is old and overcome by the woe that has come upon him.'),(13345,' But I will speak out to thee, and this word shall verily be brought to pass. '),(13346,'If this fellow conquers thee and proves the better man, I will fling thee into a black ship and send thee to the mainland  to King Echetus, the maimer of all men, who will cut off thy nose and ears with the pitiless bronze, and will draw forth thy vitals and give them raw to dogs to rend.” '),(13347,' \nSo he spoke, and thereat yet greater trembling seized the other\'s limbs, '),(13348,'and both men put up their hands.'),(13349,'and both men put up their hands.'),(13350,'  Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus was divided in mind whether he should strike him so that life should leave him even there as he fell, or whether he should deal him a light blow and stretch him on the earth.'),(13351,' And, as he pondered, this seemed to him the better course, to deal him a light blow, that the Achaeans might not take note of him.'),(13352,'  Then verily, when they had put up their hands, Irus let drive at the right shoulder, but Odysseus smote him on the neck beneath the ear and crushed in the bones, '),(13353,' and straightway the red blood ran forth from his mouth, and down he fell in the dust with a moan, and he gnashed his teeth, kicking the ground with his feet. '),(13354,' But the lordly wooers  raised their hands, and were like to die with laughter.'),(13355,' Then Odysseus seized him by the foot, and dragged him forth through the doorway until he came to the court and the gates of the portico. '),(13356,'And he set him down and leaned him against the wall of the court, '),(13357,'and thrust his staff into his hand and spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(13358,'\n  “Sit there now, and scare off swine and dogs, and do not thou be lord of strangers and beggars, miserable that thou art, lest haply thou meet with some worse thing to profit withal.\"'),(13359,'He spoke, and flung about his shoulders his miserable wallet, full of holes, '),(13360,'and slung by a twisted cord.'),(13361,'  Then back to the threshold he went and sat down; '),(13362,'and the wooers went within, laughing merrily, and they greeted him, saying:'),(13363,'\n“May Zeus grant thee, stranger, and the other immortal gods what thou desirest most, and the dearest wish of thy heart, seeing that thou hast made this insatiate fellow to cease from begging  in the land. '),(13364,'For soon shall we take him to the mainland to King Echetus, the maimer of all men.\"'),(13365,'So they spoke, and goodly Odysseus was glad at the word of omen.'),(13366,' And Antinous set before him the great paunch, filled with fat and blood, '),(13367,'and Amphinomus  took up two loaves from the basket and set them before him, and pledged him in a cup of gold, and said:'),(13368,'\n“Hail, Sir stranger; may happy fortune be thine in time to come, '),(13369,'though now thou art the thrall of many sorrows.” '),(13370,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: '),(13371,'  “Amphinomus, verily thou seemest to me to be a man of prudence; '),(13372,' and such a man, too, was thy father, for I have heard of his fair fame, that Nisus of Dulichium was a brave man and a wealthy.'),(13373,' From him, they say, thou art sprung, and thou seemest a man soft of speech.'),(13374,' Wherefore I will tell thee, and do thou give heed and hearken.'),(13375,'  Nothing feebler does earth nurture than man, of all things that on earth are breathing and moving.'),(13376,' For he thinks that he will never suffer evil in time to come, so long as the gods give him prosperity and his knees are quick; '),(13377,' but when again the blessed gods decree him sorrow,  this too he bears in sore despite with steadfast heart; '),(13378,'for the spirit of men upon the earth is even such as the day which the father of gods and men brings upon them.'),(13379,' For I, too, was once like to be prosperous among men, but many deeds of wantonness I wrought, yielding to my might and my strength,  and trusting in my father and my brethren.'),(13380,' Wherefore let no man soever be lawless at any time, but let him keep in silence whatever gifts the gods give. '),(13381,'Aye, for I see the wooers devising wantonness, wasting the wealth and dishonoring the wife  of a man who, I tell thee, will not long be away from his friends and his native land; '),(13382,' nay, he is very near.'),(13383,'But may some god lead thee forth hence to thy home, and mayest thou not meet him when he comes home to his dear native land.'),(13384,' For not without bloodshed, methinks,  will the wooers and he part one from the other when once he comes beneath his roof.”'),(13385,'So he spoke, and pouring a libation, drank of the honey-sweet wine, and then gave back the cup into the hands of the marshaller of the people.'),(13386,' But Amphinomus went through the hall with a heavy heart, bowing his head; '),(13387,'for his spirit boded bane.'),(13388,'  Yet even so he did not escape his fate,'),(13389,' but him, too, did Athena set in bonds so that he might be slain outright at the hands of Telemachus and by his spear.'),(13390,' So he sat down again on the chair from which he had risen.'),(13391,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, put it in the heart of the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope,  to show herself to the wooers, that she might set their hearts a-flutter and win greater honor from her husband and her son than heretofore.'),(13392,' Then she laughed a meaningless laugh and spoke, and addressed the nurse:'),(13393,'\n“Eurynome, my heart longs, though it has never longed before,  to show myself to the wooers, hateful though they are. '),(13394,' Also I would say a word to my son that will be for his profit, namely, that he should not consort ever with the overweening wooers, who speak him fair but have evil plans thereafter.” '),(13395,' \nThen the housewife, Eurynome, spoke to her and said:'),(13396,'   “Aye, verily, child, all this hast thou spoken aright. '),(13397,'Go, then, reveal thy word to thy son and hide it not; but first wash thy body and anoint thy face, '),(13398,'and go not as thou art with both cheeks stained with tears. Go, for it is ill to grieve ever without ceasing.'),(13399,'  For now, behold, thy son is of such an age, and it has been thy dearest prayer to the immortals to see him a bearded man.\"'),(13400,'Then wise Penelope answered her again:'),(13401,' “Eurynome, beguile me not thus in thy love to wash my body and anoint me with oil.'),(13402,'  All beauty of mine have the gods, that hold Olympus, destroyed since the day when my lord departed in the hollow ships.'),(13403,' But bid Autonoe and Hippodameia come to me, that they may stand by my side in the hall. '),(13404,'for I am ashamed.”'),(13405,'for I am ashamed.”'),(13406,'  So she spoke, and the old woman went forth through the chamber to bear tidings to the women, and bid them come.'),(13407,' Then again the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel.'),(13408,'On the daughter of Icarius she shed sweet sleep, and she leaned back and slept  there on her couch, and all her joints were relaxed. '),(13409,' And meanwhile the fair goddess was giving her immortal gifts, that the Achaeans might marvel at her.'),(13410,' With balm she first made fair her beautiful face, with balm ambrosial, such as that wherewith Cytherea, of the fair crown, anoints herself when she goes into the lovely dance of the Graces; '),(13411,' and she made her taller, too, and statelier to behold, and made her whiter than new-sawn ivory.'),(13412,' Now when she had done this the fair goddess departed, and the white-armed handmaids came forth from the chamber and drew near with sound of talking.'),(13413,' Then sweet sleep released Penelope,  and she rubbed her cheeks with her hands, and said:'),(13414,' “Ah, in my utter wretchedness soft slumber enfolded me.'),(13415,'\n Would that pure Artemis would even now give so soft a death, that I might no more waste my life away with sorrow at heart, longing for  the manifold excellence of my dear husband, for that he was pre-eminent among the Achaeans.”'),(13416,' \nSo saying, she went down from the bright upper chamber, not alone, '),(13417,'for two handmaids attended her.'),(13418,' Now when the fair lady reached the wooers she stood by the doorpost of the well-built hall,  holding before her face her shining veil; '),(13419,'and a faithful handmaid stood on either side of her.'),(13420,' Straightway then the knees of the wooers were loosened and their hearts enchanted with love, and they all prayed, each that he might lie by her side.'),(13421,' But she spoke to Telemachus, her dear son:'),(13422,'  “Telemachus, thy mind and thy thoughts are no longer steadfast as heretofore.'),(13423,'When thou wast but a child thou wast wont to revolve in thy mind thoughts more cunning;'),(13424,'  but now that thou art grown and hast reached the bounds of manhood, and wouldest be called a rich man\'s son by one who looked only to thy stature and thy comeliness, being himself a stranger from afar,  thy mind and thy thoughts are no longer right as before.'),(13425,' What a thing is this that has been done in these halls, that thou hast suffered yon stranger to be so maltreated!'),(13426,' How now, if the stranger, while sitting thus in our house, should come to some harm through grievous mishandling?'),(13427,' On thee, then, would fall shame and disgrace among men.\"'),(13428,' Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(13429,' “My mother, in this matter I take it not ill that thou art filled with anger.'),(13430,' Yet of myself I know in my heart and understand each thing, the good and the evil, '),(13431,'whereas heretofore I was but a child.'),(13432,'  But I am not able to plan all things wisely,'),(13433,' for these men here thwart my will, keeping by me, one on this side and one on that, with evil purpose, and I have none to help me.'),(13434,' Howbeit, I can tell thee, this battle between the stranger and Irus fell not out according to the mind of the wooers, but the stranger proved the better man.'),(13435,'  I would, O father Zeus, and Athena, and Apollo, that even now the wooers were thus subdued in our halls, and were hanging their heads, some in the court and some within the hall, and that each man\'s limbs were loosened, even as Irus now sits yonder by the gate of the court,  hanging his head like a drunken man, and cannot stand erect upon his feet, or go home to whatsoever place he is wont to go, because his limbs are loosened.\"'),(13436,'Thus they spoke to one another.'),(13437,' But Eurymachus addressed Penelope, and said:'),(13438,'\n  “Daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, if all the Achaeans throughout Iasian Argos could see thee, even more wooers would be feasting in your halls from to-morrow on, for thou excellest all women in comeliness and stature, and in the wise heart within thee.” '),(13439,' \n  Then wise Penelope answered him:'),(13440,'“Eurymachus, all excellence of mine, both of beauty and of form, the immortals destroyed on the day when the Argives embarked for Ilios, and with them went my husband Odysseus.'),(13441,' If he might but come and watch over this life of mine,  greater would be my fame and fairer.'),(13442,' so many woes has some god brought upon me.'),(13443,' so many woes has some god brought upon me.'),(13444,' Verily, when he went forth and left his native land, he clasped my right hand by the wrist, and said:'),(13445,'\n“‘Wife, I deem not that the well-greaved Achaeans  will all return from Troy safe and unscathed, '),(13446,' for the Trojans, men say, are men of war, hurlers of the spear, and drawers of the bow, and drivers of swift horses, such as most quickly decide the great strife of equal war.'),(13447,'  Therefore I know not whether the god will bring me back, or whether I shall be cut off there in the land of Troy:'),(13448,' so have thou charge of all things here.'),(13449,' Be mindful of my father and my mother in the halls even as thou art now, or yet more, while I am far away.'),(13450,' But when thou shalt see my son a bearded man,  wed whom thou wilt, and leave thy house.’'),(13451,' and now all this is being brought to pass.'),(13452,' and now all this is being brought to pass.'),(13453,'The night shall come when a hateful marriage shall fall to the lot of me accursed, whose happiness Zeus has taken away.'),(13454,' But herein has bitter grief come upon my heart and soul,'),(13455,' for such as yours was never the way of wooers heretofore. '),(13456,'They who are fain to woo a lady of worth and the daughter of a rich man and vie with one another, these bring of themselves cattle and goodly flocks, a banquet for the friends of the bride, and give to her glorious gifts; '),(13457,'  but they do not devour the livelihood of another without atonement.”'),(13458,'So she spoke, and the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus was glad, because she drew from them gifts, and beguiled their souls with gentle words, but her mind was set on other things.'),(13459,'Then Antinous, son of Eupeithes, spoke to her again, and said:  “Daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, as for gifts, if any man of the Achaeans is minded to bring them hither, do thou take them; '),(13460,'for it is not well to refuse a gift.'),(13461,' But for us, we will go neither to our lands nor elsewhither, until thou weddest him whosoever is best of the Achaeans.” '),(13462,' \n  So spoke Antinous, and his word was pleasing to them, '),(13463,'and each man sent forth a herald to bring his gifts.'),(13464,' For Antinous he brought a large and beautiful robe, richly broidered, '),(13465,'and in it were golden brooches, twelve in all, fitted with curved clasps.'),(13466,' And a chain did another straightway bring to Eurymachus, '),(13467,'one cunningly wrought of gold, strung with amber beads, bright as the sun.'),(13468,' A pair of earrings his squires brought to Eurydamas, with three clustering drops, '),(13469,' and great grace shone therefrom.'),(13470,' And out of the house of lord Peisander, son of Polyctor,  his squire brought a necklace, a jewel exceeding fair. '),(13471,'So of the Achaeans one brought one fair gift and one another.'),(13472,' But she thereafter, the fair lady, went up to her upper chamber, and her handmaids bare for her the beautiful gifts.\nBut the wooers  turned to dance and gladsome song, and made them merry, and waited for evening to come on. '),(13473,'And as they made merry dark evening came upon them.'),(13474,' Presently they set up three braziers in the hall to give them light,'),(13475,'and round about them placed dry faggots, long since seasoned and hard, and newly split with the axe;  and in the spaces between they set torches;'),(13476,'and in turn the handmaids of Odysseus, of the steadfast heart, kindled the flame.'),(13477,' Then Zeus-born Odysseus, of many wiles, himself spoke among the maids, and said:'),(13478,'\n“Maidens of Odysseus, that has long been gone, go to the chambers where your honored queen abides, '),(13479,'\n and twist the yarn by her side, and make glad her heart, as you sit in the chamber, or card the wool with your hands; '),(13480,' but I will give light to all these men.'),(13481,' For if they wish to wait for fair-throned Dawn, they shall in no wise outdo me. '),(13482,'I am one that can endure much.”'),(13483,'  So he spoke, and the maids broke into a laugh, and glanced at one another. '),(13484,' And fair-cheeked Melantho rated him shamefully, Melantho, whom Dolius begot, but whom Penelope had reared and cherished as her own child, and gave her playthings to her heart\'s desire.'),(13485,' Yet even so she had at heart no sorrow for Penelope,  but she loved Eurymachus and was wont to lie with him. '),(13486,'She then rated Odysseus with reviling words:'),(13487,'“Wretched stranger, thou art but a crack-brained fellow, unwilling to go to a smithy to sleep, or to a common lodge, but pratest here continually,  unabashed in the company of many lords, and hast no fear at heart. '),(13488,' Surely wine has mastered thy wits, or else thy mind is ever thus, '),(13489,'that thou dost babble idly.'),(13490,' Art thou beside thyself because thou hast beaten that vagrant Irus?'),(13491,'Beware, lest presently another better than Irus shall rise up against thee  to beat thee about the head with heavy hands, and befoul thee with streams of blood, and send thee forth from the house.” '),(13492,' \nThen with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered her:'),(13493,' “Presently shall I go yonder, thou shameless thing, and tell Telemachus, since thou speakest thus, that on the spot he may cut thee limb from limb.”'),(13494,'\n  So he spoke, and with his words scattered the women, '),(13495,' who fled through the hall, and the limbs of each were loosened beneath her in terror, '),(13496,'for they thought that he spoke truth.'),(13497,' But Odysseus took his stand by the burning braziers to give light, and looked upon all the men.'),(13498,'  Yet other things was the heart within him pondering—things that were not to be unfulfilled.'),(13499,'But Athena would in no wise suffer the proud wooers to abstain from bitter outrage, that pain might sink yet deeper into the heart of Odysseus, son of Laertes.'),(13500,' So among them Eurymachus, son of Polybus, began to speak,  jeering at Odysseus, '),(13501,' and making mirth for his companions:'),(13502,'“Hear me, wooers of the glorious queen, that I may say what the heart in my breast bids me.'),(13503,' Not without the will of the gods has this man come to the palace of Odysseus; '),(13504,'in any case there is a glare of torches from him—  from his head, for there is no hair on it, no, not a trace.”'),(13505,'Therewith he called to Odysseus, sacker of cities:'),(13506,' “Stranger, wouldest thou have a mind to serve for hire, if I should take thee into service on an outlying farm—thy pay shall be assured thee—gathering stones for walls, and planting tall trees?'),(13507,'  There would I provide thee with food the year through, and clothe thee with raiment and give thee sandals for thy feet.'),(13508,' But since thou hast learned only deeds of evil, thou wilt not care to busy thyself with work, but art minded rather to go skulking through the land, that thou mayest have wherewith to feed thy insatiate belly.” '),(13509,' \n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: '),(13510,' “Eurymachus, I would that we two might have a match in working in the season of spring, when the long days come, at mowing the grass, I with a curved scythe in my hands and thou with another like it,  and that the grass might be in plenty that so we might test our work, fasting till late evening.'),(13511,' Or I would again that there were oxen to drive—the best there are, tawny and large, both well fed with grass, of like age and like power to bear the yoke, tireless in strength—and that there were a field of four acres, and the soil should yield before the plough:'),(13512,'  then shouldest thou see me, whether or no I could cut a straight furrow to the end.'),(13513,' Or I would again that this day the son of Cronos might bring war upon us from whence he would, and I had a shield and two spears and a helmet all of bronze, that fitted well my temples: then shouldest thou see me mingling amid the foremost fighters,  and wouldest not prate, taunting me with this belly of mine.'),(13514,' But right insolent art thou, and thy heart is cruel,'),(13515,' and forsooth thou thinkest thyself to be some great man and mighty, because thou consortest with few men and weak. '),(13516,' If but Odysseus might return, and come to his native land,  soon would yonder doors, right wide though they are, prove all too narrow for thee in thy flight out through the doorway.\"'),(13517,'So he spoke, and Eurymachus waxed the more wroth at heart, and with an angry glance from beneath his brows spoke to him winged words:'),(13518,'“Wretch, presently will I work thee evil, that thou pratest thus,  unabashed in the presence of many lords, and hast no fear at heart.'),(13519,' Surely wine has mastered thy wits, or else thy mind is ever thus, '),(13520,' that thou dost babble idly.'),(13521,'Art thou beside thyself because thou hast beaten that vagrant Irus?” '),(13522,' \nSo saying, he seized a footstool,'),(13523,'but Odysseus  sat down at the knees of Amphinomus of Dulichium, in fear of Eurymachus.'),(13524,' And so Eurymachus struck a cup-bearer on the right hand, '),(13525,'and the wine-jug fell to the ground with a clang, and the bearer groaned, and fell backwards in the dust.'),(13526,' Then the wooers broke into uproar throughout the shadowy halls,  and thus would one man speak with a glance at his neighbor: '),(13527,'“Would that yon stranger had perished elsewhere on his wanderings or ever he came hither; '),(13528,'then should he never have brought among us all this tumult.'),(13529,' But now we are brawling about beggars, nor shall there be any joy in our rich feast, since worse things prevail.”'),(13530,'  Then among them spoke the strong and mighty Telemachus: “Strange sirs, ye are mad, and no longer hide that ye have eaten and drunk;'),(13531,'some god surely is moving you.'),(13532,' Nay, now that you have well feasted, go to your homes and take your rest, when your spirits bid you.'),(13533,' Yet do I drive no man forth.”'),(13534,'  So he spoke, and they all bit their lips, and marvelled at Telemachus, that he spoke boldly.'),(13535,' But Amphinomus spoke, and addressed them—he was son of the noble prince Nisus, son of Aretias:'),(13536,'\n“Friends, no man in answer to what has been fairly spoken  would wax wroth and make reply with wrangling words. '),(13537,'Abuse not any more this stranger nor any one of the slaves that are in the house of divine Odysseus.'),(13538,' Nay, come, let the bearer pour drops for libation in the cups, that we may pour libations, and go home to take our rest.'),(13539,'As for this stranger,  let us leave him in the halls of Odysseus to be cared for by Telemachus;'),(13540,' for to his house has he come.”'),(13541,'So said he, and the words that he spoke were pleasing to all.'),(13542,' Then a bowl was mixed for them by the lord Mulius, a herald from Dulichium, '),(13543,'who was squire to Amphinomus.'),(13544,'  And he served out to all, coming up to each in turn;'),(13545,' and they made libations to the blessed gods, and drank the honey-sweet wine.'),(13546,' Then when they had made libations and had drunk to their heart\'s content, they went their way, each man to his own house, to take their rest.'),(13547,' So goodly Odysseus was left behind in the hall, planning with Athena\'s aid the slaying of the wooers,'),(13548,'and he straightway spoke winged words to Telemachus:'),(13549,'\n“Telemachus, the weapons of war thou must needs lay away within  one and all, '),(13550,'and when the wooers miss them and question thee, thou must beguile them with gentle words, saying:'),(13551,' ‘Out of the smoke have I laid them, since they are no longer like those which of old Odysseus left behind him, when he went forth to Troy, but are all befouled, so far as the breath of fire has reached them.'),(13552,'  And furthermore this greater fear has a god put in my heart, lest haply, when heated with wine, you may set a quarrel afoot among you, and wound one another, and so bring shame on your feast and on your wooing.'),(13553,' For of itself does the iron draw a man to it.’”'),(13554,' So he spoke, and Telemachus hearkened to his dear father,  and calling forth the nurse Eurycleia, said to her:'),(13555,'“Nurse, come now, I bid thee, shut up the women in their rooms, while I lay away in the store-room the weapons of my father, the goodly weapons which all uncared-for the smoke bedims in the hall since my father went forth, '),(13556,'and I was still a child.'),(13557,'  But now I am minded to lay them away, where the breath of the fire will not come upon them.\"'),(13558,'Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered him:'),(13559,' “Aye, child, I would thou mightest ever take thought to care for the house and guard all its wealth.'),(13560,' But come, who then shall fetch a light and bear it for thee, '),(13561,' since thou wouldest not suffer the maids, who might have given light, to go before thee?\"'),(13562,'Then wise Telemachus answered her;'),(13563,' “This stranger here; '),(13564,' “This stranger here; for I will suffer no man to be idle who touches my portion of meal, even though he has come from afar.\"'),(13565,' So he spoke, but her word remained unwinged,'),(13566,' and she locked the doors of the stately hall.'),(13567,'  Then the two sprang up, Odysseus and his glorious son, and set about bearing within the helmets and the bossy shields and the sharp-pointed spears;'),(13568,'and before them Pallas Athena, bearing a golden lamp, made a most beauteous light.'),(13569,'  Then Telemachus suddenly spoke to his father, and said:'),(13570,'“Father, verily this is a great marvel that my eyes behold;'),(13571,'\n certainly the walls of the house and the fair beams and cross-beams of fir and the pillars that reach on high, glow in my eyes as with the light of blazing fire.'),(13572,'  Surely some god is within, one of those who hold broad heaven.”'),(13573,'\nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(13574,' “Hush, check thy thought, and ask no question; '),(13575,'this, I tell thee, is the way of the gods that hold Olympus.'),(13576,' But do thou go and take thy rest and I will remain behind here,  that I may stir yet more the minds of the maids and of thy mother;'),(13577,' and she with weeping shall ask me of each thing separately.” '),(13578,' \nSo he spoke, and Telemachus went forth through the hall by the light of blazing torches to go to his chamber to lie down, where he had heretofore been wont to rest, when sweet sleep came upon him.'),(13579,'  There now too he lay down and waited for the bright Dawn.'),(13580,' But goodly Odysseus was left behind in the hall, planning with Athena\'s aid the slaying of the wooers.'),(13581,'\nThen wise Penelope came forth from her chamber like unto Artemis or golden Aphrodite,'),(13582,' and for her they set by the fire, where she was wont to sit, a chair inlaid with spirals of ivory and silver, '),(13583,'which of old the craftsman Icmalius had made, and had set beneath it a foot-stool for the feet, that was part of the chair, and upon it a great fleece was wont to be laid.'),(13584,' On this then wise Penelope sat down, '),(13585,' and the white-armed maids came forth from the women\'s hall.'),(13586,' These began to take away the abundant food, the tables, and the cups from which the lordly men had been drinking, '),(13587,' and they cast the embers from the braziers on to the floor, and piled upon the braziers fresh logs in abundance, to give light and warmth.'),(13588,'\n  But Melantho began again a second time to rate Odysseus, saying: '),(13589,'“Stranger, wilt thou even now still be a plague to us through the night, roaming through the house, and wilt thou spy upon the women?'),(13590,' Nay, get thee forth, thou wretch, and be content with thy supper,'),(13591,'or straightway shalt thou even be smitten with a torch, and so go forth.\"'),(13592,'  Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered her:'),(13593,' “Good woman, why, pray, dost thou thus assail me with angry heart?'),(13594,'Is it because I am foul and wear mean raiment on my body, and beg through the land?'),(13595,'  Aye, for necessity compels me. '),(13596,'Of such sort are beggars and vagabond folk.  For I too once dwelt in a house of my own among men, a rich man in a wealthy house, and full often I gave gifts to a wanderer, whosoever he was and with whatsoever need he came.'),(13597,' Slaves too I had past counting and all other things in abundance whereby men live well and are reputed wealthy. '),(13598,' so, I ween, was his good pleasure.'),(13599,' so, I ween, was his good pleasure.'),(13600,' Wherefore, woman, beware lest thou too some day lose all the glory whereby thou now hast excellence among the handmaids;'),(13601,' lest perchance thy mistress wax wroth and be angry with thee, or Odysseus come home; '),(13602,'for there is yet room for hope.'),(13603,'  But if, even as it seems, he is dead, and is no more to return, yet now is his son by the favour of Apollo such as he was—even Telemachus.'),(13604,' Him it escapes not if any of the women in the halls work wantonness; for he is no longer the child he was.” '),(13605,' \nSo he spoke, and wise Penelope heard him;  and she rebuked the handmaid and spoke, and addressed her:'),(13606,'“Be sure, thou bold and shameless thing, that thy outrageous deed is in no wise hid from me, and with thine own head shalt thou wipe out its stain.'),(13607,' Full well didst thou know, for thou hast heard it from my own lips, that I was minded  to question the stranger in my halls concerning my husband; for I am sore distressed.”'),(13608,'With this she spoke also to the housewife Eurynome, and said:'),(13609,' “Eurynome, bring hither a chair and a fleece upon it, that the stranger may sit down and tell his tale, and listen to me; '),(13610,'for I am fain to ask him of all things.” '),(13611,'  So she spoke, and Eurynome speedily brought a polished chair and set it in place, and on it cast a fleece.'),(13612,' Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus sat down upon it, '),(13613,'and the wise Penelope spoke first, and said:'),(13614,'\n“Stranger, this question will I myself ask thee first.'),(13615,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?”'),(13616,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?”'),(13617,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(13618,' “Lady, no one of mortals upon the boundless earth could find fault with thee, '),(13619,' for thy fame goes up to the broad heaven, as does the fame of some blameless king, who with the fear of the gods in his heart,  is lord over many mighty men, upholding justice; and the black earth bears wheat and barley, and the trees are laden with fruit, the flocks bring forth young unceasingly, and the sea yields fish, all from his good leading; and the people prosper under him.'),(13620,'  Wherefore question me now in thy house of all things else, but ask not concerning my race and my native land, lest thou fill my heart the more with pains, as I think thereon; for I am a man of many sorrows.'),(13621,' Moreover it is not fitting  that I should sit weeping and wailing in another\'s house, for it is ill to grieve ever without ceasing. '),(13622,'I would not that one of thy maidens or thine own self be vexed with me, and say that I swim in tears because my mind is heavy with wine.\"'),(13623,'Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(13624,'“Stranger, all excellence of mine, both of beauty and of form,  the immortals destroyed on the day when the Argives embarked for Ilios, and with them went my husband, Odysseus. If he might but come, and watch over this life of mine, greater would be my fame and fairer.'),(13625,' so many woes has some god brought upon me.'),(13626,' so many woes has some god brought upon me.'),(13627,'  For all the princes who hold sway over the islands—Dulichium and Same and wooded Zacynthus—and those who dwell around in clear-seen Ithaca itself, all these woo me against my will, and lay waste my house.'),(13628,' Wherefore I pay no heed to strangers or to suppliants  or in any wise to heralds, whose trade is a public one; '),(13629,'but in longing for Odysseus I waste my heart away.'),(13630,' and I wind a skein of wiles. '),(13631,' and I wind a skein of wiles. '),(13632,'First some god breathed the thought in my heart to set up a great web in my halls and fall to weaving a robe—  fine of thread was the web and very wide; '),(13633,'and I straightway spoke among them:'),(13634,'“‘Young men, my wooers, since goodly Odysseus is dead, be patient, though eager for my marriage, until I finish this robe—I would not that my spinning should come to naught—a shroud for the lord Laertes against the time when  the fell fate of grievous death shall strike him down; '),(13635,' lest any one of the Achaean women in the land should be wroth with me, if he were to lie without a shroud, who had won great possessions.’ '),(13636,' \n“So I spoke, and their proud hearts consented.'),(13637,' Then day by day I would weave at the great web,  but by night would unravel it, when I had let place torches by me. '),(13638,'Thus for three years I kept the Achaeans from knowing, and beguiled them; '),(13639,' but when the fourth year came, as the seasons rolled on, as the months waned, and the many days were brought in their course, then verily by the help of my maidens, shameless creatures and reckless,  they came upon me and caught me, and upbraided me loudly. '),(13640,'So I finished the web against my will perforce.'),(13641,' And now I can neither escape the marriage nor devise any counsel more, '),(13642,' and my parents are pressing me to marry, and my son frets, while these men devour his livelihood,  as he takes note of it all;'),(13643,'for by now he is a man, and fully able to care for a household to which Zeus grants honor.'),(13644,' Yet even so tell me of thy stock from whence thou art; '),(13645,' for thou art not sprung from an oak of ancient story, or from a stone.\"'),(13646,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(13647,'  “Honored wife of Odysseus, son of Laertes, wilt thou never cease to ask me of my lineage?'),(13648,' Well, I will tell thee; '),(13649,'though verily thou wilt give me over to pains yet more than those by which I am now held in thrall; '),(13650,'for so it ever is, when a man has been far from his country as long as I have now,  wandering through the many cities of men in sore distress.'),(13651,'Yet even so will I tell thee what thou dost ask and enquire.'),(13652,' There is a land called Crete, in the midst of the wine-dark sea, a fair, rich land, begirt with water, '),(13653,' and therein are many men, past counting, and ninety cities.'),(13654,'  They have not all the same speech, but their tongues are mixed.'),(13655,' There dwell Achaeans, there great-hearted native Cretans, there Cydonians, and Dorians of waving plumes, and goodly Pelasgians. '),(13656,' Among their cities is the great city Cnosus, where Minos reigned when nine years old, he that held converse with great Zeus,  and was father of my father, great-hearted Deucalion. Now Deucalion begat me and prince Idomeneus.'),(13657,' Idomeneus had gone forth in his beaked ships to Ilios with the sons of Atreus; but my famous name is Aethon; I was the younger by birth, '),(13658,'while he was the elder and the better man.'),(13659,'  There it was that I saw Odysseus and gave him gifts of entertainment; '),(13660,'for the force of the wind had brought him too to Crete, as he was making for the land of Troy, and drove him out of his course past Malea.'),(13661,' So he anchored his ships at Amnisus, where is the cave of Eilithyia, in a difficult harbor, and hardly did he escape the storm. '),(13662,' \n  Then straightway he went up to the city and asked for Idomeneus;'),(13663,'for he declared that he was his friend, beloved and honored.'),(13664,' But it was now the tenth or the eleventh dawn since Idomeneus had gone in his beaked ships to Ilios.'),(13665,' So I took him to the house, and gave him entertainment  with kindly welcome of the rich store that was in the house, '),(13666,'and to the rest of his comrades who followed with him I gathered and gave out of the public store barley meal and flaming wine and bulls for sacrifice, that their hearts might be satisfied.'),(13667,' There for twelve days the goodly Achaeans tarried, '),(13668,'  for the strong North Wind penned them there, and would not suffer them to stand upon their feet on the land, for some angry god had roused it.'),(13669,' But on the thirteenth day the wind fell and they put to sea.\"'),(13670,'He spoke, and made the many falsehoods of his tale seem like the truth,'),(13671,' and as she listened her tears flowed and her face melted '),(13672,' as the snow melts on the lofty mountains, the snow which the East Wind thaws when the West Wind has strewn it, '),(13673,'and as it melts the streams of the rivers flow full:'),(13674,' so her fair cheeks melted as she wept and mourned for her husband, who even then was sitting by her side. '),(13675,'And Odysseus  in his heart had pity for his weeping wife, but his eyes stood fixed between his lids as though they were horn or iron, '),(13676,' and with guile he hid his tears.'),(13677,' But she, when she had had her fill of tearful wailing, again answered him and spoke, saying:'),(13678,'\n  “Now verily, stranger, am I minded to put thee to the test, whether or no thou didst in very truth entertain there in thy halls my husband with his godlike comrades, even as thou sayest.'),(13679,' Tell me what manner of raiment he wore about his body, and what manner of man he was himself; and tell me of the comrades who followed him.\"'),(13680,'  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(13681,'“Lady, hard is it for one that has been so long afar to tell thee this, '),(13682,' for it is now the twentieth year since he went thence and departed from my country.'),(13683,' But I will tell thee as my mind pictures him.'),(13684,'  A fleecy cloak of purple did goodly Odysseus wear, a cloak of double fold, '),(13685,' but the brooch upon it was fashioned of gold with double clasps, '),(13686,' and on the front it was curiously wrought:'),(13687,' a hound held in his fore paws a dappled fawn, and pinned it in his jaws as it writhed.'),(13688,' And at this all men marvelled,  how, though they were of gold, the hound was pinning the fawn and strangling it, and the fawn was writhing with its feet and striving to flee.'),(13689,' And I noted the tunic about his body, all shining as is the sheen upon the skin of a dried onion, '),(13690,' so soft it was; and it glistened like the sun.'),(13691,'  Verily many women gazed at him in wonder.'),(13692,' And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(13693,' I know not whether Odysseus was thus clothed at home, or whether one of his comrades gave him the raiment when he went on board the swift ship, or haply even some stranger, since to many men  was Odysseus dear, '),(13694,' for few of the Achaeans were his peers.'),(13695,' \n I, too, gave him a sword of bronze, and a fair purple cloak of double fold, and a fringed tunic, and with all honor sent him forth on his benched ship.'),(13696,' Furthermore, a herald  attended him, a little older than he, '),(13697,'and I will tell thee of him too, what manner of man he was.'),(13698,'He was round-shouldered, dark of skin, and curly-haired, and his name was Eurybates; '),(13699,' and Odysseus honored him above his other comrades, because he was like-minded with himself.\"'),(13700,'So he spoke, and in her heart aroused yet more the desire of weeping,  as she recognized the sure tokens that Odysseus told her.'),(13701,' But she, when she had had her fill of tearful wailing,'),(13702,' made answer and said to him:'),(13703,'\n“Now verily, stranger, though before thou wast pitied, shalt thou be dear and honored in my halls, '),(13704,' for it was I that gave him this raiment, since thou describest it thus, and folded it, and brought it forth from the store-room, and added thereto the shining brooch to be a thing of joy to him.'),(13705,' But my husband I shall never welcome back, returning home to his dear native land.'),(13706,' Wherefore it was with an evil fate that Odysseus  went forth in the hollow ship to see evil Ilios, that should never be named.”'),(13707,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(13708,' “Honored wife of Odysseus, son of Laertes, mar not now thy fair face any more, nor waste thy heart at all in weeping for thy husband.'),(13709,' I count it indeed no blame in thee; '),(13710,' for any woman weeps when she has lost her wedded husband, to whom she has borne children in her love, though he were far other than Odysseus, who, they say, is like unto the gods.'),(13711,' Yet do thou cease from weeping, and hearken to my words; '),(13712,'for I will tell thee with sure truth, and will hide nothing,  how but lately I heard of the return of Odysseus, that he is near at hand in the rich land of the Thesprotians, and yet alive,'),(13713,'and he is bringing with him many rich treasures, as he begs through the land.'),(13714,' But he lost his trusty comrades and his hollow ship on the wine-dark sea,  as he journeyed from the isle Thrinacia; '),(13715,'for Zeus and Helios waxed wroth against him '),(13716,'because his comrades had slain the kine of Helios. '),(13717,' \nSo they all perished in the surging sea, '),(13718,'  but he on the keel of his ship was cast forth by the wave on the shore, on the land of the Phaeacians, who are near of kin to the gods.  These heartily showed him all honor, as if he were a god, and gave him many gifts, and were fain themselves to send him home unscathed.'),(13719,' Yea, and Odysseus would long since have been here, '),(13720,'only it seemed to his mind more profitable to gather wealth by roaming over the wide earth; '),(13721,'  so truly does Odysseus beyond all mortal men know many gainful ways, nor could any mortal beside vie with him.'),(13722,' Thus Pheidon, king of the Thesprotians, told me the tale.'),(13723,' Moreover he swore in my own presence, as he poured libations in his halls, that the ship was launched and the men ready  who were to convey him to his dear native land.'),(13724,' But me he sent forth first,'),(13725,' for a ship of the Thesprotians chanced to be setting out for Dulichium, rich in wheat.'),(13726,' And he showed me all the treasure that Odysseus had gathered; '),(13727,' verily unto the tenth generation would it feed his children after him,  so great was the wealth that lay stored for him in the halls of the king.'),(13728,' But Odysseus, he said, had gone to Dodona to hear the will of Zeus from the high-crested oak of the god, even how he might return to his dear native land after so long an absence, whether openly or in secret.'),(13729,'\n  “Thus, as I tell thee, he is safe, and will presently come; he is very near, and not long will he now be far from his friends and his native land.'),(13730,' Yet will I give thee an oath.'),(13731,' Be Zeus my witness first, highest and best of gods, and the hearth of noble Odysseus to which I am come, '),(13732,' that verily all these things shall be brought to pass even as I tell thee.'),(13733,'In the course of this very month shall Odysseus come hither, as the old moon wanes and the new appears.\"'),(13734,'Then wise Penelope answered him:'),(13735,' “Ah, stranger, I would that this word of thine might be fulfilled.'),(13736,'  Then shouldest thou straightway know of kindness and many a gift from me, so that one who met thee would call thee blessed.'),(13737,' Yet in my heart I forebode it thus, even as it shall be.'),(13738,' Neither shall Odysseus any more come home, nor shalt thou obtain a convoy hence, since there are not now in the house such masters  as Odysseus was among men—as sure as ever such a man there was—to send reverend strangers on their way, and to welcome them. '),(13739,' \nBut still, my maidens, wash the stranger\'s feet and prepare his bed—bedstead and cloaks and bright coverlets—that in warmth and comfort he may come to the golden-throned Dawn.'),(13740,'  And right early in the morning bathe him and anoint him, that in our house at the side of Telemachus he may bethink him of food as he sits in the hall.'),(13741,' And worse shall it be for any man among them who vexes this man\'s soul with pain; '),(13742,' naught thereafter shall he accomplish here, how fierce soever his wrath.'),(13743,'  For how shalt thou learn of me, stranger, whether I in any wise excel other women in wit and prudent counsel, if all unkempt and clad in poor raiment thou sittest at meat in my halls?'),(13744,' Men are but short-lived. '),(13745,'If one be himself hard, and have a hard heart,  on him do all mortal men invoke woes for the time to come, while he still lives, and when he is dead all men mock at him.'),(13746,' But if one be blameless and have a blameless heart, his fame do strangers bear far and wide among all men, and many call him a true man.\"'),(13747,'  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(13748,'“Honored wife of Odysseus, son of Laertes, verily cloaks and bright coverlets became hateful in my eyes on the day when first I left behind me the snowy mountains of Crete, as I fared on my long-oared ship.  Nay, I will lie, as in time past I was wont to rest through sleepless nights;'),(13749,' for many a night have I lain upon a foul bed and waited for the bright-throned Dawn.'),(13750,' Aye, and baths for the feet give my heart no pleasure, '),(13751,'nor shall any woman touch my foot  of all those who are serving-women in thy hall, unless there is some old, true-hearted dame who has suffered in her heart as many woes as I; '),(13752,' such an one I would not grudge to touch my feet.\"'),(13753,' Then wise Penelope answered him again: '),(13754,' “Dear stranger, '),(13755,' “Dear stranger, never yet has a man discreet as thou, of those who are strangers from afar, come to my house as a more welcome guest, so wise and prudent are all thy words. '),(13756,' I have an old dame with a heart of understanding in her breast, who lovingly nursed and cherished my hapless husband,  and took him in her arms on the day when his mother bore him. She shall wash thy feet, weak with age though she be.'),(13757,' Come now, wise Eurycleia, arise and wash the feet of one of like age with thy master.'),(13758,' Even such as his are now haply the feet of Odysseus, and such his hands, '),(13759,' for quickly do men grow old in evil fortune.”'),(13760,' \nSo she spoke, and the old woman hid her face in her hands and let fall hot tears, uttering words of lamentation:'),(13761,'\n“Ah, woe is me, child, because of thee, for that I can do naught.'),(13762,' Surely Zeus hated thee above all men, though thou hadst a god-fearing heart.'),(13763,'  For never yet did any mortal burn to Zeus, who hurls the thunderbolt, so many fat thigh-pieces or so many choice hecatombs as thou gavest him, with prayers that thou mightest reach a sleek old age and rear thy glorious son.'),(13764,' But lo, now, from thee alone has he wholly cut off the day of thy returning.'),(13765,'  Even thus, I ween, did women mock at him too, in a strange and distant land, when he came to some man\'s glorious house, as these shameless creatures here all mock at thee. It is to shun insult now from them and their many taunts that thou dost not suffer them to wash thy feet,'),(13766,' but me, who am nothing loath, has  the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, bidden to wash thee. '),(13767,'Therefore will I wash thy feet, both for Penelope\'s own sake and for thine, for the heart within me is stirred with sorrow.'),(13768,' But come now, hearken to the word that I shall speak.'),(13769,' Many sore-tried strangers have come hither,  but I declare that never yet have I seen any man so like another as thou in form, and in voice, and in feet art like Odysseus.\"'),(13770,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(13771,'“Old dame, so say all men whose eyes have beheld us two, that  we are very like each other, even as thou thyself dost note and say.”'),(13772,'So he spoke, and the old dame took the shining cauldron with water wherefrom she was about to wash his feet, and poured in cold water in plenty, and then added thereto the warm.'),(13773,' But Odysseus sat him down away from the hearth and straightway turned himself toward the darkness,'),(13774,' for he at once had a foreboding at heart that, as she touched him, she might note a scar, and the truth be made manifest.'),(13775,' So she drew near and began to wash her lord, '),(13776,'and straightway knew the scar of the wound which long ago a boar had dealt him with his white tusk, when Odysseus had gone to Parnassus to visit Autolycus and the sons of Autolycus,  his mother\'s noble father, who excelled all men in thievery and in oaths.'),(13777,' It was a god himself that had given him this skill, even Hermes, '),(13778,'for to him he was wont to burn acceptable sacrifices of the thighs of lambs and kids; '),(13779,'so Hermes befriended him with a ready heart.'),(13780,' Now Autolycus, on coming once to the rich land of Ithaca,  had found his daughter\'s son a babe new-born, '),(13781,'and when he was finishing his supper, Eurycleia laid the child upon his knees and spoke, and addressed him:'),(13782,'\n“Autolycus, find now thyself a name to give to thy child\'s own child; '),(13783,'be sure he has long been prayed for.” '),(13784,' \n  Then Autolycus answered her, and said:'),(13785,'“My daughter\'s husband and my daughter, give him whatsoever name I say.'),(13786,' Lo, inasmuch as I am come hither as one that has been angered with many, both men and women, over the fruitful earth, '),(13787,' therefore let the name by which the child is named be Odysseus.'),(13788,'And for my part,  when he is a man grown and comes to the great house of his mother\'s kin at Parnassus, where are my possessions, I will give him thereof and send him back rejoicing.\"'),(13789,'It was for this reason that Odysseus had come, that Autolycus might give him the glorious gifts.'),(13790,' And Autolycus and the sons of Autolycus  clasped his hands in welcome and greeted him with gentle words, '),(13791,'and Amphithea, his mother\'s mother, took Odysseus in her arms and kissed his head and both his beautiful eyes.'),(13792,'  But Autolycus called to his glorious sons to make ready the meal,'),(13793,' and they hearkened to his call.  At once they led in a bull, five years old,'),(13794,' which they flayed and dressed, and cut up all the limbs. Then they sliced these cunningly and pierced them with spits, and roasted them skilfully and distributed the portions.'),(13795,' So, then, all day long till set of sun  they feasted, nor did their hearts lack aught of the equal feast.'),(13796,'But when the sun set and darkness came on they lay down to rest and took the gift of sleep.'),(13797,'\nBut as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, they went forth to the hunt, the hounds and  the sons of Autolycus too, '),(13798,'and with them went goodly Odysseus.'),(13799,' Up the steep mountain Parnassus, clothed with forests, they climbed, and presently reached its windy hollows.'),(13800,' The sun was now just striking on the fields, as he rose from softly-gliding, deep-flowing Oceanus,  when the beaters came to a glade. '),(13801,'Before them went the hounds, tracking the scent, and behind them the sons of Autolycus, '),(13802,' and among these the goodly Odysseus followed, close upon the hounds, brandishing his long spear.'),(13803,' Now thereby a great wild boar was lying in a thick lair, '),(13804,' through which the strength of the wet winds could never blow nor the rays of the bright sun beat, nor could the rain pierce through it,'),(13805,' so thick it was; and fallen leaves were there in plenty. '),(13806,' Then about the boar there came the noise of the feet of men and dogs  as they pressed on in the chase,'),(13807,' and forth from his lair he came against them with bristling back and eyes flashing fire, and stood there at bay close before them.'),(13808,' Then first of all Odysseus rushed on, holding his long spear on high in his stout hand, eager to smite him; '),(13809,' but the boar was too quick for him and struck him  above the knee, charging upon him sideways, and with his tusk tore a long gash in the flesh, but did not reach the bone of the man.'),(13810,' But Odysseus with sure aim smote him on the right shoulder, and clear through went the point of the bright spear,  '),(13811,'and the boar fell in the dust with a cry, and his life flew from him. '),(13812,' \n  Then the dear sons of Autolycus busied themselves with the carcase, and the wound of noble, god-like Odysseus they bound up skilfully, and checked the black blood with a charm, and straightway returned to the house of their dear father. '),(13813,'And when Autolycus and the sons of Autolycus  had fully healed him, and had given him glorious gifts, they quickly sent him back with joy to his native land, to Ithaca.'),(13814,' Then his father and his honored mother rejoiced at his return, and asked him all the story, how he got his wound; '),(13815,'and he told them all the truth,  how, while he was hunting, a boar had struck him with his white tusk when he had gone to Parnassus with the sons of Autolycus.'),(13816,'\nThis scar the old dame, when she had taken the limb in the flat of her hands, knew by the touch, and she let fall the foot.'),(13817,' Into the basin the leg fell, and the brazen vessel rang.  Over it tilted,'),(13818,'  and the water was spilled upon the ground. '),(13819,'Then upon her soul came joy and grief in one moment, and both her eyes were filled with tears and the flow of her voice was checked.'),(13820,' But she touched the chin of Odysseus, and said:'),(13821,'\n“Verily thou art Odysseus, dear child, '),(13822,'and I knew thee not,  till I had handled all the body of my lord.”'),(13823,'She spoke, and with her eyes looked toward Penelope, fain to show her that her dear husband was at home.'),(13824,' But Penelope could not meet her glance nor understand, '),(13825,'for Athena had turned her thoughts aside. '),(13826,' But Odysseus,  feeling for the woman\'s throat, seized it with his right hand, and with the other drew her closer to him, and said:'),(13827,'\n“Mother, why wilt thou destroy me?'),(13828,' Thou didst thyself nurse me at this thy breast, '),(13829,'and now after many grievous toils I am come in the twentieth year to my native land.'),(13830,'  But since thou hast found me out, and a god has put this in thy heart, be silent lest any other in the halls learn hereof.'),(13831,'For thus will I speak out to thee, and verily it shall be brought to pass:'),(13832,'  if a god shall subdue the lordly wooers unto me, I will not spare thee, my nurse though thou art, when  I slay the other serving-women in my halls.”'),(13833,'Then wise Eurycleia answered him:'),(13834,' “My child, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth!'),(13835,' Thou knowest how firm my spirit is and unyielding: I shall be as close as hard stone or iron.'),(13836,'  And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart. '),(13837,'If a god shall subdue the lordly wooers unto thee, then will I name over to thee the women in thy halls, which ones dishonor thee, and which are guiltless.” '),(13838,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:  “Mother, why, pray, wilt thou speak of them?'),(13839,'  Thou needest not at all.'),(13840,' Of myself will I mark them well, and come to know each one.'),(13841,' Nay, keep the matter to thyself, and leave the issue to the gods.\"'),(13842,'So he spoke, and the old woman went forth through the hall to bring water for his feet, '),(13843,'for all the first was spilled.'),(13844,'  And when she had washed him, and anointed him richly with oil, Odysseus again drew his chair nearer to the fire to warm himself, and hid the scar with his rags.'),(13845,'\nThen wise Penelope was the first to speak, saying:'),(13846,' “Stranger, this little thing further will I ask thee myself, '),(13847,'  for it will soon be the hour for pleasant rest, for him at least on whom sweet sleep may come despite his care.'),(13848,' But to me has a god given sorrow that is beyond all measure, '),(13849,'for day by day I find my joy in mourning and lamenting, while looking to my household tasks and those of my women in the house,  '),(13850,' but when night comes and sleep lays hold of all, I lie upon my bed, and sharp cares, crowding close about my throbbing heart, disquiet me, as I mourn. '),(13851,'Even as when the daughter of Pandareus, the nightingale of the greenwood, sings sweetly, when spring is newly come,  as she sits perched amid the thick leafage of the trees, and with many trilling notes pours forth her rich voice in wailing for her child, dear Itylus, whom she had one day slain with the sword unwittingly, Itylus, the son of king Zethus; even so my heart sways to and fro in doubt,  whether to abide with my son and keep all things safe, my possessions, my slaves, and my great, high-roofed house, respecting the bed of my husband and the voice of the people, or to go now with him whosoever is best of the Achaeans, who woos me in the halls and offers bride-gifts past counting.'),(13852,'  Furthermore my son, so long as he was a child and slack of wit, would not suffer me to marry and leave the house of my husband; '),(13853,'but now that he is grown and has reached the bounds of manhood, lo, he even prays me to go back again from these halls, being vexed for his substance that the Achaeans devour to his cost.'),(13854,'  But come now, hear this dream of mine, and interpret it for me.'),(13855,' Twenty geese I have in the house that come forth from the water and eat wheat, and my heart warms with joy as I watch them.'),(13856,' But forth from the mountain there came a great eagle with crooked beak and broke all their necks and killed them; '),(13857,' and they lay strewn  in a heap in the halls, while he was borne aloft to the bright sky. '),(13858,' Now for my part I wept and wailed, in a dream though it was, and round me thronged the fair-tressed Achaean women, as I grieved piteously because the eagle had slain my geese. '),(13859,' \nThen back he came and perched upon a projecting roof-beam,  and with the voice of a mortal man checked my weeping, and said:'),(13860,'\n“‘Be of good cheer, daughter of far-famed Icarius;'),(13861,' this is no dream, but a true vision of good which shall verily find fulfillment.'),(13862,' The geese are the wooers, and I, that before was the eagle, am now again come back as thy husband,  who will let loose a cruel doom upon all the wooers.’'),(13863,'“So he spoke, and sweet sleep released me, '),(13864,' and looking about I saw the geese in the halls, feeding on wheat beside the trough, where they had before been wont to feed.\"'),(13865,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her and said:'),(13866,'  “Lady, in no wise is it possible to wrest this dream aside and give it another meaning, since verily Odysseus himself has shewn thee how he will bring it to pass.'),(13867,' For the wooers\' destruction is plain to see, for one and all; not one of them shall escape death and the fates.\"'),(13868,'Then wise Penelope answered him again:'),(13869,'  “Stranger, dreams verily are baffling and unclear of meaning, and in no wise do they find fulfillment in all things for men.'),(13870,' For two are the gates of shadowy dreams, '),(13871,' and one is fashioned of horn and one of ivory.'),(13872,' Those dreams that pass through the gate of sawn ivory  deceive men, bringing words that find no fulfillment. '),(13873,'But those that come forth through the gate of polished horn bring true issues to pass, when any mortal sees them.'),(13874,' But in my case it was not from thence, methinks, that my strange dream came.'),(13875,' Ah, truly it would then have been welcome to me and to my son.'),(13876,'  But another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(13877,' Even now is coming on this morn of evil name which is to cut me off from the house of Odysseus; '),(13878,'for now I shall appoint for a contest those axes which he was wont to set up in line in his halls, like props of a ship that is building, twelve in all, '),(13879,'   and he would stand afar off and shoot an arrow through them.'),(13880,' \nNow then I shall set this contest before the wooers:'),(13881,' whosoever shall most easily string the bow in his hands, and shoot an arrow through all twelve axes, with him will I go and forsake this house  of my wedded life, a house most fair and filled with livelihood, '),(13882,' which, methinks, I shall ever remember even in my dreams.\"'),(13883,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: “Honored wife of Odysseus, son of Laertes, no longer now do thou put off this contest in thy halls;'),(13884,'  for, I tell thee, Odysseus of many wiles will be here, ere these men, handling this polished bow, shall have strung it, and shot an arrow through the iron.”'),(13885,'Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(13886,'“If thou couldest but wish, stranger, to sit here in my halls  and give me joy, sleep should never be shed over my eyelids. '),(13887,'But it is in no wise possible that men should forever be sleepless, '),(13888,' for the immortals have appointed a proper time for each thing upon the earth, the giver of grain.'),(13889,'But I verily will go to my upper chamber  and lay me on my bed, which has become for me a bed of wailings, ever bedewed with my tears, since the day when Odysseus went to see evil Ilios, that should never be named.'),(13890,' There will I lay me down, '),(13891,'but do thou lie down here in the hall, when thou hast strewn bedding on the floor; or let the maids set a bedstead for thee.” '),(13892,'  So saying, she went up to her bright upper chamber, not alone, for with her went her handmaids as well.'),(13893,' And when she had gone up to her upper chamber with her handmaids, she then bewailed Odysseus, her dear husband, until flashing-eyed Athena cast sweet sleep upon her eyelids.'),(13894,' But the goodly Odysseus lay down to sleep in the fore-hall of the house.'),(13895,' On the ground he spread an undressed ox-hide and above it many fleeces of sheep, which the Achaeans were wont to slay, '),(13896,' and Eurynome threw over him a cloak, when he had laid him down.'),(13897,'  There Odysseus, pondering in his heart evil for the wooers, lay sleepless.'),(13898,' And the women came forth from the hall, those that had before been wont to lie with the wooers, making laughter and merriment among themselves.'),(13899,' But the heart was stirred in his breast,'),(13900,' and much he debated in mind and heart, whether he should rush after them and deal death to each, or suffer them to lie with the insolent wooers for the last and latest time; and his heart growled within him. '),(13901,'And as a bitch stands over her tender whelps  growling, when she sees a man she does not know, and is eager to fight, so his heart growled within him in his wrath at their evil deeds;'),(13902,' but he smote his breast, and rebuked his heart, saying:'),(13903,'a worse thing even than this didst thou once endure '),(13904,'a worse thing even than this didst thou once endure '),(13905,'on that day when the Cyclops, unrestrained in daring, devoured my  mighty comrades; '),(13906,' but thou didst endure until craft got thee forth from the cave where thou thoughtest to die.\"'),(13907,'So he spoke, chiding the heart in his breast, '),(13908,'and his heart remained bound within him to endure steadfastly; '),(13909,'but he himself lay tossing this way and that.'),(13910,'  And as when a man before a great blazing fire turns swiftly this way and that a paunch full of fat and blood, and is very eager to have it roasted quickly, so Odysseus tossed from side to side, pondering how he might put forth his hands upon the shameless wooers,  one man as he was against so many.'),(13911,' Then Athena came down from heaven'),(13912,' and drew near to him in the likeness of a woman,'),(13913,'and she stood above his head, and spoke to him, and said:'),(13914,'\n“Why now again art thou wakeful, ill-fated above all men?'),(13915,' Lo, this is thy house, and here within is thy wife  and thy child, such a man, methinks, as anyone might pray to have for his son.”'),(13916,'And Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(13917,' “Yea, goddess, all this hast thou spoken aright.'),(13918,'But the heart in my breast is pondering somewhat upon this, how I may put forth my hands upon the shameless wooers,  all alone as I am, '),(13919,'while they remain always in a body in the house. '),(13920,'And furthermore this other and harder thing I ponder in my mind:'),(13921,' even if I were to slay them by the will of Zeus and of thyself, where then should I find escape from bane?'),(13922,' Of this I bid thee take thought.” '),(13923,' \nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(13924,'  “Obstinate one, many a man puts his trust even in a weaker friend than I am, one that is mortal, and knows not such wisdom as mine; '),(13925,' but I am a god, that guard thee to the end in all thy toils.'),(13926,' And I will tell thee openly; '),(13927,' if fifty troops of mortal men  should stand about us, eager to slay us in battle, even their cattle and goodly sheep shouldest thou drive off. '),(13928,' Nay, let sleep now come over thee.'),(13929,'There is weariness also in keeping wakeful watch the whole night through; and even now shalt thou come forth from out thy perils.\"'),(13930,'So she spoke, and shed sleep upon his eyelids,  but herself, the fair goddess, went back to Olympus.'),(13931,'Now while sleep seized him, loosening the cares of his heart, sleep that loosens the limbs of men, his true-hearted wife awoke, '),(13932,' and wept, as she sat upon her soft bed.'),(13933,' But when her heart had had its fill of weeping,  to Artemis first of all the fair lady made her prayer:'),(13934,'\n“Artemis, mighty goddess, daughter of Zeus, would that now thou wouldest fix thy arrow in my breast and take away my life even in this hour; or that a storm-wind might catch me up and bear me hence over the murky ways,  and cast me forth at the mouth of backward-flowing Oceanus,'),(13935,' even as on a time storm-winds bore away the daughters of Pandareus.'),(13936,' Their parents the gods had slain, and they were left orphans in the halls, and fair Aphrodite tended them with cheese, and sweet honey, and pleasant wine,'),(13937,' and Here gave them beauty and wisdom above all women, and chaste Artemis gave them stature, and Athena taught them skill in famous handiwork. '),(13938,'But while beautiful Aphrodite was going to high Olympus to ask for the maidens the accomplishment of gladsome marriage—  going to Zeus who hurls the thunderbolt, for well he knows all things, both the happiness and the haplessness of mortal men—meanwhile the spirits of the storm snatched away the maidens and gave them to the hateful Erinyes to deal with.'),(13939,' Would that even so those who have dwellings on Olympus would blot me from sight,  or that fair-tressed Artemis would smite me, so that with Odysseus before my mind I might even pass beneath the hateful earth, and never gladden in any wise the heart of a baser man. '),(13940,'Yet when a man weeps by day with a heart sore distressed,  but at night sleep holds him, this brings with it an evil that may well be borne—for sleep makes one forget all things, the good and the evil, when once it envelops the eyelids—but upon me a god sends evil dreams as well.'),(13941,' For this night again there lay by my side one like him, even such as he was when he went forth with the host,  '),(13942,'and my heart  was glad, for I deemed it was no dream, but the truth at last.”'),(13943,' \nSo she spoke, and straightway came golden-throned Dawn.'),(13944,' But as she wept goodly Odysseus heard her voice, '),(13945,'and thereupon he mused, and it seemed to his heart that she knew him and was standing by his head.'),(13946,'  Then he gathered up the cloak and the fleeces on which he was lying and laid them on a chair in the hall, and carried the ox-hide out of doors and set it down; and he lifted up his hands and prayed to Zeus:'),(13947,'\n“Father Zeus, if of your good will ye gods have brought me over land and sea to my own country, when ye had afflicted me sore,  let some one of those who are awaking utter a word of omen for me within, and without let a sign from Zeus be shown besides.\"'),(13948,'So he spoke in prayer,'),(13949,' and Zeus the counsellor heard him. Straightway he thundered from gleaming Olympus, from on high from out the clouds; '),(13950,'and goodly Odysseus was glad. '),(13951,'   And a woman, grinding at the mill, uttered a word of omen from within the house hard by, where the mills of the shepherd of the people were set. At these mills twelve women in all were wont to ply their tasks, making meal of barley and of wheat, the marrow of men. '),(13952,' Now the others were sleeping, for they had ground their wheat,  but she alone had not yet ceased, for she was the weakest of all. '),(13953,'She now stopped her mill and spoke a word, a sign for her master:'),(13954,' \n“Father Zeus, who art lord over gods and men, verily loud hast thou thundered from the starry sky, yet nowhere is there any cloud:'),(13955,'surely this is a sign that thou art showing to some man.'),(13956,' Fulfil now even for wretched me the word that I shall speak.'),(13957,' May the wooers this day for the last and latest time hold their glad feast in the halls of Odysseus. They that have loosened my limbs with bitter labour,'),(13958,' as I made them barley meal, '),(13959,'may they now sup their last.”'),(13960,'  So she spoke, and goodly Odysseus was glad at the word of omen and at the thunder of Zeus, '),(13961,'for he thought he had gotten vengeance on the guilty.'),(13962,'Now the other maidens in the fair palace of Odysseus had gathered together and were kindling on the hearth unwearied fire,'),(13963,' and Telemachus rose from his bed, a godlike man,  and put on his clothing. '),(13964,' He slung his sharp sword about his shoulder, '),(13965,'and beneath his shining feet he bound his fair sandals; and he took his mighty spear,  '),(13966,'tipped with sharp bronze,'),(13967,'and went and stood upon the threshold, and spoke to Eurycleia:'),(13968,'“Dear nurse, have ye honored the stranger in our house  with bed and food, or does he lie all uncared for? '),(13969,'For such is my mother\'s way, wise though she is:'),(13970,' in wondrous fashion she honours one of mortal men,'),(13971,' \n though he be the worse, while the better she sends unhonored away.” '),(13972,' \nThen wise Eurycleia answered him:'),(13973,'  “In this matter, child, thou shouldest not blame her, who is without blame.'),(13974,' He sat here and drank wine as long as he would, but for food he said he had no more hunger,'),(13975,' for she asked him. '),(13976,' But when he bethought him of rest and sleep, she bade the maidens strew his bed.\n But he, as one wholly wretched and hapless, would not sleep on a bed and under blankets, but on an undressed ox-hide and fleeces of sheep he slept in the fore-hall, '),(13977,'and we flung over him a cloak.\"'),(13978,'So she spoke, and Telemachus went forth through the hall  with his spear in his hand, and with him went two swift hounds.'),(13979,' And he went his way to the place of assembly to join the company of the well-greaved Achaeans,'),(13980,' but Eurycleia, the goodly lady, daughter of Ops, son of Peisenor, called to her maidens, saying:'),(13981,'“Come, let some of you busily sweep the hall  and sprinkle it, and throw on the shapely chairs coverlets of purple, '),(13982,'  and let others wipe all the tables with sponges and cleanse the mixing-bowls and the well-wrought double cups,'),(13983,'and others still go to the spring for water and bring it quickly here.'),(13984,'  For the wooers will not long be absent from the hall, but will return right early; for it is a feast-day for all men.\"'),(13985,'So she spoke, and they readily hearkened and obeyed.'),(13986,' Twenty of them went to the spring of dark water, and the others busied themselves there in the house in skilful fashion.'),(13987,'  Then in came the serving-men of the Acheans, '),(13988,'who thereafter split logs of wood well and skilfully; and the women came back from the spring.'),(13989,' After them came the swineherd, driving three boars which were the best in all his herd.'),(13990,' These he let be to feed in the fair courts,  but himself spoke to Odysseus with gentle words:'),(13991,'“Stranger, do the Achaeans look on thee with any more regard, or do they dishonor thee in the halls as before?\"'),(13992,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: '),(13993,'“Ah, Eumaeus, I would that the gods might take vengeance on the outrage  wherewith these men in wantonness devise wicked folly in another\'s house, and have no place for shame.\"'),(13994,'Thus they spoke to one another. And near to them came Melanthius the goatherd,'),(13995,' leading she-goats that were the best in all the herds,  to make a feast for the wooers,'),(13996,'and two herdsmen followed with him. '),(13997,'The goats he tethered beneath the echoing portico, and himself spoke to Odysseus with taunting words:'),(13998,'\n“Stranger, wilt thou even now still be a plague to us here in the hall, asking alms of men, and wilt thou not begone?'),(13999,'  \'Tis plain, methinks, that we two shall not part company till we taste one another\'s fists, for thy begging is in no wise decent.'),(14000,' Also it is not here alone that there are feasts of the Achaeans.” '),(14001,' \nSo he spoke, but Odysseus of many wiles made no answer, but he shook his head in silence, pondering evil in the deep of his heart.'),(14002,'\n  Besides these a third man came, Philoetius, a leader of men, driving for the wooers a barren heifer and fat she-goats.'),(14003,' These had been brought over from the mainland by ferrymen, who send other men, too, on their way, whosoever comes to them.'),(14004,' The beasts he tethered carefully beneath the echoing portico,  but himself came close to the swineherd and questioned him, saying: '),(14005,'“Who is this stranger, swineherd, who has newly come to our house? '),(14006,'From what men does he declare himself to be sprung? '),(14007,' Where are his kinsmen and his native fields? '),(14008,' Hapless man! Yet truly in form he is like a royal prince; '),(14009,' howbeit the gods bring to misery far-wandering men, whenever they spin for them the threads of trouble, even though they be kings.\"'),(14010,'Therewith he drew near to Odysseus, and stretching forth his right hand in greeting, spoke and addressed him with winged words:'),(14011,'\n“Hail, Sir stranger; '),(14012,' may happy fortune be thine in time to come, '),(14013,'though now thou art the thrall of many sorrows!'),(14014,' Father Zeus, no other god is more baneful than thou;'),(14015,' thou hast no pity on men when thou hast thyself given them birth, but bringest them into misery and wretched pains. '),(14016,'The sweat broke out on me when I marked the man, and my eyes are full of tears  as I think of Odysseus; for he, too, I ween, is clothed in such rags and is a wanderer among men, if indeed he still lives and beholds the light of the sun.'),(14017,' But if he is already dead and in the house of Hades, then woe is me for blameless Odysseus, who  set me over his cattle, when I was yet a boy, in the land of the Cephallenians. '),(14018,' And now these wax past counting; in no other wise could the breed of broad-browed cattle yield better increase for a mortal man.'),(14019,' But strangers bid me drive these now for themselves to eat, '),(14020,' and they care nothing for the son in the house,  nor do they tremble at the wrath of the gods, '),(14021,'for they are eager now to divide among themselves the possessions of our lord that has long been gone.'),(14022,' Now, as for myself, the heart in my breast keeps revolving this matter:'),(14023,' a very evil thing it is, while the son lives, to depart along with my cattle and go to a land of strangers,  even to an alien folk;'),(14024,' but this is worse still, to remain here and suffer woes in charge of cattle that are given over to others.'),(14025,' Aye, verily, long ago would I have fled and come to some other of the proud kings, for now things are no more to be borne; '),(14026,' but still I think of that hapless one, if perchance he might come back I know not whence,  and make a scattering of the wooers in his house.”'),(14027,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(14028,' “Neatherd, since thou seemest to be neither an evil man nor a witless, and I see for myself that thou hast gotten an understanding heart, therefore will I speak out and swear a great oath to confirm my words.'),(14029,'  Now be my witness Zeus above all gods, and this hospitable board, and the hearth of noble Odysseus to which I am come, that verily while thou art here Odysseus shall come home,'),(14030,'and thou shalt see with thine eyes, if thou wilt, the slaying of the wooers, who lord it here.\"'),(14031,'  Then the herdsman of the cattle answered him: '),(14032,'“Ah, stranger, I would that the son of Cronos might fulfil this word of thine!'),(14033,' Then shouldest thou know what manner of might is mine, and how my hands obey.\"'),(14034,'And even in like manner did Eumaeus pray to all the gods that wise Odysseus might come back to his own home.'),(14035,'\n  Thus they spoke to one another, but the wooers meanwhile were plotting death and fate for Telemachus; '),(14036,' howbeit there came to them a bird on their left, an eagle of lofty flight, clutching a timid dove.'),(14037,' Then Amphinomus spoke in their assembly, and said:'),(14038,' \n  “Friends, this plan of ours will not run to our liking, even the slaying of Telemachus; '),(14039,'nay, let us bethink us of the feast.\"'),(14040,'So spoke Amphinomus, and his word was pleasing to them. '),(14041,'Then, going into the house of godlike Odysseus, they laid their cloaks on the chairs and high seats,  and men fell to slaying great sheep and fat goats, aye, and fatted swine, and the heifer of the herd.'),(14042,' Then they roasted the entrails and served them out, and mixed wine in the bowls, '),(14043,'and the swineherd handed out the cups.'),(14044,' And Philoetius, a leader of men, handed them bread  in a beautiful basket, and Melanthius poured them wine. '),(14045,'So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(14046,'\nBut Telemachus, with crafty thought, made Odysseus sit within the well-built hall by the threshold of stone, and placed for him a mean stool and a little table.'),(14047,'  Beside him he set portions of the entrails and poured wine in a cup of gold, and said to him:'),(14048,'\n“Sit down here among the lords and drink thy wine,'),(14049,'and the revilings and blows of all the wooers will I myself ward from thee; for this is no public  resort, but the house of Odysseus, and it was for me that he won it.'),(14050,' And for your part, ye wooers, refrain your minds from rebukes and blows, that no strife or quarrel may arise.” '),(14051,' \nSo he spoke, and they all bit their lips and marvelled at Telemachus for that he spoke boldly; '),(14052,' and Antinous, son of Eupeithes, spoke among them, saying:'),(14053,'\n“Hard though it be, Achaeans, let us accept the word of Telemachus,'),(14054,'though boldly he threatens us in his speech.'),(14055,' For Zeus, son of Cronos, did not suffer it,'),(14056,' else would we ere now have silenced him in the halls, clear-voiced talker though he is.\"'),(14057,'but Telemachus paid no heed to his words.'),(14058,'but Telemachus paid no heed to his words.'),(14059,' Meanwhile the heralds were leading through the city the holy hecatomb of the gods,'),(14060,' and the long-haired Achaeans gathered together beneath a shady grove of Apollo, the archer-god.'),(14061,'\nBut when they had roasted the outer flesh and drawn it off the spits,  they divided the portions and feasted a glorious feast. '),(14062,'And by Odysseus those who served set a portion equal to that which they received themselves, '),(14063,'for so Telemachus commanded, the dear son of divine Odysseus.'),(14064,'\nBut the proud wooers Athena  would in no wise suffer to abstain from bitter outrage, that pain might sink yet deeper into the heart of Odysseus, son of Laertes.'),(14065,' There was among the wooers a man with his heart set on lawlessness—Ctesippus was his name, and in Same was his dwelling—'),(14066,'who, trusting forsooth in his boundless wealth,  wooed the wife of Odysseus, that had long been gone. '),(14067,'He it was who now spoke among the haughty wooers:'),(14068,'\n“Hear me, ye proud wooers, that I may say somewhat.'),(14069,' A portion has the stranger long had, an equal portion, as is meet; '),(14070,'for it is not well nor just to rob of their due  the guests of Telemachus, whosoever he be that comes to this house. '),(14071,' Nay, come, I too will give him a stranger\'s-gift, that he in turn may give a present either to the bath-woman or to some other of the slaves who are in the house of godlike Odysseus.” '),(14072,' \nSo saying, he hurled with strong hand the hoof of an ox, '),(14073,' taking it up from the basket where it lay. '),(14074,'But Odysseus avoided it with a quick turn of his head, and in his heart he smiled a right grim and bitter smile; '),(14075,' and the ox\'s hoof struck the well-built wall.'),(14076,' Then Telemachus rebuked Ctesippus, and said:'),(14077,'\n“Ctesippus, verily this thing fell out more to thy soul\'s profit.'),(14078,' for he himself avoided thy missile,'),(14079,' for he himself avoided thy missile,'),(14080,' else surely would I have struck thee through the middle with my sharp spear, and instead of a wedding feast thy father would have been busied with a funeral feast in this land.'),(14081,' Wherefore let no man, I warn you, make a show of forwardness in my house;'),(14082,' for now I mark and understand all things,  the good and the evil,'),(14083,' whereas heretofore I was but a child.'),(14084,' But none the less we still endure to see these deeds, while sheep are slaughtered, and wine drunk, and bread consumed,'),(14085,' for hard it is for one man to restrain many.'),(14086,' Yet come, no longer work me harm of your evil wills.'),(14087,'  But if you are minded even now to slay me myself with the sword, even that would I choose, and it would be better far to die than continually to behold these shameful deeds, strangers mishandled and men dragging the handmaidens in shameful fashion through the fair hall.\"'),(14088,'  So he spoke, and they were all hushed in silence,'),(14089,'but at last there spoke among them Agelaus, son of Damastor:'),(14090,'“Friends, no man in answer to what has been fairly spoken would wax wroth and make reply with wrangling words.'),(14091,' Abuse not any more the stranger nor any  of the slaves that are in the house of divine Odysseus. '),(14092,' But to Telemachus and his mother I would speak a gentle word, if perchance it may find favour in the minds of both.'),(14093,'So long as the hearts in your breasts had hope that wise Odysseus would return to his own house,  so long there was no ground for blame that you waited, and restrained the wooers in your halls; for this was the better course, had Odysseus returned and come back to his house.'),(14094,'  But now this is plain, that he will return no more.'),(14095,'Nay then, come, sit by thy mother and tell her this,  namely that she must wed him whosoever is the best man, and who offers the most gifts; to the end that thou mayest enjoy in peace all the heritage of thy fathers, eating and drinking, and that she may keep the house of another.”'),(14096,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(14097,'“Nay, by Zeus, Agelaus, and by the woes of my father,  who somewhere far from Ithaca has perished or is wandering, in no wise do I delay my mother\'s marriage, but I bid her wed what man she will, and I offer besides gifts past counting.'),(14098,' But I am ashamed to drive her forth from the hall against her will by a word of compulsion. '),(14099,'May God never bring such a thing to pass.” '),(14100,' \n  So spoke Telemachus, '),(14101,'but among the wooers Pallas Athena roused unquenchable laughter, and turned their wits awry.'),(14102,' And now they laughed with alien lips, and all bedabbled with blood was the flesh they ate,'),(14103,'and their eyes were filled with tears and their spirits set on wailing.'),(14104,' Then among them spoke godlike Theoclymenus:'),(14105,'\n“Ah, wretched men, what evil is this that you suffer?'),(14106,' Shrouded in night are your heads and your faces and your knees beneath you; '),(14107,' kindled is the sound of wailing, bathed in tears are your cheeks, and sprinkled with blood are the walls and the fair rafters.'),(14108,'  And full of ghosts is the porch and full the court, of ghosts that hasten down to Erebus beneath the darkness,'),(14109,'and the sun has perished out of heaven and an evil mist hovers over all.\"'),(14110,'So he spoke, but they all laughed merrily at him.'),(14111,' And among them Eurymachus, son of Polybus, was the first to speak:'),(14112,'  “Mad is the stranger that has newly come from abroad. '),(14113,'Quick, ye youths, convey him forth out of doors to go his way to the place of assembly, since here he finds it like night.\"'),(14114,'Then godlike Theoclymenus answered him:'),(14115,' “Eurymachus, in no wise do I bid thee give me guides for my way.'),(14116,'  I have eyes and ears and my two feet, and a mind in my breast that is in no wise meanly fashioned.'),(14117,' With these will I go forth out of doors, for I mark evil coming upon you which not one of the wooers may escape or avoid, of all you who in the house of godlike Odysseus  insult men and devise wicked folly.”'),(14118,'So saying, he went forth from the stately halls and came to Piraeus, who received him with a ready heart.'),(14119,' But all the wooers, looking at one another, sought to provoke Telemachus by laughing at his guests.'),(14120,'  And thus would one of the proud youths speak:'),(14121,'“Telemachus, no man is more unlucky in his guests than thou, '),(14122,'seeing that thou keepest such a filthy vagabond as this man here, always wanting bread and wine, and skilled neither in the works of peace nor those of war, but a mere burden of the earth.'),(14123,'  And this other fellow again stood up to prophesy. '),(14124,'Nay, if thou wouldst hearken to me it would be better far:'),(14125,' let us fling these strangers on board a benched ship, and send them to the Sicilians, whence they would bring thee in a fitting price.\"'),(14126,'So spake the wooers,'),(14127,'  but he paid no heed to their words.  Nay, in silence he watched his father, ever waiting until he should put forth his hands upon the shameless wooers.'),(14128,'\nBut the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, had set her beautiful chair over against them, and heard the words of each man in the hall.'),(14129,'  For they had made ready their meal in the midst of their laughing, a sweet meal, and one to satisfy the heart, for they had slain many beasts.'),(14130,' But never could meal have been more graceless than a supper such as a goddess and a mighty man were soon to set before them.'),(14131,' For unprovoked they were contriving deeds of shame.'),(14132,' But the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, put it into the heart of the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, to set before the wooers in the halls of Odysseus the bow and the gray iron, to be a contest and the beginning of death.'),(14133,'  She climbed the high stairway to her chamber, and took the bent key in her strong hand—a goodly key of bronze,'),(14134,' and on it was a handle of ivory.'),(14135,' And she went her way with her handmaidens to a store-room, far remote, '),(14136,'where lay the treasures of her lord,  bronze and gold and iron, wrought with toil. '),(14137,' And there lay the back-bent bow and the quiver that held the arrows, and many arrows were in it, fraught with groanings—gifts which a friend of Odysseus had given him when he met him once in Lacedaemon, even Iphitus, son of Eurytus, a man like unto the immortals.'),(14138,'  They two had met one another in Messene in the house of wise Ortilochus.'),(14139,' Odysseus verily had come to collect a debt which the whole people owed him, '),(14140,'for the men of Messene had lifted from Ithaca in their benched ships three hundred sheep and the shepherds with them.'),(14141,'  It was on an embassy in quest of these that Odysseus had come a far journey, while he was but a youth; '),(14142,' for his father and the other elders had sent him forth.'),(14143,' And Iphitus, on his part, had come in search of twelve brood mares, which he had lost, with sturdy mules at the teat; '),(14144,'but to him thereafter did they bring death and doom,  when he came to the stout-hearted son of Zeus, the man Heracles, who well knew deeds of daring; for Heracles slew him, his guest though he was, in his own house, ruthlessly, and had regard neither for the wrath of the gods nor for the table which he had set before him, '),(14145,'but slew the man thereafter,  and himself kept the stout-hoofed mares in his halls. '),(14146,'It was while asking for these that Iphitus met Odysseus, and gave him the bow, which of old great Eurytus had been wont to bear, and had left at his death to his son in his lofty house.'),(14147,' And to Iphitus Odysseus gave a sharp sword and a mighty spear,  as the beginning of loving friendship;'),(14148,'yet they never knew one another at the table, '),(14149,' for ere that might be the son of Zeus had slain Iphitus, son of Eurytus, a man like unto the immortals, who gave Odysseus the bow. '),(14150,'This bow goodly Odysseus, when going forth to war, would never  take with him on the black ships, but it lay in his halls at home as a memorial of a dear friend, and he carried it in his own land. '),(14151,' \nNow when the fair lady had come to the store-room, and had stepped upon the threshold of oak, which of old the carpenter had skilfully planed and made straight to the line—  thereon had he also fitted door-posts, and set on them bright doors—straightway she quickly loosed the thong from the handle and thrust in the key, and with sure aim shot back the bolts.'),(14152,' And as a bull bellows  when grazing in a meadow, '),(14153,'even so bellowed the fair doors, smitten by the key; and quickly they flew open before her.'),(14154,'  Then she stepped upon the high floor,'),(14155,' where the chests stood in which fragrant raiment was stored, '),(14156,'and stretched out her hand from thence and took from its peg the bow together with the bright case which surrounded it.'),(14157,'  And there she sat down and laid the case upon her knees and wept aloud, and took out the bow of her lord.'),(14158,' But when she had had her fill of tearful wailing, she went her way to the hall, to the company of the lordly wooers, bearing in her hands the back-bent bow and the quiver  that held the arrows,'),(14159,'and many arrows were in it, fraught with groanings. '),(14160,' And by her side her maidens bore a chest, wherein lay abundance of iron and bronze, the battle-gear of her lord.'),(14161,' Now when the fair lady reached the wooers, she stood by the door-post of the well-built hall,  holding before her face her shining veil; '),(14162,'and a faithful handmaid stood on either side of her.'),(14163,' Then straightway she spoke among the wooers, and said:'),(14164,'\n“Hear me, ye proud wooers, who have beset this house to eat and drink ever without end,  since its master has long been gone,'),(14165,'nor could you find any other plea to urge, save only as desiring to wed me and take me to wife.'),(14166,' Nay, come now, ye wooers, since this is shewn to be your prize.'),(14167,' I will set before you the great bow of divine Odysseus, '),(14168,' and whosoever shall most easily string the bow in his hands and shoot an arrow through all twelve axes, with him will I go, and forsake this house of my wedded life, a house most fair and filled with livelihood, which, methinks I shall ever remember even in my dreams.” '),(14169,' \n  So she spoke, and bade Eumaeus, the goodly swineherd, set for the wooers the bow and the grey iron.'),(14170,' And, bursting into tears, Eumaeus took them and laid them down,'),(14171,' and in another place the neatherd wept, when he saw the bow of his lord.'),(14172,' Then Antinous rebuked them, and spoke, and addressed them:'),(14173,'\n  “Foolish boors, who mind only the things of the day! Wretched pair, why now do you shed tears, and trouble the soul in the breast of the lady,'),(14174,'  whose heart even as it is lies low in pain, seeing that she has lost her dear husband?'),(14175,'Nay, sit and feast in silence,  or else go forth and weep, and leave the bow here behind as a decisive contest for the wooers; '),(14176,' for not easily, methinks, is this polished bow to be strung.'),(14177,' For there is no man among all these here such as Odysseus was, '),(14178,'  and I myself saw him.  For I remember him, though I was still but a child.”'),(14179,'So he spoke, but the heart in his breast hoped that he would string the bow and shoot an arrow through the iron.'),(14180,' Yet verily he was to be the first to taste of an arrow from the hands of noble Odysseus, whom then he,  as he sat in the halls, was dishonoring, and urging on all his comrades.'),(14181,'Then among them spoke the strong and mighty Telemachus: '),(14182,'“Lo now, of a truth Zeus, son of Cronos, has made me witless.'),(14183,'My dear mother, for all that she is wise, declares that she will follow another lord, forsaking this house; '),(14184,' yet I laugh, and am glad with a witless mind. '),(14185,'Come then, ye wooers, since this is shewn to be your prize, a lady, the like of whom is not now in the Achaean land, neither in sacred Pylos, nor in Argos, nor in Mycene,'),(14186,' \nWith this he flung the scarlet cloak from off his back, and sprang up erect; and he laid his sharp sword from off his shoulders.'),(14187,'  First then he set up the axes, when he had dug a trench, one long trench for all, and made it straight to the line, and about them he stamped in the earth.'),(14188,' And amazement seized all who saw him, that he set them out so orderly,'),(14189,' though before he had never seen them. '),(14190,' Then he went and stood upon the threshold, and began to try the bow. '),(14191,' Thrice he made it quiver in his eagerness to draw it, and thrice he relaxed his effort, though in his heart he hoped to string the bow and shoot an arrow through the iron.'),(14192,' And now at the last he would haply have strung it in his might, as for the fourth time he sought to draw up the string, but Odysseus nodded in dissent, and checked him in his eagerness.'),(14193,'  Then the strong and mighty Telemachus spoke among them again:'),(14194,'“Out on it, even in days to come shall I be a coward and a weakling, or else I am too young, and have not yet trust in my might to defend me against a man, when one waxes wroth without a cause.'),(14195,' But, come now, you that are mightier than I,  make trial of the bow, and let us end the contest.”'),(14196,'So saying, he set the bow from him on the ground, leaning it against the jointed, polished door, and hard by he leaned the swift arrow against the fair bow-tip, and then sat down again on the seat from which he had risen.'),(14197,'\n  Then Antinous, son of Eupeithes, spoke among them: '),(14198,'“Rise up in order, all you of our company, from left to right, beginning from the place where the cupbearer pours the wine.”'),(14199,' So spoke Antinous, and his word was pleasing to them.'),(14200,'Then first arose Leiodes, son of Oenops,  who was their soothsayer, and ever sat by the fair mixing-bowl in the innermost part of the hall; '),(14201,'deeds of wanton folly were hateful to him alone, and he was full of indignation at all the wooers.'),(14202,' He it was who now first took the bow and swift arrow,'),(14203,' and he went and stood upon the threshold, and began to try the bow;  but he could not string it.'),(14204,' Ere that might be his hands grew weary, as he sought to draw up the string, his unworn delicate hands;'),(14205,' and he spoke among the wooers:'),(14206,'\n“Friends, it is not I that shall string it; let another take it.'),(14207,'For many princes shall this bow rob of spirit and of life, since verily it is better far  to die than to live on and fail of that for the sake of which we ever gather here, waiting expectantly day after day.'),(14208,' Now many a man even hopes in his heart and desires to wed Penelope, the wife of Odysseus;'),(14209,'but when he shall have made trial of the bow, and seen the outcome, thereafter let him woo  some other of the fair-robed Achaean women with his gifts, and seek to win her; '),(14210,'then should Penelope wed him who offers most, and who comes as her fated lord.” '),(14211,' \nSo he spoke, and set the bow from him, leaning it against the jointed, polished door,  and hard by he leaned the swift arrow against the fair bow-tip, and then sat down on the seat from which he had risen.'),(14212,' But Antinous rebuked him, and spoke, and addressed him: '),(14213,'“Leiodes, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth, a dread word and grievous! I am angered to hear it,  if forsooth this bow is to rob princes of spirit and of life, because thou art not able to string it.'),(14214,' For, I tell thee, thy honored mother did not bear thee of such strength as to draw a bow and shoot arrows;'),(14215,'but others of the lordly wooers will soon string it.\"'),(14216,'  So he spoke, and called to Melanthius, the goatherd: '),(14217,' “Come now, light a fire in the hall, Melanthius; and set by it a great seat with a fleece upon it, and bring forth a great cake of the fat that is within, that we youths may warm the bow, and anoint it with fat,  and so make trial of it, and end the contest.”'),(14218,'So he spoke, and Melanthius straightway rekindled the unwearied fire, and brought and placed by it a great seat with a fleece upon it, and he brought forth a great cake of the fat that was within.'),(14219,' Therewith the youths warmed the bow, and made trial of it, '),(14220,'but they could not  string it, for they were far lacking in strength.'),(14221,'Now Antinous was still persisting and godlike Eurymachus, leaders of the wooers, '),(14222,'who were far the best in valiance; '),(14223,' but those other two had gone forth both together from the hall, the neatherd and the swineherd of divine Odysseus; '),(14224,' and after them Odysseus himself went forth from the house. '),(14225,'But when they were now outside the gates and the court, he spoke and addressed them with gentle words:'),(14226,' \n“Neatherd, and thou too swineherd, shall I tell you something or keep it to myself?'),(14227,' Nay, my spirit bids me tell it.'),(14228,'  What manner of men would you be to defend Odysseus, if he should come from somewhere thus suddenly, and some god should bring him?'),(14229,' Would you bear aid to the wooers or to Odysseus?'),(14230,' Speak out as your heart and spirit bid you.\"'),(14231,'Then the herdsmen of the cattle answered him:'),(14232,'  “Father Zeus, oh that thou wouldest fulfil this wish! Grant that that man may come back, and that some god may guide him.'),(14233,' Then shouldest thou know what manner of might is mine, and how my hands obey.\"'),(14234,'And even in like manner did Eumaeus pray to all the gods that wise Odysseus; might come back to his own home. '),(14235,' \n  But when he knew with certainty the mind of these, he made answer, and spoke to them again, saying:'),(14236,'\n“At home now in truth am I here before you, my very self. After many grievous toils I am come in the twentieth year to my native land.'),(14237,' And I know that by you two  alone of all my thralls is my coming desired,'),(14238,'but of the rest have I heard not one praying that I might come back again to my home.'),(14239,' But to you two will I tell the truth, even as it shall be.'),(14240,' If a god shall subdue the lordly wooers unto me, I will bring you each a wife, and will give you possessions  and a house built near my own, '),(14241,'and thereafter you two shall be in my eyes friends and brothers of Telemachus.'),(14242,' Nay, come, more than this, I will shew you also a manifest sign, that you may know me well and be assured in heart, even the scar of the wound which long ago a boar dealt me with his white tusk,  when I went to Parnassus with the sons of Autolycus.\"'),(14243,'So saying, he drew aside the rags from the great scar.'),(14244,' And when the two had seen it, and had marked each thing well, they flung their arms about wise Odysseus, and wept; and they kissed his head and shoulders in loving welcome. And even in like manner Odysseus kissed their heads and hands.'),(14245,' And now the light of the sun would have gone down upon their weeping, had not Odysseus himself checked them, and said:'),(14246,'\n“Cease now from weeping and wailing, lest some one come forth from the hall and see us, and make it known within as well.'),(14247,'  But go within one after another, not all together, I first and you thereafter, '),(14248,'and let this be made a sign.'),(14249,' All the rest, as many as are lordly wooers, will not suffer the bow and the quiver to be given to me; '),(14250,'but do thou, goodly Eumaeus, as thou bearest the bow through the halls,  place it in my hands, and bid the women bar the close-fitting doors of their hall. And if any one of them hears groanings or the din of men within our walls, let them not rush out, but remain where they are in silence at their work.'),(14251,'  But to thee, goodly Philoetius, do I give charge to fasten with a bar the gate of the court, and swiftly to cast a cord upon it.\"'),(14252,'So saying, he entered the stately house,'),(14253,' and went and sat down on the seat from which he had risen. '),(14254,' And the two slaves of divine Odysseus went in as well.'),(14255,'\n  Eurymachus was now handling the bow, warming it on this side and on that in the light of the fire; '),(14256,' but not even so was he able to string it; and in his noble heart he groaned,'),(14257,' and with a burst of anger he spoke and addressed them:'),(14258,'“Out on it! Verily I am grieved for myself and for you all.'),(14259,'  It is in no wise for the marriage that I mourn so greatly, grieved though I am; '),(14260,'for there are many other Achaean women, some in sea-girt Ithaca itself, and some in other cities; '),(14261,' but I mourn if in truth we fall so far short of godlike Odysseus in might, seeing that we cannot string  his bow. '),(14262,'This is a reproach for men that are yet to be to hear of.”'),(14263,' \nThen Antinous, son of Eupeithes, answered him:'),(14264,'and thou of thyself too knowest it.'),(14265,'and thou of thyself too knowest it.'),(14266,' For to-day throughout the land is the feast of the god—a holy feast.'),(14267,' Who then would bend a bow?'),(14268,' Nay, quietly  set it by; '),(14269,'and as for the axes—what if we should let them all stand as they are?'),(14270,' No man, methinks, will come to the hall of Odysseus, son of Laertes, and carry them off.'),(14271,' Nay, come, let the bearer pour drops for libation into the cups, that we may pour libations, and lay aside the curved bow.'),(14272,'  And in the morning bid Melanthius, the goatherd, to bring she-goats, far the best in all the herds, that we may lay thigh-pieces on the altar of Apollo, the famed archer; and so make trial of the bow, and end the contest.\"'),(14273,'So spoke Antinous, and his word was pleasing to them.'),(14274,'  Then the heralds poured water over their hands, and youths filled the bowls brim full of drink, and served out to all, pouring first drops for libation into the cups.'),(14275,' But when they had poured libations, and had drunk to their heart\'s content, then with crafty mind Odysseus of many wiles spoke among them:'),(14276,'  “Hear me, wooers of the glorious queen,'),(14277,' that I may say what the heart in my breast bids me.'),(14278,' To Eurymachus most of all do I make my prayer, and to godlike Antinous, since this word also of his was spoken aright, namely that for the present you cease to try the bow, and leave the issue with the gods;'),(14279,' and in the morning the god will give the victory to whomsoever he will. '),(14280,' But come, give me the polished bow, that in your midst I may prove my hands and strength, whether I have yet might such as was of old in my supple limbs, or whether by now my wanderings and lack of food have destroyed it.”'),(14281,'  So he spoke, and they all waxed exceeding wroth, fearing lest he might string the polished bow.'),(14282,' And Antinous rebuked him, and spoke and addressed him:'),(14283,'\n“Ah, wretched stranger, thou hast no wit, no, not a trace. '),(14284,'Art thou not content  that thou feastest undisturbed in our proud company, and lackest naught of the banquet, but hearest our words and our speech, '),(14285,'while no other that is a stranger and beggar hears our words?'),(14286,' It is wine that wounds thee, honey-sweet wine, which works harm to others too, if one takes it in great gulps, and drinks beyond measure.'),(14287,'  It was wine that made foolish even the centaur, glorious Eurytion, in the hall of greathearted Peirithous, when he went to the Lapithae:'),(14288,' and when his heart had been made foolish with wine, in his madness he wrought evil in the house of Peirithous. '),(14289,' Then grief seized the heroes,  and they leapt up and dragged him forth through the gateway, when they had shorn off his ears and his nostrils with the pitiless bronze, '),(14290,' and he, made foolish in heart, went his way, bearing with him the curse of his sin in the folly of his heart.'),(14291,' From hence the feud arose between the centaurs and mankind; but it was for himself first that he found evil, being heavy with wine.'),(14292,'  Even so do I declare great harm for thee, if thou shalt string the bow,'),(14293,' for thou shalt meet with no kindness at the hands of anyone in our land, but we will send thee straightway in a black ship to king Echetus, the maimer of all men, '),(14294,'from whose hands thou shalt in no wise escape alive.'),(14295,' Nay, then, be still,  and drink thy wine, and do not strive with men younger than thou.”'),(14296,' \nThen wise Penelope answered him:'),(14297,' “Antinous, it is not well nor just to rob of their due the guests of Telemachus, whosoever he be that comes to this house. '),(14298,'Dost thou think that, if yon stranger  strings the great bow of Odysseus, trusting in his strength and his might, he will lead me to his home, and make me his wife?'),(14299,' Nay, he himself, I ween, has not this hope in his breast; '),(14300,'so let no one of you on this account sit at meat here in sorrow of heart; nay, that were indeed unseemly.\"'),(14301,'  Then Eurymachus, son of Polybus, answered her: '),(14302,'“Daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, it is not that we think the man will lead thee to his home—'),(14303,'that were indeed unseemly—'),(14304,'but that we dread the talk of men and women, lest hereafter some base fellow among the Achaeans should say:  ‘Truly men weaker far are wooing the wife of a noble man, and cannot string his polished bow.'),(14305,' But another, a beggar, that came on his wanderings, easily strung the bow, and shot through the iron.'),(14306,'’ Thus will men speak, but to us this would become a reproach.\"'),(14307,'  Then wise Penelope answered him again:'),(14308,'“Eurymachus, in no wise can there be good report in the land for men who dishonor and consume the house of a prince.'),(14309,'  Why then do you make this matter a reproach?'),(14310,'This stranger is right tall and well-built,  and declares himself to be born the son of a good father.'),(14311,'Nay, come, give him the polished bow and let us see.'),(14312,' For thus will I speak out to thee, and this word shall verily be brought to pass; '),(14313,' if he shall string the bow, and Apollo grant him glory, I will clothe him with a cloak and tunic, fair raiment,  and will give him a sharp javelin to ward off dogs and men, and a two-edged sword; '),(14314,' and I will give him sandals to bind beneath his feet, and will send him whithersoever his heart and spirit bid him go.\"'),(14315,'Then wise Telemachus answered her: '),(14316,'“My mother, as for the bow, no man of the Achaeans  has a better right than I to give or to deny it to whomsoever I will—no, not all those who lord it in rocky Ithaca, or in the islands towards horse-pasturing Elis.'),(14317,' No man among these shall thwart me against my will, even though I should wish to give this bow outright to the stranger to bear away with him.'),(14318,'  But do thou go thy chamber, and busy thyself with thine own tasks, the loom and the distaff, and bid thy handmaids ply their tasks.'),(14319,' The bow shall be for men, for all, but most of all for me; '),(14320,'since mine is the authority in the house.” '),(14321,' \nShe then, seized with wonder, went back to her chamber, '),(14322,' for she laid to heart the wise saying of her son.'),(14323,'Up to her upper chamber she went with her handmaids, and then bewailed Odysseus, her dear husband, until flashing-eyed Athena cast sweet sleep upon her eyelids.'),(14324,'\nNow the goodly swineherd had taken the curved bow and was bearing it, '),(14325,' but the wooers all cried out in the halls. '),(14326,' And thus would one of the proud youths speak:'),(14327,'\n“Whither, pray, art thou bearing the curved bow, miserable swineherd, thou man distraught?'),(14328,' Soon by thy swine, alone and apart from men, shall the swift hounds devour thee—hounds thyself didst rear—if but Apollo  be gracious to us, and the other immortal gods.\"'),(14329,'So they spoke, and he set down the bow, as he bore it, in that very place, seized with fear because many men were crying out aloud in the halls.'),(14330,' But Telemachus on the other side called out threateningly:'),(14331,'“Father, bear the bow onward'),(14332,'—soon shalt thou rue giving heed to all—  lest, younger though I am, I drive thee to the field, and pelt thee with stones; '),(14333,'for in strength I am the better.'),(14334,'I would that I were even so much better in strength and might than all the wooers that are in the house;'),(14335,'  then would I soon send many a one  forth from our house to go his way in evil case; for they devise wickedness.\"'),(14336,'So he spoke, but all the wooers laughed merrily at him, and relaxed the bitterness of their anger against Telemachus.'),(14337,' Howbeit the swineherd bore the bow through the hall, and came up to wise Odysseus, and put it in his hands.'),(14338,'  Then he called forth the nurse Eurycleia, and said to her:'),(14339,'\n“Telemachus bids thee, wise Eurycleia, to bar the close-fitting doors of the hall,'),(14340,' and if any of the women hear within groanings or the din of men within our walls, let them not  rush out, but remain where they are in silence at their work.”'),(14341,'So he spoke, but her word remained unwinged; and she barred the doors of the stately halls.'),(14342,' \nBut in silence Philoetius hastened forth from the house, and barred the gates of the well-fenced court.'),(14343,'  Now there lay beneath the portico the cable of a curved ship, made of byblus plant, wherewith he made fast the gates, and then himself went within.'),(14344,' Thereafter he came and sat down on the seat from which he had risen, and gazed upon Odysseus; '),(14345,'now he was already handling the bow, turning it round and round, and trying it this way and that,  lest worms might have eaten the horns, while its lord was afar.'),(14346,' And thus would one speak with a glance at his neighbor:'),(14347,'“Verily he has a shrewd eye, and is a cunning knave with a bow.'),(14348,' It may be haply that he has himself such bows stored away at home, or else he is minded to make one, that he thus  turns it this way and that in his hands, the rascally vagabond.”'),(14349,' \nAnd again another of the proud youths would say:'),(14350,' “Would that the fellow might find profit in just such measure as he shall prove able ever to string this bow.\"'),(14351,'So spoke the wooers, '),(14352,'but Odysseus of many wiles,  as soon as he had lifted the great bow and scanned it on every side—even as when a man well-skilled in the lyre and in song easily stretches the string about a new peg, making fast at either end the twisted sheep-gut—so without effort did Odysseus string the great bow.'),(14353,'  And he held it in his right hand, and tried the string, '),(14354,'which sang sweetly beneath his touch, like to a swallow in tone.'),(14355,' But upon the wooers came great grief, and the faces of them changed color, '),(14356,' and Zeus thundered loud, shewing forth his signs.'),(14357,'Then glad at heart was the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus '),(14358,' that the son of crooked-counselling Cronos sent him an omen, '),(14359,' and he took up a swift arrow, which lay by him on the table, bare, '),(14360,' but the others were stored within the hollow quiver, even those of which the Achaeans were soon to taste.'),(14361,'This he took, and laid upon the bridge of the bow, and drew the bow-string and the notched arrow  even from the chair where he sat, and let fly the shaft with sure aim, and did not miss the end of the handle of one of the axes, but clean through and out at the end passed the arrow weighted with bronze. '),(14362,'But he spoke to Telemachus, saying:'),(14363,'“Telemachus, the stranger  that sits in thy halls brings no shame upon thee, nor in any wise did I miss the mark, or labour long in stringing the bow; '),(14364,'still is my strength unbroken—not as the wooers scornfully taunt me.'),(14365,' But now it is time that supper too be made ready for the Achaeans, while yet there is light, and thereafter must yet other sport be made  with song and with the lyre; '),(14366,'for these things are the accompaniments of a feast.\"'),(14367,'He spoke, and made a sign with his brows,'),(14368,' and Telemachus, the dear son of divine Odysseus, girt about him his sharp sword, and took his spear in his grasp, and stood by the chair at his father\'s side, armed with gleaming bronze.'),(14369,' But Odysseus of many wiles stripped off his rags and sprang to the great threshold with the bow and the quiver full of arrows, and poured forth the swift arrows right there before his feet, and spoke among the wooers:'),(14370,'  “Lo, now at last is this decisive contest ended;'),(14371,' and now as for another mark, which till now no man has ever smitten, I will know if haply I may strike it, and Apollo grant me glory.\"'),(14372,'He spoke, and aimed a bitter arrow at Antinous.'),(14373,'Now he was on the point of raising to his lips a fair goblet,  a two-eared cup of gold, and was even now handling it, that he might drink of the wine, '),(14374,'and death was not in his thoughts.'),(14375,' For who among men that sat at meat could think that one man among many, how strong soever he were, would bring upon himself evil death and black fate?'),(14376,'  But Odysseus took aim, and smote him with an arrow in the throat, and clean out through the tender neck passed the point;'),(14377,'he sank to one side, and the cup fell from his hand as he was smitten, and straightway up through his nostrils there came a thick jet of the blood of man; '),(14378,'and quickly  he thrust the table from him with a kick of his foot, and spilled all the food on the floor, '),(14379,' and the bread and roast flesh were befouled.'),(14380,' Then into uproar broke the wooers through the halls, as they saw the man fallen, and from their high seats they sprang, driven in fear through the hall, gazing everywhere along the well-built walls; '),(14381,' but nowhere was there a shield or mighty spear to seize. '),(14382,' But they railed at Odysseus with angry words:'),(14383,'\n“Stranger, to thy cost dost thou shoot at men; '),(14384,'never again shalt thou take part in other contests; '),(14385,'now is thy utter destruction sure.'),(14386,' Aye, for thou hast now slain a man who was far the best  of the youths in Ithaca; '),(14387,' therefore shall vultures devour thee here.”'),(14388,'So spoke each man, for verily they thought that he had not slain the man willfully; '),(14389,' and in their folly they knew not this, that over themselves one and all the cords of destruction had been made fast.'),(14390,' Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered them:'),(14391,'\n  “Ye dogs, ye thought that I should never more come home from the land of the Trojans, seeing that ye wasted my house, and lay with the maidservants by force, and while yet I lived covertly wooed my wife, having no fear of the gods, who hold broad heaven,  nor of the indignation of men, that is to be hereafter. '),(14392,' Now over you one and all have the cords of destruction been made fast.” '),(14393,' \nSo he spoke, and thereat pale fear seized them all, '),(14394,' \nand each man gazed about to see how he might escape utter destruction;'),(14395,'Eurymachus alone answered him, and said:'),(14396,'\n  “If thou art indeed Odysseus of Ithaca, come home again, this that thou sayest is just regarding all that the Achaeans have wrought—many deeds of wanton folly in thy halls and many in the field.'),(14397,' But he now lies dead, who was to blame for all, even Antinous; '),(14398,' for it was he who set on foot these deeds,  not so much through desire or need of the marriage, but with another purpose, which the son of Cronos did not bring to pass for him, that in the land of settled Ithaca he might himself be king, and might lie in wait for thy son and slay him.'),(14399,' But now he lies slain, as was his due, but do thou spare the people  that are thine own; '),(14400,'  and we will hereafter go about the land and get thee recompense for all that has been drunk and eaten in thy halls, and will bring each man for himself in requital the worth of twenty oxen, and pay thee back in bronze and gold until thy heart be warmed; '),(14401,' but till then no one could blame thee that thou art wroth.\"'),(14402,'  Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered him: '),(14403,'“Eurymachus, not even if you should give me in requital all that your fathers left you, even all that you now have, and should add other wealth thereto from whence ye might, not even so would I henceforth stay my hands from slaying until the wooers had paid the full price of all their transgression.'),(14404,'  Now it lies before you to fight in open fight, or to flee, if any man may avoid death and the fates; '),(14405,'but many a one, methinks, shall not escape from utter destruction.”'),(14406,'So he spoke, and their knees were loosened where they stood, and their hearts melted; '),(14407,'and Eurymachus spoke among them again a second time:'),(14408,'\n  “Friends, for you see that this man will not stay his invincible hands, but now that he was got the polished bow and the quiver, will shoot from the smooth threshold until he slays us all, '),(14409,'come, let us take thought of battle.'),(14410,'Draw your swords, and hold the tables before you against  the arrows that bring swift death,'),(14411,' and let us all have at him in a body, in the hope that we may thrust him from the threshold and the doorway, and go throughout the city, and so the alarm be swiftly raised; '),(14412,'then should this fellow soon have shot his last.” '),(14413,' \nSo saying, he drew his sharp sword  of bronze, two-edged, and sprang upon Odysseus with a terrible cry,'),(14414,'but at the same instant goodly Odysseus let fly an arrow, and struck him upon the breast beside the nipple, and fixed the swift shaft in his liver. '),(14415,' And Eurymachus let the sword fall from his hand to the ground, and writhing over the table  he bowed and fell, and spilt upon the floor the food and the two-handled cup.'),(14416,' With his brow he beat the earth in agony of soul, and with both his feet he spurned and shook the chair, '),(14417,'and a mist was shed over his eyes.'),(14418,'Then Amphinomus made at glorious Odysseus,  rushing straight upon him, and had drawn his sharp sword, in hope that Odysseus might give way before him from the door.'),(14419,' But Telemachus was too quick for him, and cast, and smote him from behind with his bronze-tipped spear between the shoulders, and drove it through his breast; '),(14420,' and he fell with a thud, and struck the ground full with his forehead.'),(14421,'  But Telemachus sprang back, leaving the long spear where it was, fixed in Amphinomus, '),(14422,'for he greatly feared lest, as he sought to draw forth the long spear, one of the Achaeans might rush upon him and stab with his sword, or deal him a blow as he stooped over the corpse.'),(14423,' So he started to run, and came quickly to his dear father,  and standing by his side spoke to him winged words: '),(14424,'“Father, now will I bring thee a shield and two spears and a helmet all of bronze, well fitted to the temples, and when I come back I will arm myself, and will give armour likewise to the swineherd and yon neatherd; '),(14425,'for it is better to be clothed in armour.\"'),(14426,'  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said: '),(14427,'“Run, and bring them, while yet I have arrows to defend me, lest they thrust me from the door, alone as I am.\"'),(14428,'So he spoke, and Telemachus hearkened to his dear father, and went his way to the store-chamber where the glorious arms were stored.'),(14429,'  Thence he took four shields and eight spears and four helmets of bronze, with thick plumes of horse-hair; '),(14430,' and he bore them forth, and quickly came to his dear father. Then first of all he himself girded the bronze about his body,'),(14431,'  and even in like manner the two slaves put on them the beautiful armour,  and took their stand on either side of Odysseus, the wise and crafty-minded.'),(14432,' But he, so long as he had arrows to defend him, '),(14433,'would ever aim, and smite the wooers one by one in his house, '),(14434,'and they fell thick and fast.'),(14435,'But when the arrows failed the prince, as he shot,  he leaned the bow against the door-post of the well-built hall, and let it stand against the bright entrance wall. For himself, he put about his shoulders a four-fold shield, and set on his mighty head a well-wrought helmet with horse-hair plume, and terribly did the plume wave above him; '),(14436,'  and he took two mighty spears, tipped with bronze.'),(14437,' \nNow there was in the well-built wall a certain postern door, and along the topmost level of the threshold of the well-built hall was a way into a passage, and well-fitting folding doors closed it.'),(14438,' This postern Odysseus bade the goodly swineherd watch,  taking his stand close by, '),(14439,'for there was but a single way to reach it.'),(14440,'Then Agelaus spoke among the wooers, and declared his word to all:'),(14441,'\n“Friends, will not one mount up by the postern door, and tell the people, that so an alarm may be raised straightway?'),(14442,' Then should this fellow soon have shot his last.”'),(14443,'\n  Then Melanthius, the goatherd, answered him:'),(14444,' “It may not be, Agelaus, fostered of Zeus,'),(14445,' for terribly near is the fair door of the court, and the mouth of the passage is hard.'),(14446,' One man could bar the way for all, so he were valiant.'),(14447,' But come, let me bring you  from the store-room arms to don, '),(14448,'for it is within, methinks, and nowhere else that Odysseus and his glorious son have laid the arms.\"'),(14449,'So saying, Melanthius, the goatherd, mounted up by the steps of the hall to the store-rooms of Odysseus.'),(14450,' Thence he took twelve shields, as many spears,  and as many helmets of bronze with thick plumes of horsehair, '),(14451,'and went his way, and quickly brought and gave them to the wooers.'),(14452,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 22.147-22.149'),(14453,' Then the knees of Odysseus were loosened and his heart melted, when he saw them donning armour and brandishing long spears in their hands, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 147 to line 149'),(14454,'  but quickly he spoke to Telemachus winged words:'),(14455,'“Telemachus, verily some one of the women in the halls is rousing against us an evil battle, or haply it is Melanthius.\"'),(14456,'Then wise Telemachus answered him: '),(14457,'“Father, it is I myself that am at fault in this, and no other  is to blame, for I left the close-fitting door of the store-room open:'),(14458,' their watcher was better than I.'),(14459,' But go now, goodly Eumaeus, close the door of the store-room, and see whether it is one of the women who does this, or Melanthius, son of Dolius, as I suspect.”'),(14460,'  Thus they spoke to one another. But Melanthius, the goatherd, went again to the store-room to bring beautiful armour; '),(14461,'howbeit the goodly swineherd marked him, and straightway said to Odysseus who was near:'),(14462,'“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices,  yonder again is the pestilent fellow, whom we ourselves suspect, going to the store-room.'),(14463,' But do thou tell me truly, shall I slay him, if I prove the better man, or shall I bring him hither to thee, that the fellow may pay for the many crimes that he has planned in thy house?” '),(14464,' \n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said: '),(14465,'  “Verily I and Telemachus will keep the lordly wooers within the hall, how fierce soever they be, '),(14466,' but do you two bend behind him his feet and his arms above, and cast him into the store-room, and tie boards behind his back;  then make fast to his body a twisted rope, and hoist him up the tall pillar, till you bring him near the roof-beams, that he may keep alive long, and suffer grievous torment.\"'),(14467,'So he spoke, and they readily hearkened and obeyed. Forth they went to the store-room, unseen of him who was within.'),(14468,'  He truly was seeking for armour in the innermost part of the store-room, and the two lay in wait, standing on either side of the door-posts.'),(14469,' And when Melanthius, the goatherd, was about to pass over the threshold, bearing in one hand a goodly helm, and in the other a broad old shield, flecked with rust—  the shield of lord Laertes, which he was wont to bear in his youth, '),(14470,' but now it was laid by, and the seams of its straps were loosened'),(14471,' —then the two sprang upon him and seized him. They dragged him in by the hair, and flung him down on the ground in sore terror, and bound his feet and hands with galling bonds,  binding them firmly behind his back, as the son of Laertes bade them, the much enduring, goodly Odysseus; '),(14472,'and they made fast to his body a twisted rope, and hoisted him up the tall pillar, till they brought him near the roof-beams.'),(14473,' Then didst thou mock him, swineherd Eumaeus, and say:'),(14474,'\n  “Now verily, Melanthius, shalt thou watch the whole night through, lying on a soft bed, as befits thee,'),(14475,'nor shalt thou fail to mark the early Dawn, golden-throned, as she comes forth from the streams of Oceanus, at the hour when thou art wont to drive thy she-goats for the wooers, to prepare a feast in the halls.\"'),(14476,'  So he was left there, stretched in the direful bond,'),(14477,'but the two put on their armour, and closed the bright door, and went to Odysseus, the wise and crafty-minded.'),(14478,' There they stood, breathing fury, those on the threshold but four, while those within the hall were many and brave.'),(14479,'  Then Athena, daughter of Zeus, drew near them, like unto Mentor in form and voice, '),(14480,'and Odysseus saw her, and was glad; and he spoke, saying:'),(14481,'\n“Mentor, ward off ruin, and remember me, thy dear comrade, who often befriended thee.'),(14482,' Thou art of like age with myself.” '),(14483,' \n  So he spoke, deeming that it was Athena, the rouser of hosts.'),(14484,'  But the wooers on the other side shouted aloud in the hall,'),(14485,' and first Agelaus, son of Damastor, rebuked Athena, saying:'),(14486,'\n“Mentor, let not Odysseus beguile thee with his words to fight against the wooers and bear aid to himself.'),(14487,'  For in this wise, methinks, shall our will be brought to pass: '),(14488,'when we have killed these men, father and son, thereafter shalt thou too be slain with them, such deeds art thou minded to do in these halls:'),(14489,' with thine own head shalt thou pay the price.'),(14490,' But when with the sword we have stripped you of your might,  all the possessions that thou hast within doors and in the fields we will mingle with those of Odysseus, '),(14491,'  and will not suffer thy sons or thy daughters to dwell in thy halls, nor thy faithful wife to fare at large in the city of Ithaca.\"'),(14492,'So he spoke, and Athena waxed the more wroth at heart,  and she rebuked Odysseus with angry words:'),(14493,'\"Odysseus, no longer hast thou steadfast might nor any valor, such as was thine when for high-born Helen of the white arms thou didst for nine years battle with the Trojans unceasingly, and many men thou slewest in dread conflict,  and by thy counsel was the broad-wayed city of Priam taken.'),(14494,'How is it that now, when thou hast come to thy house and thine own possessions, thou shrinkest with wailing from playing the man, and that against the wooers?'),(14495,' Nay, friend, come hither and take thy stand by my side, and see my deeds, that thou mayest know what manner of man  Mentor, son of Alcimus, is to repay kindness in the midst of the foe.\"'),(14496,'She spoke, but did not give him strength utterly to turn the course of the battle, but still made trial of the might and valor of Odysseus and his glorious son;'),(14497,' and for herself,  she flew up to the roof-beam of the smoky hall, and sat there in the guise of a swallow to look upon.'),(14498,'Now the wooers were urged on by Agelaus, son of Damastor, by Eurynomus, and Amphimedon and Demoptolemus and Peisander, son of Polyctor, and wise Polybus,'),(14499,' for these were in valiance far the best of all the wooers  who still lived and fought for their lives; '),(14500,'but the rest the bow and the swiftly-falling arrows had by now laid low.'),(14501,' But Agelaus spoke among them, and declared his word to all:'),(14502,'\n“Friends, now at length will this man stay his invincible hands.'),(14503,' Lo, Mentor has gone from him, and has but uttered empty boasts,  and they are left alone there at the outer doors.'),(14504,'Therefore hurl not now upon them your long spears all at once, but come, do you six throw first in the hope that Zeus may grant that Odysseus be struck, and that we win glory.'),(14505,' Of the rest there is no care, once he shall have fallen.” '),(14506,' \n  So he spoke, and they all hurled their spears, as he bade, eagerly; '),(14507,' but Athena made all vain. One man smote the door-post of the well-built hall, another the close-fitting door,'),(14508,' another\'s ashen spear, heavy with bronze, struck upon the wall.'),(14509,'  But when they had avoided the spears of the wooers, first among them spoke the much-enduring goodly Odysseus:'),(14510,'\n“Friends, now I give the word that we too cast our spears into the throng of the wooers, who are minded to slay us in addition to their former wrongs.”'),(14511,'\n  So he spoke, and they all hurled their sharp spears with sure aim.'),(14512,' Odysseus smote Demoptolemus, Telemachus Euryades, the swineherd Elatus, and the herdsmen of the cattle slew Peisander.'),(14513,' So these all at the same moment bit the vast floor with their teeth,  and the wooers drew back to the innermost part of the hall.'),(14514,' But the others sprang forward and drew forth their spears from the dead bodies.'),(14515,'\nThen again the wooers hurled their sharp spears eagerly, '),(14516,'but Athena made them vain, many as they were. '),(14517,' One man  smote the door-post of the well-built hall, another the close-fitting door, '),(14518,' another\'s ashen spear, heavy with bronze, struck upon the wall.'),(14519,' But Amphimedon smote Telemachus on the hand by the wrist, a grazing blow, and the bronze tore the surface of the skin.'),(14520,' And Ctesippus with his long spear  grazed the shoulder of Eumaeus above his shield, '),(14521,' but the spear flew over and fell upon the ground.'),(14522,'Then once more Odysseus, the wise and crafty-minded, and his company hurled their sharp spears into the throng of the wooers,'),(14523,'  and again Odysseus, the sacker of cities, smote Eurydamas, and Telemachus Amphimedon, the swineherd Polybus,'),(14524,' and thereafter the herdsman of the cattle smote Ctesippus in the breast, and boasted over him, saying:'),(14525,'\n“Son of Polytherses, thou lover of revilings, never more at all do thou speak big, yielding to folly, but leave the matter to the gods, since verily they are mightier far.'),(14526,'  This is thy gift of welcome to match the hoof which of late thou gavest to godlike Odysseus, when he went begging through the house.” '),(14527,' \nSo spoke the herdsman of the sleek cattle.'),(14528,' But Odysseus wounded the son of Damastor in close fight with a thrust of his long spear, '),(14529,'and Telemachus wounded Leiocritus, son of Evenor,  with a spear-thrust full upon the groin, and drove the bronze clean through, '),(14530,' and he fell headlong and struck the ground full with his forehead.'),(14531,' Then Athena held up her aegis, the bane of mortals, on high from the roof, '),(14532,' and the minds of the wooers were panic-stricken, '),(14533,'and they fled through the halls like a herd of kine '),(14534,' that the darting gad-fly falls upon and drives along in the season of spring, when the long days come.'),(14535,' And even as vultures of crooked talons and curved beaks come forth from the mountains and dart upon smaller birds,'),(14536,' which scour the plain, flying low beneath the clouds,  and the vultures pounce upon them and slay them, and they have no defence or way of escape, '),(14537,' and men rejoice at the chase; '),(14538,' even so did those others set upon the wooers and smite them left and right through the hall.'),(14539,' And therefrom rose hideous groaning as heads were smitten, and all the floor swam with blood.'),(14540,'\n  But Leiodes rushed forward and clasped the knees of Odysseus, and made entreaty to him, and spoke winged words:'),(14541,'and do thou respect me and have pity.'),(14542,'and do thou respect me and have pity.'),(14543,' For I declare to thee that never yet have I wronged one of the women in thy halls by wanton word or deed; '),(14544,' nay,  I sought to check the other wooers, when any would do such deeds.'),(14545,' But they would not hearken to me to withhold their hands from evil, '),(14546,'wherefore through their wanton folly they have met a cruel doom.'),(14547,' Yet I, the soothsayer among them, that have done no wrong, shall be laid low even as they; so true is it that there is no gratitude in aftertime for good deeds done.\"'),(14548,'  Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered him: '),(14549,'“If verily thou dost declare thyself the soothsayer among these men, often, I ween, must thou have prayed in the halls that far from me the issue of a joyous return might be removed, and that it might be with thee that my dear wife should go and bear thee children; '),(14550,' wherefore thou shalt not escape grievous death.”'),(14551,'So saying, he seized in his strong hand a sword that lay near, which Agelaus had let fall to the ground when he was slain, '),(14552,'and with this he smote him full upon the neck.'),(14553,' And even while he was yet speaking his head was mingled with the dust. '),(14554,' \n  Now the son of Terpes, the minstrel, was still seeking to escape black fate, even Phemius, who sang perforce among the wooers.'),(14555,' He stood with the clear-toned lyre in his hands near the postern door, '),(14556,'and he was divided in mind whether he should slip out from the hall  and sit down by the well-built altar of great Zeus, the God of the court, whereon Laertes and Odysseus had burned many things of oxen, or whether he should rush forward and clasp the knees of Odysseus in prayer.'),(14557,' And as he pondered this seemed to him the better course, to clasp the knees of Odysseus, son of Laertes.'),(14558,'  So he laid the hollow lyre on the ground between the mixing-bowl and the silver-studded chair, and himself rushed forward and clasped Odysseus by the knees, and made entreaty to him, and spoke winged words:'),(14559,' and do thou respect me and have pity; '),(14560,' and do thou respect me and have pity; '),(14561,' on thine own self shall sorrow come hereafter, if thou slayest the minstrel, even me, who sing to gods and men.'),(14562,' Self-taught am I, and the god has planted in my heart all manner of lays, '),(14563,' and worthy am I to sing to thee as to a god; '),(14564,'wherefore be not eager to cut my throat.'),(14565,'  Aye, and Telemachus too will bear witness to this, thy dear son, how that through no will or desire of mine I was wont to resort to thy house to sing to the wooers at their feasts, but they, being far more and stronger, led me hither perforce.\"'),(14566,'So he spoke, and the strong and mighty Telemachus heard him,  and quickly spoke to his father, who was near:'),(14567,'“Stay thy hand, and do not wound this guiltless man with the sword.'),(14568,' Aye, and let us save also the herald, Medon, who ever cared for me in our house, when I was a child—unless perchance Philoetius has already slain him, or the swineherd,  or he met thee as thou didst rage through the house.\"'),(14569,'So he spoke, and Medon, wise of heart, heard him,'),(14570,' for he lay crouching beneath a chair, and had clothed himself in the skin of an ox, newly flayed, seeking to avoid black fate.'),(14571,'Straightway he rose from beneath the chair and stripped off the ox-hide,  and then rushed forward and clasped Telemachus by the knees, and made entreaty to him, and spoke winged words:'),(14572,' \n“Friend, here I am; stay thou thy hand and bid thy father stay his, lest in the greatness of his might he harm me with the sharp bronze in his wrath against the wooers, who wasted his  possessions in the halls, and in their folly honored thee not at all.”'),(14573,'\nBut Odysseus of many wiles smiled, and said to him:'),(14574,' “Be of good cheer, for he has delivered thee and saved thee, that thou mayest know in thy heart and tell also to another, how far better is the doing of good deeds than of evil.'),(14575,'  But go forth from the halls and sit down outside in the court away from the slaughter, thou and the minstrel of many songs, till I shall have finished all that I must needs do in the house.” '),(14576,' \nSo he spoke, and the two went their way forth from the hall and sat down by the altar of great Zeus,  gazing about on every side, ever expecting death. '),(14577,' And Odysseus too gazed about all through his house to see if any man yet lived, and was hiding there, seeking to avoid black fate.'),(14578,'  But he found them one and all fallen in the blood and dust—all the host of them, like fishes that fishermen  have drawn forth in the meshes of their net from the grey sea upon the curving beach,  '),(14579,'and they all lie heaped upon the sand, longing for the waves of the sea, '),(14580,'and the bright sun takes away their life;'),(14581,'even so now the wooers lay heaped upon each other.'),(14582,'   Then Odysseus of many wiles spoke to Telemachus:'),(14583,'\n“Telemachus, go call me the nurse Eurycleia, that I may tell her the word that is in my mind.”'),(14584,'\nSo he spoke, and Telemachus hearkened to his dear father, and shaking the door said to Eurycleia:'),(14585,'\n  “Up and hither, aged wife, that hast charge of all our woman servants in the halls.'),(14586,'  my father calls thee, that he may tell thee somewhat.\"'),(14587,'  my father calls thee, that he may tell thee somewhat.\"'),(14588,'So he spoke, but her word remained unwinged; she opened the doors of the stately hall,  and came forth, '),(14589,'and Telemachus led the way before her.'),(14590,' There she found Odysseus amid the bodies of the slain, all befouled with blood and filth, like a lion that comes from feeding on an ox of the farmstead,'),(14591,' and all his breast and his cheeks on either side  are stained with blood, and he is terrible to look upon;'),(14592,' even so was Odysseus befouled, his feet and his hands above.'),(14593,' But she, when she beheld the corpses and the great welter of blood, made ready to utter loud cries of joy, seeing what a deed had been wrought.'),(14594,' But Odysseus stayed and checked her in her eagerness,  and spoke and addressed her with winged words:'),(14595,'\n“In thine own heart rejoice, old dame, but refrain thyself and cry not out aloud:'),(14596,' an unholy thing is it to boast over slain men.'),(14597,' These men here has the fate of the gods destroyed and their own reckless deeds, '),(14598,'for they honored no one of men upon the earth,  were he evil or good, whosoever came among them; '),(14599,'wherefore by their wanton folly they brought on themselves a shameful death.'),(14600,' But come, name thou over to me the women in the halls, which ones dishonor me and which are guiltless.\"'),(14601,'Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered him:'),(14602,' “Then verily, my child, will I tell thee all the truth.'),(14603,'  Fifty women servants hast thou in the halls, women that we have taught to do their work, to card the wool and bear the lot of slaves.'),(14604,' Of these twelve in all have set their feet in the way of shamelessness,  and regard not me nor Penelope herself. '),(14605,'And Telemachus is but newly grown to manhood, and his mother would not suffer him to rule over the women servants.'),(14606,' But come, let me go up to the bright upper chamber and bear word to thy wife, on whom some god has sent sleep.” '),(14607,' \n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(14608,' “Wake her not yet, but do thou bid come hither the women, who in time past have contrived shameful deeds.\"'),(14609,'So he spoke, and the old dame went forth through the hall to bear tidings to the women, and bid them come; '),(14610,'  but Odysseus called to him Telemachus and the neatherd and the swineherd, and spoke to them winged words:'),(14611,'\n“Begin now to bear forth the dead bodies and bid the women help you, '),(14612,' and thereafter cleanse the beautiful chairs and the tables with water and porous sponges.'),(14613,'  But when you have set all the house in order, lead the women forth from the well-built hall to a place between the dome and the goodly fence of the court, and there strike them down with your long swords, until you take away the life from them all, and they forget the love  which they had at the bidding of the wooers, when they lay with them in secret.”'),(14614,'So he spoke, and the women came all in a throng, wailing terribly and shedding big tears.'),(14615,' First they bore forth the bodies of the slain and set them down beneath the portico of the well-fenced court,  propping them one against the other; '),(14616,' and Odysseus himself gave them orders and hastened on the work, '),(14617,' and they bore the bodies forth perforce.'),(14618,' Then they cleansed the beautiful high seats and the tables with water and porous sponges. '),(14619,'But Telemachus and the neatherd and the swineherd  scraped with hoes the floor of the well-built house,'),(14620,'and the women bore the scrapings forth and threw them out of doors.'),(14621,' But when they had set in order all the hall, they led the women forth from the well-built hall to a place between the dome and the goodly fence of the court,  and shut them up in a narrow space, whence it was in no wise possible to escape. '),(14622,' Then wise Telemachus was the first to speak to the others, saying:'),(14623,'\n“Let it be by no clean death that I take the lives of these women, who on my own head have poured reproaches and on my mother, and were wont to lie with the wooers.” '),(14624,' \n  So he spoke, and tied the cable of a dark-prowed ship to a great pillar and flung it round the dome, stretching it on high that none might reach the ground with her feet.'),(14625,' And as when long-winged thrushes or doves fall into a snare that is set in a thicket,  as they seek to reach their resting-place, and hateful is the bed that gives them welcome, even so the women held their heads in a row, and round the necks of all nooses were laid, that they might die most piteously.'),(14626,'And they writhed a little while with their feet, but not long.'),(14627,'Then forth they led Melanthius through the doorway and the court, '),(14628,' and cut off his nostrils and his ears with the pitiless bronze, and drew out his vitals for the dogs to eat raw, and cut off his hands and his feet in their furious wrath.'),(14629,'Thereafter they washed their hands and feet, and went into the house to Odysseus, and the work was done. '),(14630,' But Odysseus said to the dear nurse Eurycleia:'),(14631,' “Bring sulphur, old dame, to cleanse from pollution, and bring me fire, that I may purge the hall;'),(14632,' and do thou bid Penelope come hither with her handmaidens, '),(14633,'and order all the women in the house to come.\"'),(14634,'  Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered him:'),(14635,' “Yea, all this, my child, hast thou spoken aright. '),(14636,'But come, let me bring thee a cloak and a tunic for raiment, and do not thou stand thus in the halls with thy broad shoulders wrapped in rags; '),(14637,' that were a cause for blame.”'),(14638,'\n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her: '),(14639,'“First of all let a fire now be made me in the hall.\"'),(14640,'So he spoke, and the dear nurse Eurycleia did not disobey, but brought fire and sulphur;'),(14641,'but Odysseus throughly purged the hall and the house and the court.'),(14642,'\n  Then the old dame went back through the fair house of Odysseus to bear tidings to the women and bid them come; '),(14643,' and they came forth from their hall with torches in their hands.'),(14644,' They thronged about Odysseus and embraced him, and clasped and kissed his head and shoulders  and his hands in loving welcome; '),(14645,'and a sweet longing seized him to weep and wail, for in his heart he knew them all.'),(14646,' Then the old dame went up to the upper chamber, laughing aloud, to tell her mistress that her dear husband was in the house.'),(14647,' Her knees moved nimbly, but her feet trotted along beneath her; '),(14648,'and she stood above her lady\'s head, and spoke to her, and said:'),(14649,'\n  “Awake, Penelope, dear child, that with thine own eyes thou mayest see what thou desirest all thy days.'),(14650,' Odysseus is here, and has come home, late though his coming has been, '),(14651,'and has slain the proud wooers who vexed his house, and devoured his substance, and oppressed his son.\"'),(14652,'  Then wise Penelope answered her:'),(14653,'“Dear nurse, the gods have made thee mad, they who can make foolish even one who is full wise, and set the simple-minded in the paths of understanding; '),(14654,'though heretofore thou wast sound of mind.'),(14655,'though heretofore thou wast sound of mind.'),(14656,'  Why dost thou mock me, who have a heart full of sorrow, to tell me this wild tale, and dost rouse me out of slumber, the sweet slumber that bound me and enfolded my eyelids?'),(14657,' For never yet have I slept so sound since the day when Odysseus went forth to see evil Ilios that should not be named.'),(14658,'  Nay come now, go down and back to the women\'s hall,'),(14659,' for if any other of the women that are mine had come and told me this, and had roused me out of sleep, straightway would I have sent her back in sorry wise to return again to the hall,'),(14660,' but to thee old age shall bring this profit.”'),(14661,'  Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered her: '),(14662,' “I mock thee not, dear child, but in very truth Odysseus is here, and has come home, even as I tell thee. He is that stranger to whom all men did dishonor in the halls. '),(14663,'But Telemachus long ago knew that he was here,  yet in his prudence he hid the purpose of his father, till he should take vengeance on the violence of overweening men.\"'),(14664,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 23.32-23.33'),(14665,'So she spoke, and Penelope was glad, and she leapt from her bed and flung her arms about the old woman and let the tears fall from her eyelids; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 32 to line 33'),(14666,'\n  “Come now, dear nurse, I pray thee tell me truly, if verily he has come home, as thou sayest, how he put forth his hands upon the shameless wooers, all alone as he was, while they remained always in a body in the house.\"'),(14667,'Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered her:'),(14668,'  “I saw not, I asked not; only I heard the groaning of men that were being slain.'),(14669,' As for us women, we sat terror-stricken in the innermost part of our well-built chambers, and the close-fitting doors shut us in, until the hour when thy son Telemachus called me from the hall, '),(14670,'for his father had sent him forth to call me.'),(14671,'  Then I found Odysseus standing among the bodies of the slain, '),(14672,'and they, stretched all around him on the hard floor, lay one upon the other; '),(14673,'the sight would have warmed thy heart with cheer. '),(14674,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 23.48-23.51'),(14675,'and sent me forth to call thee.'),(14676,' Nay, come with me, that the hearts of you two may enter into joy, for you have suffered many woes.'),(14677,' But now at length has this thy long desire been fulfilled:'),(14678,'  he has come himself, alive to his own hearth, and he has found both thee and his son in the halls;'),(14679,'while as for those, even the wooers, who wrought him evil, on them has he taken vengeance one and all in his house.\"'),(14680,'Then wise Penelope answered her:'),(14681,' “Dear nurse, boast not yet loudly over them with laughter.'),(14682,'  Thou knowest how welcome the sight of him in the halls would be to all, but above all to me and to his son, born of us two.'),(14683,' But this is no true tale, as thou tellest it; nay, some one of the immortals has slain the lordly wooers in wrath at their grievous insolence and their evil deeds.'),(14684,'  For they honored no one among men upon the earth, were he evil or good, whosoever came among them; '),(14685,'therefore it is through their own wanton folly that they have suffered evil.'),(14686,' But Odysseus far away has lost his return to the land of Achaea, and is lost himself.\"'),(14687,'Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered her:'),(14688,'  “My child, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth, in that thou saidst that thy husband, who even now is here, at his own hearth, would never more return!'),(14689,' Thy heart is ever unbelieving.'),(14690,' Nay come, I will tell thee a manifest sign besides, even the scar of the wound which long ago the boar dealt him with his white tusk.'),(14691,'  This I marked while I washed his feet, and was fain to tell it to thee as well, '),(14692,' but he laid his hand upon my mouth, and in the great wisdom of his heart would not suffer me to speak.'),(14693,' So come with me;'),(14694,'  but I will set my very life at stake that, if I deceive thee, thou shouldest slay me by a most pitiful death.\"'),(14695,'  Then wise Penelope answered her: '),(14696,'“Dear nurse, it is hard for thee to comprehend the counsels of the gods that are forever, how wise soever thou art.'),(14697,' Nevertheless let us go to my son, that I may see the wooers dead and him that slew them.” '),(14698,' \n  So saying, she went down from the upper chamber,'),(14699,'and much her heart pondered whether she should stand aloof and question her dear husband, or whether she should go up to him, and clasp and kiss his head and hands.'),(14700,' But when she had come in and had passed over the stone threshold, she sat down opposite Odysseus in the light of the fire  beside the further wall; '),(14701,'but he was sitting by a tall pillar, looking down, and waiting to see whether his noble wife would say aught to him, when her eyes beheld him.'),(14702,' Howbeit she sat long in silence, and amazement came upon her soul; '),(14703,'and now with her eyes she would look full upon his face, and now again  she would fail to know him, for that he had upon him mean raiment. '),(14704,' But Telemachus rebuked her, and spoke, and addressed her:'),(14705,'\n“My mother, cruel mother, that hast an unyielding heart, why dost thou thus hold aloof from my father, and dost not sit by his side and ask and question him?'),(14706,'  No other woman would harden her heart as thou dost, and stand aloof from her husband, who after many grievous toils had come back to her in the twentieth year to his native land:'),(14707,' but thy heart is ever harder than stone.” '),(14708,'Then wise Penelope answered him:'),(14709,'  “My child, the heart in my breast is lost in wonder, and I have no power to speak at all, nor to ask a question, nor to look him in the face.'),(14710,' But if in very truth he is Odysseus, and has come home, we two shall surely know one another more certainly; '),(14711,' for we have signs which we two alone know, signs hidden from others.”'),(14712,'So she spoke, and the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus smiled, and straightway spoke to Telemachus winged words:'),(14713,'\n“Telemachus, suffer now thy mother to test me in the halls; '),(14714,'presently shall she win more certain knowledge.'),(14715,'  But now because I am foul, and am clad about my body in mean clothing, she scorns me, and will not yet admit that I am he.'),(14716,' But for us, let us take thought how all may be the very best. '),(14717,'For whoso has slain but one man in a land, even though it be a man that leaves not many behind to avenge him,  he goes into exile, and leaves his kindred and his native land;'),(14718,' but we have slain those who were the very stay of the city, far the noblest of the youths of Ithaca.'),(14719,' Of this I bid thee take thought.”'),(14720,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(14721,' “Do thou thyself look to this, dear father; '),(14722,'for thy  counsel, they say, is the best among men, nor could any other of mortal men vie with thee.'),(14723,' As for us, we will follow with thee eagerly, nor methinks shall we be wanting in valor, so far as we have strength.” '),(14724,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said:  “Then will I tell thee what seems to me to be the best way.'),(14725,' First bathe yourselves, and put on your tunics, and bid the handmaids in the halls to take their raiment. '),(14726,'But let the divine minstrel with his clear-toned lyre in hand be our leader in the gladsome dance,  that any man who hears the sound from without, whether a passer-by or one of those who dwell around, may say that it is a wedding feast; '),(14727,'and so the rumor of the slaying of the wooers shall not be spread abroad throughout the city before we go forth to our well-wooded farm.'),(14728,' There  shall we afterwards devise whatever advantage the Olympian may vouchsafe us.”'),(14729,'So he spoke, and they all readily hearkened and obeyed. First they bathed and put on their tunics, and the women arrayed themselves, '),(14730,' and the divine minstrel took the hollow lyre and aroused in them the desire  of sweet song and goodly dance. '),(14731,' So the great hall resounded all about with the tread of dancing men and of fair-girdled women; '),(14732,'and thus would one speak who heard the noise from without the house:'),(14733,'“Aye, verily some one has wedded the queen wooed of many.'),(14734,' Cruel she was, nor had she the heart to keep the great house of her wedded husband to the end, even till he should come.”'),(14735,'So they would say, but they knew not how these things were.'),(14736,'Meanwhile the housewife Eurynome bathed the great-hearted Odysseus in his house, and anointed him with oil,  and cast about him a fair cloak and a tunic; '),(14737,' and over his head Athena shed abundant beauty, making him taller to look upon and mightier, '),(14738,' and from his head she made locks to flow in curls like the hyacinth flower.'),(14739,'And as when a man overlays silver with gold,  a cunning workman whom Hephaestus and Pallas Athena have taught all manner of craft, and full of grace is the work he produces,'),(14740,' even so the goddess shed grace on his head and shoulders, '),(14741,'and forth from the bath he came, in form like unto the immortals.'),(14742,' Then he sat down again on the chair from which he had risen,  opposite his wife; and he spoke to her and said:'),(14743,'“Strange lady! to thee beyond all women have the dwellers on Olympus given a heart that cannot be softened.'),(14744,' No other woman would harden her heart as thou dost, and stand aloof from her husband who after many grievous toils  had come to her in the twentieth year to his native land.'),(14745,' Nay come, nurse, strew me a couch, that all alone I may lay me down,'),(14746,' for verily the heart in her breast is of iron.\"'),(14747,'Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(14748,'“Strange sir, I am neither in any wise proud, nor do I scorn thee,  nor yet am I too greatly amazed, but right well do I know what manner of man thou wast, when thou wentest forth from Ithaca on thy long-oared ship.'),(14749,' Yet come, Eurycleia, strew for him the stout bedstead outside the well-built bridal chamber which he made himself.'),(14750,' Thither do ye bring for him the stout bedstead, and cast upon it bedding,  fleeces and cloaks and bright coverlets.”'),(14751,' \nSo she spoke, and made trial of her husband.'),(14752,' But Odysseus, in a burst of anger, spoke to his true-hearted wife, and said:'),(14753,' “Woman, truly this is a bitter word that thou hast spoken.'),(14754,' Who has set my bed elsewhere? '),(14755,'Hard would it be for one,  though never so skilled, unless a god himself should come and easily by his will set it in another place.'),(14756,' But of men there is no mortal that lives, be he never so young and strong, who could easily pry it from its place, for a great token is wrought in the fashioned bed, '),(14757,'and it was I that built it and none other.'),(14758,'  A bush of long-leafed olive was growing within the court, strong and vigorous, '),(14759,'and girth it was like a pillar.'),(14760,' Round about this I built my chamber, till I had finished it, with close-set stones, and I roofed it over well, and added to it jointed doors, close-fitting.'),(14761,'  Thereafter I cut away the leafy branches of the long-leafed olive, and, trimming the trunk from the root, I smoothed it around with the adze well and cunningly, and made it straight to the line, thus fashioning the bed-post; and I bored it all with the augur.'),(14762,' Beginning with this I hewed out my bed, till I had finished it,  inlaying it with gold and silver and ivory, '),(14763,'and I stretched on it a thong of ox-hide, bright with purple.'),(14764,' Thus do I declare to thee this token; '),(14765,' but I know not, woman, whether my bedstead is still fast in its place, or whether by now some man has cut from beneath the olive stump, and set the bedstead elsewhere.”'),(14766,'  So he spoke, and her knees were loosened where she sat, and her heart melted, as she knew the sure tokens which Odysseus told her.'),(14767,' Then with a burst of tears she ran straight toward him, and flung her arms about the neck of Odysseus, and kissed his head, and spoke, saying:'),(14768,'\n“Be not vexed with me, Odysseus, for in all else  thou wast ever the wisest of men.'),(14769,'It is the gods that gave us sorrow, the gods who begrudged that we two should remain with each other and enjoy our youth, and come to the threshold of old age.'),(14770,' But be not now wroth with me for this, nor full of indignation, because at the first, when I saw thee, I did not thus give thee welcome.'),(14771,'  For always the heart in my breast was full of dread, lest some man should come and beguile me with his words; '),(14772,'for there are many that plan devices of evil.'),(14773,'Nay, even Argive Helen, daughter of Zeus, would not have lain in love with a man of another folk,  had she known that the warlike sons of the Achaeans were to bring her home again to her dear native land.'),(14774,' Yet verily in her case a god prompted her to work a shameful deed; '),(14775,'nor until then did she lay up in her mind the thought of that folly, the grievous folly from which at the first sorrow came upon us too.'),(14776,'  But now, since thou hast told the clear tokens of our bed, which no mortal beside has ever seen save thee and me alone and one single handmaid, the daughter of Actor, whom my father gave me or ever I came hither, even her who kept the doors of our strong bridal chamber, lo, thou dost convince my heart, unbending as it is.”'),(14777,' \nSo she spoke, and in his heart aroused yet more the desire for lamentation; '),(14778,'\nand he wept, holding in his arms his dear and true-hearted wife.'),(14779,' And welcome as is the sight of land to men that swim, whose well-built ship Poseidon  has smitten on the sea as it was driven on by the wind and the swollen wave, '),(14780,'and but few have made their escape from the gray sea to the shore by swimming, and thickly are their bodies crusted with brine, and gladly have they set foot on the land and escaped from their evil case; '),(14781,'even so welcome to her was her husband, as she gazed upon him,  and from his neck she could in no wise let her white arms go. '),(14782,'And now would the rosy-fingered Dawn have arisen upon their weeping, had not the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, taken other counsel. '),(14783,'The long night she held back at the end of its course, and likewise stayed the golden-throned Dawn at the streams of Oceanus, and would not suffer her  to yoke her swift-footed horses that bring light to men, Lampus and Phaethon, who are the colts that bear the Dawn.'),(14784,' \nThen to his wife said Odysseus of many wiles: “Wife, we have not yet come to the end of all our trials, but still hereafter there is to be measureless toil,  long and hard, which I must fulfil to the end; '),(14785,'for so did the spirit of Teiresias foretell to me on the day when I went down into the house of Hades to enquire concerning the return of my comrades and myself.'),(14786,' But come, wife, let us to bed, that  lulled now by sweet slumber we may take our joy of rest.\"'),(14787,'Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(14788,'“Thy bed shall be ready for thee whensoever thy heart shall desire it, since the gods have indeed caused thee to come back to thy well-built house and thy native land.'),(14789,'  But since thou hast bethought thee of this, and a god has put it into thy heart, come, tell me of this trial, for in time to come, methinks, I shall learn of it, and to know it at once is no whit worse.” '),(14790,' \nAnd Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(14791,'“Strange lady! why dost thou now so urgently bid me  tell thee?'),(14792,' Yet I will declare it, and will hide nothing.'),(14793,'Verily thy heart shall have no joy of it,'),(14794,'  even as I myself have none; for Teiresias bade me go forth to full many cities of men, bearing a shapely oar in my hands, till I should come  to men that know naught of the sea, and eat not of food mingled with salt; '),(14795,' aye, and they know naught of ships with purple cheeks, or of shapely oars that serve as wings to ships.'),(14796,' And he told me this sign, right manifest; nor will I hide it from thee.'),(14797,' When another wayfarer, on meeting me,  should say that I had a winnowing fan on my stout shoulder, then he bade me fix my oar in the earth, and make goodly offerings to lord Poseidon—a ram and a bull and a boar, that mates with sows—and depart for my home, and offer sacred hecatombs  to the immortal gods, who hold broad heaven, to each one in due order.'),(14798,' And death shall come to me myself far from the sea, a death so gentle, that shall lay me low, when I am overcome with sleek old age, '),(14799,' and my people shall dwell in prosperity around me.'),(14800,' All this, he said, should I see fulfilled.\"'),(14801,'  Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(14802,'“If verily the gods are to bring about for thee a happier old age, there is hope then that thou wilt find an escape from evil.\"'),(14803,'Thus they spoke to one another; '),(14804,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 23.289-23.290'),(14805,'Thus they spoke to one another; and meanwhile Eurynome and the nurse made ready the bed  of soft coverlets by the light of blazing torches. ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 289 to line 290'),(14806,' and when she had led them to the bridal chamber, she went back.'),(14807,'And they then gladly came to the place of the couch that was theirs of old.'),(14808,' But Telemachus and the neatherd and the swineherd stayed their feet from dancing, and stayed the women, and themselves lay down to sleep throughout the shadowy halls.'),(14809,'\n  But when the two had had their fill of the joy of love, they took delight in tales, speaking each to the other. She, the fair lady, told of all that she had endured in the halls, looking upon the destructive throng of the wooers, who for her sake  slew many beasts, cattle and goodly sheep; and great store of wine was drawn from the jars.'),(14810,' But Zeus-born Odysseus recounted all the woes that he had brought on men, and all the toil that in his sorrow he had himself endured, '),(14811,'and she was glad to listen, nor did sweet sleep fall upon her eyelids, till he had told all the tale. '),(14812,' \n  He began by telling how at the first he overcame the Cicones, and then came to the rich land of the Lotus-eaters, '),(14813,'and all that the Cyclops wrought, and how he made him pay the price for his mighty comrades, whom the Cyclops had eaten, and had shown no pity. '),(14814,'Then how he came to Aeolus, who received him with a ready heart,  and sent him on his way; but it was not yet his fate to come to his dear native land, nay, the storm-wind caught him up again, and bore him over the teeming deep, groaning heavily.'),(14815,' Next how he came to Telepylus of the Laestrygonians, who destroyed his ships and his well-greaved comrades  one and all, '),(14816,'and Odysseus alone escaped in his black ship. '),(14817,' Then he told of all the wiles and craftiness of Circe, and how in his benched ship he had gone to the dank house of Hades to consult the spirit of Theban Teiresias, and had seen all his comrades  and the mother who bore him and nursed him, when a child. '),(14818,'And how he heard the voice of the Sirens, who sing unceasingly, and had come to the Wandering Rocks, and to dread Charybdis, and to Scylla, from whom never yet had men escaped unscathed.'),(14819,' Then how his comrades slew the kine of Helios, '),(14820,' and how Zeus, who thunders on high, smote his swift ship with a flaming thunderbolt, and his goodly comrades perished all together, while he alone escaped the evil fates.'),(14821,' And how he came to the isle Ogygia and to the nymph Calypso, who kept him there  in her hollow caves, yearning that he should be her husband, and tended him, and said that she would make him immortal and ageless all his days; '),(14822,'yet she could never persuade the heart in his breast. '),(14823,'Then how he came after many toils to the Phaeacians, who heartily showed him all honor, as if he were a god,  and sent him in a ship to his dear native land, after giving him stores of bronze and gold and raiment.'),(14824,' This was the end of the tale he told, when sweet sleep, that loosens the limbs of men, leapt upon him, loosening the cares of his heart. '),(14825,' \nThen again the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel.'),(14826,'  When she judged that the heart of Odysseus had had its fill of dalliance with his wife and of sleep, straightway she roused from Oceanus golden-throned Dawn to bring light to men;'),(14827,'and Odysseus rose from his soft couch, and gave charge to his wife, saying:'),(14828,'\n  “Wife, by now have we had our fill of many trials, thou and I, thou here, mourning over my troublous journey home, '),(14829,' while as for me, Zeus and the other gods bound me fast in sorrows far from my native land, all eager as I was to return.'),(14830,'But now that we have both come to the couch of our desire,  do thou care for the wealth that I have within the halls; as for the flocks which the insolent wooers have wasted, I shall myself get me many as booty, and others will the Achaeans give, until they fill all my folds; '),(14831,'but I verily will go to my well-wooded farm  to see my noble father, who for my sake is sore distressed, '),(14832,'and on thee, wife, do I lay this charge, wise though thou art.'),(14833,' Straightway at the rising of the sun will report go abroad concerning the wooers whom I slew in the halls.'),(14834,' Therefore go thou up to thy upper chamber with thy handmaids,  and abide there. Look thou on no man, nor ask a question.”'),(14835,'He spoke, and girt about his shoulders his beautiful armour, and roused Telemachus and the neatherd and the swineherd, and bade them all take weapons of war in their hands.'),(14836,' They did not disobey, but clad themselves in bronze,  and opened the doors, and went forth, '),(14837,'and Odysseus led the way. '),(14838,'By now there was light over the earth, but Athena hid them in night, and swiftly led them forth from the city.'),(14839,' Meanwhile Cyllenian Hermes called forth the spirits of the wooers.'),(14840,' He held in his hands his wand, a fair wand of gold, wherewith he lulls to sleep the eyes of whom he will, while others again he wakens even out of slumber;'),(14841,' with this he roused and led the spirits, and they followed gibbering.'),(14842,' And as in the innermost recess of a wondrous cave bats flit about gibbering, when one has fallen from off the rock from the chain in which they cling to one another, so these went with him gibbering,'),(14843,' and   Hermes, the Helper, led them down the dank ways.'),(14844,'Past the streams of Oceanus they went, past the rock Leucas, past the gates of the sun and the land of dreams, '),(14845,'and quickly came to the mead of asphodel, where the spirits dwell, phantoms of men who have done with toils.'),(14846,'  Here they found the spirit of Achilles, son of Peleus, and those of Patroclus, of peerless Antilochus, and of Aias, who in comeliness and form was the goodliest of all the Danaans after the peerless son of Peleus.'),(14847,'So these were thronging about Achilles, and near to them  drew the spirit of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, sorrowing; '),(14848,' and round about him others were gathered, the spirits of all those who were slain with him in the house of Aegisthus, and met their fate.'),(14849,' And the spirit of the son of Peleus was first to address him, saying:'),(14850,'“Son of Atreus, we deemed that thou  above all other heroes wast all thy days dear to Zeus, who hurls the thunderbolt, because thou wast lord over many mighty men in the land of the Trojans, where we Achaeans suffered woes.'),(14851,' But verily on thee too was deadly doom to come all too early, the doom that not one avoids of those who are born.'),(14852,'  Ah, would that in the pride of that honor of which thou wast master thou hadst met death and fate in the land of the Trojans.'),(14853,' Then would the whole host of the Achaeans have made thee a tomb, and for thy son too wouldst thou have won great glory in days to come; '),(14854,'but now, as it seems, it has been decreed that thou shouldst be cut off by a most piteous death.” '),(14855,' \n  Then the spirit of the son of Atreus answered him: '),(14856,' “Fortunate son of Peleus, godlike Achilles, that wast slain in the land of Troy far from Argos, '),(14857,' and about thee others fell, the best of the sons of the Trojans and Achaeans, fighting for thy body; '),(14858,'and thou in the whirl of dust  didst lie mighty in thy mightiness, forgetful of thy horsemanship.'),(14859,' We on our part strove the whole day long,'),(14860,' nor should we ever have stayed from the fight, had not Zeus stayed us with a storm.'),(14861,' But after we had borne thee to the ships from out the fight, we laid thee on a bier, and cleansed thy fair flesh  with warm water and with ointment,'),(14862,' and many hot tears did the Danaans shed around thee, and they shore their hair.'),(14863,' And thy mother came forth from the sea with the immortal sea-nymphs, when she heard the tidings,'),(14864,'and a wondrous cry arose over the deep, and thereat trembling laid hold of all the Achaeans.'),(14865,'  Then would they all have sprung up and rushed to the hollow ships, had not a man, wise in the wisdom of old, stayed them, even Nestor, whose counsel had before appeared the best.'),(14866,' He with good intent addressed their assembly, and said:'),(14867,'\n“‘Hold, ye Argives; flee not, Achaean youths.'),(14868,'  \'Tis his mother who comes here forth from the sea with the immortal sea-nymphs to look upon the face of her dead son.\''),(14869,'“So he spoke, and the great-hearted Achaeans ceased from their flight.'),(14870,' Then around thee stood the daughters of the old man of the sea wailing piteously, and they clothed thee about with immortal raiment.'),(14871,'  And the Muses, nine in all, replying to one another with sweet voices, led the dirge.'),(14872,' There couldst thou not have seen an Argive but was in tears,'),(14873,' so deeply did the clear-toned Muse move their hearts.'),(14874,' Thus for seventeen days alike by night and day did we bewail thee, immortal gods and mortal men, '),(14875,' and on the eighteenth we gave thee to the fire, and many well-fatted sheep we slew around thee and sleek kine.'),(14876,' So thou wast burned in the raiment of the gods and in abundance of unguents and sweet honey; '),(14877,' and many Achaean warriors moved in their armour about the pyre, when thou wast burning,  both footmen and charioteers,'),(14878,' and a great din arose. But when the flame of Hephaestus had made an end of thee, in the morning we gathered thy white bones, Achilles, and laid them in unmixed wine and unguents.'),(14879,' Thy mother had given a two-handled, golden urn,'),(14880,' and  said that it was the gift of Dionysus, and the handiwork of famed Hephaestus.'),(14881,'In this lie thy white bones, glorious Achilles, and mingled with them the bones of the dead Patroclus, son of Menoetius, but apart lie those of Antilochus, whom thou didst honor above all the rest of thy comrades after the dead Patroclus.'),(14882,'  And over them we heaped up a great and goodly tomb, we the mighty host of Argive spearmen, on a projecting headland by the broad Hellespont, that it might be seen from far over the sea both by men that now are and that shall be born hereafter. '),(14883,' \n  But thy mother asked of the gods beautiful prizes, and set them in the midst of the list for the chiefs of the Achaeans.'),(14884,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 24.87-24.89'),(14885,' Ere now hast thou been present at the funeral games of many men that were warriors, when at the death of a king the young men gird themselves and make ready the contests, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 87 to line 89'),(14886,'for very dear wast thou to the gods.'),(14887,' Thus not even in death didst thou lose thy name, but ever shalt thou have fair renown among all men, Achilles.  But, as for me, what pleasure have I now in this, that I wound up the skein of war?'),(14888,' For on my return Zeus devised for me a woeful doom at the hands of Aegisthus and my accursed wife.”'),(14889,'Thus they spoke to one another, but the messenger, Argeiphontes, drew near,  leading down the spirits of the wooers slain by Odysseus; and the two, seized with wonder, went straight toward them when they beheld them.'),(14890,' And the spirit of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, recognized the dear son of Melaneus, glorious Amphimedon, '),(14891,' who had been his host, dwelling in Ithaca.'),(14892,' Then the spirit of the son of Atreus spoke first to him and said: '),(14893,'“Amphimedon, what has befallen you that ye have come down beneath the dark earth, all of you picked men and of like age?'),(14894,' One would make no other choice, were one to pick the best men in a city.'),(14895,' Did Poseidon smite you on board your ships,  when he had roused cruel winds and long waves?'),(14896,'Or did foemen work you harm on the land, while you were cutting off their cattle and fair flocks of sheep, or while they fought in defence of their city and their women?'),(14897,'for I declare that I am a friend of thy house.'),(14898,'for I declare that I am a friend of thy house.'),(14899,'  Dost thou not remember when I came thither to your house with godlike Menelaus to urge Odysseus to go with us to Ilios on the benched ships?'),(14900,' A full month it took us to cross all the wide sea, for hardly could we win to our will Odysseus, the sacker of cities.\"'),(14901,'  Then the spirit of Amphimedon answered him, and said: '),(14902,'“Most glorious son of Atreus, king of men, Agamemnon, I remember all these things, O thou fostered of Zeus, even as thou dost tell them; '),(14903,'and on my part I will frankly tell thee all the truth, how for us an evil end of death was wrought.'),(14904,'  We wooed the wife of Odysseus, that had long been gone,'),(14905,' and she neither refused the hateful marriage, nor would she ever make an end, devising for us death and black fate. Nay, she contrived in her heart this guileful thing also:'),(14906,' she set up in her halls a great web, and fell to weaving—  fine of thread was the web and very wide; '),(14907,'and straightway she spoke among us:'),(14908,'“‘Young men, my wooers, since goodly Odysseus is dead, be patient, though eager for my marriage, until I finish this robe—I would not that my spinning should come to naught—a shroud for the lord Laertes against the time when  the fell fate of grievous death shall strike him down; lest any of the Achaean women in the land should be wroth at me, if he were to lie without a shroud, who had won great possessions.’ '),(14909,' \n“So she spoke, and our proud hearts consented.'),(14910,' Then day by day she would weave at the great web,  but by night would unravel it, when she had let place torches by her. '),(14911,'Thus for three years she by her craft kept the Achaeans from knowing, and beguiled them;'),(14912,' but when the fourth year came, as the seasons rolled on, as the months waned and many days were brought in their course, even then one of her women who knew all, told us,  and we caught her unravelling the splendid web. '),(14913,'So she finished it against her will perforce.'),(14914,'\n“Now when she had shewn us the robe, after weaving the great web and washing it, and it shone like the sun or the moon, then it was that some cruel god brought Odysseus from somewhere  to the border of the land, where the swineherd dwelt.'),(14915,' Thither too came the dear son of divine Odysseus on his return from sandy Pylos in his black ship, '),(14916,'and these two, when they had planned an evil death for the wooers, came to the famous city, Odysseus verily  later, but Telemachus led the way before him.'),(14917,' Now the swineherd brought his master, clad in mean raiment, in the likeness of a woeful and aged beggar, leaning on a staff,'),(14918,' and miserable was the raiment that he wore about his body;'),(14919,'and not one of us could know that it was he,  when he appeared so suddenly, no, not even those that were older men, but we assailed him with evil words and with missiles.'),(14920,' Howbeit he with steadfast heart endured for a time to be pelted and taunted in his own halls; '),(14921,'but when at last the will of Zeus, who bears the aegis, roused him,  with the help of Telemachus he took all the beautiful arms and laid them away in the store-room and made fast the bolts. Then in his great cunning he bade his wife set before the wooers his bow and the grey iron to be a contest for us ill-fated men and the beginning of death.'),(14922,'  And no man of us was able to stretch the string of the mighty bow; nay, we fell far short of that strength.'),(14923,' But when the great bow came to the hands of Odysseus, then we all cried out aloud not to give him the bow, how much soever he might speak; '),(14924,' but Telemachus alone urged him on, and bade him take it. '),(14925,'Then he took the bow in his hand, the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus, and with ease did he string it and send an arrow through the iron. Then he went and stood on the threshold, and poured out the swift arrows, glaring about him terribly, and smote king Antinous.'),(14926,'  And thereafter upon the others he with sure aim let fly his shafts, fraught with groanings, '),(14927,'and the men fell thick and fast.'),(14928,' Then was it known that some god was their helper;'),(14929,' for straightway rushing on through the halls in their fury they slew men left and right, and therefrom rose hideous groaning,  as heads were smitten, and all the floor swam with blood.'),(14930,' Thus we perished, Agamemnon, and even now our bodies still lie uncared-for in the halls of Odysseus;'),(14931,' for our friends in each man\'s home know naught as yet—our friends who might wash the black blood from our wounds  and lay our bodies out with wailing; '),(14932,'for that is the due of the dead.”'),(14933,' \nThen the spirit of the son of Atreus answered him:'),(14934,' “Happy son of Laertes, Odysseus of many devices, of a truth full of all excellence was the wife thou didst win, '),(14935,'so good of understanding was peerless Penelope,  daughter of Icarius, '),(14936,'in that she was loyally mindful of Odysseus, her wedded husband. '),(14937,'Therefore the fame of her virtue shall never perish, but the immortals shall make among men on earth a pleasant song in honor of constant Penelope. Not on this wise did the daughter of Tyndareus devise evil deeds  and slay her wedded husband, and hateful shall the song regarding her be among men, and evil repute doth she bring upon all womankind, even upon her that doeth uprightly.\"'),(14938,'Thus the two spoke to one another, as they stood in the house of Hades beneath the depths of the earth.'),(14939,'\n  But Odysseus and his men, when they had gone down from the city, quickly came to the fair and well-ordered farm of Laertes, which he had won for himself in days past, and much had he toiled for it.'),(14940,' There was his house, and all about it ran the sheds in which ate, and sat, and slept  the servants that were bondsmen, that did his pleasure; '),(14941,' but within it was an old Sicilian woman, who tended the old man with kindly care there at the farm, far from the city.'),(14942,' Then Odysseus spoke to the servants and to his son, saying:'),(14943,'\n“Do you now go within the well-built house,  and straightway slay for dinner the best of the swine;'),(14944,'but I will make trial of my father, and see whether he will recognize me and know me by sight, or whether he will fail to know me, since I have been gone so long a time.\"'),(14945,'So saying, he gave to the slaves his battle-gear.'),(14946,'  They thereafter went quickly to the house; but Odysseus drew near to the fruitful vineyard in his quest.'),(14947,' Now he did not find Dolius as he went down into the great orchard, nor any of his slaves or of his sons,'),(14948,' but as it chanced  they had gone to gather stones for the vineyard wall, and the old man was their leader.'),(14949,'But he found his father alone in the well-ordered vineyard, digging about a plant;'),(14950,'  and he was clothed in a foul tunic, patched and wretched, and about his shins he had bound stitched greaves of ox-hide to guard against scratches,  and he wore gloves upon his hands because of the thorns, '),(14951,' and on his head a goatskin cap; and he nursed his sorrow. '),(14952,' \nNow when the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus saw him, worn with old age and laden with great grief at heart, he stood still beneath a tall pear tree, and shed tears.'),(14953,'  Then he debated in mind and heart whether to kiss and embrace his father, and tell him all, how he had returned and come to his native land, or whether he should first question him, and prove him in each thing.'),(14954,' And, as he pondered, this seemed to him the better course,  to prove him first with mocking words. '),(14955,'So with this in mind the goodly Odysseus went straight toward him.'),(14956,' He verily was holding his head down, digging about a plant,'),(14957,'and his glorious son came up to him, and addressed him, saying:'),(14958,'“Old man, no lack of skill hast thou to tend  a garden; nay, thy care is good, and there is naught whatsoever, either plant or fig tree, or vine, nay, or olive, or pear, or garden-plot in all the field that lacks care.'),(14959,' But another thing will I tell thee, and do thou not lay up wrath thereat in thy heart: thou thyself enjoyest no good care, but  thou bearest woeful old age, and therewith art foul and unkempt, and clad in mean raiment.'),(14960,' Surely it is not because of sloth on thy part that thy master cares not for thee, nor dost thou seem in any wise like a slave to look upon either in form or in stature;'),(14961,' for thou art like a king, '),(14962,' even like one who, when he has bathed and eaten,  should sleep soft; '),(14963,'for this is the way of old men.'),(14964,' But come, tell me this, and declare it truly. Whose slave art thou,'),(14965,' and whose orchard dost thou tend?'),(14966,' and whose orchard dost thou tend? And tell me this also truly, that I may know full well, whether this is indeed Ithaca, to which we are now come, as  a man yonder told me, who met me but now on my way hither. In no wise over sound of wit was he, for he deigned not to tell me of each thing, nor to listen to my word, when I questioned him about a friend of mine, whether haply he still lives, or is now dead and in the house of Hades.'),(14967,'  For I will tell thee, and do thou give heed and hearken.'),(14968,' I once entertained in my dear native land a man that came to our house, and never did any man beside of strangers that dwell afar come to my house a more welcome guest.'),(14969,' He declared that by lineage he came from Ithaca, and said  that his own father was Laertes, son of Arceisius. '),(14970,' So I took him to the house and gave him entertainment with kindly welcome of the rich store that was within, and I gave him gifts of friendship, such as are meet. '),(14971,'Of well-wrought gold  I gave him seven talents, and a mixing-bowl all of silver, embossed with flowers, and twelve cloaks of single fold, and as many coverlets, and as many fair mantles, and as many tunics besides, and furthermore women, skilled in goodly handiwork, four comely women, whom he himself was minded to choose.” '),(14972,' \n  Then his father answered him, weeping: '),(14973,' “Stranger, verily thou art come to the country of which thou dost ask, but wanton and reckless men now possess it.'),(14974,' And all in vain didst thou bestow those gifts, the countless gifts thou gavest. '),(14975,'For if thou hadst found him yet alive in the land of Ithaca,  then would he have sent thee on thy way with ample requital of gifts and good entertainment; for that is the due of him who begins the kindness.'),(14976,' But come, tell me this, and declare it truly. How many years have passed since thou didst entertain that guest, that hapless guest, my son—as sure as ever such a man there was—  my ill-starred son,'),(14977,' whom far from his friends and his native land haply the fishes have devoured in the deep, or on the shore he has become the spoil of beasts and birds?'),(14978,' Nor did his mother deck him for burial and weep over him, nor his father, we who gave him birth, '),(14979,'no, nor did his wife, wooed with many gifts, constant Penelope,  bewail her own husband upon the bier, as was meet, when she had closed his eyes in death; '),(14980,' though that is the due of the dead.'),(14981,' And tell me this also truly, that I may know full well.'),(14982,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(14983,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(14984,' Where is the swift ship moored that brought thee hither  with thy godlike comrades? '),(14985,'Or didst thou come as a passenger on another\'s ship, and did they depart when they had set thee on shore?\"'),(14986,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(14987,' “Then verily will I frankly tell thee all.'),(14988,' I come from Alybas, where I have a glorious house,  and I am the son of Apheidas, son of lord Polypemon, '),(14989,' and my own name is Eperitus.'),(14990,' But a god drove me wandering from Sicania to come hither against my will '),(14991,' and my ship lies yonder off the tilled land away from the city.'),(14992,'But as for Odysseus, it is now the fifth year  since he went thence, and departed from my country. Hapless man!'),(14993,' Yet he had birds of good omen, when he set out, birds upon the right. So I was glad of them, as I sent him on his way,'),(14994,' and he went gladly forth, and our hearts hoped that we should yet meet as host and guest and give one another glorious gifts.\"'),(14995,'  So he spoke, and a dark cloud of grief enwrapped Laertes, '),(14996,'and with both his hands he took the dark dust and strewed it over his grey head with ceaseless groaning.'),(14997,' Then the heart of Odysseus was stirred, and up through his nostrils shot a keen pang, as he beheld his dear father.'),(14998,' And he sprang toward him, and clasped him in his arms, and kissed him, saying:'),(14999,'“Lo, father, I here before thee, my very self, am that man of whom thou dost ask; I am come in the twentieth year to my native land.'),(15000,' But cease from grief and tearful lamenting, '),(15001,' though great is the need of haste.'),(15002,' though great is the need of haste.'),(15003,'  The wooers have I slain in our halls, and have taken vengeance on their grievous insolence and their evil deeds.” '),(15004,' \nThen Laertes answered him again, and said:'),(15005,' “If it is indeed as Odysseus, my son, that thou art come hither, tell me now some clear sign, that I maybe sure.\"'),(15006,'  And Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said: '),(15007,'“This scar first do thou mark with thine eyes, the scar of the wound which a boar dealt me with his white tusk on Parnassus, when I had gone thither.'),(15008,' It was thou that didst send me forth, thou and my honored mother, to Autolycus, my mother\'s father, that I might get  the gifts which, when he came hither, he promised and agreed to give me. '),(15009,' And come, I will tell thee also the trees in the well-ordered garden which once thou gavest me, and I, who was but a child, was following thee through the garden, and asking thee for this and that.'),(15010,' It was through these very trees that we passed, and thou didst name them, and tell me of each one.'),(15011,'  Pear-trees thirteen thou gavest me, and ten apple-trees, and forty fig-trees.'),(15012,' And rows of vines too didst thou promise to give me, even as I say, fifty of them, which ripened severally at different times—'),(15013,'and upon them are clusters of all sorts—whensoever the seasons of Zeus weighed them down from above.”'),(15014,'  So he spoke, and his father\'s knees were loosened where he stood, and his heart melted, as he knew the sure tokens which Odysseus told him.'),(15015,' About his dear son he flung both his arms, '),(15016,'and the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus caught him unto him fainting.'),(15017,' But when he revived, and his spirit returned again into his breast,  once more he made answer, and spoke, saying:'),(15018,'“Father Zeus, verily ye gods yet hold sway on high Olympus, if indeed the wooers have paid the price of their wanton insolence.'),(15019,' But now I have wondrous dread at heart, lest straightway all the men of Ithaca come hither against us, and  send messengers everywhere to the cities of the Cephallenians.”'),(15020,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(15021,' “Be of good cheer, and let not these things distress thy heart.'),(15022,' But let us go to the house, which lies near the orchard, '),(15023,'for thither  I sent forward Telemachus and the neatherd and the swineherd, that with all speed they might prepare our meal.”'),(15024,'So spoke the two, and went their way to the goodly house.'),(15025,' And when they had come to the stately house, they found Telemachus, and the neatherd, and the swineherd carving flesh in abundance, and mixing the flaming wine. '),(15026,' \n  Meanwhile the Sicilian handmaid bathed great-hearted Laertes in his house, and anointed him with oil, and about him cast a fair cloak.'),(15027,' But Athena drew near, and made greater the limbs of the shepherd of the people, and made him taller than before and mightier to behold.'),(15028,'  Then he came forth from the bath,'),(15029,' and his dear son marvelled at him, seeing him in presence like unto the immortal gods.'),(15030,' And he spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(15031,'\n“Father, surely some one of the gods that are forever has made thee goodlier to behold in comeliness and in stature.\"'),(15032,'  Then wise Laertes answered him: '),(15033,'“I would, O father Zeus, and Athena, and Apollo, that in such strength as when I took Nericus, the well built citadel on the shore of the mainland, when I was lord of the Cephallenians, even in such strength I had stood by thy side yesterday in our house  with my armour about my shoulders, and had beaten back the wooers.'),(15034,' So should I have loosened the knees of many of them in the halls, and thy heart would have been made glad within thee.\"'),(15035,'So they spoke to one another.'),(15036,' But when the others had ceased from their labour, and had made ready the meal,  they sat down in order on the chairs and high seats. '),(15037,'Then they were about to set hands to their food, when the old man Dolius drew near, and with him the old man\'s sons, wearied from their work in the fields, for their mother, the old Sicilian woman, had gone forth and called them, she who  saw to their food, and tended the old man with kindly care, now that old age had laid hold of him. '),(15038,'And they, when they saw Odysseus, and marked him in their minds, stood in the halls lost in wonder.'),(15039,' But Odysseus addressed them with gentle words, and said:'),(15040,'\n“Old man, sit down to dinner, and do ye wholly forget your wonder, '),(15041,' for long have we waited in the halls, though eager to set hands to the food, ever expecting your coming.\"'),(15042,'So he spoke, and Dolius ran straight toward him with both hands outstretched, and he clasped the hand of Odysseus and kissed it on the wrist, and spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(15043,'\n  “Dear master, since thou hast come back to us, who sorely longed for thee, but had no more thought to see thee, and the gods themselves have brought thee—hail to thee, and all welcome, and may the gods grant thee happiness.'),(15044,' And tell me this also truly, that I may know full well. Does wise Penelope yet know surely  that thou hast come back hither, or shall we send her a messenger?”'),(15045,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: “Old man, she knows already; '),(15046,'why shouldst thou be busied with this?”'),(15047,'So he spoke, and the other sat down again on the polished chair. '),(15048,'And even in like manner the sons of Dolius gathered around glorious Odysseus  and greeted him in speech, and clasped his hands. Then they sat down in order beside Dolius, their father. '),(15049,' \nSo they were busied with their meal in the halls; '),(15050,'but meanwhile Rumor, the messenger, went swiftly throughout all the city, telling of the terrible death and fate of the wooers.'),(15051,'  And the people heard it all at once, and gathered from every side with moanings and wailings before the palace of Odysseus. Forth from the halls they brought each his dead, and buried them; and those from other cities they sent each to his own home, placing them on swift ships for seamen to bear them, '),(15052,' but they themselves went together to the place of assembly, sad at heart.'),(15053,' Now when they were assembled and met together Eupeithes arose and spoke among them, '),(15054,'for comfortless grief for his son lay heavy on his heart, even for Antinous, the first man whom goodly Odysseus had slain.'),(15055,'  Weeping for him he addressed their assembly and said:'),(15056,'“Friends, a monstrous deed has this man of a truth devised against the Achaeans.'),(15057,' Some he led forth in his ships, many men and goodly, and he has lost his hollow ships and utterly lost his men; '),(15058,' and others again has he slain on his return, and these by far the best of the Cephallenians.  Nay then, come, before the fellow goes swiftly to Pylos or to goodly Elis, where the Epeans hold sway, let us go forth; '),(15059,'verily even in days to come shall we be disgraced forever.'),(15060,' For a shame is this even for men that are yet to be to hear of, if we shall not  take vengeance on the slayers of our sons and our brothers. '),(15061,'To me surely life would then no more be sweet; rather would I die at once and be among the dead.'),(15062,' Nay, let us forth, lest they be too quick for us, and cross over the sea.\"'),(15063,'So he spoke, weeping, and pity laid hold of all the Achaeans.'),(15064,'Then near them came Medon and the divine minstrel  from the halls of Odysseus, for sleep had released them; and they took their stand in the midst, '),(15065,'and wonder seized every man.'),(15066,' Then Medon, wise of heart, spoke among them:'),(15067,'\n“Hearken now to me, men of Ithaca, '),(15068,'for verily not without the will of the immortal gods has Odysseus devised these deeds.'),(15069,'  Nay, I myself saw an immortal god, who stood close beside Odysseus, and seemed in all things like unto Mentor.'),(15070,' Yet as an immortal god now in front of Odysseus would he appear, heartening him, and now again would rage through the hall, scaring the wooers; '),(15071,'and they fell thick and fast.” '),(15072,' \n  So he spoke, and thereat pale fear seized them all. '),(15073,' Then among them spoke the old lord Halitherses, son of Mastor, '),(15074,' for he alone saw before and after: '),(15075,'he with good intent addressed their assembly, and said:'),(15076,'“Hearken now to me, men of Ithaca, to the word that I shall say.'),(15077,' Through your own cowardice, friends, have these deeds been brought to pass, '),(15078,' for you would not obey me, nor Mentor, shepherd of the people, to make your sons cease from their folly. They wrought a monstrous deed in their blind and wanton wickedness, wasting the wealth and dishonoring the wife  of a prince,'),(15079,' who, they said, would never more return. '),(15080,'and do you hearken to me, as I bid.'),(15081,'and do you hearken to me, as I bid.'),(15082,' Let us not go forth, lest haply many a one shall find a bane which he has brought upon himself.\"'),(15083,'So he spoke, but they sprang up with loud cries, more than half of them,'),(15084,' but the rest remained together in their seats; '),(15085,' for his speech was not to their mind, but they hearkened to Eupeithes, '),(15086,' and quickly thereafter they rushed for their arms.'),(15087,' Then when they had clothed their bodies in gleaming bronze, they gathered together in front of the spacious city.'),(15088,' And Eupeithes led them in his folly, '),(15089,' for he thought to avenge the slaying of his son; yet he was himself never more to come back, but was there to meet his doom.'),(15090,'\nBut Athena spoke to Zeus, son of Cronos, saying:'),(15091,' “Father of us all, thou son of Cronos, high above all lords, tell to me that ask thee what purpose thy mind now hides within thee.'),(15092,'  Wilt thou yet further bring to pass evil war and the dread din of battle, or wilt thou establish friendship betwixt the twain?\"'),(15093,'Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered her, and said:'),(15094,' “My child, why dost thou ask and question me of this?'),(15095,' Didst thou not thyself devise this plan,  that verily Odysseus should take vengeance on these men at his coming? '),(15096,'but I will tell thee what is fitting. '),(15097,'but I will tell thee what is fitting. '),(15098,' Now that goodly Odysseus has taken vengeance on the wooers, let them swear a solemn oath, and let him be king all his days, and let us on our part  bring about a forgetting of the slaying of their sons and brothers; '),(15099,'and let them love one another as before, and let wealth and peace abound.\"'),(15100,'So saying, he roused Athena, who was already eager, and she went darting down from the heights of Olympus.'),(15101,'\nBut when they had put from them the desire of honey-hearted food,  the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus was the first to speak among his company, saying:'),(15102,' “Let one go forth and see whether they be not now drawing near.\"'),(15103,' and a son of Dolius went forth, as he bade; '),(15104,' and a son of Dolius went forth, as he bade; '),(15105,'he went and stood upon the threshold, and saw them all close at hand, '),(15106,'and straightway he spoke to Odysseus winged words: '),(15107,'Quick, let us arm.”'),(15108,'Quick, let us arm.”'),(15109,' \nSo he spoke, and they rose up and arrayed themselves in armour: Odysseus and his men were four, and six the sons of Dolius, '),(15110,'and among them Laertes and Dolius donned their armour, grey-headed though they were, warriors perforce.'),(15111,'  But when they had clothed their bodies in gleaming bronze, they opened the doors and went forth, and Odysseus led them.'),(15112,'\nThen Athena, daughter of Zeus, drew near them in the likeness of Mentor both in form and in voice, '),(15113,'and the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus was glad at sight of her,'),(15114,' and straightway spoke to Telemachus, his dear son:'),(15115,'\n“Telemachus, now shalt thou learn this—having thyself come to the place of battle, where the best warriors are put to the trial—to bring no disgrace upon the house of thy fathers, for we have ever excelled in strength and in valor over all the earth.\"'),(15116,'  And wise Telemachus answered him: '),(15117,'“Thou shalt see me, if thou wilt, dear father, in my present temper, bringing no disgrace upon thy house, even as thou sayest.\"'),(15118,'So said he, and Laertes was glad, and spoke, saying:'),(15119,' Verily right glad am I:'),(15120,' Verily right glad am I:'),(15121,'my son and my son\'s son are vying with one another in valor.”'),(15122,'Then flashing-eyed Athena came near him and said:'),(15123,' “Son of Arceisius, far the dearest of all my friends, make a prayer to the flashing-eyed maiden and to father Zeus, and then straightway raise aloft thy long spear, and hurl it.”'),(15124,'  So spoke Pallas Athena, and breathed into him great might. Then he prayed to the daughter of great Zeus, and straightway raised aloft his long spear, and hurled it, and smote Eupeithes through the helmet with cheek-piece of bronze.'),(15125,' This stayed not the spear, but the bronze passed through,  and he fell with a thud, and his armour clanged about him. '),(15126,'Then on the foremost fighters fell Odysseus and his glorious son, and thrust at them with swords and double-pointed spears.'),(15127,' And now would they have slain them all, and cut them off from returning, had not Athena, daughter of Zeus, who bears the aegis,  shouted aloud, and checked all the host, saying:'),(15128,'“Refrain, men of Ithaca, from grievous war, that with all speed you may part, and that without bloodshed.\"'),(15129,'So spoke Athena, and pale fear seized them.'),(15130,' Then in their terror the arms flew from their hands  and fell one and all to the ground, as the goddess uttered her voice, '),(15131,'and they turned toward the city, eager to save their lives.'),(15132,' Terribly then shouted the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus, and gathering himself together he swooped upon them like an eagle of lofty flight, '),(15133,'and at that moment the son of Cronos cast a flaming thunderbolt,  and down it fell before the flashing-eyed daughter of the mighty sire.'),(15134,' Then flashing-eyed Athena spoke to Odysseus saying:'),(15135,'\n“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, stay thy hand, and make the strife of equal war to cease, lest haply the son of Cronos be wroth with thee, even Zeus, whose voice is borne afar.\"'),(15136,'  So spoke Athena, and he obeyed, and was glad at heart. '),(15137,'Then for all time to come a solemn covenant betwixt the twain was made by Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus, who bears the aegis, in the likeness of Mentor both in form and in voice.');
